[Event "Amsterdam"]
[Site "Amsterdam NED"]
[Date "1889.08.26"]
[Round "1"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Johann Hermann Bauer"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A03"]
[PlyCount "75"]
[EventDate "1889.08.26"]

{Already the first move of the first game shows the profound psychology of
Emanuel Lasker. Against a lesser known opponent, he choses an offbeat opening
just to throw him off his guard.} 1. f4 d5 2. e3 Nf6 3. b3 {[pgndiagram] After
1..d5, White essentialy plays a reversed Dutch Defence} e6 4. Bb2 Be7 5. Bd3 $5
{A strange looking move, but not that bad at all. White blocks his d-pawn, but
develops his bishop on an agressive post.} b6 6. Nc3 Bb7 7. Nf3 Nbd7 8. O-O O-O
{[pgndiagram] Black has developed naturally and is by no means worse. However,
now he has to find a concrete plan} 9. Ne2 $6 {This is probably not the best,
as it gives up a bishop pair for no compensation} (9. a4 a5 10. Qe1 {Trying to
bring the queen into attack, was interesting way. The position is
approximately equal}) 9... c5 $6 (9... Nc5 {Would have exchanged White's
dangerous light squared bishop and given Black an excellent position}) 10. Ng3
Qc7 11. Ne5 {[pgndiagram] Objectively, this jump shouldn't be dangerous, but
in those years, defence wasn't the strongest point of any chess player.} Nxe5
$2 {A mistake} (11... g6 {Was comparatively the best, blocking the d3 bishop
and preventing future Nh5, which  makes the knight on g3 look rather silly.})
12. Bxe5 $6 (12. fxe5 {Was much better, even though it blocks the bishop} Ne4 {
The best move} (12... Nd7 13. Qh5 h6 {Already the only move} (13... g6 {Is
losing immediately} 14. Qh6 {Now Nh5 is a deadly threat, there is also Rxf7 in
the air} Nxe5 (14... Rac8 15. Nh5) 15. Nh5) 14. Rf4 {And White has an
extremely dangerous attack}) 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Rf4 Rad8 15. Nxe4 {And White
has an excellent position}) 12... Qc6 13. Qe2 $6 {Allowing Black another
chance for g6} (13. Nh5 $1 {Was very good, solving the problem piece at once}
d4 14. Rf2) 13... a6 {[pgndiagram] And this is the decisive mistake. Making
this move for Black is complete luxury} (13... g6 {Was absolutely necessary.
It is not clear how White will continue}) 14. Nh5 $1 {Now White has a winning
attack} Nxh5 $2 {And this is going from the frying pan to fire} (14... Rfd8 {
Is the lesser evil} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxh7+ Kf8 {And White retains an
advantage, but the game continues} (16... Kxh7 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19.
Qh6 {[pgndiagram] And Black is busted})) 15. Bxh7+ $1 {[pgndiagram] The first
bishop sacrifice} Kxh7 16. Qxh5+ Kg8 17. Bxg7 $3 {[pgndiagram] The second
bishop sacrifice and the main reason why this not particularly important games
is famous nowadays. This attacking maneouvre is a typical idea nowadays, but
Lasker was first to discover it in over the board game} Kxg7 18. Qg4+ $1 {Very
important check, forcing the black king on the h-file} (18. Rf3 $2 {Would be a
terrible mistake} Rh8 19. Rg3+ Bg5 20. Rxg5+ Kf6 {[pgndiagram] And suddenly
White is lost}) 18... Kh7 19. Rf3 {Black has to give up his queen in order to
defend against mate} e5 20. Rh3+ Qh6 21. Rxh6+ Kxh6 22. Qd7 $1 {[pgndiagram]
And this is an additional problem. Without this move, Black would be probably
be able to resist, but now White wins one of the bishops and the game is
effectively decided} Bf6 23. Qxb7 {The rest is a matter of straightforward
technique} Kg7 24. Rf1 Rab8 25. Qd7 Rfd8 26. Qg4+ Kf8 27. fxe5 Bg7 28. e6 Rb7
29. Qg6 f6 30. Rxf6+ Bxf6 31. Qxf6+ Ke8 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Qg7+ Kxe6 34. Qxb7 Rd6
35. Qxa6 d4 36. exd4 cxd4 37. h4 d3 38. Qxd3 {[pgndiagram] A beautiful
attacking game, not without its errors. The best example of the "psychological
chess" that Lasker played} 1-0

[Event "St Petersburg"]
[Site "St. Petersburg  RUS"]
[Date "1914.05.18"]
[Round "7"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Jose Raul Capablanca"]
[Result "*"]
[ECO "C68"]
[PlyCount "83"]
[EventDate "1914.04.21"]

1. e4 {[pgndiagram] This game was a must win for Lasker. Two rounds before the
finish, he was behind Capablanca by a whole point. Moreover, the Cuban had not
lost any games in the whole tournament before this encounter.} e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.
Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 $1 {An amazing decision. Although the Exchange Variation of the
Ruy Lopez was a formidable weapon in Lasker's hands, few could have thought
that it would work against Capablanca, whose virtuoso endgame technique was
already widely known.} dxc6 5. d4 (5. O-O {Nowadays, castling first is
considered as the best move. Robert James Fischer was the first to realize the
strength of this move}) 5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4 {[pgndiagram]
Objectively speaking, White shouldn't claim any advantage in this position
whatsoever. Black has great compensation for the inferior pawn structure in
view of the two bishops and free development.} Bd6 (7... Bd7 {With castling
long has been played more often, with comfortable game}) 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. O-O O-O
10. f4 $6 {[pgndiagram] A rather double edged, objectively not a very good
move. White is burning his bridges prematurely. But Lasker is laying for the
win} (10. Be3 {Is more normal, although here White doesn't have the advantage})
10... Re8 {Black prevents Be3 due to a knight jump, and also threatens Bc5} (
10... Bc5 11. Be3 Re8 {Is also possible} 12. Rae1 f6 {With comfortable game}) (
10... f6 {Is also decent}) 11. Nb3 f6 {Preparing the development of the bishop
via b6-Lb7} (11... a5 {Is the computer way, grabbing some space for free} 12.
e5 Bb4 13. a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 b6 {And Black has an excellent position}) 12. f5 {
[pgndiagram] "It has been wrongly claimed that this wins the game, but I would
like nothing better than to have such a position again" - Capablanca.   And
indeed, this move is double edged. On one hand it hands the e5 square for free,
but on the other hand, White eyes the e6 square.   However, under normal
circumstances he shouldn't be allowed to put his knight there} b6 13. Bf4 Bb7
$2 {Only this is a serious mistake, after which White's play is completely
justified} (13... Bxf4 14. Rxf4 c5 15. Rd1 Bb7 {Was more logical. The point is
that White's invasion is not dangerous} 16. Rd7 Rac8 {And his knight and rook
are stuck on b3 and f4. Black is better}) 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Nd4 {[pgndiagram]
Now Black has  to keep eye over e6. Although his pawn chain looks nice, it is
not that mobile and White's knights have many potential targets} Rad8 $2 {And
this is allowing too much. Capablanca is rather careless and allows the White
knight to resident permanently on e6} (15... Bc8 {Was neccessary, intending c5
next and preventing White's plan} 16. Rad1 c5 {And now White has to give up
the idea of occupying the e6 square} 17. Ne6 Bxe6 18. fxe6 Rad8 19. Nd5 Nc6 {
[pgndiagram] And White doesn't have any advantage}) 16. Ne6 {After this the
play is completely one sided} Rd7 17. Rad1 {[pgndiagram] Capablanca said that
he was now on point of playing c6-c5, but suddenly he became ambitious. 
Indeed, 17... c5 was better} Nc8 (17... c5 18. Rf3 $1 {Preventing d5 in a
tactical way} (18. Nd5 {Is the only move mentioned by Kasparov and Capablanca,
but here it seems Black can defend - the d6 weakness is shielded} Bxd5 (18...
Nxd5 19. exd5) 19. exd5 h5 {Preventing g4. Black is ok}) 18... d5 $2 19. exd5
Nxd5 $4 20. Rfd3 {And White wins}) 18. Rf2 b5 19. Rfd2 Rde7 20. b4 Kf7 21. a3 {
[pgndiagram] White has a dream position. The play is completely on one goal}
Ba8 $2 {"Once again changing my plan and this time without any good reason" -
Capablanca.} (21... Rxe6 {Was indeed the best move} 22. fxe6+ Rxe6 {And Black
is very much in the game}) 22. Kf2 {[pgndiagram] Now White will push his
kingside pawns, opening a second front} Ra7 (22... h5 $2 {Simply loses a pawn}
23. Rd3 {And after Rh3-Nf3, White will win the h5 pawn}) 23. g4 h6 24. Rd3 a5
$2 {This is a bad idea, as only White will benefit from the opening of the
a-file} (24... Rae7 {Waiting passively was better, although not sufficient} 25.
h4 {And now the exchange sacrifice doesn't work that well after} Rxe6 26. fxe6+
Rxe6 27. Kf3 Bb7 28. h5 Re5 29. Kf4 Re6 30. a4 $1 {[pgndiagram] And White is
bound to break through sooner or later. The advance of the kingside pawns
makes a big difference}) 25. h4 axb4 26. axb4 Rae7 $6 {[pgndiagram] It was
probably wiser not to move the rook from the a-file} (26... Ra3 {Is a blank
shot though} 27. g5) (26... Rh8 {Awaiting the opening of the h-file, was more
subtle. White shouldn't rush, but prepare it with say} 27. Rg1 Ra3 28. g5 {
[pgndiagram] But this push is strong all the same. White is close to winning;
tactics work in his favour} hxg5 29. hxg5 Rh2+ 30. Ke3 Nb6 (30... Rxc2 {Falls
to} 31. Nxb5 Rxd3+ (31... cxb5 32. Rxa3) 32. Kxd3) 31. gxf6 gxf6 32. Rg7+ {and
wins}) 27. Kf3 Rg8 28. Kf4 g6 $6 (28... Rh8 {Was wiser}) 29. Rg3 (29. g5 $1 {
Was more energetic. Black doesn't have a good reply} gxf5 30. exf5 fxg5+ 31.
hxg5 hxg5+ 32. Nxg5+ Kf8 33. Nce4 {And wins}) 29... g5+ {[pgndiagram]} (29...
gxf5 {It is hard to suggest a better move} 30. exf5 d5 31. Ne2 Nd6 32. N2d4 Ne4
33. Ra3 {And White penetrates}) 30. Kf3 Nb6 $6 {Desperation. An attempt to
jump with the knight on the e5 square} (30... Rge8 31. hxg5 fxg5 {Was more
resistant}) 31. hxg5 hxg5 32. Rh3 Rd7 (32... Nc4 {Is met very nicely with} 33.
Kg3 $1 {And now it is hard to suggest a move for Black. White intends e5 next}
(33. Rh7+ Ke8 34. Nc7+ {Also wins though} Kd7 35. Rxe7+ Kxe7 36. Ra1) 33... Ne5
34. Rxd6) 33. Kg3 Ke8 34. Rdh1 Bb7 35. e5 $1 {[pgndiagram] The knockout blow.
With this clearance sacrifice, White opens the e4 square for his other knight
and Black gets overwhelmed} dxe5 (35... fxe5 36. Ne4 {Was not better}) (35...
c5 {Was more tricky, because now} 36. Rh8 {Is the onl way to win} Bxh1 37.
Rxg8+ Ke7 38. exd6+ {[pgndiagram] And White wins a piece} Kxd6 39. bxc5+ Kc6
40. cxb6 {And wins}) 36. Ne4 $1 {f6 and c5 are too weak, h-file is owned by
White, the game is over} Nd5 37. N6c5 Bc8 38. Nxd7 Bxd7 39. Rh7 Rf8 40. Ra1 Kd8
41. Ra8+ Bc8 42. Nc5 {[pgndiagram] Playing important games with great power
and energy was always Lasker's forte and he always managed to score a win when
he needed one the most} *

[Event "St. Petersburg 1895/96"]
[Site "St. Petersburg RUS"]
[Date "1896.01.04"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Harry Nelson Pillsbury"]
[Black "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "D50"]
[PlyCount "60"]
[EventDate "1895.12.13"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Bg5 {[pgndiagram] This was
Pillsbury's favourite move against the Semi-Tarrasch defence, which is
somewhat risky from the modern viewpoint.} (5. e3) (5. cxd5 {Are both more in
the vogue nowadays}) 5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 (6. Nxd4 {Later it was established that
after this move} e5 $1 {Is an immediate equalizer}) 6... Nc6 {This looks
natural, but it might not be the best, as it allows the ruination of the
Black's kingside structure} (6... Be7 {First is correct} 7. Rd1 {And only now}
Nc6 {With equality}) 7. Qh4 $6 (7. Bxf6 $1 {Was the right move, asking Black
some immediate questions} gxf6 {The only correct move} (7... Nxd4 8. Bxd8 Nxf3+
(8... Nc2+ 9. Kd2 Nxa1 10. Bh4 {[pgndiagram] And the Knight will fall}) 9. exf3
Kxd8 10. cxd5 {[pgndiagram] And White has won a pawn}) 8. Qh4 {And White has
chances for an opening advantage}) 7... Be7 8. O-O-O $6 {And this is extremely
risky. Half a century later, Keres suffered a hard defeat in a similar manner
from the hands of the Botvinnik} (8. e3 Qb6 {Is mildly unpleasant, but now
castling makes more sense since the queen is better on a5 than on b6} 9. O-O-O
(9. Rb1 {Also comes into consideration} h6 10. Bd3 O-O 11. Bxh6 gxh6 12. Qxh6 {
And it would appear that White has the perpetual check.. at least.})) 8... Qa5
{[pgndiagram] White is in danger and has to play precisely} 9. e3 $2 {And this
is already almost the decisive error} (9. cxd5 {Was necessary.} exd5 10. e4 $1
{Only energetic play will do in this position} (10. e3 {Subjects white to a
strong attack once again} h6 11. Bd3 Be6 12. Nd4 Nxd4 13. exd4 O-O {
[pgndiagram] And Black is enjoying this position}) 10... Be6 (10... dxe4 11.
Bxf6 {Is the point} Bxf6 12. Qxe4+ Be6 13. Bc4 {And White is relatively safe})
11. Bb5 {And White has managed to develop and shouldn't be worse}) 9... Bd7 (
9... h6 {Was even stronger} 10. Bd3 Rf8 {Avoiding all tactics connected with
castling} (10... O-O {On} 11. cxd5 $3 {Works} Nxd5 (11... hxg5 $2 12. Nxg5 {
And White is almost winning}) 12. Bxe7 Ncxe7 {Is not that clear}) 11. cxd5 $4 {
Is now bad} hxg5) 10. Kb1 $6 {Allowing h6, after which White doesn't have
enough time for Bb5 ideas} (10. cxd5 {Was better} exd5 11. Bb5 {Eliminating
the danger} a6 12. Bxc6 bxc6 (12... Bxc6 13. Nd4 {Is good for White}) 13. Ne5)
10... h6 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nd4 {[pgndiagram] White is forced to cut his losses}
(12. Bb5 O-O {Is now a major difference, White is forced to react on the
kingside} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 {And White doesn't have time to swap queens due to} 14.
Qa4 Bf5+ 15. Ka1 Qxc3 $3 16. Rd2) 12... O-O 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. Qh5 {It is
apparent that White's opening hasn't been successful. But the spectacular part
of the game is yet to follow} Nxd4 (14... Be6 {Was interesting} 15. f4 Rac8 16.
f5 Bd7 {And Black is winning}) 15. exd4 Be6 $5 {It would appear that Lasker
already knew how he would respond to the advance of the f-pawn} 16. f4 $6 {
Probably not justified} (16. Bc4 {Finishing the development and bringing the
bishop to defensive post was better}) 16... Rac8 17. f5 Rxc3 $3 {[pgndiagram]
A brilliant combination.} (17... Bd7 {Was perfectly possible though} 18. Qf3
Bc6 19. g4 b5 {And Black is faster with his attack nevertheless. However, we
probably wouldn't be annotating this game in that case}) 18. fxe6 (18. bxc3 Rc8
{Is hopeless for White} (18... Bd7 {Even this prosaic move wins easily})) 18...
Ra3 $1 {[pgndiagram] The crux of the combination. Black sacrifices his rook on
a3, forcing White to take the rook and shatter his kingside pawn structure} 19.
exf7+ $2 {And this is the losing move} (19. bxa3 {Seems hopeless, but..} Qb6+
20. Bb5 $1 {This defensive resource is also featured in the main game, but
here it is extremely strong} (20. Ka1 Bxd4+ 21. Rxd4 Qxd4+ 22. Kb1 fxe6 {Is
hopeless for White. Rf2 is very strong threat}) (20. Kc2 Rc8+ {Also doesn't
finish to well after} 21. Kd2 Qxd4+ 22. Ke1 Qe3+ 23. Be2 fxe6 {And Black has
all sorts of threats}) 20... Qxb5+ 21. Ka1 fxe6 {[pgndiagram] And White is
worse, but the game is not over}) 19... Rxf7 20. bxa3 Qb6+ 21. Bb5 $1 {
[pgndiagram] Similarly as in previous variations, all other moves lose more
quickly} Qxb5+ 22. Ka1 Rc7 $2 {This move almost throws the whole advantage for
Black} (22... Qc4 {The difference between this and previously examined
variations is the fact that black doesn't have to recapture on e6 and has one
tempo to create a threat. A tempo that makes every difference.} 23. Qg4 Re7 {
The threats are Re4 and Re2 and Black wins}) 23. Rd2 Rc4 24. Rhd1 $2 {
[pgndiagram] It is now Pillsbury's moment to go wrong} (24. Re1 {Would lead to
a pretty draw after} Qa5 25. Re8+ Kh7 26. Qf5+ g6 27. Re7+ Bxe7 (27... Kg8 28.
Qxg6+) 28. Qf7+ {With perpetual}) 24... Rc3 $2 {[pgndiagram] Another error,
which even passes the advantage to white} (24... Qc6 {Would have won. The
point is that after} 25. Kb1 Bg5 {Wins}) 25. Qf5 Qc4 {Now suddenly White has
to make only one precise move and he can even start thinking about winning} 26.
Kb2 $4 {A tragic move and one of the historic chess moves with grave
consequences for Pillsbury.} (26. Kb1 {Keeping everything defended, especially
the a2 pawn, was good for White.} Rxa3 27. Rc1 {And Black has unplesant
problems} Qb5+ 28. Rb2 Qd3+ 29. Qxd3 Rxd3 30. Rxb7 Bxd4 {And it is hard to
believe that Black can hold this endgame}) 26... Rxa3 $3 {[pgndiagram] For the
second time in the game, the rook is sacrificed on a3. One of those instances
which induced Lasker's contemporaries to accuse him that he hypnotized his
opponents} 27. Qe6+ (27. Kxa3 {Walks into a mate} Qc3+ 28. Ka4 b5+ 29. Kxb5
Qc4+ 30. Ka5 Bd8#) 27... Kh7 $2 {Once again a mistake} (27... Kh8 {Would have
won. There is a crucial difference between the White queen on e6 and f5 (cf.
the later variation)} 28. Kb1 Bxd4 29. Qe8+ (29. Rxd4 Qxa2+) 29... Kh7 30. Qe2
Qb4+ {And wins}) 28. Kxa3 $4 {[pgndiagram] A final mistake of the game.
Pillsbury walks in the previously examined mating pattern} (28. Qf5+ Kh8 29.
Kb1 {WAs now possible, because with the queen on f5, White has f8 check,
capturing the rook on a3} Rxa2 $1 {Black can force the perpetual with this move
} (29... Bxd4 $4 30. Qf8+ Kh7 31. Qxa3) 30. Rxa2 Qb3+ 31. Kc1 Bg5+ 32. Rad2
Qc3+ 33. Kb1 (33. Qc2 Qa1+ 34. Qb1 Qc3+) 33... Qb3+) 28... Qc3+ {Now the game
is over} 29. Ka4 b5+ 30. Kxb5 Qc4+ {[pgndiagram] A fantastic struggle, in
which Lasker almost threw away the deserved victory. If Pillsbury won this
game, he would have also won the whole tournament and probably been regarded
as the undisputed number one in the world. Alas...} 0-1

[Event "Cambridge Springs"]
[Site "Cambridge Springs, PA USA"]
[Date "1904.04.28"]
[Round "3.3"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "William Ewart Napier"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "B72"]
[PlyCount "69"]
[EventDate "1904.04.25"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. Nf3 g6 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 d6 {[pgndiagram]
One of those rare instances of the Dragon variation of the Sicilian in the
20th century} 7. h3 {The plan of the extended fianchetto is definitely not the
most challenging one, but it is also not without it's venom if not handled
properly} Nf6 {Nothing wrong with this, because White hardly has another
square for this knight. The g5 push is not that significant} 8. g4 {The
typical idea of the variation. White intends to continue with Bg2, 0-0, f4 and
attack on the kingside.} O-O 9. g5 $6 {[pgndiagram] But this is premature in
my opinion. White is not sufficiently developed for such displays of aggression
} (9. Bg2 {Is more normal} Bd7 10. O-O Ne5 {With typical, Dragon play}) 9...
Ne8 $6 (9... Nh5 {Came into consideration. The point is that} 10. Be2 {Is met
by} Nf4) (9... Nd7 {Also seems more logical than the text move}) 10. h4 Nc7 11.
f4 $6 {Typcial Lasker, but once again, White should complete his development
instead} (11. Qd2) 11... e5 $5 {A typical reaction. Black responds to a wing
attack with the central blow} 12. Nde2 d5 $6 {But this, surprisingly is not
the best move in the position, although it is typical and does look rather
attractive} (12... exf4 {First of all, the typical capture, opening the e5
square for the pieces, was possible.} 13. Nxf4 Bxc3+ $1 {Capturing the
defender of the d5 square and ruining White's queenside structure}) (12... f5
$1 {Secondly, this unexpected resource, opening the position from the other
side, was extremely strong. It is hard to say what Black should do} 13. gxf6
Bxf6 14. Bf2 exf4 {And Black is almost winning}) 13. exd5 Nd4 $2 {[pgndiagram]
And this is almost a decisive mistake. In such a sharp position, every wrong
move is very costly.} (13... exf4 {This intermezzo was essential} 14. Bxf4 (14.
Nxf4 Re8 15. Qd2 Bd4 $1) 14... Nb4 {And Black gets extremely good compensation
for the piece}) 14. Nxd4 Nxd5 (14... exd4 15. Bxd4 {Is just a clear pawn for
White}) 15. Nf5 $1 {Lasker was very strong in these positions} Nxc3 16. Qxd8
Rxd8 17. Ne7+ Kh8 (17... Kf8 {Runs into} 18. Bc5) 18. h5 $1 {[pgndiagram] A
fantastic conception. White ignores the piece, but simply continues to attack,
even after the queen exchange} (18. bxc3 {Actually doesn't win a piece.} exf4
19. Bd4 Re8) (18. f5 {Was arguably even stronger} Ne4 (18... Bxf5 19. bxc3) 19.
f6 Bf8 20. Bc4 Nd6 21. Bb3 {With advantage}) 18... Re8 19. Bc5 (19. f5 {Is
once again computer's suggestion, threatening the knight on c3 (removing the
exf4 counter)} gxf5 {The only move. Tactics work in Black's favour} 20. Nxc8
Nd5 21. Bf2 Rexc8 22. O-O-O {[pgndiagram] And White is much better}) 19... gxh5
$2 {And this is a serious mistake} (19... exf4 {Pinning the knight on e7 and
defending its counterpart on c3 was necessary. After} 20. hxg6 fxg6 21. Bd3 Nd5
22. Rxh7+ Kxh7 23. Bxg6+ Kh8 24. Bxe8 Bg4 25. Nxd5 Rxe8+ 26. Kd2 {Black can
resist in the endgame}) 20. Bc4 $2 {The way chess was played in the early 20th
century. Taking the piece was often rejected in favour of an attacking
continuation} (20. bxc3 {WAs now good, because the knight on e7 is defended}
exf4 21. O-O-O) (20. Rxh5 {Was also better than the text move}) 20... exf4 $2 {
The position is obviously very complex. Black defends the knight in an
indirect way, but this proves to be another tactical mistake} (20... Ne4 {
Gaining a tempo on the bishop on c5, was important} 21. Ba3 Ng3 {This move
hurts White} 22. Rg1 exf4 23. Bxf7 Bg4 24. Bxe8 Rxe8 {[pgndiagram] And
amazingly, computer claims Black is completely winning here. It does seem that
White is tied up, but it is hard to find it 4 moves in advance}) 21. Bxf7 Ne4
22. Bxe8 Bxb2 (22... Nxc5 23. Bxh5 {Is hopeless. White has a clear exchange
and an attack}) 23. Rb1 Bc3+ 24. Kf1 {[pgndiagram]At the moment, White has a
clear rook for two pawns, but Black can regain some of his material} Bg4 (24...
Nxc5 {Was better} 25. Bxh5 Kg7 {And Black is still in a precarious position,
but he has some hopes of resisting in the endgame}) 25. Bxh5 Bxh5 26. Rxh5 Ng3+
27. Kg2 Nxh5 28. Rxb7 {[pgndiagram] It is not hard to understand why Napier
went for this position. The material is equal, and White's position doesn't
look that threatening. However, in reality, Black is completely tied up} a5 29.
Rb3 {Changing the track and going for the h-pawn} Bg7 30. Rh3 Ng3 31. Kf3 {
[pgndiagram] All Black's pawns are weak and White's pieces are much more active
} Ra6 32. Kxf4 Ne2+ 33. Kf5 Nc3 34. a3 Na4 $2 {A final blunder} (34... a4 {WAs
more resilient. Now Be3 is not winning immediately} 35. Be3 Ra5+ 36. Kf4) 35.
Be3 {[pgndiagram]There is no way of preventing g6, with decisive threats.
Black finally resigned. Another fantastic struggle with many mistakes, in
which Lasker managed to outplay his opponent from an aggressive, but dubious
position} 1-0

