[PlyCount "91"]
[EventDate "1894.??.??"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 Nge7 {[pgndiagram] This is
Steinitz's classical defence. The knight is heading to g6, bolstering the e5
square. On the other hand, Black loses some time. White should be better in
this variation, but Black is rather solid} 6. Be3 (6. d5 Nb8 7. Bxd7+ (7. a4 $5
) 7... Nxd7 8. Be3 {Is another way of treating this position}) 6... Ng6 7. Qd2
Be7 8. O-O-O a6 9. Be2 (9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. h4 $5 {Is interesting. The point is
that} Nxh4 11. Nxh4 Bxh4 12. dxe5 dxe5 13. Rxh4 Qxh4 14. Bg5 {[pgndiagram]
Wins for White}) 9... exd4 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 {[pgndiagram] Not allowing
the exchange of the bishops. White has more space, but in this Spanish
structure (e4 vs d6 pawn) Black has less space, but he doesn't have any
weaknesses (his pawn structure is compact).} Bf6 12. Qd2 Bc6 13. Nd5 O-O 14. g4
$6 {But this is premature agression. Pawns don't move backwards. Although this
move is played automaticaly by many lower rated players, pawn attacks should
always be prepared} (14. f3 {With a small plus was better}) (14. h4 {If White
had attacking ideas, he might have considered opening the h-file instead} Bxh4
15. g3 Be7 {With compensation for the pawn}) 14... Re8 15. g5 Bxd5 16. Qxd5 $2
{[pgndiagram] A second mistake, after which White is seriously worse} (16. exd5
{Was necessary, after which Black can sacrifice the exchange:} Rxe3 17. fxe3
Bxg5 {[pgndiagram] With sufficient compensation. Still, White retains some
advantage}) 16... Re5 $1 17. Qd2 $6 {After this white loses two pawns without
any compensation} (17. Qxb7 {Was required} Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Rxg5 19. h4 {And
although Black has some advantage, White has maintained the material balance
for the moment}) 17... Bxg5 18. f4 (18. Bxg5 Qxg5 {Is just horrible. Pawn down,
better knight, everything is in Black's favour}) 18... Rxe4 $1 {[pgndiagram]
The tactical point. Black exploits the position of the White bishops and wins
his piece back} 19. fxg5 Qe7 20. Rdf1 $2 {The final mistake} (20. Bf3 {
Regaining one pawn, was the best} Rxe3 21. Bxb7 Rb8 22. Rhe1 $1 {And this is
better for White than what he did in the game}) 20... Rxe3 21. Bc4 {
[pgndiagram] Objectively, White should be lost. But Lasker's stubbornes is the
main reason why this not so spectacular game has became famous. He digs in,
creates his chances and continues playing like nothing has happened} Nh8 $5 {
A typical Steinitz move, but slightly artificial} (21... Rf8 22. h4 b5 {Was
more normal, asking the bishop where it wants to go} 23. Bd3 {Else Re2 is
unpleasant} Qe5 {And Black is winning}) 22. h4 c6 (22... b5 23. Bd5 {Now gains
a tempo} Re2 24. Qd3 Re8 25. Bc6 {But still, White's position is unenviable.
Although this is the better version than in the previous note (the knight
looks strange on h8)}) 23. g6 $5 {Very creative. Throwing in another pawn just
to open the kingside completely} d5 $2 {[pgndiagram] And immediately Steinitz
makes a mistake that probably throws the win away already} (23... hxg6 {Black
should have taken the bait} 24. h5 gxh5 25. Rxh5 Re5 {leads to a nice variation
} 26. Rxh8+ Kxh8 27. Qh2+ Kg8 28. Bxf7+ Qxf7 29. Rxf7 Kxf7 {[pgndiagram] And
two rooks should outweigh the queen}) 24. gxh7+ Kxh7 25. Bd3+ Kg8 26. h5 {
[pgndiagram] Although Black is still material up, the situation has changed.
White's pieces are perfectly placed, the knight is out of play, and files are
opened. Still, two pawns mean Black is not worse, but he isn't clearly better
anymore as well} Re8 27. h6 g6 (27... gxh6 28. Rfg1+ Ng6 29. Bxg6 fxg6 30.
Rxg6+ Kf7 {Is something only computer would consider, but Black's king is safe
here, he has counterchances on the other side of the board}) 28. h7+ Kg7 29.
Kb1 $5 {[pgndiagram] But this move is really amazing; at the height of the
battle White makes a quiet move with his king and puts the ball into Black's
court. Although it is by no means the best move in this position, this puts
Steinitz in a hard psychological position} (29. Qh2 {Was objectively better
and only after} Qg5 30. Kb1) 29... Qe5 {This is better place for the queen
than g5} 30. a3 c5 31. Qf2 c4 $6 (31... f5 $1 {Is once again the computer's
choice, nipping White's attack in the bud.} 32. Rfg1 Kf7 {And White has
nothing.}) 32. Qh4 {[pgndiagram] "In this game there is a certain Tal effect.
White's attack is rather abstract, but it will not come to an end."} f6 33. Bf5
$3 {Kasparov refuses to give an exclamation mark to this move, but to my mind
it is amazing. White simply gives up a piece} Kf7 {Not yet fatal, but there
were better alternatives} (33... c3 $1 {Would lead to a forced draw} 34. b3
gxf5 35. Rhg1+ Kf7 36. Qh5+ Ke7 37. Rxf5 (37. Rg8 {Is impossible due to} Kd6
38. Rxf5 Qd4 {Leads to mate now}) 37... Re1+ 38. Ka2 Qe2 39. Rg7+ Ke6 40. Qxe8+
Kxf5 41. Qc8+ Qe6 42. Qxh8 Re2 43. Kb1 Re1+ {[pgndiagram] With perpetual check}
) (33... gxf5 {Was also good enough} 34. Rhg1+ Kf7 35. Qh5+ Ke7 36. Rxf5 (36.
Rg8 $5 {Might be even better here} Kd6 37. Rxf5 Qd4 {There is no mate}) 36...
Qe6 $1 37. Rxd5 {[pgndiagram] Although here, White can continue playing}) 34.
Rhg1 $1 gxf5 (34... c3 {Once again came into consideration} 35. Bd3 Kg7 36. Qb4
b5 37. bxc3 g5 {And Black is better}) 35. Qh5+ Ke7 36. Rg8 $1 {[pgndiagram]} (
36. Rxf5 {Was also possible} Qe6 37. Rxd5 Re1+ 38. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 39. Rd1 Qe4)
36... Kd6 $2 {With mating ideas connected with c3 unavailable, It was better
to keep the king in touch with the rook on e8} (36... Kd7 {Was safer} 37. Rxf5
Qe6 38. Rxe8 Qxe8 39. Qg4 {Although White is the only player playing for the
win}) 37. Rxf5 Qe6 $2 {[pgndiagram] A final mistake} (37... Re1+ 38. Ka2 Qe2 {
Was better nevertheless} 39. Rxd5+ Kc6 40. Rc5+ Kb6 41. Qxe2 R1xe2 42. Rxc4 {
With only one pawn for the piece , but serious winning chances}) 38. Rxe8 Qxe8
39. Rxf6+ Kc5 40. Qh6 {The f-pawn was more important than the d and c pawns}
Re7 41. Qh2 {[pgndiagram] In practical game it would be extremely hard to play
Black here, even if he wasn't completely lost} (41. Qd2 {Is probably easier
way of winning} Qd8 42. Qb4+ Kd4 43. Rd6 {Is another way of winning} Qf8 44.
Qd2+ Ke4 45. Qxd5+) 41... Qd7 42. Qg1+ d4 43. Qg5+ Qd5 44. Rf5 Qxf5 45. Qxf5+
Kd6 46. Qf6+ {[pgndiagram] A fascinating game, very hard to judge from the
modern viewpoint since it contains many mistakes detected instantly by the
engines. But you can try to imagine how incomprehensive it was for the
contemporaries; I really doubt highly anyone understood what a fierce battle
between two chess gladiators this encounter really was.} 1-0

[Event "Lasker - Schlechter World Championship "]
[Site "Berlin GER"]
[Date "1910.02.08"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Carl Schlechter"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "D94"]
[PlyCount "141"]
[EventDate "1910.??.??"]

{To this day, the conditions surrounding this game aren't clear. According to
some sources, the regulations of the match included a two point clause;
Schlechter needed to win the match by a two point margin.  However, it is not
clear whether such a clause existed. Schlechter's aggressive play was
attributed to the fact that he was quite honorable and he played for the win
in order not to win a match by a "fluke", after Lasker's blunder from a better
position in game 5.  We may never find out the truth, but the players have
provided us with a fantastic game nevertheless.} 1. d4 {This is the first time
that Lasker avoided 1 e4 in the match} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 $5 {At
those time 4..g6 contradicted everything taught about chess. "I did not want
to play for a draw in the last game and I chose a little-known continuation,
leading to interesting complications." - Schlechter} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O (
6... Bg4 {Is a typical idea for this variation, exchanging the light squared
bishop.} 7. Qb3 Bxf3 8. gxf3 Qd7 {With solid position}) 7. Qc2 $6 {Avoiding
Bg4 at all costs, but this costs him a tempo} (7. O-O Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6
{Is a position typical of this variation. White is slightly better, but Black
is extremely solid}) 7... Na6 (7... c5 $1 {Is a typical Grünfeld idea which
was probably too revolutionary for those years.} 8. dxc5 Qa5 9. O-O (9. cxd5
Nxd5 10. Bd2 Nb4 11. Qb1 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Na6 {And Black is already better}) 9...
dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxc5 {With easy equality}) 8. a3 dxc4 (8... c5 $1 {Was once
again more energetic}) 9. Bxc4 b5 $2 {[pgndiagram] But this is too extravagant.
Black is weakening his queenside without any good reason} (9... c5 {Is once
again the best}) (9... Nc7 {Is probably also better than the game move}) 10.
Bd3 {Now Black's queenside construction is silly} b4 $6 {This is also probably
not necessary. You can feel that equal play didn't interest Schlechter} (10...
c5 {Was objectively better, although it loses a pawn}) (10... Bb7 11. b4 {With
a terrible bind} Nc7 12. O-O a5 13. Bd2) 11. Na4 bxa3 12. bxa3 Bb7 $2 {But
after this Black is indeed almost lost} (12... c5 {Was definitely the last
chance} 13. Bxa6 (13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Qxc5 Bb7 {Is surprisingly equal}) 13...
Bxa6 14. Nxc5 Rc8 {With some counterplay} 15. Qa4 Rxc5 16. Qxa6 (16. dxc5 Qd3
17. Qd1 Qxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Ne4 {Is horrible for White}) 16... Ra5 17. Qe2 {With
some chances of holding the game}) 13. Rb1 {[pgndiagram] Now White has
complete control of the board and c5 is never in question} Qc7 14. Ne5 $6 {
However, at this moment Lasker starts playing nervously} (14. O-O {Was simply
good} c5 15. dxc5 {With a clear pawn}) 14... Nh5 $6 (14... c5 $5) 15. g4 $6 {
Lasker explained this move with the fllowing words: "When so much depends on
one game, the players become very excited and their imagination transforms
into recklessness"} (15. O-O {Was once again more normal}) (15. f4 {Is also
more solid}) 15... Bxe5 (15... Nf6 16. f4 {And White has weakened his king,
although he retains an advantage}) (15... c5 16. Rxb7 Qxb7 17. Be4 {Is winning}
) 16. gxh5 $2 {[pgndiagram] Also a mistake, Black's bishop was more important}
(16. dxe5 Ng7 17. O-O {And although White doesn't have as ideal position as he
could have reached a couple of moves ago, he is still markedly better}) 16...
Bg7 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Qc4 {[pgndiagram] Threatening Bxg6} Bc8 $1 (18... c5 {In
my great predeccessors, Kasparov claims that this move is bad, but he misses a
detail} 19. Rg1 e6 $1 (19... Qxh2 20. Rxg6 {As mentioned by Kasparov, is
indeed not the best for Black}) 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21. Qxa6 Qxa6 22. Bxa6 cxd4 {
[pgndiagram] And Black is actually not worse}) 19. Rg1 $2 (19. h4 $1 {
Definitely the best move} Qa5+ {There is nothing better} 20. Bd2 Qd5 21. Qxd5
cxd5 22. h5 {And White has an attack}) (19. Bd2 $5 {This developing move is
also more natural and better than Lasker's choice} Rb8 20. Rc1 Qd6 21. h4 $1)
19... Qa5+ (19... Qxh2 $1 {Was the best move} 20. Rxg6 Nc7 $1 {Also doesn't
lose} (20... Qh1+ $2 {Is only move mentioned by Kasparov and it indeed loses}
21. Kd2 Be6 (21... Nc7 22. Bb2) 22. Rxg7+ Kxg7 23. Qxa6) (20... Be6 $1 21.
Rxg7+ Kxg7 22. Qxa6 Qg1+ 23. Kd2 Qxf2+ 24. Kc3 Rab8 {And Black is not worse})
21. Bb2 Ba6) 20. Bd2 {[pgndiagram] Now White is indeed safer and better} Qd5
21. Rc1 Bb7 22. Qc2 $6 {Very risky} (22. Qxd5 cxd5 {Was more pragmatic}) (22.
h4 {Is also better for White} Qh5 $2 23. Bxg6) 22... Qh5 23. Bxg6 $2 {
Underestimating Black's counterplay} (23. Qb3 $1 Qxh2 24. Rxg6 {Was the best}
Qh1+ 25. Bf1 Rfb8 26. Qc4 Nc7 {And White is better}) 23... Qxh2 24. Rf1 fxg6
25. Qb3+ Rf7 26. Qxb7 Raf8 {[pgndiagram] Black's pieces, apart from the
wayward knight on a6, are suddenly idealy placed} 27. Qb3 (27. f4 {Was
probably better, but here Black can give a perpetual starting with} Qh4+ 28.
Kd1 (28. Ke2 Qh5+ 29. Kd3 Qf5+ 30. e4 {Is losing here} Qh3+ 31. Be3 (31. Ke2
Qg2+ 32. Kd3 Rd8) 31... Bxd4) 28... Qg4+ 29. Kc2 Qf5+ {And White can't avoid it
} 30. Kc3 $2 Bxd4+ 31. exd4 Qh3+ 32. Kc2 Rb8 {[pgndiagram] And suddenly White
is lost}) 27... Kh8 28. f4 g5 $1 (28... Qh4+ $2 {Now leads nowhere, due to} 29.
Ke2 Qh5+ 30. Kd3 Qf5+ 31. e4 Qh3+ 32. Be3 Bxd4 33. Rh1 {[pgndiagram] The point.
King on h8 harms Black}) (28... e5 {Was also interesting} 29. dxe5 Rd8 30. Qc2
Qg3+ 31. Ke2 Qg4+ {And White probably can't escape the checks once again}) 29.
Qd3 gxf4 30. exf4 Qh4+ 31. Ke2 (31. Kd1 Qg4+ 32. Kc2 Qf5 {Leads to
simplifications and a draw}) 31... Qh2+ 32. Rf2 Qh5+ 33. Rf3 Nc7 34. Rxc6 $6 {
[pgndiagram] This pawn grabbing when under fire is usually not to be
recommended} (34. Nc5 {Was more sensible, including the knight into play}) (34.
Rh1 {Winning the queen, was also an interesting possibility} Qxh1 35. Rh3+ Qxh3
36. Qxh3+ Kg8 37. Nc5 {And White is better} Bxd4 38. Qg2+ Rg7 39. Qxc6) 34...
Nb5 $1 35. Rc4 $2 (35. Ke1 {Thraetening Rh3} Qh1+ 36. Qf1 Qxf1+ 37. Rxf1 {Is
safe for White, but he can probably forget about winning}) 35... Rxf4 $2 {
[pgndiagram] The combination is incorrect} (35... Rd8 {Was strong} 36. Ke1 (36.
Be3 {Is met by} e5 $1) 36... Kg8 {Preventing Rh3} 37. d5 Bf6 {And Black has
the initiative}) (35... Qg4 {Thraetening Rxf4, was also decisive} 36. Nc3 Rxf4
37. Bxf4 Rxf4 38. Nxb5 Qg2+ 39. Ke1 Rxf3 40. Rc8+ Bf8 41. Qe2 Qg1+ {And Black
is winning}) 36. Bxf4 Rxf4 37. Rc8+ Bf8 38. Kf2 Qh2+ {[pgndiagram]} (38... Qh4+
{Schlechter admitted that he missed that this check can be met by} 39. Kg2 Qg4+
40. Rg3 $1 Qxc8 41. Qg6 {[pgndiagram] And suddenly White checkmates}) 39. Ke1
Qh1+ $2 {Allowing the White king to escape from checks} (39... Qh4+ {Was
correct} 40. Kd2 Qh2+ 41. Ke1 (41. Kc1 Qh1+ 42. Kb2 Rxf3 43. Qxb5 Rf2+ {Is
better for Black}) 41... Qh4+ {With perpetual}) 40. Rf1 Qh4+ 41. Kd2 Rxf1 42.
Qxf1 Qxd4+ 43. Qd3 {[pgndiagram] Now Lasker has a clear advantage} Qf2+ 44. Kd1
Nd6 45. Rc5 (45. Rd8 {Keeping the bishop pinned, was probably more accurate})
45... Bh6 (45... Bg7 $5) 46. Rd5 Kg8 47. Nc5 Qg1+ 48. Kc2 Qf2+ 49. Kb3 Bg7 50.
Ne6 {[pgndiagram]} (50. Rg5 {Is probably the most accurate way of converting}
Qb2+ 51. Ka4 Qb6 52. Qd5+ Kh7 53. Nd7 {Although it is scary to play like this
when you are human}) 50... Qb2+ $2 (50... Qb6+ $1 {Was essential, driving the
king back to the open kingside}) 51. Ka4 {The king is surprisingly safe here}
Kf7 52. Nxg7 Qxg7 53. Qb3 Ke8 54. Qb8+ Kf7 55. Qxa7 {[pgndiagram] White
captures the a-pawn and now the rest is indeed a matter of the technique and
precision} Qg4+ 56. Qd4 Qd7+ 57. Kb3 Qb7+ 58. Ka2 Qc6 59. Qd3 Ke6 60. Rg5 Kd7
61. Re5 Qg2+ 62. Re2 Qg4 63. Rd2 Qa4 64. Qf5+ Kc7 65. Qc2+ Qxc2+ 66. Rxc2+ Kb7
67. Re2 Nc8 68. Kb3 Kc6 69. Rc2+ Kb7 70. Kb4 Na7 71. Kc5 {[pgndiagram] An end
of a titanic struggle and the most difficult match for Lasker. One of the most
beautiful games in the history, unique because of the fact that both sides
player for the win with extremely high stakes. Naturally, the fight contained
many mistakes, but the complications and the irrationality of the position
easily excuse these mistakes} 1-0

[Event "8, New York"]
[Site "New York, NY USA"]
[Date "1893.10.10"]
[Round "8"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Harry Nelson Pillsbury"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C60"]
[PlyCount "113"]
[EventDate "1893.??.??"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 $5 {A rare move, but a playable one nevertheless}
4. Bxc6 {As already mentioned, Lasker enjoyed exchanging his bishop for the
knight on c6. With this move White transposes to some sort of anti-Berlin lines
} (4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 Nge7 {Is another variation with a lot of theory}) 4... dxc6
5. d3 Bg7 6. Nc3 Be6 7. Be3 {[pgndiagram] The position is somewhat resembling
a Rossolimo line of the Sicilian. White's plan might include the advance in
the centre (d4) or play on the kingside. Black's plan will depend on the place
of the White king} Qe7 $6 {I don't like this move, it was more flexible to
develop a knight on this square} (7... Ne7 8. O-O O-O 9. b3 Qd6) 8. Qe2 c5 $6 {
Black also weakens his queenside and indeed transposes to the unfavorable
Sicilian structure. The subsequent games in the 20th century would show that
these positions are quite dangerous for Black.   Another drawback of this move
is that due to the queen on e7, Black's knight is far away from the d4 square}
(8... Nf6 9. O-O Ng4 10. Bd2 f6 {Was more natural}) 9. h3 $6 {Also probably
not necessary move} (9. O-O f6 {And now Whit can pursue a typical a3-b4 plan}
10. a3 Nh6 11. b4 cxb4 12. axb4 Nf7 (12... Qxb4 {Is a bad idea} 13. Qd2 Nf7 14.
Rfb1 Qd6 15. Rxb7) 13. Nd5 $1 {And White is markedly better}) 9... c6 $6 {It
was better to refrain from this move and play only b6} (9... b6 10. O-O f6) 10.
a4 b6 11. Nd2 (11. a5 $1 {Opening the a-file or weakening c5 was good} b5 12.
O-O f6 13. Nd2 Nh6 14. f4 $1 {White has the initiative}) 11... Nf6 12. f3 $6 {
I don't like Lasker's play at this particular moment} (12. a5 O-O {Is not that
good now}) (12. O-O {Was more natural}) 12... Nd7 13. O-O g5 $2 {Preventing f4,
but such an ugly move is weakening Black's kingside} (13... O-O 14. f4 {If
this was White's plan, why not play it without 12 f3?!} exf4 15. Rxf4 {And
Black has a good positiion}) 14. Nd1 h6 15. c3 $6 {[pgndiagram] The type of
the position was too advanced for 1893! This move has no purpose, because d4
is very hard to achieve, and now d3 is weakened} (15. Bf2 O-O 16. Ne3 Nf6 17.
g4 $1 {Installing one knight on f5, other on c4 and continuing from there, was
better}) 15... O-O 16. Nf2 Rfd8 17. Rfd1 Nf8 {The knight is heading for f4. 
The position is balanced} 18. a5 {Somewhat too late} Ng6 19. axb6 axb6 20. Qf1
{Not allowing the knight to jump on f4 with tempo. Again we see Lasker ending
up in an unfavorable position and continuing to fight with all his might} Nf4
21. Rxa8 Rxa8 22. Ra1 Qb7 23. Qb1 Ra6 24. Kh2 Bf8 25. g3 $2 {[pgndiagram] A
further weakening, I guess also not mandatory} (25. Nf1 Kg7 26. Ng3 {Heading
for f5 at once, was probably better}) 25... Ng6 26. Kg2 Qa7 27. Rxa6 Qxa6 28.
Nf1 {[pgndiagram] Black's two bishops, his control of space and the backward
pawn on d3 give him the advantage} Bd6 29. c4 $6 {Another "ugly" move} (29. Bd2
{Going with the knight to e3, without other weakenings, was better}) 29... f6
30. Bd2 h5 31. Ne3 h4 $2 (31... b5 {Not handing the g4 square to White's
knights was wiser} 32. Nf5 Bf8 33. b3 Qa7 {And Black retains all pluses of his
position}) 32. Nfg4 $1 Bxg4 $6 {[pgndiagram] Not a necessary exchange, giving
up his good bishop} (32... Be7 33. Nf5 Kf8 {Was probably wiser}) 33. hxg4 hxg3
34. Nf5 {[pgndiagram] Now this knight is a champion and it is very hard to
challenge it} Bf8 (34... Nh4+ 35. Nxh4 gxh4 36. Kh3 {And White can simply
collect both pawns with his king}) 35. Kxg3 Qa7 {The objective outcome of the
game should be a draw, but wonders are awaiting us} 36. Qf1 Qd7 37. Qb1 Ne7 (
37... Qa7 {Black should have repeated the position}) 38. Be3 Nxf5+ $6 {This
exchange gives White the idea to sacrifice on g5. It doesn't spoil the game
yet, but it could have been avoided} (38... Ng6 {Continuing to wait was better.
I don't see a convincing way for White to strengthen his position}) 39. exf5
Qh7 40. Kg2 Qd7 41. Kf2 Qa7 (41... Qh7 $5 {Nipping the Bxg5 ideas in the bud,
was probably sounder} 42. Ke2 Bd6 43. Qf1 Qa7 44. Qh1 Qh7 $11) 42. Ke2 Bd6 43.
Bd2 Qa4 44. Qh1 Qa7 45. Be3 Kg7 $2 {[pgndiagram] A careless move, offering
Lasker with the opportunity he doesn't miss} (45... Qh7 {Was good enough}) (
45... e4 $1 {Is also a nice pawn sacrifice} 46. fxe4 Qa2 47. Qh6 Qxb2+ 48. Kf3
Qe5 {And with f6 pawn defended, Black is in no danger of losing}) 46. Bxg5 $3 {
[pgndiagram] A fantastic move and the reason why this not particularly
attractive game was selected for this list. Lasker finds a tactical shot out
of nowhere. It does not win the game by itself, but it presents Black with
difficult problems} fxg5 47. f6+ $1 Kg8 (47... Kxf6 {Would lose a queen to} 48.
Qh6+ Ke7 49. Qh7+) 48. Qh6 Qf7 $2 {Probably the losing move, but it wasn't
easy to find the right response here} (48... Qd7 {The computer indicates
defending the fragile Black queen is the most important thing in this position}
49. Qxg5+ Kf7 50. Qg7+ Ke8 51. Qg6+ Kd8 52. Qg8+ (52. Qe4 Kc7 53. g5 Qh3 {And
Black has enough counterplay to save the game}) 52... Qe8 53. Qh7 e4 $1 54.
fxe4 Qe5) (48... Bb8 $1 {Is another paradoxical computer move, defending the
queen} 49. Qxg5+ Kf7 50. Qg7+ Ke6 51. Qg6 Qa4 {And Black will manage to give
pereptual}) 49. Qxg5+ Kh8 50. Qf5 {Now Black has a difficult position. White's
plan is simple. Just push the pawns} Bf8 51. g5 $2 {Probably too hasty,
throwing the win away. Black's queen should have been denied of the h5 square}
(51. Ke3) 51... Qh5 52. Qxe5 b5 $2 (52... Kg8 {Would probably save the game}
53. Ke3 Qh4 54. Qe6+ Kh8 55. Qf5 Qe1+ 56. Kf4 Bd6+ 57. Kg4 Qg1+ 58. Kh5 Qh1+
59. Kg4 {With perpetual}) 53. Ke3 Qh4 $4 {Losing instantly} (53... Kg8 {Was
the only move once again}) (53... Qh1 {Is losing to the same idea} 54. f7+ Kh7
55. Qf5+ Kh8 56. Qf6+ Kh7 57. g6+ Kh6 58. g7+) 54. f7+ {[pgndiagram] And just
like that, the game is over. Black collapsed in 9 moves} Kh7 55. Qf5+ {Here
Pilssbury resigned. The finish could have been} Kh8 56. Qf6+ Kh7 57. g6+ {And
the queen on h4 is lost} 1-0

[Event "Lasker - Schlechter World Championship "]
[Site "Berlin GER"]
[Date "1910.02.08"]
[Round "10"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Carl Schlechter"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "D94"]
[PlyCount "141"]
[EventDate "1910.??.??"]

{To this day, the conditions surrounding this game aren't clear. According to
some sources, the regulations of the match included a two point clause;
Schlechter needed to win the match by a two point margin.  However, it is not
clear whether such a clause existed. Schlechter's aggressive play was
attributed to the fact that he was quite honorable and he played for the win
in order not to win a match by a "fluke", after Lasker's blunder from a better
position in game 5.  We may never find out the truth, but the players have
provided us with a fantastic game nevertheless.} 1. d4 {This is the first time
that Lasker avoided 1 e4 in the match} d5 2. c4 c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 $5 {At
those time 4..g6 contradicted everything taught about chess. "I did not want
to play for a draw in the last game and I chose a little-known continuation,
leading to interesting complications." - Schlechter} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O (
6... Bg4 {Is a typical idea for this variation, exchanging the light squared
bishop.} 7. Qb3 Bxf3 8. gxf3 Qd7 {With solid position}) 7. Qc2 $6 {Avoiding
Bg4 at all costs, but this costs him a tempo} (7. O-O Bg4 8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 e6
{Is a position typical of this variation. White is slightly better, but Black
is extremely solid}) 7... Na6 (7... c5 $1 {Is a typical Grünfeld idea which
was probably too revolutionary for those years.} 8. dxc5 Qa5 9. O-O (9. cxd5
Nxd5 10. Bd2 Nb4 11. Qb1 Nxd3+ 12. Qxd3 Na6 {And Black is already better}) 9...
dxc4 10. Bxc4 Qxc5 {With easy equality}) 8. a3 dxc4 (8... c5 $1 {Was once
again more energetic}) 9. Bxc4 b5 $2 {[pgndiagram] But this is too extravagant.
Black is weakening his queenside without any good reason} (9... c5 {Is once
again the best}) (9... Nc7 {Is probably also better than the game move}) 10.
Bd3 {Now Black's queenside construction is silly} b4 $6 {This is also probably
not necessary. You can feel that equal play didn't interest Schlechter} (10...
c5 {Was objectively better, although it loses a pawn}) (10... Bb7 11. b4 {With
a terrible bind} Nc7 12. O-O a5 13. Bd2) 11. Na4 bxa3 12. bxa3 Bb7 $2 {But
after this Black is indeed almost lost} (12... c5 {Was definitely the last
chance} 13. Bxa6 (13. Nxc5 Nxc5 14. Qxc5 Bb7 {Is surprisingly equal}) 13...
Bxa6 14. Nxc5 Rc8 {With some counterplay} 15. Qa4 Rxc5 16. Qxa6 (16. dxc5 Qd3
17. Qd1 Qxd1+ 18. Kxd1 Ne4 {Is horrible for White}) 16... Ra5 17. Qe2 {With
some chances of holding the game}) 13. Rb1 {[pgndiagram] Now White has
complete control of the board and c5 is never in question} Qc7 14. Ne5 $6 {
However, at this moment Lasker starts playing nervously} (14. O-O {Was simply
good} c5 15. dxc5 {With a clear pawn}) 14... Nh5 $6 (14... c5 $5) 15. g4 $6 {
Lasker explained this move with the fllowing words: "When so much depends on
one game, the players become very excited and their imagination transforms
into recklessness"} (15. O-O {Was once again more normal}) (15. f4 {Is also
more solid}) 15... Bxe5 (15... Nf6 16. f4 {And White has weakened his king,
although he retains an advantage}) (15... c5 16. Rxb7 Qxb7 17. Be4 {Is winning}
) 16. gxh5 $2 {[pgndiagram] Also a mistake, Black's bishop was more important}
(16. dxe5 Ng7 17. O-O {And although White doesn't have as ideal position as he
could have reached a couple of moves ago, he is still markedly better}) 16...
Bg7 17. hxg6 hxg6 18. Qc4 {[pgndiagram] Threatening Bxg6} Bc8 $1 (18... c5 {In
my great predeccessors, Kasparov claims that this move is bad, but he misses a
detail} 19. Rg1 e6 $1 (19... Qxh2 20. Rxg6 {As mentioned by Kasparov, is
indeed not the best for Black}) 20. Rxb7 Qxb7 21. Qxa6 Qxa6 22. Bxa6 cxd4 {
[pgndiagram] And Black is actually not worse}) 19. Rg1 $2 (19. h4 $1 {
Definitely the best move} Qa5+ {There is nothing better} 20. Bd2 Qd5 21. Qxd5
cxd5 22. h5 {And White has an attack}) (19. Bd2 $5 {This developing move is
also more natural and better than Lasker's choice} Rb8 20. Rc1 Qd6 21. h4 $1)
19... Qa5+ (19... Qxh2 $1 {Was the best move} 20. Rxg6 Nc7 $1 {Also doesn't
lose} (20... Qh1+ $2 {Is only move mentioned by Kasparov and it indeed loses}
21. Kd2 Be6 (21... Nc7 22. Bb2) 22. Rxg7+ Kxg7 23. Qxa6) (20... Be6 $1 21.
Rxg7+ Kxg7 22. Qxa6 Qg1+ 23. Kd2 Qxf2+ 24. Kc3 Rab8 {And Black is not worse})
21. Bb2 Ba6) 20. Bd2 {[pgndiagram] Now White is indeed safer and better} Qd5
21. Rc1 Bb7 22. Qc2 $6 {Very risky} (22. Qxd5 cxd5 {Was more pragmatic}) (22.
h4 {Is also better for White} Qh5 $2 23. Bxg6) 22... Qh5 23. Bxg6 $2 {
Underestimating Black's counterplay} (23. Qb3 $1 Qxh2 24. Rxg6 {Was the best}
Qh1+ 25. Bf1 Rfb8 26. Qc4 Nc7 {And White is better}) 23... Qxh2 24. Rf1 fxg6
25. Qb3+ Rf7 26. Qxb7 Raf8 {[pgndiagram] Black's pieces, apart from the
wayward knight on a6, are suddenly idealy placed} 27. Qb3 (27. f4 {Was
probably better, but here Black can give a perpetual starting with} Qh4+ 28.
Kd1 (28. Ke2 Qh5+ 29. Kd3 Qf5+ 30. e4 {Is losing here} Qh3+ 31. Be3 (31. Ke2
Qg2+ 32. Kd3 Rd8) 31... Bxd4) 28... Qg4+ 29. Kc2 Qf5+ {And White can't avoid it
} 30. Kc3 $2 Bxd4+ 31. exd4 Qh3+ 32. Kc2 Rb8 {[pgndiagram] And suddenly White
is lost}) 27... Kh8 28. f4 g5 $1 (28... Qh4+ $2 {Now leads nowhere, due to} 29.
Ke2 Qh5+ 30. Kd3 Qf5+ 31. e4 Qh3+ 32. Be3 Bxd4 33. Rh1 {[pgndiagram] The point.
King on h8 harms Black}) (28... e5 {Was also interesting} 29. dxe5 Rd8 30. Qc2
Qg3+ 31. Ke2 Qg4+ {And White probably can't escape the checks once again}) 29.
Qd3 gxf4 30. exf4 Qh4+ 31. Ke2 (31. Kd1 Qg4+ 32. Kc2 Qf5 {Leads to
simplifications and a draw}) 31... Qh2+ 32. Rf2 Qh5+ 33. Rf3 Nc7 34. Rxc6 $6 {
[pgndiagram] This pawn grabbing when under fire is usually not to be
recommended} (34. Nc5 {Was more sensible, including the knight into play}) (34.
Rh1 {Winning the queen, was also an interesting possibility} Qxh1 35. Rh3+ Qxh3
36. Qxh3+ Kg8 37. Nc5 {And White is better} Bxd4 38. Qg2+ Rg7 39. Qxc6) 34...
Nb5 $1 35. Rc4 $2 (35. Ke1 {Thraetening Rh3} Qh1+ 36. Qf1 Qxf1+ 37. Rxf1 {Is
safe for White, but he can probably forget about winning}) 35... Rxf4 $2 {
[pgndiagram] The combination is incorrect} (35... Rd8 {Was strong} 36. Ke1 (36.
Be3 {Is met by} e5 $1) 36... Kg8 {Preventing Rh3} 37. d5 Bf6 {And Black has
the initiative}) (35... Qg4 {Thraetening Rxf4, was also decisive} 36. Nc3 Rxf4
37. Bxf4 Rxf4 38. Nxb5 Qg2+ 39. Ke1 Rxf3 40. Rc8+ Bf8 41. Qe2 Qg1+ {And Black
is winning}) 36. Bxf4 Rxf4 37. Rc8+ Bf8 38. Kf2 Qh2+ {[pgndiagram]} (38... Qh4+
{Schlechter admitted that he missed that this check can be met by} 39. Kg2 Qg4+
40. Rg3 $1 Qxc8 41. Qg6 {[pgndiagram] And suddenly White checkmates}) 39. Ke1
Qh1+ $2 {Allowing the White king to escape from checks} (39... Qh4+ {Was
correct} 40. Kd2 Qh2+ 41. Ke1 (41. Kc1 Qh1+ 42. Kb2 Rxf3 43. Qxb5 Rf2+ {Is
better for Black}) 41... Qh4+ {With perpetual}) 40. Rf1 Qh4+ 41. Kd2 Rxf1 42.
Qxf1 Qxd4+ 43. Qd3 {[pgndiagram] Now Lasker has a clear advantage} Qf2+ 44. Kd1
Nd6 45. Rc5 (45. Rd8 {Keeping the bishop pinned, was probably more accurate})
45... Bh6 (45... Bg7 $5) 46. Rd5 Kg8 47. Nc5 Qg1+ 48. Kc2 Qf2+ 49. Kb3 Bg7 50.
Ne6 {[pgndiagram]} (50. Rg5 {Is probably the most accurate way of converting}
Qb2+ 51. Ka4 Qb6 52. Qd5+ Kh7 53. Nd7 {Although it is scary to play like this
when you are human}) 50... Qb2+ $2 (50... Qb6+ $1 {Was essential, driving the
king back to the open kingside}) 51. Ka4 {The king is surprisingly safe here}
Kf7 52. Nxg7 Qxg7 53. Qb3 Ke8 54. Qb8+ Kf7 55. Qxa7 {[pgndiagram] White
captures the a-pawn and now the rest is indeed a matter of the technique and
precision} Qg4+ 56. Qd4 Qd7+ 57. Kb3 Qb7+ 58. Ka2 Qc6 59. Qd3 Ke6 60. Rg5 Kd7
61. Re5 Qg2+ 62. Re2 Qg4 63. Rd2 Qa4 64. Qf5+ Kc7 65. Qc2+ Qxc2+ 66. Rxc2+ Kb7
67. Re2 Nc8 68. Kb3 Kc6 69. Rc2+ Kb7 70. Kb4 Na7 71. Kc5 {[pgndiagram] An end
of a titanic struggle and the most difficult match for Lasker. One of the most
beautiful games in the history, unique because of the fact that both sides
player for the win with extremely high stakes. Naturally, the fight contained
many mistakes, but the complications and the irrationality of the position
easily excuse these mistakes} 1-0

[Event "Lasker - Steinitz World Championship"]
[Site "Philadelphia, PA USA"]
[Date "1894.04.14"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C62"]
[PlyCount "97"]
[EventDate "1894.??.??"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 {Steinitz remains faithful to his favourite
opening} 4. Nc3 {A very rare move} a6 5. Bc4 $6 {Objectively not the best
continuation} (5. Bxc6+ {Has most sense in combination with Nc3}) 5... Be6 $6 {
This move also comes slightly too early.} (5... Be7 {(Preventing Ng6 for the
moment)} 6. O-O Nf6 {Was more natural}) 6. Bxe6 fxe6 7. d4 {[pgndiagram] Now
White's position is quite good} exd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 9. Qxd4 Ne7 (9... Nf6 {
Avoding ideas connected to e5} 10. O-O Be7 11. e5 {White has the advantage})
10. Bg5 {Not necessary} (10. Be3 {Is more natural}) 10... Nc6 11. Bxd8 $2 {A
faulty idea} (11. Qd2 Be7 12. h4 {And White retains a slight pull}) 11... Nxd4
12. O-O-O Nb5 $2 {[pgndiagram] Steinitz takes his opponent at his word} (12...
Rxd8 13. Rxd4 Be7 {Is just a better endgame for Black}) 13. Nxb5 axb5 (13...
Rxd8 14. Nd4 {And White's knight is better on d4 than it was on c3.}) 14. Bxc7
Rxa2 15. Bb6 {An equal endgame has arisen} (15. Kb1 Ra6 {Would trap the bishop}
) 15... Be7 16. c3 $6 {Not sure if this move was required} (16. Kb1 Ra6 17. Bd4
Kf7 18. f4 {And White has a slight pull}) 16... Kf7 $6 (16... b4 $1 {Was very
interesting} 17. cxb4 Bf6 (17... Ra4 {Might be even better} 18. Ba5 O-O 19. f3
b6) 18. Rhe1 Ke7 (18... Rxb2 $4 19. e5) 19. Bd4 Ra4 20. Bxf6+ gxf6 21. Re3 Rxb4
{With equality}) 17. Kc2 {[pgndiagram] Now White activates his king and can
start playing for the win due to his better pawn structure} Rha8 18. Kb3 R2a4
19. f3 R8a6 20. Bd4 g6 21. Rd3 Ke8 22. Rhd1 e5 $2 {[pgndiagram] A clear
concesion, limiting the dark squared bishop further and creating a backward d6
pawn} (22... Rc6 {It was better to wait} 23. g4 Bf8 24. h4 Rca6 25. Bf2) 23.
Be3 Kd7 24. Bc5 $1 {Another great move, bringing the bishop to a3 and
hindering Black's play} Ra1 {Seeking counterplay} (24... Kc7 25. Ba3 Rc6 26.
Rd5 Rb6 27. Bb4 {And Black is completely paralyzed}) 25. R1d2 $1 {[pgndiagram]
Fantastic judgement by Lasker. He realizes that his attacking chances are
higher with four rooks on the board} (25. Rxa1 Rxa1 26. Ba3 Rh1 {Is suddenly
completely equal} 27. h3 Re1 28. Rd2 Kc6) 25... Ke6 (25... Rh1 {Would lose the
b5 pawn after} 26. h3 Re1 27. Rd5 Kc7 28. Bb4 Rf1 (28... Rb6 $4 29. Ba5) 29.
Rxb5) 26. Ba3 g5 $1 {Trying to create some counterplay on the kingside is the
correct decision} 27. Rd5 Rb6 28. Kb4 g4 $1 {[pgndiagram]} 29. Ka5 $1 {Strong
play from Lasker. His king is a monster} (29. fxg4 Re1 {Would create a lot of
counterplay for Black} 30. Ka5 Rc6 31. Kxb5 Rxe4) 29... Ra6+ (29... Bd8 30.
Rxb5) 30. Kxb5 h5 31. Rd1 $1 {[pgndiagram] Amazing skill in the endgame.
Having rejected the exchange just a couple of moves ago, Lasker, having
accomplished certain goals (b5) realizes it is time to exchange Black's active
rook and go into the technical phase of the game} Rxd1 32. Rxd1 gxf3 33. gxf3 {
White is a clear pawn up, but there is still some work to be done} Ra8 $2 {It
was wiser not to allow the White king to approach the be pawn} (33... Kd7 {It
is hard to believe that Black can save himself with passive moves, though} 34.
Rg1 Ra8 35. Rg7 (35. Kb6 {Is now not that powerful} Rf8 36. Rf1 Kc8) 35... Rf8
36. c4 {And White is close to winning, c5 is coming next}) 34. Kb6 $1 {
[pgndiagram] Now the pawn on b7 falls and the game is virtually over} Rg8 35.
Kxb7 Rg2 36. h4 Rh2 37. Kc6 Bxh4 38. Rxd6+ Kf7 39. Kd5 (39. c4 {Was even faster
}) 39... Bf6 40. Rd7+ Kg6 41. Ke6 h4 42. Rd1 h3 43. Rg1+ Rg2 44. Rxg2+ hxg2 45.
Bc5 Bd8 46. b4 Kg5 47. Kd7 Bf6 48. b5 Kf4 49. b6 {[pgndiagram] An impressive
technical achievement from Lasker, who outplayed his strong opponent in
Carlsen style, from a completely equal position} 1-0

[Event "Paris"]
[Site "Paris FRA"]
[Date "1900.06.14"]
[Round "15"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Harry Nelson Pillsbury"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "A83"]
[PlyCount "169"]
[EventDate "1900.??.??"]

1. d4 f5 2. e4 $1 {The so called Staunton's gambit, a sharp but not fully
correct way of meeting the Dutch defence} fxe4 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 c6 (4... g6 {
I like the fiancheto of the bishop as Black in this variation} 5. Bxf6 exf6 6.
Nxe4 d5 7. Nc3 Bh6 {And Black has a comfortable game}) 5. f3 exf3 $6 {
Accepting the pawn on f3 is objectively dangerous, especially when Bg5 and c6
have already been played} 6. Nxf3 e6 $6 {I don't like this move as well} (6...
d6 7. Bc4 Qb6 8. Qd2 Bg4 {Developing some pieces, was better for Black}) 7. Bd3
{[pgndiagram] Now White has fluid development and a strong attack in exchange
for just one pawn} Be7 (7... d6 {Preventing the jump to e5, was necessary.}) 8.
Ne5 $1 {White is already winning} O-O 9. Bxf6 $1 Rxf6 {The best capture} (9...
Bxf6 10. Qh5 g6 11. Nxg6 {Is curtains}) (9... gxf6 10. Qg4+ Kh8 11. Ng6+ hxg6
12. Bxg6 {Is also dead lost}) 10. Qh5 g6 11. Nxg6 {[pgndiagram] Black should
be completely busted here} Qe8 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 13. O-O-O (13. Ne4 {Including
the knight into attack, was stronger}) 13... d5 {Now the e4 square is taken
from the knight, but Black's bishop resembles a pawn} 14. Rde1 $2 {Not the
strongest continuation of attack} (14. Rhf1 {If White exchanges a defensive
piece for his attacking one, it is to his advantage, because he can easily
bring his reserves} Nd7 (14... Rxf1 15. Rxf1 {Is of course horrible for Black}
Nd7 16. Bxh7+ Qxh7 17. Qe8+ Kg7 18. Rf7+) 15. Rf3 Rxf3 16. gxf3 Nf6 17. Rg1+
Kh8 18. Qh4 Bd7 19. Bxh7 {[pgndiagram] And White wins}) 14... Nd7 15. Re3 Rf7
16. Rg3+ Kh8 17. Bg6 $2 {[pgndiagram] With this move Lasker releases major
part of his advantage} (17. Rf1 {Once again going for the same principle of
exchanging defensive pieces, was decisive} Rxf1+ 18. Bxf1 Nf6 19. Qe5 Bd7 20.
Rf3 Rf8 21. Bd3 {And Black is busted} Kg8 22. Rg3+ Kh8 23. Bxh7) 17... Rg7 18.
Rf1 Nf6 19. Qh4 Ng8 $1 {Black has managed to defend, for now} 20. Qxe7 Rxe7 21.
Bd3 Bd7 22. Nb1 $3 {[pgndiagram] To my mind a fantastic move. When you are not
certain what to do, then improve your worst piece. The knight is heading to f3,
clamping down on the e5 square} Rae8 23. Nd2 e5 {Black has to play this before
Nf3} (23... Nh6 24. Nf3 {Is just terrible for Black}) 24. dxe5 Rxe5 25. Nf3 Re3
26. Ng5 $1 {Spoling his pawn structure, but activating the knight.} Rxg3 27.
hxg3 h6 28. Nf7+ Kg7 29. Nd6 {White has made 5 moves out of his last seven
with the knight. The result? He won a pawn on b7} Re7 30. Nxb7 Nf6 31. Nc5 Bg4
32. Rf4 {[pgndiagram] Lasker is now a clear pawn up and his pieces are still
active} Bc8 33. Ra4 Ng4 34. Ba6 (34. Kd2 {activating the king, would have
allowed less counterplay} Ne5 (34... Ne3 35. Nb3 Nxg2 36. Nd4 {And wins}) 35.
Be2 Kg6 36. Nb3 {And White remains in control}) 34... Bf5 35. Rf4 Ne3 36. c3 {
[pgndiagram] Now things have improved somewhat for Black, his pieces are well
placed} Kg6 37. Rf2 $2 (37. Bd3 {Exchanging the dangerous bishop, was good}
Bxd3 38. Nxd3 Nxg2 39. Rf8 {And White is better}) 37... Be4 $2 {Missing his
chance} (37... Nc4 $1 {This counterintuitive move would have boxed the White
king and completely equalized} 38. Bxc4 dxc4 39. Kd2 Re5 40. b4 cxb3 41. Nxb3 {
And the endgame is equal; White's doubled pawns on the g-file are suddenly
meaningless}) 38. b3 {[pgndiagram] Now the knight can never go to c4} Bxg2 39.
Bd3+ (39. Bb7 {Winning the pawn, was better} Rf7 40. Rxf7 Kxf7 41. Bxc6 Nf1 42.
g4 Ne3 43. Nd3 Nxg4 44. Nf4 {And White retains some chances of success}) 39...
Kg5 $2 (39... Be4 40. Rf8 Bxd3 41. Nxd3 Kg5 {Is equal}) 40. Rf8 Kg4 41. Rg8+ (
41. Rf6 {Was correct, attacking Black's weak pawns}) 41... Kf3 {now the king
is extremely active} 42. Rg6 Ng4 43. Bf5 h5 44. Rg5 Re1+ 45. Kb2 Rh1 $2 {Too
materialistic} (45... Re2+ {Avoiding the pin on the knight was better} 46. Ka3
Kxg3 47. Rxh5 Nf6 48. Rh6 Ne4 {Creating a passed pawn on the d-file, was good
enough for equality}) 46. Bg6 Kxg3 47. Bxh5 Bh3 48. Bxg4 Bxg4 49. Rg6 {
[pgndiagram] Suddenly, all Black's pieces are far away from home} Rh2+ 50. Ka3
Rc2 $2 {Missing a tactical nuance, allowing White to win c6 and defend his own
c3 soldier} (50... Kf4 {Would have allowed Black to go for the more important
pawn - the a pawn.} 51. Rxc6 Bf5 52. Ra6 Bb1 53. Kb4 Rxa2 54. Na4 {And White
will win the a7 pawn, but it is hard to judge whether the resulting endgame is
a draw or not}) 51. Nd3 Kh4 52. Ne5 Bf5 53. Rxc6 {[pgndiagram] Now Black
doesn't have counterplay (Bb1 is impossible) and White is winning} Kg3 54. Rc5
Rd2 55. Nc6 (55. Nc4 $1) 55... Kf4 56. Nb4 d4 57. cxd4 Rxd4 58. Ra5 Rd7 59. Nc6
Be4 60. Nxa7 {[pgndiagram] The rest doesn't require any commentary} Rd2 61. Nb5
Rd5 62. Kb4 Bd3 63. Nc7 Rxa5 64. Kxa5 Ke5 65. Kb4 Kd6 66. Nb5+ Kc6 67. a4 Kb6
68. Na3 Be2 69. Nc4+ Ka6 70. Kc3 Bd1 71. Nb2 Bh5 72. b4 Be8 73. Kb3 Bc6 74. Kc4
Bd7 75. Kc5 Bg4 76. Nc4 Bd1 77. b5+ Ka7 78. a5 Bf3 79. Ne5 Bg2 80. Nc6+ Ka8 81.
Kb6 Bh3 82. Nb4 Bg2 83. Na6 Bf3 84. Nc7+ Kb8 85. a6 {[pgndiagram] A fine win
against his former competitor, although it has to be admitted that Pillsbury
was merely a shadow of his former self at this moment .} 1-0

[Event "Hastings"]
[Site "Hastings ENG"]
[Date "1895.08.16"]
[Round "9"]
[White "Emanuel Lasker"]
[Black "Wilhelm Steinitz"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C75"]
[PlyCount "79"]
[EventDate "1895.08.05"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 {No exchange this time} d6 {A familiar
variation} 5. O-O Nge7 6. c3 Bd7 7. d4 Ng6 8. Re1 Be7 9. Nbd2 (9. d5 Nb8 10.
Bc2 $5) 9... O-O 10. Nf1 Qe8 $6 {This is highly artificial} (10... exd4 11.
cxd4 b5 12. Bb3 Bf6 {Was interesting}) 11. Bc2 $1 {[pgndiagram] A good move,
emphasizing the lack of space that Black pieces don't enjoy. Avoiding
exchanges while having more space is a good rule of thumb one should follow} (
11. d5 {Is now inferior} Nd4 {Revealing the point behind Qe8}) 11... Kh8 12.
Ng3 (12. Ne3 {Preventing Bg4 and eyeing f5, was probably even better}) 12...
Bg4 (12... Nh4 {Comes to mind} 13. d5 Nb8 14. Nxh4 Bxh4 15. Bd2 a5) 13. d5 Nb8
14. h3 Bc8 $6 (14... Bxf3 {Was comparatively better} 15. Qxf3 Nd7 {With
inferior position}) 15. Nf5 $1 {[pgndiagram] Now White gets a very strong
attack} Bd8 (15... Bxf5 $2 {Is a bad decision} 16. exf5 Nh4 17. Ng5 {And White
is winning the wayward knight}) 16. g4 $5 {The centre is blocked and there is
no counterplay on the other side of the board. Therefore White is correct to
start pushing the pawns on the kingside, even if his own king is residing
there.} Ne7 17. Ng3 (17. Be3 {Was also possible, since Black doesn't really
want to take on f5}) 17... Ng8 18. Kg2 Nd7 19. Be3 Nb6 $6 {It was probably
wiser to keep this knight closer to the kingside} (19... Ne7) 20. b3 Bd7 21. c4
Nc8 22. Qd2 Nce7 23. c5 $1 {[pgndiagram] Now Lasker opens up another front and
can choose on which wing he wants to play. Since he has more space, it is
easier for him to move his pieces from one side of the board to another.} g6 $2
{The losing move. Black willingly weakens his kingside for no good reason} (
23... b6 24. b4 a5 {Playing on the queenside, was better}) 24. Qc3 f5 $2 {This
faulty plan by Black is met with a thunderous response} 25. Nxe5 $3 {
[pgndiagram] A great sacrifice} dxe5 26. Qxe5+ $2 {Unfortunately, Lasker
doesn't crown his play with a brilliant stroke} (26. g5 $3 {Was a fantastic
way to win the game} Nc8 (26... Nc6 27. f4 $1) 27. exf5 gxf5 28. Bd2 {And
Black is busted}) 26... Nf6 27. Bd4 fxg4 28. hxg4 Bxg4 (28... Kg8 {Was a
better defence} 29. g5 Nexd5 30. exd5 Qxe5 31. Rxe5 Ng4 32. Re2 Bxg5 {And
suddenly Black has a perfectly playable position}) 29. Qg5 Qd7 30. Bxf6+ Kg8
31. Bd1 Bh3+ 32. Kg1 Nxd5 $2 {[pgndiagram] And this is a final mistake in a
difficult position} (32... h6 33. Qh4 Nxd5 34. Bxd8 Qf7 {Was more tricky.
White would be forced to find a precise way fo consolidate his advantage after}
35. Ne2 (35. f3 Nf4 36. Nf5 (36. Be7 Qg7 {Is not so clear}) 36... gxf5 37. Qxf4
Qg7+ {And the rook on a1 is falling}) 35... Raxd8 36. exd5 Rxd5 37. f4 {
[pgndiagram] And White is winning. But Black still has some counterchances})
33. Bxd8 Nf4 (33... Qf7 34. f3 Nf4 35. Nf5 {Is a huge difference compared to
variation with the queen on h4}) 34. Bf6 {[pgndiagram] Now the game is over
and Lasker concludes it in a spectacular fashion} Qd2 35. Re2 Nxe2+ 36. Bxe2
Qd7 37. Rd1 Qf7 38. Bc4 Be6 39. e5 Bxc4 40. Nf5 {A brilliant, one sided game,
in which Lasker relinquished his advantage only briefly, and essentialy
dominated from start to finish} 1-0



