[Event "St. Petersburg"]
[Site "St. Petersburg"]
[Date "1909"]
[Round ""]
[White "Lasker"]
[Black "Teichmann"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "C86"]

1. e4 { Notes by Lasker}  1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6.
Qe2 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3 O-O 9. d4 exd4 10. cxd4 Bg4 11. Rd1 d5 { White was
threatening e5, followed by Bd5.}  12. e5 Ne4 13. Nc3 Nxc3 14. bxc3 f6 {
Premature. He should have played ...Na5 first.}  15. h3 Bh5 { Obviously ...Be6
was ruled out by 16 exf6 Rxf6 17 Bg5 Rg6 18 Bc2. As for ...Bf5 16 g4! this was
just as unpleasant for Black as ...Bc8 16 a4 with numerous threats, such as
Qa2.}  16. g4 Bf7 17. e6 { This had to be very carefully considered. It was
risky to give Black his d6-square and to face the possibility of the advanced
pawn being cut off from his fellows by ...f5.}  17... Bg6 18. Nh4 Na5 19. Nxg6
{ This exchange was necessary since, after 19 Bc2 Bxc2 20 Qxc2 Nc4 21 f4 Nd6 22
f5 Ne4 White would have bottled up his lines of attack.}  19... hxg6 20. Bc2 f5
21. Kh1 Bd6 22. gxf5 Qh4 23. Qf3 gxf5 24. Rg1 { Threatening Bg5, as well as 25
Bxf5 Qf6 26 Qg2.}  24... f4 25. Rg4 Qh6 26. e7 Bxe7 27. Bxf4 Qe6 { Seeing that
28 Rxg7+ would be immediately decisive Black resigned even before White had
moved.}   1-0

[Event "Match G/02"]
[Site "Paris"]
[Date "1909"]
[Round ""]
[White "Janowski"]
[Black "Lasker"]
[Result "0-1"]
[ECO "C49"]

1. e4 { Notes by Simon Alapin}  1... e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O
O-O 6. d3 d6 7. Bg5 Bxc3 8. bxc3 Ne7 { This is the usual move introduced by
Pillsbury, the alternative 8...Qe7 is not very attractive.}  9. Bc4 { The usual
Bxf6 is better, but Janowski had a predilection for preserving his 2 Bishops.} 
9... Ng6 10. Nh4 { ?}  10... Nf4 { ! This very strong move was first made by
Pillsbury.}  11. Bxf4 exf4 12. Nf3 { Loss of time; 12 g3 followed by Ng2 was
preferable.}  12... Bg4 13. h3 Bh5 14. Rb1 b6 15. Qd2 { Unnecessary, but
Janowski evidently hoped for attacking chances on the open g-file.}  15... Bxf3
16. gxf3 Nh5 17. Kh2 Qf6 18. Rg1 Rae8 19. d4 Kh8 20. Rb5 Qh6 21. Rbg5 f6 22.
R5g4 g6 23. Bd3 { So as to stop ...f5.}  23... Re7 24. c4 { A careless move:
White might have tried something more passive such as Qc1 or Rg2, but he was
under great time pressure.}  24... Ng7 { !}  25. c3 { ? d5!}  25... Ne6 26. Bf1
f5 { !}  27. R4g2 Rf6 { !}  28. Bd3 g5 { !}  29. Rh1 { Only now White sees the
terrible threat of the Queen sacrifice, but there is no defence anyway.}  29...
g4 30. Be2 Ng5 31. fxg4 f3 32. Rg3 fxe2  0-1

