*[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Preface"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The Danish Grandmaster Bent Larsen spent many years living in Spain andArgentina and he noted that Spanish speakers, as your author is, hold JoséRaúl Capablanca in particularly high esteem, due to the linguistic connection,and as a consequence we have tended to seriously undervalue two of his greatrivals, the Russian Alexander Alekhine and the subject of this book, EmanuelLasker of Germany. --- It is possible that Larsen was right; it's certainlytrue that until recently there were not many good books about Lasker. Recently,however, an excellent book, John Nunn's Chess Course, was published, in whichNunn deeply analyzes Lasker's play. --- As soon I was assigned the gratifyingtask of writing the present book I naturally studied Lasker's games moredeeply than I had done in the past, and for more than a year there hasscarcely been a day when I haven't marvelled at his strength. 'What a goodplayer Lasker was!' was a spontaneous thought every day, providing a greatdegree of justification for Larsen's assertion.} 1. Z0 {I found so much toadmire: often it was how Lasker conducted the defence; at other times, it wasfor his handling of the endgame, or his astonishing ability to find tacticalresources in defence, or the way in an inferior position he could createserious difficulties for the opponent, or provoke errors in balanced positions,or handle equal positions in such a way that he would keep accumulating smalladvantages with quiet manoeuvring, etc. In short, Lasker was a completechessplayer. --- Regarding the openings, in Lasker's day these were not giventhe same importance as began to be the case some decades later, but all thesame Lasker introduced new ideas. Several lines carry his name, as we'll see.--- One of the greatest surprises to me was that Lasker's famous advice "Ifyou find a good move, look for an even better one" was not something towhich he himself always gave priority, or to be more precise, at least notwhen he had a much superior or winning position. Then he would frequentlyprefer a safe continuation, eschewing complications. --- On the other hand,when Lasker stood worse, he certainly searched for the best moves; in suchpositions he had no equal in finding the best chances for resistance andcounterattack. I don't think that there has been any other world champion whodrew or even won from so many inferior positions.} (1. Z0 {As in my previousbooks in the Move by Move series, I shall give voice to the wisdom of otherchess masters who have provided annotations, many very instructive, toLasker's games during the past one hundred years or more. --- With theappearance of ever-stronger analysis engines, it has become apparent that theannotators of the past sometimes made analytical errors and today's engineshelp us correct these. However, I think a degree of moderation is required,since there is a danger of going over the top and quoting long lines ofcomputer-generated analysis. Moreover, in complicated positions care isrequired with the results of engine analysis; their calculations andevaluations are different today from those of ten years ago and presumablythey will be different again within a short time. --- Finding the bestcontinuation in a complex position requires accurate calculation of many movesand over the board this is sometimes beyond the powers even of the bestplayers in the world, with limited time for reflection, the onset of tiredness,etc. And then the objective truth of the position doesn't always match thepractical needs of the player, as Lasker shows us. --- One of the mostimportant parts of Lasker's legacy is that he demonstrates with his play thatchess is a fight. Lasker himself gave one of his books the title of Struggle.Even in worse positions there are usually ways to fight and chances of puttingup resistance, no matter what the engines say. That's why in my annotations Itry to convey the practical situation as well as the objective evaluation.}) (1. Z0 {When I was very young I read somewhere that Lasker had not created arecognisable 'school', because he had no definite style. I don't think that'sreally true; it's easy to recognise Lasker in the manoeuvring play ofclassical players such as Petrosian and especially Karpov. Lasker's wide rangeof defensive skills is evident in the games of Petrosian and Korchnoi.Nevertheless, in the present day the player who most resembles Lasker is theworld champion Magnus Carlsen, especially in his capacity to extract anadvantage in seemingly barren positions and also in his excellent handling ofthe endgame. --- It has been a pleasure to 'rediscover' the second worldchampion, Emanuel Lasker, in this, the 150th anniversary of his birth. I hopethat the reader will also share that emotion.}) (1. Z0 {Zenón Franco,Ponteareas, October 2018}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Introduction"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{First of all, let's consider some testimony from some of the great championsconcerning the style or characteristics of Lasker's play. We'll follow thiswith some typical examples of his handling of different phases of the game,giving special emphasis to his defensive play and his skill in thecounter-attack.} 1. Z0 {Then the bulk of this book is devoted to forty-six ofLasker's best games, arranged in chronological order.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "The Style of Emanuel Lasker"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Much has been written about the style of Emanuel Lasker, mainly highlightinghis tactical skills and his introduction of the psychological element into thestruggle over the chessboard. --- Let us start with the opinion of Laskerhimself. In 1937 he wrote: "Much has been written about my style: here wefind clear and unclear, deep and shallow, praise and condemnation, exultationand despair. I believe that my gift lies in the realm of combinations. To findthe most interesting and substantial line among a great many possibilities -that is what attracts me." This provides corroboration of the generalopinion concerning the first element of his style. --- Concerning the secondelement, an interview for De Telegraaf in 1924 included the question: "Ihave heard that after you have carefully studied some of your opponent's games,you know both his weak and strong points?" --- Lasker replied: "That isself-understood and is entirely in line with my theoretical conception of thefight. A game of chess, after all, is a fight in which all possible factorsmust be made use of, and in which a knowledge of the opponent's good and badqualities is of the greatest importance. Thus Réti 's games, for instance,show that he plays better with White than with Black; Maróczy's is that he isvery cautious in defence, and that he attacks only when driven by necessity;Janowski's that he may stand to win six times, but finds it regrettable thatthe game should end and that finally he manages to lose. In New York [referring to the New York 1924 tournament] he has performed the impossible inthis respect. In short, there is much to be learned from a few serious gamesof one's opponent."} 1. Z0 {Richard Réti highlighted one of the aspects ofLasker's game that he considered weak: "Like Morphy, he is not as infalliblein closed positions as he is in the open game and in closed positions notinfrequently drifts into danger of defeat". Nevertheless, he considered thatthis wasn't an irreparable fault: "But since no closed position can beoverthrown by strategy alone and since a final decision can only be achievedby breaking through and opening up the game, none of his opponents canentirely eliminate this open phase of the game in which Lasker is mostdangerous. This is one of the reasons why Lasker, more often than any otherchess master, has succeeded when already in an unfavourable position inregaining the initiative." --- Réti also emphasized that "Lasker's mostoriginal contribution to chess, however, is not a purely technical, but apsychological element, the psychological play". --- Referring to theabove-mentioned event in New York 1924, Réti quoted two theories that werecurrent at the time; of the first, he wrote: "In analyzing Lasker'stournament games, I was struck by his lasting and at first seeminglyincredible good luck. There are tournaments in which he came out on top andwon almost every game, though in a losing position in every other game, sothat many masters spoke of Lasker's hypnotic influence over his opponents."--- It's curious that this hypnotic influence was later also attributed toMikhail Tal, among others. Réti didn't believe in this hypnotic influence,but as time went by his own alternative explanation, that Lasker deliberatelyplayed badly in order to reach positions in which the opponent would feeluncomfortable, received less and less credence. --- Nevertheless, let's quotepart of Réti's argument: "Again and again I studied Lasker's games todiscover the secret of his success. There is no denying the fact that over andover again Lasker's lay-out of the game is poor, that he is in a losingposition a hundred times and nevertheless wins in the end. The hypothesis oflasting luck is too improbable. A man who steadily wins such success must bepossessed of surprising power. But why then the bad, the losing positions? ---"There is only one answer which may sound paradoxical at first: Lasker oftendeliberately plays badly. [...] He studies the game, the manner of playing,the strong and the weak points of the masters whom he is to meet. He is not somuch interested in making the objectively best moves as those mostdisagreeable to his opponent; he turns the game in a direction not suitable tothe style of his opponent and on this unaccustomed road leads him to the abyss.[...] This is why Lasker's opponent never has a chance of playing a positionthat suits him. [...] Awkward situations must be attended to in haste,difficulties appear to become overwhelming and then all of a sudden Laskerbegins to play magnificently and to show his real strength."} (1. Z0 {Capablanca's opinion was: "Lasker was born a genius; he developed this bymeans of exceptionally hard work in the early stage of his career, but neverrestricted himself to the kind of game which could have been classified as adefinite style. This occasioned a number of masters to opine that Lasker hadabsolutely no style. They said that Lasker is an individualist; that he fightsmainly against his opponent's individual weaknesses. But speaking of Lasker, Ido not think that such a statement can be taken absolutely. [...] In recentyears, when I have had occasion to watch Lasker play, it seemed to me that hewould frequently change tactics, even against one and the same opponent. [...]On the other hand, Lasker has great gifts. He is most stubborn and unyielding.He has an amazing capacity to defend himself in difficult positions. [...]Once seized with attacking fire, Lasker could bring it to a successfulconclusion as few others can. Lasker's combinative gift in the endgame wasalso very great." --- Regarding the theories of Réti and others, Capablancaemphasized that "None of the great players has been so incomprehensible tothe majority of amateurs and even masters, as Emanuel Lasker.'}) (1. Z0 {Let's now consider the opinion of a world champion of our own era, VladimirKramnik: "In my view Lasker is the pioneer of modern chess. When you look atSteinitz`s games, you understand that they have a smack of the past ages. AndLasker had a lot of games which can be regarded as the games played by amodern chess player. Lasker is the first link in a chain of 'global' chess,where different elements of the struggle are taken into account. Steinitz putthe emphasis mainly on a certain element of position. For example, if he hadthe better pawn structure and the prospect of an attack the king, heconsidered his advantage almost decisive. As to Lasker, he understood thatthere are different elements of a position, which balance one another. Herealized that there are different kinds of advantage and that they may beconverted one into another: tactical advantage changes into a strategic onesand vice versa. --- "Lasker is the great figure; he understood many globalthings in chess. Recently I've looked through his games again and wassurprised: Lasker knew a great deal for his time! He was the first tounderstand the importance of psychological aspects of the game and began totake proper account of them; he was the first to modify his strategy and evenpartly his style depending on an opponent. While Steinitz stuck to one concept,he believed: this is correct but this is wrong. --- "Lasker understood quitea complicated idea for those times (when chess was conceived categorically, inblack and white colours): chess is such a complicated game that it'simpossible to understand which way of playing is correct and which is not. Onecan act in absolutely different ways. Lasker was very flexible and he wasundogmatic, perhaps, the first chess player in history who was undogmatic. Hedidn't operate with such categories as 'this is bad and this is good': forexample, if you have occupied the centre - it's good; if you haven't -it's bad. And this was a great step forward in the development of chessthought. --- "By the way, not many people know that Lasker objected to thealleged 'psychological' influence upon an opponent and said: 'My success isbased mainly on understanding the strength of the pieces and not on takinginto account an opponent's character'. --- "It seems to me that hisundogmatic character gave him a deeper understanding of chess. He violated thedogma and everybody thought that it was done 'in view of an opponent'. AndLasker began to realize that these dogmas are not so indisputable. Let'sremember, for example, his famous move f4-f5 in the game against Capablanca."}) (1. Z0 {John Nunn drew attention, among many other considerations, toanother of Lasker's strong points: "One of the tests of a player's mentaltoughness is how he reacts when things go wrong. If you have a winningposition and then make a mistake throwing away all your advantage, it's veryhard to put the history of the position out of your mind and play as if it wasjust any other equal position. This is why many players, once they have blowna large advantage, then go on to make further mistakes and eventually lose.One of Lasker's strengths was his ability to remain level-headed even aftermaking a mistake." --- Finally, let's briefly see some praise for Laskerfrom other great champions: Alekhine: "Lasker was my teacher, and withouthim I could not have become whom I became. The idea of chess art isunthinkable without Emanuel Lasker." --- Tal: "The greatest of thechampions was, of course, Emanuel Lasker. At the chess board he accomplishedthe impossible! He was an amazing tactician, winning games that wereapparently quite hopeless." --- Korchnoi: "My Chess Hero. Chess consistsof scientific, artistic, sporting, psychological and other elements, and ofthem all Lasker valued most the combative character, the duel of wits. On theother hand, I believe that he underestimated the scientific element." ---Kasparov: "It has to be said that in his best years he always won thedecisive games. The ability to accomplish such competitive feats is preciselywhat distinguishes champions."}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker in the Opening"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{It's noteworthy that such important figures as Mikhail Botvinnik believedthat "Lasker held no opinion on opening theory; much like Capablanca, he didnot think it was very significant." Robert Fischer went further; at the ageof twenty-three he wrote that Lasker "Knew nothing about openings".However, both great players expressed different opinions later. --- NaturallyLasker didn't have the same focus on the openings as Botvinnik, who was muchmore analytical, in part because the opening lines that he played tended to bemore complicated tactically. On another occasion Botvinnik expressed adifferent opinion: "It was in fact Lasker who was the first of the greatmasters to understand the importance of preparing for events." --- Fischeralso changed his mind some years later and spoke of Lasker with admiration,according to Robert Byrne.} 1. Z0 {In the book Last Lectures (1941), JoséRaúl Capablanca quoted Walter Penn Shipley, a friend of Lasker's and thearbiter of the 1894 World Championship between Steinitz and Lasker: "Beforethis match, as Shipley told me one day, Lasker made a thorough study of theopenings, especially those variations Steinitz loved. This refutes theassertion of many contemporary commentators that Lasker never paid anyattention to the opening. In fact, Lasker knew his openings very well, butopenly disagreed with many tenets of accepted theory. He knew as much as hethought necessary, but his goals were frequently at odds with whole schools ofother masters." --- At the end of the 19th and the start of the 20thcenturies the openings didn't receive as much attention as today. Systems werenot analyzed to exhaustion as they are these days, but we can say that Laskerwas ahead of the usual treatment of the openings at the time. --- Lasker hadseveral favourite lines, in particular the Exchange variation of the Ruy Lopez,with which he gained some important victories, although less because of theopening than through outplaying his opponents in the resulting middlegame andendgame.} (1. Z0 {There are also several important lines which carry his name.Let's consider the most important of these (see the following games).}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Queen's Gambit Lasker Defence"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "D55"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "12"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. Bg5 O-O 6. e3 {In his 1907 worldchampionship match against Frank Marshall, Lasker played the variation thatcarries his name for the first time:} Ne4 {. With this unpinning manoeuvreBlack gains freer play for his pieces compared to the more usual lines of thetime. Lasker played it three times in this 1907 match and gained two and ahalf points. --- Later, against Gideon Ståhlberg in Moscow 1935, Laskeremployed the move order that became popular later, ...h6, and only after theretreat Bh4, ...Ne4. This variation has passed the test of time. "The Laskervariation of the Queen's Gambit is a solid and reliable weapon. Black's playis strategically simple and on sound positional foundations", according toYusupov. --- The line reached one of its highest points in a decisive gameplayed by another world champion, Viswanathan Anand, who employed it againstVeselin Topalov in the final game of their match in Sofia 2010. Anand'svictory in this game enabled him to win the match and retain his title.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Evans Gambit Lasker Defence"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "C52"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "20"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 {This pawn sacrifice was very popularfrom around the middle of the 19th century onwards, and White scored manybrilliant victories with it, thanks to the advantage in development. Inparticular it was a deadly weapon in the hands of Paul Morphy.} Bxb4 5. c3 Ba56. O-O d6 7. d4 Bb6 $1 {This move is "The famous Lasker's Defence which putthe Evans out of commission last century", according to Fischer. --- Blackabstains from capturing more pawns, but instead returns his extra pawn. One ofits foundations is that after} 8. dxe5 ({In Game 17 we'll see} 8. a4 {employedin M.Chigorin-Em.Lasker, St. Petersburg 1895.}) 8... dxe5 9. Qxd8+ ({The mainline is} 9. Qb3 {.}) 9... Nxd8 10. Nxe5 Be6 {, "In view of the weakness ofWhite's queenside pawns, Black has a favourable endgame", according toKasparov, who quoted as an example the game M.Chigorin-H.Pillsbury, London1899.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Reti's Opening Lasker System"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "A12"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "26"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{In the New York tournament of 1924 Richard Réti managed to break the longunbeaten run of the world champion Capablanca, which had lasted ten years. Hedid so using a system that he'd used twice in Mährisch Ostrau 1923, whichconsisted of opening with 1 Nf3, followed by the fianchetto of both bishops.In that tournament Réti had White against Lasker, but opted to play 2 d4.However, in their game in New York Réti decided to play the idea that wasgiving him such success:} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 3. b3 Bf5 {This is the first linkin Lasker's idea; he's playing the London System with reversed colours, basedon developing the queen's bishop outside the pawn chain. In earlier rounds ofthe New York tournament, Fred Yates, Edward Lasker and Efim Bogoljubow allopted to play with the bishop inside the pawn chain. Réti won all three games.} 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Nbd7 6. Bb2 e6 {Having played ...Bf5, Black erects abarrier against the g2-bishop.} 7. O-O Bd6 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 e5 {Later Blackpreferred to play this advance only after further preparation.} 10. cxd5 cxd511. Rc1 Qe7 12. Rc2 a5 13. a4 h6 {. This is another important element of thesystem, designed to preserve the bishop, although usually it is played earlier.The rest can be seen in its entirety in our Game 41.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "From Gambit Lasker Variation"][Black "?"][Result "*"][ECO "A02"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "11"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. f4 e5 {This pawn sacrifice is known as From's Gambit. It was played in oneof the oldest known games, G.Greco-NN, Europe 1620.} 2. fxe5 d6 {Of course,this is the idea, speeding up Black's development. The gambit's debut in theabove-mentioned game was less successful.} ({After} 2... Qh4+ $2 3. g3 Qe4 4.Nf3 Nc6 5. Nc3 {, Black's position was already very bad but he soon fell intoa trap that occurs in various lines of the Sicilian Defence:} Qf5 6. e4 Qe6 7.d4 Qe7 8. Bg5 Qb4 9. a3 Qxb2 10. Na4 {1-0.}) ({In his first From's Gambitagainst A.Reif in Breslau 1889, Lasker played} 2... f6 $6 {, against which} 3.d4 $1 {is a good reply,} ({but his opponent played feebly} 3. exf6 Nxf6 {, and after} 4. Nf3 d5 {Black gained good play. Lasker won in just 13 moves.}))3. exd6 Bxd6 4. Nf3 ({Of course, this move is more useful than} 4. g3 {,played in NN-Du Mont, casual game, Paris 1802, which ended abruptly after} Qg55. Nf3 $4 Qxg3+ 6. hxg3 Bxg3# {.}) 4... g5 {This was played for the first timein H.Bird-Em.Lasker, Newcastle upon Tyne 1892. Black threatens to win with 5...g4 and 6...Qh4+, with the same mate that we saw above. This advance is stillaccepted theory even today.} ({In this position both Steinitz and Blackburnepreferred to continue development with} 4... Nf6) ({and even} 4... Nh6) ({and} 4... Bg4 {have been played several times.}) 5. d4 g4 6. Ne5 ({Instead of this,} 6. Ng5 {is more ambitious and leads to great complications. After 6 Ne5 theexchanges give Black a good game, as we'll see in Game 4.}) *[Event "Kokomo (match)"][Site "?"][Date "1893.??.??"][Round "4"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Showalter, J"][Result "1-0"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r1r3k1/1bqn1pnp/pp2p1p1/2ppP1P1/3P4/2PBPN1Q/PP1B3P/R3K1R1 w Q - 0 17"][PlyCount "47"][EventDate "1892.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker on the Attack: Lasker has delayed committing his king and, as we cansee, finds it easier to attack the enemy king by opening lines on the kingside.He must now decide how to make progress with his offensive, since there isnothing immediate.} 17. Qf1 $1 {The f6-square is an ideal destination for thef3-knight. With this retreat Lasker prepares the way for the knight; the queengoes to f1 to prevent the idea of ...a5 followed by ...Ba6. For now the whiteking is secure on e1, because the centre is closed, although it's possiblethat the a1-rook will need to join the attack, so the king will have to move.}b5 {Black tries to make progress on the queenside by opening lines, so thatthe white king will feel less secure.} 18. h4 {Not only preparing a future h5,but more importantly clearing h2 for the knight.} c4 $6 {Although this gains atempo for the ...b4 break, the white king will not be harmed by this offensive.} ({More worrying for White was} 18... Nb6 {, followed by ...Nc4, with theplan of breaking with ...b4, but without closing the game.}) 19. Bc2 Rf8 {This is an attempt to hold up White's intended 20 Nh2, which would havefollowed any other move.} 20. Qh3 $1 {The move played is also very strong;White will profit later from the position of the queen on the h-file.} ({Black's idea was to take advantage of the 'X-ray' pressure of the f8-rookagainst the white queen by answering} 20. Nh2 {with} f5 {. However, after} 21.gxf6 Nxf6 22. exf6 $1 Qxh2 23. O-O-O {,the opening of lines against the blackking is clear and White is threatening 24 Bxg6!, which} Qxh4 {fails to prevent,since after} 24. Bxg6 $1 Rxf6 {White can play} 25. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 ({or} 25...Kf8 26. Rh1 $1 {, winning}) 26. Rh1) 20... a5 21. Nh2 b4 22. Ng4 ({The targetis the black king, so White refuses to be distracted with} 22. cxb4 {, whichwould concede some chances to Black after} c3 $1 {.}) 22... b3 23. Bd1 {Once again White prevents the queenside being opened.} ({After} 23. axb3 cxb324. Bxb3 Qb6 {Black has gained his objective of obtaining counterplay. Notetoo that Black has no way to exploit the present lack of coordination amongthe white pieces. The position is closed, meaning White that will have time toreorganize and that his attack will continue to make progress.}) 23... Nf5 {Black tries to defend h7 with this manoeuvre.} ({Meanwhile the d1-bishop'scontrol of h5 is useful: for instance, in the event of} 23... Kh8 24. h5 $1Nxh5 25. Nf6 {.}) 24. h5 Kg7 25. Nf6 {The total triumph of White's idea.Black's position is very precarious, as White threatens 26 hxg6.} Rh8 26. Bg4 {It's time to regroup the white forces.} Ne7 $2 {Black panics at thepossibility of Bxf5, but this retreat can be refuted in crushing fashion.} ({It was more tenacious to keep the knight on f5 and play something like} 26...bxa2 {.}) 27. Bxe6 $1 {"Fairly obvious, but it leads to some pretty play" (Reinfeld and Fine).} Nxe5 ({After} 27... fxe6 28. Qxe6 Nb6 {the quickest wayis} 29. Ne8+ $1 Rhxe8 30. h6+ Kf8 31. Qf6+ {and mate next.}) 28. dxe5 fxe6 29.Qxe6 Ra6 ({After} 29... Bc8 {White can still play} 30. Ne8+ $1 {,} ({White canstill play} 30. Nd7 $1 Qxd7 31. h6+ Kf8 32. Qf6+ Ke8 33. Qxh8+ {.})) 30. h6+Kf8 31. Qd7 $1 {With an extra pawn and the more active pieces, White is happyto enter an endgame.} Qxd7 ({Black must exchange queens, since} 31... Qb8 {allows} 32. Rf1 {, with a mating attack.}) 32. Nxd7+ Ke8 33. Nc5 Ra7 (33... Rb6{runs into} 34. axb3 cxb3 35. Rxa5 {.}) 34. axb3 {Even the a1-rook comes intoplay. The black position is falling apart.} cxb3 35. Rf1 Bc6 36. Nxb3 {Withtwo extra pawns and the more active pieces.} a4 37. Nd4 Rf8 38. Rf6 Bd7 39. e6Bc8 ({After} 39... Bc6 {the most elegant continuation is} 40. c4 dxc4 41. Bb4Ba8 42. Kd2 {, followed by 43 Raf1.}) 40. Nb5 1-0[Event "World Championship, Munich"][Site "?"][Date "1908.??.??"][Round "5"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Tarrasch, S"][Result "1-0"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r1r2nk1/4bp2/pq1pb2p/1p2P1p1/3p4/3Q2BP/PP3PP1/1B1RRNK1 w - - 0 23"][PlyCount "31"][EventDate "1908.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Black has weakened his king with the advance ...g5, but the position isclosed and for now the black kingside is well defended. On the other hand,White is a pawn down; he could regain it right away with 23 Qxd4, but theexchange of queens gives no advantage. --- Lasker opted instead for the attack.} 23. Qf3 $1 {The f8-knight is a good defender, neutralizing the bishop on b1and the queen on d3, so the queen seeks fresh horizons; it can go to h5 or f6at an opportune moment. The most immediate threat is 24 exd6 Bxd6 25 Qf6,winning the h-pawn.} d5 ({Opening the play with} 23... dxe5 24. Bxe5 {wouldonly weaken the black king even more; White might continue with 25 Ng3-h5 or25 Qh5.}) ({Controlling f6 with} 23... Kg7 {is only a temporary defence. After}24. exd6 Bxd6 25. Bxd6 Qxd6 26. Ng3 {White threatens 27 Nh5+ Kg8 28 Qf6, and}Qd8 {is answered with} 27. Re5 {followed by 28 h4, with a strong attack.}) 24.Qh5 Kg7 25. f4 {Lasker starts tactical operations and plays the most directmove.} ({A quieter way, also advantageous, was} 25. Nh2 {followed by Ng4,which would force Black to give up his light-squared bishop.}) 25... f5 $2 {It's hardly surprising that opening the kingside, when White has so manypieces on this wing, isn't a solution to the threat of 26 f5.} ({Tarraschrecommended} 25... Ng6 $2 26. f5 d3+ 27. Bf2 Bc5 28. Ne3 Nf4 {,} {However,instead of 29 Qg4?, White can play} 29. f6+ $1 ({on the basis that} 29. Qg4 {allows Black} d4 30. Nf1 Bd5 {, with an excellent position.} (30... Z0)) 29...Kh7 30. Bxd3+ Ng6 ({or} 30... Nxd3 31. Nf5) 31. b4 Bd4 32. Bf5 {, threatening33 Ng4, as well as 33 Rxd4 Qxd4 34 Ng4, with a winning attack.}) ({The mosttenacious defence was} 25... d3+ 26. Kh1 Ng6 {, although White's attack gainspace after} 27. f5 $1 Bxf5 28. Ne3 Be6 29. Bxd3 {, with the better prospects.})26. exf6+ Bxf6 27. fxg5 hxg5 28. Be5 $1 {"An absolutely lethal move,exchanging the main defender of Black's king and winning the pawn on g5" (Nunn).} d3+ 29. Kh1 Ng6 30. Qxg5 Bf7 31. Ng3 {And the white attack isunstoppable.} Bxe5 32. Rxe5 Rh8 33. Bxd3 Ra7 34. Rde1 Kf8 35. Bxg6 Qxg6 36. Qe3Rc7 37. Nf5 {Threatening 38 Qa3+.} Qc6 38. Qg5 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker in the Middlegame"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Here are three middlegame positions in which Lasker faces very differentsituations (see the followng games).} 1. Z0 *[Event "Cambridge Springs"][Site "?"][Date "1904.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Napier, W"][Result "1-0"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r3B2k/pp2N2p/8/2B3Pp/4npb1/2b5/P1P5/1R3K1R w - - 0 25"][PlyCount "21"][EventDate "1904.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{This position was reached after a very complicated struggle. In terms of thematerial, the position could be considered an endgame rather than a middlegame,but although the queens have left the board the tactical possibilities presentmean that the position is chaotic. --- As Réti commented, "Although Whiteis a rook ahead, his outlook is none too bright. Black has four direct threats:...Rxe8, ...Nxc5, ...Nd2+ and ...Ng3+. Moreover, White's king is in a veryexposed position." --- How did Lasker respond? With the best move in theposition:} 25. Bxh5 $3 {"White thereby relinquishes all advantage inmaterial strength, but once more assumes the attack which in spite of thereduced material strength at this disposal terminates in his completesuccess" (Réti).} ({None of the other options offer any advantage: forexample,} 25. Bb5 Nxc5 26. Nd5 Ne4 27. Nxc3 Nxc3 {when the two pawns are morethan sufficient compensation for the exchange,}) ({and even worse is} 25. Bf2$2 Rxe8 26. Nd5 Nxf2 27. Kxf2 Bd4+ 28. Kf1 ({or} 28. Kg2 Re2+ 29. Kf1 Rxc2)28... Bf3 {.}) 25... Bxh5 26. Rxh5 Ng3+ 27. Kg2 Nxh5 28. Rxb7 {This is whatLasker was aiming for. Following the exchanges, the material is equal, but allthe white pieces are the more active and, although it doesn't seem importantat the moment, Black's king is much weaker than White's. The immediate threatis to the a7-pawn.} a5 {Lasker could continue to slowly improve his position,such as with 29 Rf3, but instead adopts another plan, utilizing the third rank.} 29. Rb3 $1 {Despite the limited material, Lasker opts to attack the blackking, using the h-file.} Bg7 30. Rh3 Ng3 31. Kf3 {"The first tangiblesuccess. Black's f-pawn cannot be protected, inasmuch as 31...Be5 is followedby 32 Ng6+, a threat which has recurred again and again during the entiregame", wrote Réti. --- Following the loss of the f4-pawn, Black's knightwill become unstable and will have to leave the king's wing.} Ra6 {Now theback rank can be added to the list of Black's weaknesses.} ({After a move suchas} 31... Re8 {, though, White has time to play 32 Bd6 before capturing on f4,and Black has no useful reply.}) 32. Kxf4 Ne2+ 33. Kf5 Nc3 34. a3 ({It wasquicker to play} 34. Be3 Nd1 35. Bf4 {, followed by g6, but White's movechanges nothing.}) 34... Na4 ({Sending the knight to the edge can't be good,but there was nothing better: for example,} 34... a4 {could be answered with}35. Rd3 Ra8 36. Kf4 {, preparing 37 Nf5.}) 35. Be3 {. There's no good defenceagainst 36 g6.} 1-0[Event "World Championship, Paris"][Site "?"][Date "1909.??.??"][Round "4"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Janowski, D"][Result "1-0"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "2krr3/1pp1qbpp/p1p2p1n/8/3PP1P1/2N2N1P/PPP1Q3/2KRR3 w - - 0 16"][PlyCount "49"][EventDate "1909.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{White's position is slightly better. His pawn centre is restrained and anyadvance would leave weak squares, but it's well supported and controlsimportant central squares. The most obvious defect in Black's position is thebadly placed knight on h6. There is nothing immediate; we're entering amanoeuvring struggle in which each side tries to improve the position of hispieces.} 16. Qf2 {"A good move, which (1) strengthens White's grip on thef-file and (2) decreases Black's pressure on the e-file" (Reinfeld and Fine).} Kb8 {Preventing a possible invasion by the white queen on a7.} 17. Kb1 Bg8 {Preparing to transfer the knight from h6 to a much more useful position, d6.}18. Nh4 {The centralization of the black knight will leave the f5-squaretemporarily weak, so White seeks to occupy it.} Nf7 {Preventing Nf5, orexpelling it later, with ...g6 naturally has a cost, weakening the f6-pawn.}19. Nf5 Qf8 {Nunn outlined the next phase of the game clearly: "For themoment, there's nothing more White can do to improve his position on thekingside as further progress based on h4 and g5 will require some preparation.It's important to strike a balance between furthering your own objectives andobstructing your opponent's plans, and now it's time for White to deal withBlack's potential counterplay on the opposite flank." --- Therefore now isthe right moment to play...} 20. b3 $1 Nd6 21. Rd3 $1 {With 20 b3 White gainedcontrol of c4, which combined with this defence of the c3-knight, prevents anyblack threat of 21...Nc4, followed by ...Qa3 if possible.} Nb5 {The knightcan't go to c4 and it's inappropriate to exchange on f5, so it seeks anotherway to become active.} 22. Na4 {Lasker also reacts with a concrete idea; hisknight can go to c5 and the c-pawn is ready to go to c4.} b6 ({After} 22...Na3+ 23. Kb2 Nb5 24. Qd2 {the white position continues to improve. This renewsthe idea of playing c4,} ({but not the immediate} 24. c4 $2 {due to} Qa3+ 25.Kb1 Bxc4 {.})) 23. c4 Na3+ ({This decision was taken before playing 22...b6,since} 23... Nd6 $2 {is answered with} 24. Nxd6 {and 25 c5, destroying Black'sdefences. The manoeuvring phase has drifted into a tactical struggle. Theknight puts itself in the lion's mouth, supported by the queen and the bishop.}) 24. Kc1 $1 {When the game becomes sharper, it's essential to become moreattentive.} (24. Kb2 $2 {is obviously bad due to} Nxc4+) ({while} 24. Ka1 $2 {has another tactical problem:} g6 $1 25. Ng3 Qb4 {, threatening 26...Nxc4 and26...Bxc4, and the bad position of the king on a1 is evident in that} 26. Qd2$2 {fails to} Nc2+ {.}) 24... g6 {This is necessary now to gain more mobility.}25. Ng3 Qe7 {Preparing ...Rf8 to release the queen from the defence of thef6-pawn.} 26. Qd2 {Another manoeuvring phase begins. The queen heads for thequeenside to reinforce the defence. Once the queenside has been safeguarded,the knight on a3 will start to be in danger. This is not pleasant for Black,so at some moment he will need to give a violent turn to the game. When heplayed 22...b6 and 23...Na3+ Janowski would logically have foreseen that thissituation would arise. Tactics will dictate when is the best moment for Blackto complicate the struggle.} Kb7 $2 {Janowski misses his chance to createcomplications.} ({It was preferable to play} 26... Nxc4 $1 27. bxc4 Bxc4 28.Rde3 Qd7 29. Nb2 Bxa2 {, when for the piece Black has three pawns. For themoment these will have little influence and it's not clear whether they can beadvanced in the middlegame without risk, but, on the other hand, the whiteking lacks pawn cover and it is not clear where the white knights should go,so there are chances for both sides.}) 27. Qc3 $1 {Preventing the sacrifice onc4. As Nunn pointed out, "At first the position does not appear critical forBlack and even the computer only gives White a tiny advantage, but in realitythe situation is quite serious." --- Black now lacks chances to complicatethe struggle and White can continue to make progress without any difficulties.Curiously the knight will be worse situated on a3 than h6, because now it's indanger.} a5 {This hinders a future b4 by White, but it's symptomatic of thefact that the black position has no moves that are dangerous to White.} 28. Rf3{It's time to get back to putting pressure on Black's weaknesses.} Rf8 {Passive, but the black position was difficult.} 29. Ref1 h5 $2 {Black feelspowerless, but this advance, which leads to f5 being weakened, makes thesituation worse.} 30. gxh5 gxh5 31. Nf5 $1 {Showing that the 'threat' of 31...h4 wasn't real.} Qb4 (31... Qxe4 {loses material after} 32. Qb2 Bh7 33. Nc3 {,}({or} 33. Re3 {.})) 32. d5 $1 {Preparing Nd4, as well as eliminating theinfluence of the g8-bishop on the queenside.} Bh7 33. Nd4 Bxe4 34. Nxc6 Qxc3+35. Nxc3 Bxf3 36. Nxd8+ Rxd8 37. Rxf3 {Threatening 38 Rxf6 as well as 38 Kb2.}b5 38. cxb5 Kb6 39. Rxf6+ Rd6 40. Rf8 ({White has an overwhelming materialadvantage, and} 40. Rf8 Nxb5 {loses to} 41. Rb8+ {.}) 1-0[Event "Maehrisch Ostrau"][Site "?"][Date "1923.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Wolf, H"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r2qnrk1/pp1bppbp/3p2p1/2p5/3nP3/2NPB1PP/PPPQNPBK/R4R2 b - - 0 11"][PlyCount "49"][EventDate "1923.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{This game, which passed without any great complications, nevertheless made adeep impression on Tartakower. For now the position is very quiet, so how didLasker seek active play?} 11... Rc8 $1 {Not yet with active measures. AsTartakower remarked, "Whereas a superficial eye would think to see Black'sprimary chance lying on the wing where the kings have castled (...f5 withpossibly ...e5 to follow), the destruction of forces which this plan entailsapparently gives Dr. Lasker pause, for which reason he carries out with a firmhand the total mobilization of his queenside."} 12. Nd1 {White prepares toevict the black knight from d4 by retreating the knight before playing c3.This is a plan which is still used in similar positions.} Bc6 13. Ng1 $2 {Too optimistic.} ({If he didn't want to play} 13. c3) ({it was preferable toplay} 13. Nf4 {.}) 13... d5 $1 {The moment has arrived to open the game,because: "A chess game can only be won by dynamic moves!" according toTartakower.} 14. c3 Ne6 15. exd5 Bxd5 16. f3 $2 {White wants to make room forhis passive knight on d1, without exchanging the light-squared bishops, butthis unnatural move is asking too much of the position.} Nd6 $1 {Lasker, incontrast, makes moves which are both natural and good, qualities whichgenerally, but not always, go together. The knight goes to f5, from where itattacks both the bishop and the recently created weakness on g3.} 17. Nf2 Nf518. Ng4 Qd6 {Lasker intensifies the pressure on g3 in preparation for thefinal assault.} 19. Ne2 h5 $1 {Black's play is completely logical andconsistent; the target is g3.} 20. Nh6+ Nxh6 21. Bxh6 h4 $1 {"Ripping openthe rook's path is decisive" (Tartakower).} 22. Bxg7 Nxg7 23. Qf4 hxg3+ 24.Qxg3 e5 $1 {Naturally Black avoids the exchange of queens.} 25. Kh1 Rfe8 {Not yet deciding where the knight should go; it has three attractive squares,h5, f5 and e6.} 26. Rfd1 Qf6 27. Qf2 Ne6 {Finally the knight goes to e6,initiating the final offensive in connection with Black's next move.} 28. Rd2Kg7 $1 {The target now is the h3-pawn.} 29. Kh2 Rcd8 30. a3 Rh8 31. Re1 Ng5 32.Ng1 Qf4+ 33. Kh1 Bxf3 $1 {"The decisive combination. Black not only devisedhis game in royal manner, but he has also conducted his attack with greatvigour" (Tartakower).} 34. Bxf3 Nxh3 35. Qe3 Ng5+ {. "A typical Laskergame: It does not lend itself so much to analysis as it does to admiration",added Tartakower.} 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "1925.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "2K5/2P2R2/k7/8/8/8/2r2p2/8 w - - 0 1"][PlyCount "25"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker in the Endgame: The ending we're about to see is Lasker's most famouscomposition. This version is the one that he included in his book 'CommonSense in Chess' (second edition, 1925). Later we'll see the original position,which was published for the first time in 1890 in the magazine 'DeutschesWochenschach', with a dedication to Wilhelm Steinitz.} 1. Kb8 $1 {Threateningto queen, so Black's moves are forced.} (1. Rf3 $2 {doesn't win since, amongstother things, Black can play} Ka7 {, reaching a drawn position;} (1... Kb6) ({and} 1... Rb2 {also work.})) 1... Rb2+ 2. Ka8 Rc2 3. Rf6+ {This manoeuvre willbe repeated several times, until the black king has been driven back as far asWhite's second rank.} Ka5 4. Kb7 {Once again threatening to queen.} Rb2+ 5. Ka7Rc2 6. Rf5+ Ka4 7. Kb7 Rb2+ 8. Ka6 Rc2 9. Rf4+ Ka3 10. Kb6 {Threatening 11Rxf2.} Rb2+ 11. Ka5 Rc2 12. Rf3+ Ka2 {And now, with the Black king on a2,White wins with...} 13. Rxf2 $1 {. This is known as the 'Lasker manoeuvre'.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "1890.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "K7/2P4R/8/k7/8/8/2r4p/8 w - - 0 1"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{According to the Linders' book, "A number of players and composers triedtheir hand at extending Lasker's original idea; among these, the mostsuccessful were Paul Keres (1947), Nikolai Kopayev (1952), and VelimirKalandadze (1970)." We can add J.Hasek (1936). --- The manoeuvre is of somepractical importance and has been seen in games such as V.Tukmakov-J.Smejkal,Leningrad 1973, and I.Zaitsev-M.Dvoretsky, Moscow 1973. --- This is Lasker'soriginal version, published in the 'Deutsches Wochenschach' in 1890. --- Thesolution is very similar. Lasker altered it to rule out an alternativesolution on the first move, as both} 1. Kb7 ({and} 1. Kb8 {win in this version.}) *[Event "St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1914.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Tarrasch, S"][Result "1/2-1/2"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "5B2/6pB/p4bK1/1pp1kP2/4b3/1P6/1P5P/8 w - - 0 36"][PlyCount "24"][EventDate "1914.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The following ending is also famous. It was considered a precursor of Réti's brilliant study of 1921, in which the king manages to neutralize an enemypassed pawn that appears unstoppable.} 36. Bxg7 $4 {A very natural move, butit's a grave error. Blundering like this in the endgame was most unlike Laskerand occurred very seldom in his career, but an unsuspecting Tarrasch failed toadvantage.} ({The correct way was the far-from-obvious} 36. Kf7 $1 Bxf5 (36...Bd5+ 37. Kg6 {achieves nothing}) 37. Bxf5 Kxf5 38. Bxg7 Bxg7 39. Kxg7 {, whichtransposes to the game.}) 36... Bxf5+ 37. Kf7 Bxg7 $4 {Tarrasch returns thefavour and simplifies to reach an 'obviously' winning pawn ending.} ({He couldhave won the bishop ending resulting from} 37... Be6+ $1 38. Kg6 Bxg7 39. Kxg7Bxb3 {, giving up his bishop for the h-pawn and winning with his queensidepawn majority: for example,} 40. h4 Bd1 41. Bg6 b4 42. h5 Bxh5 43. Bxh5 c4 44.Bg6 a5 45. Bc2 Kd4 46. Kf6 b3 47. Bf5 a4 {and 48...c3.}) 38. Bxf5 Kxf5 39. Kxg7a5 {At first glance it appears that Black will win without any difficulty. Theblack king can deal with the h-pawn and White's king is a long way from thequeenside, where Black will surely create a winning passed pawn.} 40. h4 $1 Kg4{White's position looks lost.} 41. Kg6 $1 {The threat of 42 h5 forces Black tocapture on h4, so that the white king gains a vital tempo to save the game.} ({If} 41. Kf6 $2 c4 42. bxc4 bxc4 43. Ke5 c3 44. bxc3 a4 {and the a-pawn queens,but Lasker had calculated better.}) 41... Kxh4 42. Kf5 Kg3 ({After} 42... c443. bxc4 bxc4 ({if} 43... b4 {White is fine after} 44. Ke4 ({or} 44. c5)) 44.Ke4 c3 45. bxc3 {, the white king is on e4 and can go via d3, c2 and b2 tostop the a-pawn. Black must respond by sending his king to stop the c3-pawn,because} a4 $4 {loses to...} ({curiously} 45... Kg5) (45... Kg4) ({and even} 45... Kg3 {all suffice; the black king arrives in time, using the a-pawn todeflect the white king if necessary}) 46. Kd3 {and now it is too late for} Kg547. Kc4 $1 {, and White wins.}) 43. Ke4 Kf2 44. Kd5 Ke3 45. Kxc5 Kd3 46. Kxb5Kc2 47. Kxa5 Kxb3 1/2-1/2[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "1921.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Reti, R"][Black "?"][Result "1/2-1/2"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "7K/8/k1P5/7p/8/8/8/8 w - - 0 1"][PlyCount "7"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{This is Richard Réti's famous composition from 1921. We give just the mainline of this very well-known study:} 1. Kg7 h4 2. Kf6 Kb6 3. Ke5 Kxc6 4. Kf4 {"A miracle has come to pass: the king, even though two tempi behind,nevertheless has caught the pawn!" (Dvoretsky).} 1/2-1/2[Event "New York"][Site "?"][Date "1924.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Lasker, Ed"][Result "1/2-1/2"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "2r5/6P1/4k3/8/3K1P2/1p6/1N6/8 w - - 0 89"][PlyCount "30"][EventDate "1924.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The following ending was reached after a tremendous struggle in which EmanuelLasker was several times on the verge of defeat. --- At first sight heredoesn't seem to be any chance of salvation. The white king is cut off and thepawns have been stopped. After capturing the white pawns, the black king willcross over to the queenside to support the b-pawn and Black will win, sincethe white king can't move away due to the need to prevent ...Rc2, followed by ...b2.} 89. g8=Q+ $1 {Diverting the rook is the only chance for the white kingto approach the b3-pawn before Black plays ...Kf7.} Rxg8 90. Kc4 {You mightthink that little has changed. The white king has crossed over to thequeenside, but after capturing the f-pawn Black 'only' needs to defend hispawn and then bring his king across to support its advance. Surprisingly, it'snot so.} Rg3 ({The alternative was to defend the pawn from behind. After} 90...Rb8 91. Kc3 Kf5 {, one of the ways to draw, given by Shereshevsky, is} 92. Nd3Rb6 93. Nb2 ({but not} 93. Kb2 $2 {due to} Ke4) 93... Kxf4 {, and now} 94. Nc4Rb8 95. Nd2 {with a draw, since Black is unable to support the pawn with hismonarch.}) 91. Na4 Kf5 92. Kb4 Kxf4 93. Nb2 {"This is the remarkablefortress draw which Emanuel Lasker had foreseen. If Black could cross thethird rank with his king then he would be able to bring his king to c2 and win,but this isn't possible", wrote Nunn.} Ke4 94. Na4 {While there is no threat,White can continue to wait with knight moves.} Kd4 95. Nb2 Rf3 96. Na4 Re3 {Black makes one last attempt, trying to route the king to the queenside via f3.} 97. Nb2 Ke4 98. Na4 Kf3 99. Ka3 $1 {This is the only move to draw. White isplanning to play 100 Kb2 followed by capturing the pawn, taking advantage ofthe fact that the black king has strayed a long way from the pawn.} ({Whitecan no longer continue making waiting moves with the knight. After} 99. Nb2 {Black wins with} Ke2 {: for instance,} 100. Ka3 Kd2 $1 101. Nc4+ Kc1 {, andthe pawn queens after} 102. Nxe3 ({or} 102. Nb2 Rh3) 102... b2 {.}) 99... Ke4 ({Turning back, since after} 99... Ke2 100. Kb2 Kd2 {White is in time to play}101. Nc5 {, safely winning the pawn.}) 100. Kb4 Kd4 101. Nb2 {We're back inthe position we had at move 97.} Rh3 102. Na4 Kd3 103. Kxb3 Kd4+ {. "This isprobably the most incredible, the most paradoxical draw in the history ofinternational tournaments" (Vainstein), while Kasparov wrote that whenEdward Lasker extended his hand to his opponent, he said: "I didn't knowthat in the endgame a knight could draw against a rook and a pawn!".} 1/2-1/2[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1: Selected Games: 1889-1894"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Emanuel Lasker was born in Berlinchen, Prussia (now Barlinek, Poland), on the24th of December 1868. He was the second of four siblings, born after theolder Berthold, and before the younger Theofilie and Amalie. His older brotherwas sent to Berlin for his secondary education and later to study medicine.Berthold earned money by teaching and playing cards or chess for small stakesin the so-called Theehalle in Oranienburger Straße, and sometimes in theCafé Kaiserhof.} 1. Z0 {At the age of eleven, Emanuel was sent to studyalongside Berthold and under his guidance. Emanuel passed his examsbrilliantly. When he caught measles he was sent to hospital and there Bertholdtaught him to play chess. Emanuel set about studying his new passion withdetermination, especially after obtaining a copy of Dufresne's manual, KleinesLehrbuch des Schachspiels. Then after being discharged from hospital, he beganto go to the Theehalle with his brother. --- Seeing games by masters helpedEmanuel's development as a chessplayer. In the spring of 1888 Lasker completedhis secondary studies and enrolled in the university of Berlin. As forBerthold, already qualified as a doctor, he moved to Elberfeld to practisemedicine. Emanuel occupied the place that his brother had left 'vacant' in theTheehalle and at the Café Kaiserhof, devoting more and more time to chess, inan atmosphere which was very favourable to his progress, as the strongestmasters of the time gathered there. Lasker didn't fail to take advantage.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "First Appearances"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{During the winter of 1888-1889, Lasker, who had recently reached the age of20, achieved his first victory in group B of the Café Kaiserhof Championship.In June 1889 he obtained the title of Master after winning the B Tournament ofthe 6th Congress of the German Chess Federation in Breslau, after a tie-breakagainst the Viennese master von Feyerfeil.} 1. Z0 {Thanks to his victory inthis event Lasker was invited to his first important tournament, containingvarious well-known masters, such as the Englishmen Amos Burn, James Mason andIsidor Gunsberg.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "'The Lasker Combination'"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Our opening game was played in the first round of the Amsterdam tournament of1889. The demeanour of the newcomer was not exactly fearful. It was impressive,as Lasker launched his attack from the outset and produced a combination whichhas become associated with his name. --- The fact that there might beantecedents, possibly unknown to Lasker, doesn't prevent this from being 'theLasker Combination'. It has been seen many times since, inNimzowitsch-Tarrasch, St. Petersburg 1914 (played by Tarrasch), Miles-Browne,Lucerne 1982, and Polgar-Karpov, Hoogeveen 2003, to name a few illustriousexamples.} 1. Z0 {Viktor Charushin even wrote a book entitled Lasker'sCombination, containing no fewer than 160 examples of this theme, although notall with the exact combination as seen in the stem game.} *[Event "1: Amsterdam"][Site "?"][Date "1889.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Bauer, J"][Result "1-0"][ECO "A03"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "75"][EventDate "1889.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. f4 {In spite of this favourable beginning, Lasker didn't repeat this movein official tournaments, playing it only in simultaneous exhibitions.} d5 2. e3Nf6 3. b3 e6 {There is nothing wrong with continuing with development.} ({There are various ways for Black to deploy his forces and he can even exploitWhite's move order with} 3... d4 {, to which White can respond with} 4. Bd3 {,}({or even sacrifice a pawn with} 4. Bb2 dxe3 5. Qe2 {, and after} exd2+ 6. Nxd2{, followed by 0-0-0, the compensation is sufficient. --- QUESTION: But, whydid White not prevent 3...d4 by playing simply 3 Nf3 - ? --- ANSWER: Probablyto avoid 3 Nf3 being answered with 3...Bg4; the knight on f3 is very useful inWhite's chosen set-up.})) 4. Bb2 Be7 5. Bd3 b6 ({As mentioned above, Black candevelop in various different ways. Here, for instance, he could play} 5... c5 {, followed by developing the knight on c6. It's worth noting that White'stypical manoeuvre to prepare the way for the future Ne5 jump is to answer ...Nc6 with Bb5, but here, having already played 5 Bd3, it would cost a tempo.})6. Nf3 Bb7 7. Nc3 Nbd7 ({Once again} 7... c5 {deserved consideration,intending ...Nc6, but we shall see that leaving the c5-square free is alsoplayable.}) 8. O-O O-O 9. Ne2 {Bird had already employed this manoeuvre insimilar positions. The knight is heading for the kingside.} ({Another idea wasto play} 9. Ne5 {, intending Qf3 and then Nd1-f2, leaving e2 free for thebishop to retreat if necessary, but this is not really better, since after}Nxe5 10. fxe5 Nd7 11. Nb5 {, Black can start an attack on the queenside with:for example,} (11. Ne2 {is worse, on account of} Nc5) 11... Nc5 12. Be2 c6 13.Nd4 b5 {, followed by ...a5, with a pleasant position; White will not find itvery easy make progress on the kingside.}) 9... c5 ({An obvious suggestionhere is} 9... Nc5 $1 {, eliminating the dangerous bishop, but the text move isalso playable.}) 10. Ng3 Qc7 {Black continues with his development, connectingthe rooks.} ({Instead,} 10... Ne4 {was playable, since} 11. Ne5 {is not to befeared - Black can achieve a sound position with, say,} Nxe5 12. Bxe5 f6 13.Bb2 Qd7 {.}) 11. Ne5 {EXERCISE: What would you play in this position?} Nxe5 $6({ANSWER: With the knowledge of what happened in the game, the defensive move} 11... g6 $1 {comes strongly into consideration, and it is not obvious howWhite can make progress, or take advantage of the weakening of Black's kingposition.}) ({Another possibility that comes to mind is the more active move} 11... d4 $5 {. After} 12. exd4 cxd4 {White's best move is} 13. Qe2 {, keepingthe tension, with the idea of Rae1;} ({in contrast, accepting the sacrificewith} 13. Bxd4 {gives Black an excellent position after} Bc5 $1 {, regainingthe pawn and achieving the freer position after, say,} 14. Bxc5 Qxc5+ 15. Rf2Nxe5 16. fxe5 Qxe5 {, followed by ...Rfd8. --- With the text move Black agreesto a fight at close quarters and is not afraid to activate White'sdark-squared bishop, in exchange for effective pressure of his own along thea8-h1 diagonal. --- QUESTION: Is this exchange not riskier and worse than thetwo alternatives mentioned above? --- ANSWER: It's certainly riskier, and alsomore ambitious, but it is not bad; Black's position is still fine.})) 12. Bxe5{Logical, keeping the dark-squared bishop active.} ({Nevertheless,} 12. fxe5 {was also worth consideration and in fact it seems to be at least as strong.--- QUESTION: Really? So shutting in the bishop on b2 can be a good thing? ---ANSWER: Blocking the long diagonal is the drawback, but in return the f-fileis opened and the knight defending Black's king position is driven away. Afterthe natural} Nd7 $6 {, White can launch an attack with} ({instead playing} 12... Ne8 {is passive}) ({while if} 12... Ne4 {White can consider} 13. Bxe4dxe4 14. Rf4) (12... Ne4 13. Bxe4 dxe4 14. Rf4) 13. Qh5 {, which is verystrong.} {And} h6 {is no better, because White can play} ({Then if} 13... g614. Qh6 {Black can't play} Nxe5 $4 ({but} 14... d4 15. exd4 cxd4 {is hardlybetter due to} 16. Rae1 {, with the idea of 17 Nh5}) {, on account of} 15. Nh5{, mating.}) 14. Rf2 ({or} 14. Rf4 {, followed by Raf1, which is very strong})({but even better is} 14. Rf6 $1 {, because the rook is immune from captureand there is no good defence against the threat of 15 Rxh6.})) 12... Qc6 {EXERCISE: Now Black is all set up to execute his plan, which is to play atimely ...d4. How do you think Lasker responded? --- ANSWER:} 13. Qe2 $1 {"A psychologically subtle move: both prophylactically defending g2, andthreatening Bb5, which in fact is a sham - the bishop is looking in quitethe opposite direction!", commented Kasparov. --- In fact, with thisseemingly inoffensive move, Lasker has a devastating continuation in mind.} ({QUESTION: That's all very well, but it hands Black a tempo. Instead ofoverprotecting g2, wasn't it better to play the obvious} 13. Nh5 {- ? ---ANSWER: The problem is that after 13 Nh5 Black can counterattack with} d4 $1 {, and after} ({of course, not} 13... Nxh5 $2 {, which allows} 14. Bxh7+ $1 {, reaching a position similar to the game}) 14. Rf2 dxe3 15. dxe3 Nxh5 {For instance, a question later on asks whether} 16. Bxh7+ (16. Qxh5 f5 $1 {Black has no problems. Further on, we'll expand on this and clarify anyremaining doubts you might have.} (16... Z0)) 16... Kxh7 17. Qxh5+ Kg8 18. Bxg7{would win here. --- The answer is that, no, there would be no more than adraw after} Kxg7 19. Qg4+ Kh7 20. Qh5+ Kg7 {, etc, since} 21. Rf3 $2 {fails to}Qxf3 22. gxf3 Rh8 {, with a decisive advantage.}) 13... a6 $2 {Black fails tosense the danger and parries the 'threat' of Bb5 by playing a move that looksuseful, planning to play 14...b5. In reality, 14 Bb5 was not dangerous, sincealthough it would force the queen to waste a move, it would also divertWhite's bishop from the main battleground.} ({A move deserving considerationwas} 13... Ne4 {, to close the b1-h7 diagonal, and after} 14. Nxe4 dxe4 15. Bc4Rad8 16. a4 {it is not clear that White has achieved very much.}) ({Meanwhile,a more combative defence was} 13... g6 {, which also closes the diagonal ofthe bishop on d3. Although this weakens Black's king position, White cannotachieve much by slow manoeuvring, so it is essential to analyze the violentresponse} 14. f5 $5 {. Black seems to be able to resist the onslaught with}exf5 {:} {White's best response is} 15. Bxf5 $1 (15. Nxf5 $2 {fails to} gxf516. Bxf5 Bc8 $1 {, and Black can defend, with advantage.}) ({Neither does} 15.Rxf5 $6 {give White anything;} {Black has the zwischenzug} Qe6 $1 {; forexample,} ({even better than playing the immediate} 15... gxf5 16. Nxf5 Qe6 17.Nh6+ Kh8 18. Qh5 {, which is by no means bad}) 16. Bb2 gxf5 17. Nxf5 {, and now} Rfd8 ({or} 17... Bd6 18. Nh6+ Kh8 {, with the idea of 19...Be5.})) 15... Nd7{is necessary, when} ({since after} 15... gxf5 $2 16. Nxf5 {the attack isirresistible}) 16. Bb2 Qd6 17. Qg4 Nf6 18. Qf3 {"leads to an unclearposition in which White retains considerable attacking chances. The inaccuracyat move 11 has left Black in a position requiring precise defence, but hefalls at the first hurdle" (Nunn).}) 14. Nh5 $1 {Now that ...d4 doesn't gaina tempo, since g2 is defended, this is good. --- "It's surprising that theblack position is already practically hopeless" (Kasparov).} Nxh5 {EXERCISE:What did Lasker play now?} ({In the event of} 14... d4 {White gains a decisiveattack with} 15. Bxf6 $1 Bxf6 16. Qg4 $1 {EXERCISE: In this line, what is therefutation of} e5 {- ? --- ANSWER: The elegant} (16... Kh8 17. Rf3 {, with theidea of 18 Rh3, among other threats.} (17. Z0)) 17. Be4 $1 {is decisive.}) ({Instead, if} 14... Rfd8 {White can play} 15. Nxf6+ Bxf6 16. Bxh7+ {, when} Kxh7{loses to a typical manoeuvre:} 17. Qh5+ Kg8 18. Bxf6 gxf6 19. Qh6 {, followedby Rf3.}) 15. Bxh7+ $1 {ANSWER!} ({Not} 15. Qxh5 $2 {, since once again} f5 {nullifies the attack.}) 15... Kxh7 16. Qxh5+ Kg8 {EXERCISE: And now, how doesLasker's most famous combination continue? --- ANSWER:} 17. Bxg7 $1 {"Thisprototype game brought the concept of the 'double bishop sacrifice' to generalattention and was the forerunner of countless examples. In order for thedouble bishop sacrifice to lead to more than perpetual check, the attackergenerally needs to have a rook available to join the attack. Here the f1-rookcan easily participate by moving to f3", so runs Kasparov's enlighteningcommentary. "Modern computer programs find his combination with frighteningspeed: on the calculation of the main 15-move variation. Fritz, for example,spends not more than 13 seconds!" wrote Kasparov too at the start of the21st century; by 2017 they took less than a second.} Kxg7 ({There is no timeto escape with} 17... f6 {; mate follows quickly after} 18. Rf3 $1 {, as shownby} ({or} 18. Bh6 $1 Rf7 19. Qg6+ Kh8 20. Qxf7) 18... Qe8 19. Qh8+ Kf7 20. Qh7{.}) 18. Qg4+ {This check is necessary, to force the black king on to theh-file.} ({In contrast the immediate} 18. Rf3 $2 {is bad due to} Rh8 $1 19.Rg3+ Bg5 $1 20. Qxg5+ Kf8 {.}) 18... Kh7 19. Rf3 e5 {Black manages to preventmate, but not defeat, because he is saddled with "tactical weaknesses", touse Lasker's expression; here these are loose pieces.} 20. Rh3+ Qh6 21. Rxh6+Kxh6 {EXERCISE: What is the final point of the combination? --- ANSWER:} 22.Qd7 $1 {Suppressing all resistance, as White wins a piece and finally emergeswith a decisive material advantage.} ({Here} 22. Rf1 {also wins, as shown by}f5 23. Qh3+ Kg6 24. Qg3+ Kf7 25. fxe5 {, but the text move is simpler. ---QUESTION: But, if we go back a little, wouldn't this combination also work inthe line you mentioned after 13 Nh5 d4! 14 Rf2 dxe3 15 dxe3 Nxh5 - ? What Imean is, doesn't 16 Bxh7+ Kxh7 17 Qxh5+ Kg8 18 Bxg7 win here too? (See abovefor the ANSWER.)}) 22... Bf6 23. Qxb7 Kg7 24. Rf1 Rab8 25. Qd7 Rfd8 26. Qg4+Kf8 27. fxe5 Bg7 ({If} 27... Bxe5 {White wins a piece with} 28. Qf5 {.}) 28. e6Rb7 29. Qg6 f6 30. Rxf6+ Bxf6 31. Qxf6+ Ke8 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Qg7+ Kxe6 34. Qxb7Rd6 35. Qxa6 d4 36. exd4 cxd4 37. h4 d3 38. Qxd3 {. Lasker's internationaldebut was very positive overall. He finished in second place with 6 points outof 8, behind Amos Burn. --- He subsequently played a match in Berlin againstone of Germany's strongest masters, Curt von Bardeleben, which ended abruptlywhen, with the fourth game in a balanced position, and with the score equal at1½-1½, von Bardeleben resigned both the game and the match. --- There thenfollowed another match, with Jacques Mieses, in Leipzig, which surprisinglyended with a resounding 6½-1½ (+5 =3), in favour of the still largelyunknown youngster, Emanuel Lasker.} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Matches in the United Kingdom"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{In February 1890 Lasker travelled to Liverpool to play a match against themaster Henry Bird. Lasker won easily, by 8½-3½ (+7 =3 -2). --- Hedemolished Bird's Dutch Defence (which he played with both colours) easily.It's possible that Lasker abandoned 1 f4 following his famous win againstBauer because the Bird didn't seem to him to be a good opening with White, northe Dutch a good defence with Black. Rather unexpectedly Bird won games 10 and11, to some extent as Lasker sometimes did, without being better.} 1. Z0 {*Lasker was unable to arrange to play against any other English masters; hewas only able to play a short match against Nicolas Miniati, which he won 4-1 (+3 =2). --- On Lasker's return to Germany, following a team tournament inwhich he played alongside his brother Berthold, he gave a weak performance inthe short Graz Congress, finishing third with 4 points out of 6 (+3 =2 -1)behind Gyula Makovetz and Johann Hermann Bauer. --- In 1891 Lasker returned toEngland, and in March-April 1892 he won a double round-robin tournament inLondon with 6½/8 (+5 =3), overcoming Blackburne, Mason, Gunsberg and Bird.Let's see a game from the tournament.} *[Event "2: London"][Site "?"][Date "1892.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Blackburne, J"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C65"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "77"][EventDate "1892.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 d6 5. d3 ({QUESTION: A strange choice.It looks very passive, doesn't it? --- ANSWER: Lasker refrained from thenatural} 5. d4 {, which would transpose to the Steinitz Defence of the RuyLopez, which was one of his own favourite defences. 5 d3 is certainly morepassive than 5 d4, but that doesn't mean that Lasker is planning to play thewhole game passively, as we shall soon see.}) 5... Be7 6. h3 {QUESTION: Hmm,another unusual move. Wasn't it better to castle, and was Lasker really thatbothered about the possibility of ...Bg4 - ? --- ANSWER: It's another'unusual' move, as you called it. White continues to delay castling and makesa pawn move, but in a certain way this move is the result of playing 5 d3; ifLasker were to play in 'normal' manner now there would be no way for him totry to gain an advantage. This move prepares Be3 and still delays revealingthe future destination of his king. Lasker wants to create a positionallycomplex game. In this closed position there is no danger in the short term inleaving his king in the centre.} O-O 7. Be3 Ne8 {In view of White'sfar-from-energetic play, Black prepares to break with ...f5. --- EXERCISE: Howdo you think Lasker responded? --- ANSWER:} 8. g4 {Radically preventing 8...f5.--- QUESTION: But... isn't this very weakening? Where is the king going to go?--- ANSWER: Weakening, yes, but there is no way to punish White immediately.Black has many ways to play. If he insists on breaking with ...f5, he willhave to weaken his own king position with ...g6, and White has still notcastled.} ({Here we see a perhaps unexpected justification of 6 h3; Laskerconsidered that it gave him more practical chances than} 8. O-O f5 {.}) 8... a69. Ba4 {Lasker prefers to keep all his options open;} ({although} 9. Bxc6 bxc610. d4 {, with good play, deserved consideration.}) 9... Be6 10. Ne2 {Headingfor g3;} ({although it is not clear that this is objectively any better thanthe inconsistent} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. d4 {. I should stress that we are talkingobjectively here, not from the practical point of view. Lasker presents theopponent with many options; several of these are satisfactory, but... he hasto choose just one of them.}) 10... g6 {Consistent with 7...Ne8;} ({although} 10... b5 11. Bb3 Na5 {was promising, when White must acquiesce to the exchangeof his 'Spanish bishop' for the knight, since having played g4, exchanging one6, opening the f-file, looks risky.} ({Black could also play 11...d5 insteadof} 11... d5) 12. Ng3 ({White's best move seems to be} 12. d4) 12... c5 {,} 13.Bd5 $2 {is bad due to} Bxd5 14. exd5 Nf6 {.}) 11. Ng3 Ng7 12. c3 b5 {Blackpostpones his ...f5 break, instead opting for a manoeuvre that gives him goodplay.} ({Instead,} 12... f5 {could be answered with} 13. gxf5 gxf5 14. Rg1 ({or} 14. Bh6 {.})) 13. Bb3 (13. Bc2 {would also be answered with} d5 {.}) 13... d5{Black is fine. He is occupying the centre and will be able to keep developingwithout any problems, yet White is not worse.} 14. Bh6 Qd7 {More development,connecting the rooks. --- EXERCISE: How do you think Lasker continued here?} ({This is safer than} 14... dxe4 15. Bxe6 exf3 ({better than} 15... fxe6 $6 16.Nxe4) 16. Bb3 {, and Black will need to enter complications in order not tolose a pawn for nothing.}) 15. Qe2 {ANSWER: In the same spirit in which Laskerhas conducted the game from the beginning, keeping the tension, but this timewith a concrete threat: 16 Nxe5! Nxe5 17 exd5 Bxd5 18 Qxe5, threatening mateand attacking the bishop on d5. Black also needs to consider the move order 16exd5 and then 17 Nxe5.} ({The thematic strike} 15. Nf5 {seemed premature toLasker. After} gxf5 16. gxf5 Bxf5 17. exf5 Qd6 18. Qd2 Kh8 {Black repels thefirst wave of the attack, with a good game; the white king is still in thecentre, but the position is now more open.}) 15... d4 {This prevents White'sthreat in a radical way.} ({As a response it is a reasonable one, but it waspossible also to emulate Lasker with a more flexible move,} 15... Rfe8 {, which prevents the combination due to the pin on the e-file.}) 16. Bxe6 {Another move that gives Black options.} ({Once again the knight sacrifice onf5 deserved consideration, but the result is unclear. There are manypossibilities after} 16. Nf5 {;} {It's better start with} Bxb3 {and now 17axb3? would lose a piece, so} ({if} 16... gxf5 $6 17. gxf5 Bxb3 $4 {then Whitecan play advantageously} 18. Rg1 $1 Bf6 19. Bxg7 Bxg7 20. f6 {.} (20. Z0)) 17.Bxg7 {is preferable, and after the almost forced sequence} gxf5 18. Bxf8 fxe419. Bxe7 exf3 20. Qd2 {, White wins the exchange, but his pawn structure is soweak that with the queens still on the board Black has compensation after} ({not} 20. Qxf3 $2 Bd5) 20... Nxe7 {, followed by ...Ng6,} ({or} 20... Qxe7 21.axb3 dxc3 22. bxc3 b4 {, gaining d4 for the knight.})) 16... Qxe6 {All threecaptures deserved attention.} ({More ambitious, and more risky, was thesacrifice of the exchange with} 16... Nxe6 17. Bxf8 Bxf8 {, but it is notclear that this would be advantageous; to solve the problem of his king'sposition White would castle artificially with Kf1-g1-h2.}) 17. O-O {Once againthe most flexible move.} (17. cxd4 {, deserved consideration, but it isn'tclear that Black had anything to fear in that case, since he could play} Nxd418. Nxd4 exd4 {and, after almost any white move, 19...Bh4.}) 17... Rfd8 {The rook escapes the pin and now it is possible to capture twice with a pieceon d4.} ({It was not advisable to try to gain control of the d4-square with} 17... dxc3 18. bxc3 b4 $2 {in view of the reply} 19. d4 $1 {.}) 18. Rfc1 {With the obvious idea of opening the c-file at an opportune moment.} Rd7 {EXERCISE (simple): What did Lasker play here?} ({Black wants to double rookson the d-file, but this is not the best move. It was preferable to play, forinstance,} 18... Rac8 {, with the idea of ...Qf6 and ...Ne6, when Black wouldhave good play.}) 19. cxd4 {ANSWER: "Finally a concrete decision!", I hearyou say. --- Now at last Lasker decides to change the structure, seeking toexploit his 'X-ray' pressure against c7.} Nxd4 ({QUESTION: How would Laskerhave responded to the recapture} 19... exd4 {- ? --- ANSWER: It is possible totake the initiative on the queenside with} 20. a4 {;} ({but even better is} 20.Ng5 {, forcing Black into 20...Bxg5, losing control of the dark squares, since}Qd6 $2 {loses material after} 21. e5 $1 Nxe5 22. f4 Nc6 23. Qf3 {.})) 20. Nxd4exd4 $6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker exploit Black's error?} ({Natural and atfirst sight forced, but it will soon be apparent that it was preferable tosacrifice the pawn on c7, since after} 20... Rxd4 21. Rxc7 Rad8 {Black wouldbe fine. Having to acknowledge that ...Rd7 not was the best move would beannoying, but it was necessary.}) 21. f4 {ANSWER: Of course, in this case themost obvious is the best; the kingside pawn majority is set in motion.} c5 22.e5 {More concrete moves; this clears the e4-square for the knight.} Rd5 ({QUESTION: In view of the dangerous front which is forming, wasn't it better toexchange a pawn with} 22... f6 {- ? --- ANSWER: Yes, that would quite possiblybe better, although even if there is an exchange of pawns, the positionremains unpleasant for Black after, say,} 23. exf6 Qxf6 24. Qg2 $1 {,preparing to play Ne4 by ensuring that the h3-pawn is protected in the linethat we shall see. Furthermore, the white queen is well placed on the g-file,and after} Rc8 25. Ne4 {now} Qh4 $2 {, fails to} ({so Black should play} 25...Qe6 $1 {, when matters are less clear}) 26. Rxc5 $3 Rxc5 ({or} 26... Bxc5 27.Bg5) 27. Nxc5 {.}) 23. Re1 {A difficult decision.} ({Now it was Lasker who hadseveral options, one of which was} 23. a4 {, seeking to open the a-file orweaken Black's pawn structure;}) (23. Qg2 {was also attractive, with thethreat of 24 f5, exploiting the fact that the black queen is overloaded.Lasker preferred to transfer more pieces to the centre of the struggle; thethreat is 24 f5 exf5 25 Bxg7 Rxg7 26 gxf5 and the white pawns are overwhelming.}) 23... Bh4 {EXERCISE: How to respond? --- ANSWER:} 24. Qf3 {Lasker decidesto retain his options, with the advance f5 as the main idea.} ({It was verytempting to play} 24. Ne4 {, since after} Bxe1 $2 ({instead of capturing therook, Black could play} 24... c4 $1) 25. Nf6+ Kh8 26. Rxe1 {the weakness ofthe black king gives White a very strong attack:} Ne8 {doesn't help either,since White can play} ({if} 26... Rdd8 {then} 27. Qf2 $1 {with the idea of 28Qh4, and then after} Ne8 {,} 28. f5 $1 {is very strong;} (28. Z0)) 27. f5 $1gxf5 28. gxf5 Qxe5 (28... Qxf5 $2 {loses to} 29. Qg2 $1) 29. Qxe5 Rxe5 30. Rxe5Nxf6 31. Rxc5 {, with a big advantage; Black has many weaknesses.}) 24... Bxg3{With the white queen on the h1-a8 diagonal, 25 Ne4 was an even strongerthreat.} 25. Qxg3 f5 $6 {This weakening advance is a sign of panic; Blackprevents 26 f5, but at the cost of activating the opponent's pieces.} ({It was unnecessary, because there was no immediate threat of} 25... Z0 26. f5$2 {, since after} gxf5 27. Bxg7 {Black could play} f4 $1 {, closing theg-file.}) ({Instead, Black should have sought counterplay with} 25... c4 {, when the position is not so clear; White could play} 26. Bxg7 ({here} 26. Qg2{is interesting, renewing the threat of f5, but both sides have play}) 26...Kxg7 27. f5 {, but Black can defend. It's worth noting that the white king isalso weak.}) 26. exf6 Qxf6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker try to exploit theopening of the game? --- ANSWER:} 27. Qg2 $1 {A strong response that increasesBlack's discomfort, since it's not possible play ...Rd8 because of 28 Bg5. Thewhite queen is extremely strong on the long light-square diagonal.} Qd6 28. Re7$1 {Another very strong blow. The rook is immune from capture on account of 29Qxd5+ and Qxa8, and now the knight is under threat.} Ne6 29. Re1 {Until nowboth the rooks on a1 and a8 were inactive, but now the white rook joins in theattack and there is no defence.} (29. f5 {was also winning.}) 29... Qxe7 ({There is nothing else; after} 29... Nc7 {the simple} 30. Rxc7 {wins.}) 30. Qxd5Re8 31. f5 {Fearless; the following incursion by the black queen is easilyneutralized.} Qh4 32. Rxe6 Qg3+ 33. Qg2 {More than sufficient.} ({The enginesindicate that the game could be concluded more quickly with} 33. Kf1 Qxh3+ 34.Ke2 Qxg4+ ({or} 34... Qh2+ 35. Kd1) 35. Kd2 {, and the white king escapes,since a check by the black queen on g1 can be answered with a discovered checkby the white rook.}) 33... Qxg2+ 34. Kxg2 Rxe6 35. fxe6 c4 36. dxc4 bxc4 37.Kf3 c3 38. bxc3 dxc3 39. Ke3 1-0[Event "3: London (match)"][Site "?"][Date "1892.??.??"][Round "5"][White "Blackburne, J"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "E12"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "102"][EventDate "1892.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{In May 1892 Lasker played a match with Blackburne, whom he defeatedconvincingly 8-2 (+6 =4). Let us see a game from that duel.} 1. d4 d5 2. Nf3Nf6 3. c4 e6 4. Nc3 b6 {QUESTION: That's a strange move order, isn't it? ---ANSWER: Somewhat, yes, but it doesn't affect the course of the game much. Inany case, Lasker merely anticipates what later became known as the Tartakowervariation, which was regularly employed by Spassky, Karpov and Kasparov, amongothers; in fact, probably by most of the strongest grandmasters of the finaldecades of the 20th century.} ({In later years the most precise move order wasconsidered to be} 4... Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 b6 {,} ({or} 6... O-O {followed by...b6. --- QUESTION: Is it necessary to play 5...h6 here? --- ANSWER: No,that's not strictly necessary, but it gives Black more options, since the move...h6 prevents a double attack on the pawns at c7 and h7 after the c-filebecomes open (with cxd5 by White and an exchange of knights after ...Nxd5),and White plays Bd3 and Qc2. It's no big deal, for instance, it's quitepossible for Black to recapture on d5 with the pawn, but with ...h6 insertedBlack has more options.})) 5. Bg5 Be7 6. e3 Bb7 7. Rc1 {White considers thatthe rook will be useful on the c-file and so he postpones the development ofthe f1-bishop; the other rook will possibly go to d1. --- Another possibility,with an idea similar to the one employed in the game, is to move the rookquickly to d1, to deter ...c5. --- QUESTION: But wouldn't that leave thef1-rook without a good square? Its ideal square would seem to be d1? ---ANSWER: Not necessarily. In the first place, White could always play Rd2, whenthe f1-rook would have several possibilities; another option is that if Whitemanages to prevent ...c5 and Black plays ...c6, White can support a timely e4advance with Rfe1.} a6 {This was not an essential move, although Laskermanages to make use of it later.} ({There was nothing wrong with playing thenatural} 7... O-O {.}) 8. Bxf6 {This is the beginning of a typical manoeuvreaimed at stabilizing the centre by preventing Black from recapturing on d5with his knight.} Bxf6 9. cxd5 exd5 10. Qb3 {White wants to impede thedevelopment of Black's other knight.} ({Here White deviates from} 10. Bd3 Nd711. O-O O-O 12. Qb3 c6 13. Bf5 b5 14. Rfd1 Nb6 {, with a good position forBlack in J.Blackburne-F.Lee, Manchester 1890, although Blackburne ended upwinning.}) 10... O-O 11. Be2 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue? --- ANSWER:}Qd6 {Simple chess. On d6 the queen will keep the d5-pawn protected while Blackdevelops his knight to d7. Here we see an (unforeseen?) virtue of the move 7...a6. From d6, the queen also supports a timely ...c5, which is a naturaladvance, seeking to activate Black's pair of bishops.} 12. O-O Nd7 13. Rfd1Rfe8 14. Na4 {A radical method of impeding ...c5, but it decentralizes theknight, and White will have to rely on tactical measures to prevent the knightbeing badly placed if Black finally manages to play ...c5 under favourableconditions. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker now continue?} ({An idea worthconsidering here was} 14. a3 {, with the idea of 15 Qa2 and 16 b4. The knighton c3 puts pressure on d5 and limits Black's options; he can play} c5 {, butafter} 15. dxc5 {he must remain with an isolated pawn on d5 after} Nxc5 {, rather than with hanging pawns (after ...bxc5).}) 14... Rab8 {ANSWER:Defending the bishop, so as to be able to recapture with the b-pawn after ...c5.} 15. Ne1 c5 $1 {Just in time, before White could prevent it by playing 16Bf3.} 16. Qa3 Be7 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Bf3 {Both sides continue to manoeuvre,deploying their pieces on the most effective squares.} Qe6 {The queen escapesthe pressure of the d1-rook and leaves the white queen in an uncomfortablesituation on the a3-f8 diagonal.} 19. Qd3 $6 {It's natural to reposition thequeen right away, before Black can play ...c4, but this square is not the best.--- EXERCISE: How did Lasker take advantage?} ({Blackburne should have played} 19. Qc3 {, maintaining the pressure on the c5-pawn.}) 19... Ne5 {ANSWER: Ofcourse. Black can eliminate the bishop on f3, which is putting pressure on d5,and at the same time gain the bishop pair.} 20. Qd2 Nxf3+ 21. Nxf3 {The bishoppair constitutes an advantage here, as White is forced to play with great care,since in conjunction with the mobile central pawns, the bishops can becomeactive at any moment.} Rbc8 22. Nc3 $2 {White fails to demonstrate therequisite care; this move threatens Nxd5, but there is a serious snag. In factthis was a clear error. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker punish White's latestmistake?} (22. Qa5 $1 {was better, putting pressure on the c5-pawn, with thepossibility of playing a timely Qb6.}) 22... d4 $1 {ANSWER: The white kingwill be left seriously weakened.} 23. exd4 Bxf3 24. gxf3 Qg6+ 25. Kh1 Qh5 $1 ({Much better than the also advantageous} 25... Rcd8 {.}) 26. Rg1 ({Now the pawnon f3 is defenceless; after} 26. Qf4 Bg5 27. Qf5 g6 {Black wins the exchange.})26... Qxf3+ 27. Rg2 Bf6 {A difficult choice.} (27... Rcd8 {was also verystrong;}) ({and} 27... cxd4 28. Qxd4 Bf6 {, with all the pieces activelyplaced, was also interesting.}) 28. d5 {Trying to keep the position closed.} ({After} 28. dxc5 $2 {but even stronger is} Rcd8 $1 {, and if} (28... Rxc5 {is advantageous;} 29. Z0 (29. Z0)) 29. Qc2 {then} Rd4 $1 {, threatening ...Rg4,and Black wins after} 30. Kg1 Rg4 31. Rg3 ({or} 31. Rxg4 Qxg4+ 32. Kh1 Qf3+ 33.Kg1 Re5 {, with an irresistible attack}) 31... Rxg3+ 32. hxg3 Bd4 {,threatening 33...Qxg3+, and there is no good defence.}) 28... Rcd8 29. Qd1 Qf5{With the white king so weak, the exchange of queens can wait.} ({The textmove increases the pressure on the d5-pawn, but slightly more precise was} 29... Qf4 $1 {, when the pressure on the c1-rook restricts the mobility of thewhite queen.}) 30. Qb3 $6 ({The queen moves as White prepares to answer 30...Bxc3 with 31 Qxc3, threatening mate, but this fails to relieve the pressure,which could have been done with} 30. Qg4 $1 {.}) 30... g6 {Useful luft, aswell as ruling out the aforementioned possibility of mate on g7.} 31. Rd1 {White supports the d5-pawn, which is the only thing holding the black rooksback. Black therefore seeks other avenues along which to activate his rooks.}Rb8 32. Qa4 {White removes his attacked queen and at the same time putspressure on the enemy rook at e8.} Red8 {Lasker elects to maintain the tension.He renews the threat of 33...Rxb2 by moving his e8-rook away from the pressureof the white queen.} ({It was possible to take concrete measures with} 32...Bxc3 33. bxc3 Re5 $1 {, and White's back-rank weakness is beyond repair:} {slightly better is} 34. Qxa6 (34. c4 {loses to} Rb1 35. Rxb1 $2 Qxb1+ 36. Rg1Qe4+ 37. Rg2 Rg5 {;} (37... Z0)) 34... Rxd5 35. Rdg1 Rb1 36. Qe2 {, but Blackcan force the white queen to abandon the long diagonal with} Re5 $1 {, when}37. Qg4 {loses to...} ({even worse is} 37. Qd2 Rxg1+ 38. Rxg1 Qf3+ 39. Rg2 Rd5{and Black wins}) 37... Rxg1+ 38. Rxg1 Qxf2 {.}) 33. Qe4 {EXERCISE: White hasmanaged to recentralize his queen and now offers a queen exchange. How do youthink Black replied? --- ANSWER:} Qh5 ({Once again Black declines to exchangequeens, looking for more than the favourable endgame arising after} 33... Qxe434. Nxe4 Bxb2 35. Nxc5 Rb5 36. Nxa6 Rbxd5 37. Rxd5 Rxd5 {.}) 34. f3 Rb4 35. Qe2Kg7 36. Rg4 Rb7 {Once again rejecting an exchange of pieces.} ({There wereseveral other possibilities, such as} 36... Be5) ({or} 36... Rd4 {. The textmove envisages going to d7 or e7 and creates an immediate threat of 37...Bxc3,followed by ...Rxd5.}) 37. d6 $6 {The pawn will be even more vulnerable on d6.}({Here} 37. Qd2 {is more tenacious, although White remains worse, after, say,}Rdb8 {, seeking to undermine the position of the knight, and after} 38. b3 Rb4{White is very passive.}) 37... Bd4 $1 38. Rd2 Rxd6 {The loss of this pawnfurther opens lines for Black's pieces and White's position becomes untenable.}39. Ne4 Re6 40. Ng3 Qxg4 {Now, finally, the indirect exchange of queens is thesimplest, because it leads to the win of another pawn.} 41. fxg4 Rxe2 42. Rxe2Rxb2 43. Rxb2 Bxb2 44. Nf1 Bc1 ({Black can also win by activating his king with} 44... Kf6 {, but Lasker prefers first to prevent White from improving theposition of his knight.}) 45. Kg2 Kf6 46. Kf3 Ke5 47. Ke2 Bf4 {Shutting in theknight on f1.} 48. Kd3 Kd5 49. a4 a5 50. Ng3 Bxg3 51. hxg3 f6 0-1[Event "4: Newcastle upon Tyne (match)"][Site "?"][Date "1892.??.??"][Round "2"][White "Bird, H"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "A02"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "80"][EventDate "1892.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Later that year, in August, Lasker played a second match against Bird, theresult of which was even more resounding than the first - Lasker won 5-0.Let's look at a game from this encounter.} 1. f4 e5 {In contrast to the firstmatch, in which Lasker happily played against the Dutch Defence with coloursreversed, here he opts for From's Gambit, offering a pawn. Lasker clearlyshows that this time he wants to take Bird out of his usual opening pattern.Bird had considered, at least before this game, that From's Gambit was not"prudent".} 2. fxe5 ({As a 1 e4 e5 player, Lasker was not afraid of thetransposition to the King's Gambit with} 2. e4 {.}) 2... d6 3. exd6 Bxd6 4. Nf3g5 $1 ({Instead of} 4... Bg4 {or developing one of the knights, Lasker posesimmediate problems, threatening to win with 5...g4, when the knight can'tretreat because of mate after 6...Qh4+.}) 5. d4 g4 6. Ne5 {White chooses thequietest continuation.} ({One of the classic openings books of the middle ofthe 20th century, written by Panov, considered the main line to be} 6. Ng5 {, sacrificing a piece after} f5 7. e4 h6 8. e5 Be7 {, and now:} {However, thevery same computers suggest, instead,} 9. Ne4 (9. Nh3 {, opining it led to acomplex position. However, today's computers prefer Black after} gxh3 10. Qh5+Kf8 11. Bc4 Rh7 12. Qg6 Bb4+ $1 {, clearing the h4-d8 diagonal for the blackqueen, and if} 13. Ke2 ({while is worse is} 13. c3 $2 Rg7 14. Bxh6 Qh4+) 13...Rg7 14. Bxh6 Nxh6 15. Qxh6 Qg5 {.}) 9... fxe4 10. Bc4 {, when they considerthat White has more compensation for the piece}) 6... Bxe5 7. dxe5 Qxd1+ 8.Kxd1 Nc6 {White keeps his extra pawn, but at a price; his pieces lackcoordination and the extra pawn is doubled. --- Black's plan is simple: play ...Be6 and continue with ...Nge7-g6, before or after castling, the precise moveorder depending on how White plays.} 9. Bf4 Be6 10. e3 Nge7 11. Bb5 {With thismove White deters 11...Ng6 for the moment, in view of the response 12 Bxc6.}O-O-O+ 12. Kc1 ({QUESTION: Doesn't moving to c1 obstruct White's development?} 12. Ke2 {looks better, doesn't it?} {Let's dig a little deeper though. IfWhite wants to maintain the pressure on c6, and he answers} a6 {with 13 Ba4,then with the white king on e2, Black has a timely...Bc4+, which is notserious in itself, but it forces the white king away from the defence of thed2-square and allows Black's rook to infiltrate.} ({ANSWER: It's not so simple;on e2 the king is more exposed. After} 12... Rd5 {White can't play} 13. Nc3 $2{, due to} ({but he would fine after} 13. c4 $1 {, when the rook has no reallygood retreat and after 14 b3 the control of d5 is a positive achievement forWhite}) 13... Rxb5 14. Nxb5 Bc4+ {.}) {Instead, on} 13. Ba4 {, there areseveral possibilities:} ({Let's look at something more concrete: Playing} 13.Bxc6 Nxc6 {is not satisfactory for White; Black is in good shape and followsup with ...Bf5 and ...Re8, regaining the pawn;} (13... Z0)) ({while} 13. Bd3 {would end up in a position similar to the game.}) {a possibility that keepsall Black's options open is} 13... h5 {.} ({such as the simple} 13... b5 14.Bb3 Ng6 {, regaining the pawn, but it is more than likely that Lasker wouldhave wanted more.} (14... Z0)) ({Since after} 13... Bd5 {White can play} 14.Nd2 $1 Bxg2 15. Rhg1 Bd5 16. Rxg4)) 12... Bd5 {Ambitious;} ({seeking more thancould be achieved with natural} 12... a6 {, but this move is not really better;we have already seen that the g4-pawn requires protection. After} 13. Ba4 (13.Be2 Ng6 {is not to be feared}) 13... b5 14. Bb3 Ng6 {Black regains the pawnunder favourable conditions.}) 13. Rg1 a6 14. Be2 Be6 (14... h5 {would be moreconsistent if, after} 15. Nc3 {, it were not advisable to play} Be6 {anyway.So it's more flexible to play 14...Be6.}) 15. Nc3 {EXERCISE: Black is still apawn down, but the position is approximately level. How do you think Laskercontinued?} ({In the event of} 15. Bg5 Rhg8 16. Bf6 {Black solves hisimmediate difficulties with} Rde8 17. Nc3 Nd5 $1 ({more ambitious than} 17...Ng6 18. Ne4 {, when after} Bd5 {, White can choose between} (18... Ngxe5 $2 {fails to} 19. Bxe5 Nxe5 20. Nf6) 19. Bxg4+ ({and} 19. Nc3 Be6 20. Ne4 {,repeating}) 19... Kb8 20. Nc3 Ngxe5 {, which is about equal}) 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 {, intending 19...Nxe5, with good play.}) 15... h6 $1 {ANSWER: This is typicalof Lasker's play, keeping the tension and presenting his opponent with severaloptions of similar strength.} ({It's possible that Lasker rejected the natural} 15... Ng6 {because after, for instance,} 16. Bg5 Rd7 ({or} 16... Rde8) 17.Bf6 Re8 18. Rf1 {(to prevent ...Bf5)} Ngxe5 19. b3 {, followed by Kb2, White'sgame is very comfortable and, now that his pieces are active, easy to play.})16. Bd3 ({Bird wasn't satisfied with} 16. b3 Ng6 17. Kb2 Ncxe5 18. Rad1 {, with equality; he wants to obstruct Black's plan.}) 16... Ng6 $1 {Continuingin the same vein. The bishops of opposite colour are not to be feared, becausethere are still many pieces on the board, and Black's bishop will be moreactive than White's. Admittedly Black gets doubled g-pawns, which can be aweakness, but Lasker has something in mind for them.} 17. Bxg6 fxg6 {QUESTION:Isn't it a concession, not being able to recapture towards the centre? ---ANSWER: No, even if the h-pawn was still on h7 instead of h6, this capturewould be better, because after ...hxg6 the pawns would lack mobility, whereasnow Lasker is going to advance them, gaining space on the kingside.} 18. Rd1 $6{White's development lag persists.} ({It's true that after} 18. b3 {Blackregains the pawn and is fine after} h5 {and ...h4, with ...Rhf8 and/or ...Bf5also on the agenda, but the text move is inferior to 18 b3, followed by Kb2 assoon as possible.}) 18... Rde8 ({Simply} 18... Rxd1+ 19. Kxd1 g5 20. Bg3 h5 {was good, regaining the pawn, but Lasker prefers to keep more pieces on theboard. It's possible that exchanging rooks was objectively better, but now theplay is more complicated and the opponent is faced with more problems.}) 19. e4({This gains space and increases the scope of White's bishop but, once again,it made more sense to play} 19. b3 {.}) ({On the other hand, it isn'tadvisable to keep playing with the just the developed pieces: for instance,} 19. Ne4 {, heading for f6, can be met with} Bf7 $1 20. Nf6 Re6 {, followed by ...Nxe5.}) 19... g5 20. Bg3 ({If White had tried to return the pawn with} 20.Be3 {, intending to answer} Nxe5 {, with} ({Black would probably have played} 20... Bf7 $1 {, followed by 21...Rxe5, with the more active play}) 21. Bd4 Bf722. b3 {.}) 20... Rhf8 ({This isn't objectively better than} 20... h5 21. b3 h422. Bf2 Nxe5 {, but it creates more discomfort.}) 21. b3 h5 22. Rd2 ({So asnot to be left slightly worse after} 22. Kb2 h4 23. Be1 Nxe5 {.}) 22... h4 23.Bf2 Nxe5 24. Be3 $6 {A step in the wrong direction, allowing Lasker toincrease the tension.} ({White is not content to play the natural} 24. Kb2 {, with equality.}) 24... h3 $1 {Conquering the f3-square, amongst other things,as we shall see. --- Going back a bit, after the suggested 24 Kb2 Black couldplay 24...h3 in that case too, but White wouldn't have any problems with hish2-pawn because he could play 25 Bg3.} 25. Bxg5 $2 {EXERCISE: This is a clearmistake, the first one of this magnitude that White has committed. How didLasker exploit it?} ({Now} 25. g3 {is not playable due to} Nf3 26. Re2 Bd7 $1 {, preparing to lay siege to the e4-pawn with ...Bc6, followed by ...Rfe7-e7,with the option of inserting ...Bb5 to shift the rook from e2.}) ({Whiteshould respond with the long-postponed} 25. Kb2 $1 {, although Black wouldhave gained a little something by playing} hxg2 26. Rxg2 Nf3 {, with the ideaof 27...Rh8 and doubling rooks on the h-file, still with possibility of the ...Bd7-c6 manoeuvre.}) 25... g3 $1 {ANSWER: "This is the 'square' breakthrough (four pawns forming a square), which often arises in king and pawn endingsalthough it can crop up in other situations. Now Black is sure to get a passedpawn on his seventh rank, and White is in real trouble" (Nunn).} 26. hxg3 ({Slightly better, but also unpleasant, was} 26. gxh3 Nf3 27. hxg3 Nxg5 28. h4 {, with three pawns for the piece, but with some of White's pawns backward andweak. Black can play} Nf3 {,} ({or even better} 28... Nh3 {, followed by 29...Rf3 and 30...Rg8, and soon the white pawns will start to fall.})) 26... Rf1+27. Kb2 ({Of course, if} 27. Rd1 {then} hxg2 {.}) 27... Rxa1 28. Kxa1 h2 29.Rd1 Ng4 {With the threat of 30...Nf2.} 30. Rh1 {There are several ways forBlack to breach the white position. Lasker chooses one of the simplest.} Bf7 $1{With the idea of playing a timely ...Bg6 and capturing the e4-pawn.} ({The immediate} 30... Rf8 {is not any stronger, since White has} 31. Nd1 {, with the idea of Ne3.}) ({However, another way was to divert the bishop with} 30... Rh8 $1 {, threatening 31...Nf2,} {while after} 31. Bh4 {,} ({since} 31.Nd1 {can be answered strongly with} Bd7 {, planning ...Bc6;} (31... Z0)) 31...Rf8 {comes with greater force, threatening ...Rf2. If} 32. Nd1 {the key idea is} Bd7 $1 {, threatening ...Bc6 winning the pawn, so} 33. Bg5 {, once againlooking to play Ne3, and now} Rh8 $1 {, preventing} 34. Ne3 ({while if} 34. Bh4{then finally} Bc6) {, on account of} 34... Nf2 {.}) 31. Kb2 ({If Whitetransfers his knight to the kingside, sacrificing a pawn, then after} 31. Ne2Rxe4 32. Nf4 {Black can exploit the opening of the long diagonal with} Re5 $133. Bh4 Bd5 {, followed by ...Bc6 and ...Rf5, intending to sacrifice theexchange on f4 and then play ...Bxg2.}) 31... c6 $1 {Not giving White anyunnecessary chances.} ({Here} 31... Bg6 {was also good, but then if} 32. Nd5 {, with the idea of 33 Ne3 or 33 Nf6, there is only one continuation thatretains the advantage:} Re5 $1 {.}) 32. Kc1 Bg6 33. Kd2 Rxe4 {Cutting offWhite's king from the kingside, and we already know that the disappearance ofthe e4-pawn will give Black's bishop access to the long diagonal.} 34. Nd1 ({Here} 34. Bf4 {fails to} Re7 35. Nd1 Rd7+ {, with the same continuation as weshall see in the game.}) 34... Rd4+ 35. Ke2 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker finishoff the game? --- ANSWER:} Rxd1 $1 {With the same combination as he would haveplayed in answer to 34 Nd1; the h2-pawn will cost White his rook.} 36. Rxd1 Be437. Rd8+ Kc7 38. Rd1 Bxg2 39. Bd8+ Kc8 40. Bb6 Bd5 $1 {. Of course, notoverlooking the threat of mate on d8. --- Lasker sought a match againstTarrasch, but the latter considered that Lasker didn't yet have a sufficientlystrong record to merit a match. As such, Lasker realized that he didn't haveany further suitable opponents in Europe, so he made what could be consideredthe reverse of the journey taken by Paul Morphy three decades earlier; hedecided to go to play in America.} 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker in America"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{On the 6th of October 1892, Emanuel Lasker travelled to the Americancontinent, where he was made welcome at the Manhattan Chess Club in New York.--- Lasker gave simultaneous displays and also received invitations to Cubafrom the Havana Chess Club, where in 1893 he played short matches against thestrongest masters on the island, César Golmayo Zúpide, whom he defeated2½-½ (+2 =1), and Andrés Clemente Vásquez (3-0).} 1. Z0 {Between 1892 and1893 he played against one of the USA's best players, Jackson Showalter, whomhe defeated 7-3 (+6 -2 =2). Let's look at one game from this match.} *[Event "5: Kokomo (match)"][Site "?"][Date "1892.??.??"][Round "7"][White "Showalter, J"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C11"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "108"][EventDate "1892.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 dxe4 5. Bxf6 $6 {QUESTION: I'm notfamiliar with this variation, but exchanging when it's not forced strikes meas strange. --- ANSWER: It's not the usual continuation, and it is inferior to5 Nxe4, even though it was employed by some great players of the past, such asTartakower, Spielmann, Najdorf, and even by Alekhine. --- The explanationwould be this: at the cost of a tempo White wants to force Black to make aconcession. Black either recaptures with the queen, allowing 6 Nxe4 with again of time, or else with the pawn, leaving himself with doubled pawns, whichwould not be forced if Black could play 5...Be7 or 5...Nbd7.} gxf6 $1 {Blackis not afraid of having doubled pawns. Although the kingside is left weakened,Black gains time for activating his pieces and opening the game for his pairof bishops.} 6. Nxe4 f5 $1 7. Ng3 ({Against Tartakower in Vienna 1922,Alekhine preferred} 7. Nc3 {, but Black was fine after that. Alekhinecommented that Showalter's move "offered less possibilities", precisely onaccount of Lasker's response.}) 7... c5 $1 {Opening the game and vaporizingthe white centre.} 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. Bc4 {QUESTION: Sacrificing a pawn? Why? ---ANSWER: Since neither exchanging on c5 nor defending the pawn seemedattractive, White is relying on his advantage in development, either to takethe initiative or else regain the pawn under favourable conditions.} ({Hewould have preferred to play} 9. Bb5 $4 {, but this fails to} Qa5+ {.}) 9...cxd4 10. O-O h5 ({QUESTION: Based on what you've just said, isn't Blackrunning a risk, taking time out to advance this pawn? --- ANSWER: Not really,as White's development advantage hasn't equipped him with any direct threats.Lasker would have preferred to play} 10... Bg7 {, but that would allow} 11. Nh5{; now h5 is under Black's control and White has to take account of a possibleadvance with 11...h4.}) ({There was a good alternative in} 10... Bd7 11. Nxd4Qf6 {, with the idea of castling on the queenside; it would be risky for Whiteto prevent this with} 12. Nxc6 Bxc6 {, due to the pressure on g2 after atimely...Rg8.}) 11. Re1 Qf6 {Lasker decides to play it safe; he defendsagainst the threat of 12 Nxf5 and plans to play ...Bd7 and castle long.} ({Here} 11... Bb4 {came into consideration, when the exchange sacrifice} 12. Nxf5 ({instead, retreating the rook to e2 deprives the g3-knight of its best retreatsquare and after} 12. Re2 Be7 {Black would be threatening the unpleasant 13...h4}) 12... Bxe1 13. Qxe1 {is unconvincing due to} Qa5 $1 {. There are manypossibilities overall. Perhaps the more complicated option 11...Bb4 isobjectively better than the text move, but 11...Qf6 gives Black a verycomfortable game.}) 12. Bb5 {White regains the pawn and achieves a more orless equal position.} Bd7 13. Bxc6 Bxc6 14. Qxd4 {Naturally White is happy toenter the endgame, since he will be able to break up Black's bishop pair.} Qxd415. Nxd4 O-O-O 16. Nxc6 bxc6 {QUESTION: White's pawn structure is much thesuperior, with two pawn islands' against Black's four, so is White not betterhere? --- ANSWER: He would be, if only he could stabilize the game: forexample, by posting his knight on c4. The static factors in the positionfavour White, but Black will try to neutralize these by deploying his dynamictrumps, activating his bishop and his rooks.} 17. Rad1 Bd6 {For the momentBlack doesn't want to simplify, because he will need to activate both hisrooks to make his activity count.} 18. Nf1 {White transfers his knight asquickly as possible to the strong and secure post on c4.} Kc7 19. Ne3 Be5 20.Nc4 Bf6 21. c3 {This is not a serious error, but it allows Black to makeprogress. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker now continue?} ({More precise, from thepractical point of view, was} 21. Rxd8 Rxd8 22. Kf1 {, with balanced play.})21... Rd5 $1 {ANSWER: Now Black consents to the exchange of rooks, but only asthis improves his structure.} 22. Ne3 Ra5 {Provoking a new weakness. White'ssound pawn structure is beginning to be eroded; it's not serious yet, but thetension of the struggle is maintained.} 23. a3 Rb8 {The last black piece comesinto play, putting pressure on White's queenside.} 24. Re2 f4 25. Nc4 Rd5 26.Red2 $2 {EXERCISE: White is relying too much on the apparent solidity of hisposition. How did Lasker punish him? --- ANSWER:} Rxd2 $1 27. Rxd2 Bxc3 $1 {Black wins an important pawn and now has a big advantage, but there is still abig struggle ahead, since Black doesn't have a passed pawn yet, while Whitehas a strong knight and can operate along the c-file.} 28. Rc2 ({If now} 28.bxc3 $4 {Black mates after} Rb1+ {.}) 28... Bd4 29. b4 {EXERCISE: Lasker madea weak move here. Nunn maintains that it was not uncommon for Lasker toconcede chances when he had the advantage, and this is an example. What wouldyou play here?} Rd8 $6 {Very logical, occupying the open file, but it wastesan important opportunity to rid himself of the weakness on c6, and open morelines for his bishop.} ({ANSWER: That is} 29... c5 $1 {, when Black hassufficient resources to support his pawn;} 30. Nd2 {is no better: Black plays}(30. Na5 {can be answered with} Kd6 $1 {. After} 31. Nb3 {Black would replywith the elegant continuation} cxb4 $1 32. Nxd4 bxa3 {, and the weakness ofWhite's back rank, which forces him to waste a tempo, means that the passedpawn, supported by the active king and rook, wins for Black:} 33. Kf1 Kd5 34.Nf3 Rb2 {, and wins.} (34... Z0)) 30... Kd7 $1 31. bxc5 Rb2 (31... Rb5 {is also good}) 32. Rxb2 Bxb2 {, and as the white king can't take part in thestruggle, Black will capture both White's queenside pawns and remain with adecisive passed pawn.}) 30. Kf1 e5 (30... c5 $5 {was still interesting here. If} 31. Nd2 {, then} ({while after} 31. bxc5 {Black can choose between severalcontinuations; one idea is} Rd5 32. Nd6 Bxc5 {and now if} 33. Nxf7 {then} Kd7 {, when White has to worry about his offside knight, as well as his a3- andf2-pawns}) 31... Kb6 {is fine.}) 31. Ke2 e4 32. Na5 Rd6 33. a4 {"White hasmanaged to work up some significant counterplay and now threatens to play 34Kc4, pinning the bishop against the e4-pawn and intending simply 35 Nxc6. Wecan see how much better off Black would have been had he exchanged his weakc-pawn by playing ...c5 earlier" (Nunn).} f5 34. Nb3 ({If White plays} 34. b5{Black can solve his problems with} c5 35. Nc6 Kb6 {, threatening 36...a6.Then if} 36. Ne7 Rd7 37. Nxf5 Bf6 $1 {, with the idea of 38...Rd5; now} 38. Rc4{can be answered with} Rd5 39. Nh6 Rd4 $1 {, and White's queenside will sooncollapse completely.}) 34... Kd7 ({The king was uncomfortable on the c-file,but it was interesting to preface this with} 34... h4 {, with the idea ofcontinuing with 35...h3 36 gxf3 f3+, and only after} 35. h3 {play} Kd7 {, the difference being that in that case Black would have the g3-squareavailable: for example,} 36. Rc4 Be5 37. f3 Rg6 $1 38. Kf1 Rg3 ({or} 38... exf339. gxf3 Rg3 {), and Black has the advantage.})) 35. Rc4 $1 Be5 ({Slightlybetter was} 35... Bb6 36. a5 f3+ $1 37. gxf3 exf3+ 38. Ke1 ({not} 38. Kxf3 $4Rd3+) 38... Bc7 39. Nd4 Rg6 40. Nxf3 Rg4 {, but this was perhaps insufficientto win after} 41. Rc5 {.}) 36. Nc5+ $2 {And now White makes an error.} ({The idea is a good one, to weaken Black's structure, but the correct moveorder was} 36. f3 $1 Rg6 ({not} 36... e3 $2 37. Nc5+ {and Nd3}) 37. Kf1 exf338. gxf3 {, with the idea of 39 Nc5+ and Nd3, and with so many weak blackpawns, it is hard to see how Black could breach the white position.}) 36... Ke737. f3 $2 {Now White loses. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker win the game "forthe second time"?} ({It was necessary to acknowledge the error and play} 37.Nb3 $1 {. Then after} h4 {(threatening 38...h3) "} 38. h3 Rd3 39. Na5 f3+ 40.gxf3 Rxf3 41. Nxc6+ Kf6 42. Nxe5 Kxe5 43. Rc7 {White will lose a pawn, but therook ending could well be a draw; for example,} a6 44. b5 axb5 45. axb5 Rxh346. Rh7 Rb3 47. Rxh4 Rxb5 48. Rh8 {and White is out of danger" (Nunn).})37... Rd4 $1 {ANSWER: This could have been prevented by keeping the knight onb3. The exchange of rooks is forced and Black can then comfortably press homethe advantage of his extra pawn.} 38. Rxd4 Bxd4 39. Nb3 {White succeeds inexchanging two pawns, but Black still has the extra passed c-pawn.} Bc3 40.fxe4 fxe4 41. Nc5 Bxb4 42. Nxe4 Ke6 {Not only is the bishop superior to theknight when there are pawns on both wings, but here the black king is also themore active and can threaten to invade on either flank. Moreover, of course,Black has an extra pawn, which restricts the mobility of the white pieces.} 43.Kd3 Ke5 44. g3 {White exchanges another pawn, but the evaluation of the endingremains unchanged.} ({If White waits, with} 44. Ng5 {, for instance, there areseveral ways for Black to win. One is to play} Bf8 {, planning...Bg7, with theidea of advancing the passed pawn with ...Kd5 and ...c5-c4.}) 44... fxg3 45.Nxg3 ({After} 45. hxg3 {Black can win with} c5 {, threatening 46...c4+, andWhite can hardly move; if the knight retreats then 46...Be1 is decisive.})45... h4 46. Ne2 Bc5 {Now the target is the h2-pawn, which is defencelessagainst an attack by Black's bishop and king. The rest is easy.} 47. Kc4 Bf248. a5 Ke4 49. Nc1 h3 50. Nd3 Bg1 51. a6 Kf5 52. Kc3 Bxh2 53. Nf2 Bg1 54. Nxh3Bb6 {. The knight is stranded on h3 and will be lost after ...Kg4. --- On the31st of August 1893 Emanuel Lasker issued a challenge to William Steinitz forthe world title, a challenge which was accepted. The match was to be played in1894 in various cities in the USA and Canada. Shortly afterwards Laskersoundly defeated Alfred Ettlinger in New York by 5-0. --- Lasker finished 1893with another brutal display of strength; he won the New York Impromptutournament with 13 points out of 13, defeating the strongest North Americanmasters: Adolf Albin, Jackson Showalter, and, among others, the young HarryPillsbury. --- Let's see two games from this tournament.} 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Defence by infinite resistance"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Of course, the hundred percent was achieved not only with wins where Laskergradually outplayed his opponent; he also won games like this one, from aninferior, or even lost, position.} 1. Z0 {Lasker continues to offer maximumresistance, fighting to the end, seeking the most tenacious move at every turn.Nunn expresses it thus: "This is 'defence by infinite resistance', in whichthe defender seeks at all costs to deny his opponent a forced win and spinsthe game out to give the opponent a greater chance of going wrong". And, aswe have seen, and will see many times, Lasker's opponent doesn't manage tomaintain the same level of concentration and makes mistakes.} *[Event "6: New York"][Site "?"][Date "1893.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Showalter, J"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C79"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "66"][EventDate "1893.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O d6 {Lasker chooses to leavethe classical Closed Ruy Lopez and instead transposes to the Steinitz DefenceDeferred.} 6. d4 Bd7 7. Nc3 exd4 ({Here Black can also play} 7... b5 {, whichwas Schlechter's preference. Without the inclusion of 3...a6 4 Ba4, the mostcommon continuation is 6...Be7, intending after 7 Re1, which threatens to wina pawn with 8 Bxc6 and 9 dxe5, only now to play 7...exd4, avoiding theso-called 'Tarrasch Trap'. With 6...Be7 (answered not with 7 Re1, but with 7Bxc6), Lasker had suffered a resounding defeat in the second game of his 1892match against Showalter himself. This time he decided to exchange, althoughthe course of this game develops in a similar fashion.}) 8. Nxd4 Be7 9. Bxc6 ({QUESTION: Why does White give up the bishop pair? --- ANSWER: To avoidsimplification with ...Nxd4, which could follow a developing move such as} 9.Be3 {.}) ({The alternative is to double Black's pawns with} 9. Nxc6 {, butShowalter liked to exchange the bishop and retain the knight, which might bemore useful for his attacking ambitions against the black king. He wassuccessful with this set-up in his aforementioned win against Lasker and inthis game too he should have gained another victory.}) 9... bxc6 10. f4 {Showalter preferred to leave his rook on f1 precisely in order to play thismove The other rook can go to d1 or e1, but he plans for the king's rook tocreate threats from f1.} O-O 11. b3 {This is another part of White'saggressive set-up. He hopes that the bishop will become dangerous on the longdiagonal, instead of obstructing the e-file by being developed to e3 at somepoint.} c5 {Black is not wasting time and starts to direct his forces againstthe e4-pawn, preparing ...Bc6 followed by ...Re8 and ...Bf8, trying to showthat not everything is positive with 10 f4 - the e4-pawn can no longer bedefended solidly with f3.} 12. Nde2 Bc6 13. Ng3 Re8 14. Bb2 Bf8 15. Qd3 {EXERCISE (simple): One of the differences created by the inclusion of 3...a6 4Ba4 is that the pawn on a6 is now attacked. How did Lasker respond? --- ANSWER:} a5 {Seeking to shed the weakness with ...a4, and hoping to create anotherfront, to prevent White from having it all his own way on the kingside.} ({The alternative was to play the standard manoeuvre} 15... g6 {and 16...Bg7.Admittedly with the white rook on f1 rather than e1, Black would have toconsider a timely f5 advance by White more carefully than usual.}) 16. Rae1 ({QUESTION: Why does White allow ...a4 and not prevent it with} 16. a4 {- ?Isn't that much better? --- ANSWER: It's possible, but not really much betterto play 16 a4. This also has its negative side, in that it weakens White'sstructure. Black could play} Bb7 {, with the threat of 17...Ba6, and if, forinstance,} 17. Qf3 {then} Rb8 {is possible, with the idea of 18...c4 19 bxc4?Bxe4.}) 16... a4 17. Nd1 {Now that e4 is defended the knight can head for thekingside, to f2, or ideally e3.} Rb8 {Black is fine here, but in the nextphase he doesn't manage to make any progress.} ({In this position Black hasseveral ideas available: one is to open the a-file right away with} 17... axb318. axb3 {Another possible counter-blow is} h5 $5 {, with the idea of ...h4and capturing the e4-pawn. Once again,} ({and invade with} 18... Ra2 {, towhich White replies with} 19. c4 {, intending Re2;} (19. Z0)) ({another is tocontinue with} 18... g6 {and ...Bg7, but in that case Black needs to beconcerned about White breaking with f5 at an opportune moment, possiblypreceded with Qf3.}) ({Another, more attractive idea is try to exploit thefact that the knight is no longer on c3 by striking a counter-blow. ---QUESTION: A counter-blow? Where, exactly? --- ANSWER: One possibility is inthe centre, with} 18... d5 {(it is also possible to play 17...d5 immediately),which is a pawn sacrifice, but the bishop pair and White's weakened pawnstructure gives Black adequate compensation after, for instance,} 19. Bxf6 Qxf620. exd5 Rxe1 21. Rxe1 Bd7 {, attacking the pawn on f4 and with ideas of 22...Qd4+ or 22...Ra2.}) 19. Bxf6 $6 {is not advantageous. After} Qxf6 20. Nxh5 Qd4+{:} {Here} 21. Nf2 {is an improvement, but after} ({it would not be advisablefor White to go} 21. Qxd4 $6 {, because of} cxd4 22. Nf2 Bb5 23. Nd3 d5 $1 {, and the f8-bishop comes into play, as with} 24. exd5 ({or} 24. e5 Ra2) 24...Rxe1 25. Rxe1 Ra2 26. Rc1 Ba3 {. In both these lines it would be better forWhite not to accept the sacrifice, but then his attack would not easily makeprogress.}) 21... Qxd3 22. cxd3 {a new weakness on b3 appears, and Black canplay} Reb8 ({or the less direct} 22... Be7 {, controlling f6, planning to play...g6 and then activate the bishop.})) 18. c4 Bb7 {A waiting move, given that19 Ne3? is not playable due to 19...Nxe4.} ({After} 18... g6 {it would bepossible to play} 19. Ne3 {, since after} Nxe4 20. Ng4 Bg7 21. Bxg7 f5 {White would have compensation for the pawn.}) 19. Rf3 {In contrast to Black,White makes a move that might be useful. If Black plays 19...g6 White's movelends force to an eventual advance with f5, enabling the rooks to be doubledon the f-file.} axb3 20. axb3 Bc8 {Black prefers to keep waiting, relying onthe solidity of his position.} ({Once more, he rejects} 20... g6 {or even theimmediate} 21. f5 {, when after} ({which White could answer with} 21. Nf2 Z0 (21... Z0)) (21. Ne3) 21... Bg7 22. fxg6 fxg6 ({better than} 22... hxg6 $2 23.Ref1) 23. Ne3 Nxe4 24. Bxg7 Kxg7 ({and not} 24... Nxg3 $4 25. Bf6) 25. Ng4 {White has compensation for the pawn.}) 21. Ne3 Bb7 {QUESTION: I'm somewhatconfused by Black's comings and goings. What's the evaluation of thisposition? --- ANSWER: Let's allow Nunn to speak: "Lasker has handled theearly middlegame in a combative fashion, and has the two bishops and pressureagainst e4 as long-term advantages. However, in compensation White hasattacking chances on the kingside, with g7 being the main target. Currentlythe prospects are roughly balanced, but even a small slip by Black would giveWhite's attack real teeth."} 22. Nef5 {EXERCISE: How should Black respondhere?} g6 $2 {This is more serious than "a small slip". Showalter 'sprecise play over the next few moves marks this down as a grave weakening.} ({ANSWER: The correct move was} 22... Re6 $1 {, defending f6 and freeing thequeen to move to e8, continuing the pressure against the e4-pawn.}) 23. Qc3 $1{This is the problem. The invading knight is able to remain on f5 and inaddition Black suffers from the weakness of his kingside and White's pressuredown the long diagonal.} Re6 $2 {EXERCISE: How did Showalter punish Lasker forhis mistake?} (23... gxf5 $2 {was unplayable because of} 24. Nh5 $1 {, with amating attack. Lasker defends the knight in the most natural way, butShowalter's clever play will prove that it is insufficient.}) ({It wasn't easyto see that Black's best chance of defence lay in} 23... h6 $1 {, clearing h7for the monarch. With best play White could still gain an advantage, but inpractice this would be difficult, because at several points along the wayWhite would have to find the most precise move. --- Nunn analyzed the positiondeeply. Let's look at a part of what he considers to be White's bestcontinuation:} 24. Ne3 Bg7 25. f5 {(threatening to win with 26 fxg6)} Re5 $1 (25... Nh5 $2 {loses, because the exchange leaves Black's king position tooweak after} 26. Qd2 Nxg3 ({or} 26... Bxb2 27. Qxb2 {and Black must give upmaterial to prevent mate}) 27. Rxg3 Bxb2 28. Qxb2 Bxe4 29. Ng4) 26. Qc1 Nxe4 ({if} 26... Nd7 $2 {White continues his attack with} 27. Ng4 {, postponing thewin of the exchange}) 27. Bxe5 Bxe5 28. fxg6 Nxg3 29. gxf7+ Kf8 30. Rxg3 Bxg331. hxg3 Qg5 32. Qb2 $1 {("If White didn't have this tactical continuation,then he would have no advantage at all" as Nunn pointed out)} Kxf7 33. Nf5 $1Qxf5 34. Rf1 Qxf1+ 35. Kxf1 Re8 {, followed by ...Re6, trying to construct afortress; White is obviously better, but the path to victory is not clear.})24. Nh5 $1 {ANSWER: A beautiful move, designed to open the g-file and set upan awkward pin on the long diagonal, but if Black had played 23...h6!, hecould have captured the knight and sheltered his king on h7, with betterdefensive prospects.} gxh5 25. Rg3+ Kh8 26. Qf3 $1 {Once again the best move.The queen heads towards the kingside, with the threat of 27 Qxh5 followed byoccupying the g-file with 28 Qg5 or 28 Qg4. Black now has a very bad position,but Lasker was not inclined to give up without offering the maximum possibleresistance.} h4 $5 {The best method of defence. "Not allowing a simple win,extending the game and giving the opponent a tricky choice between apparentlyfavourable lines" (Nunn). The two alternatives are 27 Nxh4 and 27 Rg5.} 27.Nxh4 $2 {And at last White falters. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue tooffer the maximum resistance?} ({Instead,} 27. Rg5 $1 {was decisive, with theidea of continuing slowly with 28 Qh5 Qd7 29 Qxh4 (or 29 Nh6), or 28 Qg4 Re529 Qxh4. Black is surprisingly helpless:} {while} d5 ({for example,} 27... Be7{loses to} 28. Nh6 ({the move order} 28. Qh5 {also works, planning 29 Qxf7 or29 Nh6}) 28... Qf8 29. Qh5) 28. cxd5 Bxd5 {doesn't do anything to help; Whitecan win either by pinning the bishop with} 29. Rd1 ({or by continuing theattack with} 29. Qg4 {.})) 27... h6 $1 {ANSWER: Black protects the g5-square,which is important in order to hinder the manoeuvre Qh5, attacking f7,followed by Qg5; it also gives Black's king a possible escape square.} ({Another possibility, one that a master would be reluctant to choose over theboard, was} 27... Ra8 {, trusting in the defences of his weakened kingside tohold. Surprisingly there is no clear win for White after} 28. Qh5 ({or} 28. Qg4Re5 $1) 28... Ra2 29. Qxf7 Rxb2 30. Qxe6 Bc8 31. Qf7 Ng4 {.}) 28. Qh5 $2 {With this further error White's advantage disappears completely.} (28. Qg4 {was best, after which} Re5 $1 {is forced. White is slightly better following}29. Ng6+ $1 (29. Qf3 Re6 {yields no more than a draw}) 29... Kh7 {(forced)} ({since if} 29... fxg6 $2 {then} 30. Qxg6 {wins}) ({while} 29... Kg7 $2 {loses to} 30. Nxe5+ Nxg4 31. Nc6+) 30. Nxf8+ Qxf8 31. Qh4 Nxe4 32. fxe5 (32. Rxe4 $2Rxe4 33. Qf6 Rd4 $1 {only draws}) 32... Nxg3 33. hxg3 Re8 34. Rf1 dxe5 35. Rf6{(threatening 36 Bc1)} Re6 {, but Black can still fight on.}) 28... Qe8 $1 {The only way to defend f7.} ({Instead,} 28... Qd7 $2 {loses to} 29. Qg4 {, threatening 30 Qg8#, and this time Black doesn't have the familiar crucialdefensive resource} Re5 {, owing to the pin on the queen;}) ({while} 28... Qe7$2 {allows} 29. Nf5 {.}) 29. Nf5 $2 {And with this further error the game islost. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker now turn the position around?} ({Whitecould still draw with} 29. Qg4 Re5 30. Qf3 Re6 31. Qg4 {and a repetition ofmoves.}) ({There was also a draw to be had with} 29. Nf3 {(threatening 30 Qg4Re5 31 Qh4, as indicated by Nunn)} Bg7 30. Qh4 {, intending 31 Ng5, and if}Rxe4 31. Rxe4 Qxe4 32. Bxf6 Qb1+ 33. Kf2 Qc2+ {, etc.}) 29... Kh7 {ANSWER: Theonly move, and a winning one: the pin disappears and the f6-knight regains itsfull powers.} 30. Bxf6 {Exchanging this bishop is almost equivalent toresignation, but in any case Black is a piece up and his king is now out ofdanger.} ({If} 30. Qh4 {or even better} Nxe4 {: for example,} ({then} 30...Bxe4 {is good;} 31. Z0 (31. Z0)) 31. Ng7 Nxg3 32. Rxe6 (32. Nxe8 Rxe1+ 33. Kf2Rbxe8 {is worse}) 32... Bxg7 33. Rxe8 Bxb2 $1 {with a decisive advantage;} ({better and prettier than} 33... Rxe8 {.})) 30... Rxf6 31. Nh4 Rxf4 32. Nf3 f633. Qxe8 Rxe8 0-1[Event "7: New York"][Site "?"][Date "1893.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Albin, A"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D08"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "61"][EventDate "1893.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {It could be said that the Albin Countergambit was born inthis game; although this move had been played before, it was not in atournament of any great strength. --- The gambit was soon adopted by attackingplayers such as Marshall, and in more recent times it has been playedoccasionally by Morozevich and Nakamura, among others. Lasker himself used itonly once in an official game, although he played it more often insimultaneous displays, and with a 100% record according to Mega Database 2018.}3. dxe5 d4 4. Nf3 ({On the first appearance of this position, in C.Salvioli-M.Navallotti, Milan 1881, White played} 4. e4 {, a move that was later employedby Spassky a number of times in his youth.}) 4... Nc6 5. a3 {QUESTION: Iunderstand that this was Lasker's first game against this line and it musthave come as a surprise to him, but isn't this response far too restrained?--- ANSWER: Not really. In fact, meeting this line for the first time, Laskerplayed a move which might appear restrained, but which even today is one ofthe main continuations. Lasker also used this move again, many years later, inanother important game, against Alekhine. White not only controls theb4-square, but also prepares a timely b4, indirectly threatening the d4-pawn.}({Nevertheless, the most popular move here is} 5. g3 {.}) 5... Bg4 6. h3 ({QUESTION: What's this? First a3 and now h3! And on top of that he's invitingdoubled pawns? --- ANSWER: This time your question has greater justification,as evidenced by the fact that later Lasker himself, in his game againstAlekhine at St. Petersburg 1914, preferred the developing move} 6. Nbd2 {, so that after} Qe7 7. h3 Bxf3 {he could preserve his pawn structure with} 8.Nxf3 {. We shall see that game further on.}) ({Incidentally, in the onlytournament game where Lasker took the black side of the Albin, A.Hodges-Em.Lasker, Cambridge Springs 1904, his opponent played a weaker line which aidedBlack's development:} 6. Bg5 Be7 7. Bxe7 $6 {, and after} Qxe7 8. Nbd2 O-O-O 9.Qa4 Kb8 10. O-O-O f6 11. exf6 Nxf6 12. h3 Bh5 13. g4 Be8 $1 14. Qb3 Nd7 $1 {Black gained a clear advantage.}) 6... Bxf3 7. gxf3 {Lasker prefers to capturetowards the centre and develop then his f1-bishop on the long diagonal.} ({Curiously the alternative capture is preferred almost unanimously by today'sengines, which recommend} 7. exf3 Nxe5 8. f4 {.}) 7... Nxe5 8. f4 Nc6 ({A difficult decision, but now that White has played 7 gxf3, the move} 8... Ng6$1 {is more attractive, since unlike after the capture 7 exf3, White can nolonger protect the h4-square in healthy fashion with 9 g3. Although 8...Ng6!would leave Black's queenside unprotected, he would stand well after} 9. Qb3Rb8 {, followed by 10...Bd6, with comfortable development.}) 9. Bg2 ({Interpolating} 9. Qb3 Rb8 {is not really advantageous. It's true that Blackwould be prevented from castling long, but that wouldn't cause him problems,since he can develop his kingside minor pieces to good squares and then castleshort. Lasker had another idea.}) 9... Qd7 {EXERCISE: How do you think Laskercontinued here? --- ANSWER:} 10. b4 $1 {This marks the start of a siege of thed4-pawn.} ({Objectively (and we can see in several of Lasker's games that theobjectively best move isn't always the most effective in practice!), this moveis of similar strength to} 10. Nd2 {, but with this move order White preparesBb2. At the same time White is looking to create threats against Black'seventual queenside-castled position. Castling for White can wait.}) 10... a6 {A slight concession, but it seems acceptable.} ({To be considered weredeveloping moves, such as} 10... Nge7) (10... g6) ({or even} 10... O-O-O {. White has many options against all of these, but the play isn't clear.}) 11.Bb2 Rd8 $6 {But now this is definitely questionable.} ({QUESTION: Really? Itlooks a good move, bolstering the d4-pawn, so why is it questionable? ---ANSWER: Because it leaves Black's kingside still undeveloped and postpones thepossibility of striking at White's weaknesses on f4 and h4, which could havebeen done with} 11... Nge7 $1 {There is no need for Black to fear} 12. b5 ({and after} 12. Nd2 {Black has time to play} Ng6 {under favourable conditions.}(12... Z0)) 12... axb5 13. cxb5 Na5 {, since the d4-pawn is immune fromcapture:} 14. Qxd4 $2 {, loses to} ({while} 14. Bxd4 $2 {is also bad in view of} O-O-O 15. e3 Nf5) 14... Qxd4 15. Bxd4 Nb3 {.}) 12. Nd2 {Lasker still refusesto reveal the future location of his king. The most precise course of actionis to continue laying siege to the d4-pawn, threatening either to capture itor else open up the game with e3, activating both White's bishops.} Nge7 $6 {This leads to a difficult position.} ({Instead,} 12... Bd6 {deservedconsideration, when as well as 13 Nb3 or 13 Ne4, White can consider} 13. e3 {as such, Black has to play} Nf6 {, when White is still slightly better, butthe struggle continues and it is clear that Black is better off here than inthe game continuation.} ({after which} 13... Nge7 $2 {, loses to} 14. c5) ({while} 13... Nh6 {is dubious on account of} 14. Be4 {, followed by Qc2 and0-0-0;} (14. Z0))) 13. Nb3 Nf5 {EXERCISE: How do you think Lasker responded to13...Nf5 - ?} ({The main alternative was} 13... Ng6 {The immediate} 14. e3 $1 {also deserved consideration and it is surprising how, even though White givesup a pawn, he gains the advantage by exploiting the strength of hislight-squared bishop in the ending: for example,} ({when White would have someadvantage after} 14. Qd2 Bd6 15. e3 Nh4 16. Bd5 {, with the idea of 0-0-0,leaving White's pieces better placed than their black counterparts.} (16. Z0))14... dxe3 15. Qxd7+ Rxd7 16. fxe3 Rd3 17. Nd4 Rxe3+ 18. Kf2 Nxd4 ({or} 18...Rd3 19. Rhe1+ {, followed by Nxc6, when Black is playing without his kingsidepieces}) 19. Kxe3 Nc2+ 20. Kd2 Nxa1 21. f5 $1 {(sidetracking the knight)} Nh422. Bxb7 Nxf5 23. Rxa1 {, and White's bishops, together with his bettercoordination, give him big advantage; his passed pawns will be more dangerousthan Black's.}) 14. Qd3 $1 {ANSWER!} ({There were several good moves, such asthe simple} 14. Qd2 {, also preparing queenside castling, but the queen isbest placed on d3, putting pressure on the knight, which might lend strengthto a future Bxc6, if Black is then forced to double his pawns. Also hanging inthe air is the unpleasant idea of h4 and Bh3.}) 14... Be7 ({If} 14... Nh4 {White can, amongst other things, simply play} 15. Bxc6 Qxc6 16. O-O-O {, andthe d4-pawn is doomed.}) ({Meanwhile} 14... Bd6 {wouldn't really improve thesituation much for Black, since White could ignore it with} 15. O-O-O $1 {, renewing the threat to destroy Black's queenside with Bxc6, followed by thecapture of the d4-pawn, while} Bxf4+ {runs into} 16. e3 $1 {, when} Bh6 {can be answered strongly with...} ({and} 16... dxe3 {loses to} 17. Qe4+) 17.Nc5 Qc8 18. Nxb7 Qxb7 19. Qxf5 {.}) 15. Be4 {White pushes back the knight andgains more ground.} (15. O-O-O {was also very strong.}) 15... Nd6 16. Nc5 Qc817. Bf3 {This could be regarded as a typical decision on Lasker's part.} ({White has several good continuations here, but Lasker chooses the one thatmaintains the pressure, seeking more than he could achieve with} 17. Bxc6+ bxc618. Qxd4 f6 {.}) (17. Bd5 {was also possible;}) ({but} 17. Bxh7 {was not gooddue to} Nxc4 $1 {.}) 17... O-O {EXERCISE: Once again there are severalattractive continuations. What did Lasker choose? --- ANSWER:} 18. Rg1 $1 (18.O-O-O {was also good, but Lasker prefers to bring another piece into play andat the same time highlight the weakness of g7.}) 18... Ne8 19. Nb3 {Once againkeeping the tension in a favourable situation.} ({Lasker could have played} 19.Nxb7 Qxb7 20. b5 Rd6 21. Rb1 {with advantage} ({but not} 21. bxc6 $4 Qxb2 {), but he wants more. --- Admittedly the text move is in one sense a retreat,but it also a regrouping to return to an attack on the d4-pawn. In any case,18...Ne8 isn't exactly a developing move for Black.})) 19... Qd7 {The blackqueen emerges from imprisonment and seeks activity.} 20. O-O-O {Black'sposition is delicate, his pieces are poorly coordinated and the d4-pawn isabout to fall.} Qd6 21. Kb1 {Lasker is not bothered about handing over thef4-pawn for the sake of opening lines, relying on the fact that he will soonwin the d4-pawn, after which all his pieces will be better placed than theircounterparts.} ({It's a notable decision, because he could have won thed4-pawn for nothing, i.e.} 21. Qe4 $1 Nf6 22. Qf5 {. Objectively 21 Kb1 is notthe best move, but soon the practical element will justify Lasker's play -once again.}) 21... Qxf4 22. Rg4 Qh6 23. Bxc6 bxc6 $6 {This recapture,weakening Black's pawn structure, will give Black cause for regret.} (23...Qxc6 {was better. Even though White then has, in addition to the simple} 24.Rxd4 {, various possibilities to attack the black queen, there doesn't seem tobe anything definite.} ({It's important that} 24. Nxd4 {is harmless due to} Qa4$1 {, with the idea of 25...c5 or 25...a5.}) ({Also} 24. Na5 {is nothingserious in view of} Qh6 $5 {, when} 25. Nxb7 $6 {would be met with} Rb8 {and ...c5, at last achieving a glimmer of counterplay. In this last line, 25Qf3 is better, threatening Nxb7.})) 24. Rxd4 {Lasker wants to exchange Black'sbest-placed piece.} ({The alternative was} 24. Nxd4 {, but then Black canstart to reorganize his position a little with} f5 {, when} 25. Nxf5 $2 {, loses to} (25. Rgg1 {is better, but Black could respond with} Bf6) 25... Rxf5{.}) 24... Rd6 $6 ({Black can't play} 24... Nf6 $2 {due to} 25. Rxd8 {,exploiting the weakness of the back rank.}) ({He would like to avoid thepassive position arising after} 24... Rxd4 25. Bxd4 {,} ({or} 25. Nxd4 {with the idea of 26 Nf5 and Rg1 on the agenda, but he is paying a high price.})) 25. c5 $1 {Attacking the a6- pawn with gain of time, and preventing Blackfrom using the d6-square in the future.} Re6 26. Qxa6 ({Now Lasker prefers notto maintain the pressure advantageously, as with} 26. Re4 {, considering thatthe moment has arrived for concrete measures, since tactically the indirectexchange of pawns favours White.}) 26... Qxh3 {EXERCISE: It was unpleasant toplay a pawn down, but this is the main reason why Lasker played 26 Qxa6. Howdid he reply? --- ANSWER:} 27. R4d3 $1 {Taking advantage of the black queen'sposition to improve the position of his pieces.} Qg2 28. Nd4 {Placing Black ina critical position.} Rf6 {Black wants to prevent Nf5, but he runs intoanother problem. --- EXERCISE: With what manoeuvre did Lasker finish off thegame?} ({If} 28... Rg6 {instead:} {but rather} 29. Rf3 {, restricting theblack queen.} ({White probably would not play} 29. Nf5 {yet because of} Qe4 {;}(29... Z0)) {while after} 29... Qg4 ({Then} 29... Bf6 {would allow} 30. Nxc6 {;} (30. Z0)) 30. Qd3 ({or} 30. Nf5 Qe4+ 31. Qd3) ({but not} 30. Nxc6 $2 Qe4+ {) the ending would be very advantageous for White in view of his strong passeda-pawn, and meanwhile Black would be saddled with an uncomfortable defence ofthe c6-pawn.})) 29. Re3 $1 {ANSWER: There is no good defence to this attack onthe bishop (the point of 25 c5! becomes clear).} Bd8 30. Nc2 $1 {Gaining adecisive material advantage.} Rxf2 31. Rxd8 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1894 Match WCh Steinitz"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{1894 Match for the World Championship against Steinitz: On the 15th of March1894 the world championship match between Lasker and the champion WilhelmSteinitz began. It was contested in the cities of New York, Philadelphia andMontreal. The championship would be awarded to the first player to win tengames.} 1. Z0 {Lasker won 12-7 (+10 =4 -5)} *[Event "8: World Championship, New York"][Site "?"][Date "1894.??.??"][Round "1"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Steinitz, W"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C62"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "119"][EventDate "1894.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 {Commenting on this game, Steinitz complainedabout the not very enthusiastic reception given to this variation which bearshis name, for "I have seen nothing as yet to vitiate the equalizing effect,which, in my opinion, it possesses", an opinion which Lasker certainlyshared, as he also used it frequently.} 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 Nge7 {On the otherhand this move was never used by Lasker, nor by other masters such asCapablanca, who preferred to develop the knight to f6. --- Steinitz had playedit after 5 c3 in his world title match against Isidor Gunsberg in 1890. Laterthe knight development to e7 found several strong supporters, the mostimportant of whom was Keres, but Reshevsky, Portisch and Yusupov and othersalso played it. However, they all employed the move order of the SteinitzDefence Deferred: 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 Bb5 a6 4 Ba4 d6 5 c3 Bd7 6 d4 Nge7.} 6.Bc4 ({Lasker repeated this move, which threatens 7 Ng5, in Games 3 and 5 ofthe match, when Steinitz finally found the best defence, so that in thecrucial Game 7, Lasker switched to} 6. Be3 {, with the plan of queensidecastling...}) ({In 1896 Lasker again varied his lines against Steinitz, playing} 6. dxe5 dxe5 7. Bg5 {in one game}) ({and} 6. Bg5 {in another.}) 6... Nxd4 {Years later Steinitz looked for alternatives.} ({He experimented withpreventing 7 Ng5 with more passive moves such as} 6... h6) ({and} 6... Na5 {, although with scant success.}) 7. Nxd4 exd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qe3 Ne5 {QUESTION:Moving the knight again doesn't inspire me with much confidence. What'sBlack's idea? --- ANSWER: Yes, it looks suspect. In this game the idea was tofollow up with ...c6, to control d5, but the knight is exposed a timely f4thrust.} ({Steinitz improved with} 9... Be6 {in the fifth game;}) ({while thenatural} 9... Be7 {was Lasker's recommendation; both these moves are topchoices of today's engines.}) 10. Bb3 c6 ({In the third game Steinitz played} 10... Be6 {.}) 11. Qg3 $1 {A reminder that Black is neglecting his development;by putting pressure on g7 White prevents 11...Be7. Steinitz criticized hisnext move, preferring 11...Be6, although White would still be slightly better.}Ng6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker now follow up? --- ANSWER:} 12. h4 $1 {Consistent with the idea of preventing ...Be7.} ({This is more energetic than} 12. Be3) ({or} 12. Bg5 {, when} Be7 $6 {is weak in view of} 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14.O-O-O {.}) 12... Be6 ({If} 12... h5 {then White plays} 13. Bg5 {, leavingBlack the choice between two evils: to weaken his position further with} f6 ({or loosen his hold on the d6-square after} 13... Be7 {.})) 13. Bxe6 fxe6 14.Bg5 {A difficult decision.} ({Lasker plays the most healthy move, developingquickly with gain of time, leaving the pawn structure as it is. It wasattractive to gain space with} 14. h5 Ne5 15. f4 {;}) ({or} 14. f4 {first,planning to follow up with h5, without fearing} Be7 {, which could be answeredwith, amongst other things,} 15. Qg4 Nxh4 16. Be3 {. White follows with 0-0-0,when Black's poor coordination and weaknesses at e6 and g7 more thancompensate for the loss of the pawn.}) 14... Be7 15. O-O-O e5 ({If} 15... O-O {or} 16. Rd2 {, when White would also be slightly better.} ({White can play} 16.Bxe7 Qxe7 17. Rxd6 {. This doesn't win a pawn, because Black can play} Rxf2 {, but with} 18. h5 Nf8 19. e5 {White keeps a minimal advantage.} (19. Z0)) ({However, it is possible that Lasker would have eschewed this line and aimedfor more by keeping the tension with} 16. Kb1)) 16. Be3 {With this retreatWhite threatens 17 h5 and reduces the force of a future ...Nf4.} (16. Ne2 {could also be played, with similar ideas.}) 16... O-O {QUESTION: But White'slast move is a pawn sacrifice! Is it really sound? --- ANSWER: Taking the pawnon h4, with Black's king still in the centre, at first sight looks foolhardy,and in this case appearances are not deceptive.} ({After} 16... Bxh4 $2 17. Qg4{, White would be threatening 18 g3, followed by Rxh7.} {That just leaves uswith} Kf7 {, but White's compensation is clear after} ({Then} 17... Qe7 $2 {loses to} 18. g3 Bf6 19. Qxg6+ hxg6 20. Rxh8+ {and 21 Rxa8;} (20. Z0)) ({while} 17... O-O {looks suicidal due to} 18. Qh5 {.}) 18. g3 Bf6 19. f4 {.}) 17. Ne2{Lasker continues to offer the pawn on h4, and taking it continues to appeardubious.} ({He didn't consider it necessary to play} 17. h5 Nf4 18. h6 g6 19.Rd2) ({or the prophylactic move} 17. Kb1 {, before taking any other decisions.--- The text move controls f4, so that if ...Nf4 Black can't recapture withthe rook.}) 17... Rf7 ({Steinitz didn't seriously consider taking the pawn andhe commented, "Again Black would expose himself to great danger by} 17...Bxh4 {Probably Lasker would have chosen} 18. Qh2 $1 {, when after} (18. Qg4 {followed soon by Qh5". --- EXERCISE: In that case the sacrifice is not asclear as before and 18 Qg4 isn't really the best move - why isn't it? ---ANSWER: Because Black can get away with playing} Bxf2 $1 {: for example,} 19.Qe6+ ({there is no advantage either in playing} 19. Bxf2 Rxf2 20. Qe6+ Rf7 21.Rxh7 Qg5+ 22. Kb1 Kxh7 23. Qxf7 Qxg2 $1 {, when} 24. Rg1 {loses to} Rf8 $1)19... Kh8 20. Bxf2 {, and now not} Rxf2 $4 ({but} 20... Qg5+ $1 {(this savingcheck is an argument in favour of playing 17 Kb1), followed by ...Rxf2}) 21.Qxg6) ({Instead,} 18. Qh3 {allows} Qc8 $1 19. Qh2 Qg4 $1 {In this line} 20. Ng3{is better, but Black has time to play} (20. f3 $6 Qe6 {and after havingprovoked f3, Black can answer} 21. g3 $2 {advantageously with} Rxf3 $1 {, and once again he can exploit the position of the white king on c1: forexample,} 22. Rd3 Rxe3 $1 23. Rxe3 Bg5 24. Qxh7+ Kf7 25. Rf1+ Ke8 {, and Blackis better.} 26. Z0 (26. Z0)) 20... h6 {and after} 21. Rxd6 Bg5 {he has noproblems.}) 18... h6 19. g3 Bf6 {White has compensation in the form ofpressure on the d6-pawn and Black's weakened king position. However, we can'tspeak of a white advantage here, so it seems that 17...Bxh4 was playable afterall.}) 18. h5 ({Lasker doesn't want to continue manoeuvring, but he could havekept the tension with} 18. Qh2 {, followed by Kb1 and h5.}) 18... Nf4 19. Bxf4{QUESTION: I understand that this was Lasker's idea, but is it advantageous?Can it be good for White to exchange this bishop, as it opens the longdiagonal for Black's bishop? --- ANSWER: In this position there is no greatadvantage. Lasker considered that his knight was at least as strong as Black'sbishop. After ...exf4 not only is the long diagonal opened, but White acquiresthe d4-square for his knight, which at the right moment can go to f5, hittingthe weakness on d6. Furthermore, a subsequent exchange of the bishop for theknight would leave the backward d-pawn even weaker.} exf4 20. Qf3 ({Of course,not} 20. Nxf4 $4 Rxf4 $1 {.}) ({Other squares were possible for the queen, forinstance,} 20. Qb3 {, but then} Qb6 {would be a good reply.}) 20... Qa5 {Steinitz opts to recentralize his queen on the fine square e5, from where itwill put pressure on the e4-pawn and at the same time defend the weak pointsd6 and f4.} ({Another idea was} 20... Bf6 {.}) 21. Kb1 Qe5 22. Nd4 Bf6 23. c3 {With this move White is able to neutralize a large part of the dangersresulting from having opened the long diagonal and activated Black's bishop.}Re8 24. Rhe1 Bd8 ({QUESTION: Hmm, this is a bit passive, isn't it? Wasn't itbetter to make use of the presence of the queen on e5 to break with} 24... d5 {- ?} {but would instead have maintained the tension and kept White's minimaladvantage with} 25. Qg4 $1 {. The idea is 26 Nf3, and if} ({ANSWER: That waspossible, but wouldn't change the evaluation of the position much, which isslightly favourable to White. I would hazard a guess that Lasker would nothave exchanged his two rooks for the queen with} 25. exd5 Qxe1 26. Rxe1 Rxe1+27. Kc2 Bxd4 28. cxd4 cxd5 {with equality, as pointed out by Chigorin;} (28...Z0)) 25... dxe4 26. Nf5 Rff8 27. Nd6 {White regains the pawn and is left withthe more active pieces after, for example,} Qe6 28. Qxe6+ Rxe6 29. Rxe4 Rxe430. Nxe4 Re8 31. f3 {; it is worth noting that the pawn on f4 has become aweakness.}) 25. Qg4 {Threatening to win material with 26 Nf5.} Bc7 26. Nf3 ({It was possible to play} 26. Nf5 {, of course, but after, say,} Kh8 ({or} 26...Rff8 {, it isn't clear how White can increase the pressure. Lasker preferrednot commit his knight yet and instead gave his opponent options, which wascharacteristic of Lasker's play. Doing so is an excellent practical choice,which in this case too led to a good result.})) 26... Qf6 27. Nd2 Rfe7 28. f3 {Fortifying the besieged e4-pawn and fixing the f4-pawn, which restricts themobility of Black's bishop.} d5 {Steinitz chooses one of the many playablemoves available to Black here; he eliminates the weakness of his backward pawnand activates his bishop.} 29. Rh1 {The move 28...d5 is fine for Black, but ithas its downside too as we can now appreciate. Lasker's response unpins therook, enabling White to play exd5, creating an isolated pawn on d5, whileexchanging on e4 with ...dxe4 would leave White's knight in an excellentposition on e4.} Re5 {EXERCISE: "29...Qf7 was by far better", commentedSteinitz. What did Lasker now play that caused Steinitz to remark so? ---ANSWER:} 30. g3 {"A masterly 'coup', which relieves his position on theKingside, no matter what Black reply", wrote Steinitz, which indicates thatits psychological impact was devastating.} Rg5 ({In the event of} 30... fxg3 {the idea is mobilize the pawns, gaining space with} 31. f4 R5e7 32. e5 {, followed by 33 Qxg3, which is playable for Black nevertheless after} Qe6 33.Qxg3 Rf7 {.}) 31. Qd7 Qf7 32. Qxf7+ Kxf7 33. g4 {Lasker has achieved a smallbut promising advantage. He has stabilized the kingside and transformed thepawn on f4 into a weakness, insignificant as yet, but a weakness all the same.}Bb6 ({Steinitz considered that this move was "inferior to} 33... Rge5 {", but this seems too pessimistic. It doesn't seem to make much difference,and in any case the continuation would have been} 34. exd5 cxd5 ({or} 34...Rxd5 35. Ne4) 35. Nb3 {.}) 34. exd5 cxd5 {Depriving the knight of the idealsquare, e4.} ({Steinitz commented: "} 34... Rxd5 {is preferable, leading toa natural draw position, with which I should have been content under thecircumstances", which seems to indicate that was playing for a win, somewhatcontradicting his earlier comments. Naturally Lasker would not have resignedhimself submissively to the game ending in a draw and would have continuedplaying, as with} 35. Ne4 Red8 36. Rxd5 Rxd5 ({not} 36... cxd5 $6 37. Ng5+ Kg838. Ne6) 37. Kc2 {.}) 35. Nb3 Re6 ({Black can't improve his position to anygreat degree: for instance,} 35... Re3 {can be answered simply with} 36. Rhf1 {, allowing White to manoeuvre with the knight and the other rook.}) ({Steinitzdidn't want to play} 35... Re2 {because of} 36. Nc1 {, but this seems to befine, as after} Rg2 37. Nd3 Be3 {Black has sufficient counterplay.}) 36. Rhf1 {This wasn't strictly necessary, but as Black cannot make progress, Laskeravoids the possible loss of tempo later in the event of ...Re3.} ({Nevertheless,} 36. Nd4 {was perhaps slightly better, and after, say,} Re3 37.Rhf1 {White could continue with Nf5 or Nc2, followed by Rd3 and Rfd1.}) 36...Rge5 $6 {EXERCISE (simple): How did Lasker now continue to create problems forBlack?} ({White last move allowed} 36... g6 $1 {, White last move allowed} 37.hxg6+ Rexg6 38. Rh1 {Black has} h5 $1 {, with a balanced endgame after} 39.Rxh5 Rxh5 40. gxh5 Rg5 41. Rh1 Kg7 {, planning ...Kh6 and/or ...Rg3.}) 37. Nc1$1 {ANSWER: With the obvious threat of 38 Nd3, winning a pawn.} Bc7 $6 ({Here} 37... Be3 {was better, although Black's difficulties do not disappear after}38. Nd3 Rg5 39. Nb4 Rd6 {. Now there are several plans for White: one is toplay c4, to provoke ...d4, immediately, or perhaps preceded by} 40. Rfe1 {, which would allow him to continue with Re2, thereby activating the rookwhile stepping round the dark squares that are forbidden to him;} ({alsopossible is} 40. Rd3 {, threatening to double rooks.})) 38. Nd3 Rg5 ({It wasslightly better to play} 38... Re2 {, but after} 39. Nc5 ({in this line, thetempting} 39. Nb4 {would not be so good, because of} Bd6 $1 {, since after} 40.Nxd5 Rh2 {the game should end in a draw by repetition with} 41. Rh1 Rf2 42.Rhf1 {, etc, in view of the threat of} Ree2) 39... Rb6 40. b3 {material losseswithout sufficient compensation are unavoidable.}) 39. Nb4 Ree5 40. Rd4 {And White wins a pawn, which concludes the manoeuvring phase in Lasker'sfavour.} Bb6 41. Rxf4+ Kg8 42. Nd3 ({Steinitz preferred} 42. Nc2 {, but itdoesn't seem to make a big difference.}) 42... Re2 43. Rd1 Be3 44. Rb4 {QUESTION: What does White achieve by attacking the pawns? They can easily bedefended... --- ANSWER: Lasker wants to provoke the black pawns to advance,which will allow pawns to be exchanged and lines to be opened while theg5-rook is inactive, or else will permit White to create a passed pawn.} b6 45.Ra4 a5 46. b4 {This was Lasker's idea, although Steinitz didn't think much ofit, since "This gives Black a chance for a counterattack", but thiscounterattack didn't scare Lasker, who considered it insufficient.} d4 ({Black prefers to let White have a 3 vs. 2 pawn majority, rather than openlines for the rook with} 46... axb4 47. cxb4 {. He has a big advantage ineither case.}) 47. c4 Bd2 {EXERCISE: The bishop heads for c3, seeking tocreate threats, although the knight on d3 is an excellent defender. White hasseveral good moves now, but which do you think is best?} 48. b5 {This movemaintains the advantage. The idea is to play c5 and create a passed pawn;first White will need to play 49 a3 to prevent ...Bb4 and then he will be ableto play 50 c5 bxc5 51 Rc4.} ({ANSWER: However, it was possible to play} 48. c5$1 {right away:} {which just leaves} Bxb4 {and after} ({since after} 48... axb449. c6 {the pawn will cost Black a piece; if} Bc3 {then} 50. Ra8+ {wins.}) ({Scarcely any better is} 48... bxc5 49. bxc5 {, followed by Rc4;} (49. Z0)) 49.Nxb4 axb4 50. cxb6 Rb5 {there are several possibilities, but it seems goodenough to rely on the passed a-pawn and play} 51. Rxd4 Rxb6 52. Raxb4 {. Theending should be winning for White, irrespective of whether there is anexchange of rooks or not.}) 48... Bc3 {The bishop is unable to generate manythreats on c3 and White has a good reply.} 49. Rg1 $1 {White wins the exchangewith the unpreventable threat of 50 f4.} Rd2 ({Steinitz suggested sacrificingthe exchange in another way, with} 49... Kf7 {, and he considered that after}50. f4 Rc5 51. Nxc5 bxc5 {he would have had better drawing chances. This maybe so, but the passed pawn on b6 should still bring White victory: for example,} 52. Ra3 {, with the idea of playing Rg3 and giving back the exchange to freethe rook on a3, and after} Rb2+ 53. Kc1 Rf2 {White can win with} 54. Rg3 Bb2+55. Kd1 Bxa3 56. Rxa3 Rxf4 57. Rxa5 {, when his pawns are unstoppable.}) 50. f4Rxg4 {The game was adjourned in this position.} 51. Rxg4 Rxd3 {EXERCISE: Howdid Lasker now finish off the game? --- ANSWER:} 52. c5 $1 {"Black cannotrecover from the effects of this splendid move", commented Steinitz. At astroke White creates a passed pawn and brings the a4-rook back to life.} Re3 ({As Steinitz pointed out, "If} 52... Rd1+ 53. Kc2 Rd2+ 54. Kb3 bxc5 55. Kc4 {and wins";}) ({while after} 52... bxc5 {White can play} 53. Rg5 {.}) 53. Rc4d3 54. Rg1 {Heading for d1,} ({but not} 54. Rxc3 $2 d2 55. Kc2 Rxc3+ 56. Kxd2Rxc5 {, with a draw.}) 54... d2 55. Rd1 bxc5 56. b6 Bd4 57. b7 Re8 58. Kc2 $1 {The passive rook on d1 can now be reactivated.} Rb8 59. Rb1 Kf7 60. Ra4 {. Steinitz immediately struck back, winning the second game with a violentattack, but Lasker won the third game. Steinitz once more equalized thecontest by winning the fourth game. There followed two draws and then came theseventh game, which was of supreme importance for the course of the match.Lasker won after recovering from a lost position (see the following game).} 1-0[Event "9: World Championship, New York"][Site "?"][Date "1894.??.??"][Round "7"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Steinitz, W"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C62"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "91"][EventDate "1894.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 Nge7 6. Be3 ({The reason whyLasker didn't repeat} 6. Bc4 {, after his victories in Games 1 and 3, was thatin Game 5 after} exd4 7. Nxd4 Nxd4 8. Qxd4 Nc6 9. Qe3 {, Black had improvedwith} Be6 {and, as Steinitz commented: "Black, after different experiments,came to the conclusion that the text move is Black's best reply". After} 10.Nd5 Be7 11. Bd2 O-O 12. O-O Ne5 13. Bb3 Bxd5 {, unlike the earlier games, inwhich Steinitz lost tempi with the knight, in this game he managed to completehis development and reach a satisfactory position. The continuation was} 14.Bxd5 c6 15. Bb3 Nd7 16. Rad1 a5 {("for defensive purposes to prevent Bb4,but for attacking purpose also")} 17. c3 a4 18. Bc2 Re8 19. Qh3 Nf8 {, whenBlack had built a solid position, and subsequently, as we mentioned, heobtained winning chances.}) 6... Ng6 7. Qd2 Be7 8. O-O-O ({More ambitious than} 8. O-O O-O 9. Rad1 {, when} Bg4 $1 {is good for Black, as indicated byDvoretsky.}) 8... a6 9. Be2 exd4 {Steinitz is alert.} ({He play the obvious} 9... O-O $2 {, because of} 10. dxe5 $1 {, when after} Ngxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12.f4 {White takes the initiative.}) 10. Nxd4 Nxd4 11. Qxd4 ({QUESTION: With thequeen? Why does White allow Black to go ...Bf6 with gain of time? --- ANSWER:Lasker has aggressive ideas, so he doesn't want to allow simplification.} 11.Bxd4 {could be answered with} Bg5 {, forcing the exchange of the dark-squaredbishops.}) 11... Bf6 12. Qd2 Bc6 ({If} 12... O-O {one suggestion was} 13. f3Re8 14. Nd5 {, which gives White a small advantage, but if Lasker hadcontinued in the same aggressive spirit that he has shown so far, it'spossible that he would have played 13 h4!. Then acceptance of the pawnsacrifice would give White obvious compensation in the opening of the h-fileand the possibility of quickly playing f4, g4, etc.}) 13. Nd5 ({The positioncan be handled in various different ways, ranging from the flexible} 13. Kb1) ({to the most violent move} 13. h4 {. The text move is also good and liessomewhere between the two extremes.}) 13... O-O {White has the advantage: hispieces are the more active and has more space; he can also begin a kingsidepawn storm without Black being able to anything similar against the white king.} 14. g4 {"Pawns don't move backwards! It's hard to say whether thisaggressive move was made with the desire to unsettle his tenacious opponent,or if it involved some oversight" (Kasparov).} ({There were severalattacking possibilities. Lasker later suggested} 14. f3) ({and it was alsopossible, once again, to sacrifice with} 14. h4 {.}) ({Preparing h4 with} 14.g3 {was another suggestion, and after} Re8 {White plays} 15. f3 {, with goodprospects.} ({However, not here} 15. Bf3 {because the bishop would be loose onf3 and therefore be a tactical weakness that Black could exploit with} Bxd5 16.Qxd5 Bxb2+ $1 17. Kxb2 Qf6+ {.})) 14... Re8 15. g5 {This was the idea.} (15. f3{is less energetic and after} Bxd5 16. Qxd5 Be5 {Black's control of the darksquares gives him good play;} 17. h4 {can be answered with 18...Bf4!,} ({while after a move such as} 17. Kb1 {Black can play} c6 18. Qd2 d5 $1 {, withgood play, since} 19. exd5 $6 Qxd5 $1 20. Qxd5 cxd5 21. Rxd5 $2 {fails to} Bc7$1 {, and Black wins material after} 22. Rd3 Bf4 {.})) 15... Bxd5 {EXERCISE:This is a critical moment. There are three possibilities, but only one leadsto an equal game for White. What is it?} 16. Qxd5 $6 (16. gxf6 $2 {is bad.After} Bxe4 17. f3 Bf5 18. Bd4 {, as Dvoretsky indicated, Black gains theadvantage with the energetic sequence} c5 $1 19. Bc3 d5 $1 20. Qxd5 Nf4 21.Qxf5 Nxe2+ 22. Kb1 Nxc3+ 23. bxc3 Qb6+ 24. Ka1 {, and now the strongest move is} g6 $1 25. Qf4 Re6 {, capturing on f6 with an overwhelming advantage.}) ({ANSWER: Best was} 16. exd5 $1 {, although then Black could carry out thetypical positional exchange sacrifice} Rxe3 $1 {, with good compensation after}17. fxe3 ({of course, not} 17. Qxe3 $4 Bxg5) ({while} 17. gxf6 Rh3 18. fxg7 Qh4{is no better}) 17... Bxg5 {, followed by ...Qe7.}) 16... Re5 17. Qd2 $2 {This error leaves White in a critical position. --- EXERCISE: How did Steinitznow obtain a clear advantage?} (17. Qxb7 {was necessary, although Black has agood position after} Bxg5 18. Bxg5 Rxg5 19. Rhg1 Rc5 $1 {, and "Black has aneasy game: ...a6-a5, ...Rb8, and then an attack on the kingside pawns by ...Qh4, or an attack on the king along the b- and c- files" (Kasparov).}) 17...Bxg5 $1 {ANSWER: As in earlier lines, Black takes advantage of the loose whitepieces on the e-file.} ({Instead,} 17... Rxg5 $2 18. f4 Rg2 19. Qd3 {givesWhite good compensation for the pawn; the black rook remains exposed.}) 18. f4Rxe4 $1 {The key to Black's combination. He gains a material advantage thatwould probably have led to victory against another opponent.} 19. fxg5 Qe7 20.Rdf1 {Lasker launches an attack, assuming that his chances are practical,rather than objective. --- QUESTION: I suppose with 20 Rdf1 Lasker was awarethat he was taking excessive risks and that it was better to try to make adraw in an inferior position? He is two pawns down now, so what made him takesuch a big risk?} ({In his annotations he mentioned} 20. Bf3 {, whichobjectively might be more tenacious, but after} Rxe3 21. Bxb7 Rb8 $1 ({betterthan} 21... Re2 22. Rde1 $1 Rxd2 23. Rxe7 Nxe7 24. Kxd2 Ra7 25. Be4) 22. Rhe1 (22. Bxa6 Qxg5 {opens more files for Black's attack}) 22... Rxe1 ({seeking morethan could be achieved with} 22... Re5 23. Bxa6 Qxg5 24. Qxg5 Rxg5 25. Bc4 Ne526. Bd5 Rh5) 23. Rxe1 Qd7 24. Bd5 ({not} 24. Bxa6 $2 Qa4) 24... Ne5 {Black isbetter, although Kasparov thinks his advantage is not great.}) 20... Rxe3 {ANSWER: In the lines we've just looked at White is condemned to playing 'fortwo results', whereas with the text move, the possibilities are threefold,although the losing chances are much greater and the winning chances minimal.--- This reminds me of a survey to which several top-class players responded.They were asked which they would prefer: to defend a rook endgame a pawn downor the black position after 1 e4 f5. Tal chose the second option, and it is tobe supposed that Lasker would have done the same.} 21. Bc4 {Lasker has hissights on f7 and is planning h4-h5. --- "Lasker's play is an object lessonin creating difficulties in a position where, objectively speaking, hiscompensation for the material is insufficient" (Nunn).} Nh8 {Black mustchoose between this eccentric-looking defence and 21...Rf8. With the text movehe wants to activate his rook with ...Re8, thinking that the knight will comeback into play, once the pressure on f7 has been removed.} ({Which move isbetter? Naturally the answer can't be given at a glance, but only afteranalysis, which shows that in fact} 21... Rf8 $1 {was better, when White can'tmaintain the pressure on f7 for much longer. After} 22. h4 b5 $1 ({even betterthan} 22... Re4) 23. Bb3 ({White must choose between abandoning the attack onf7 or giving up the defence of e2; since} 23. h5 bxc4 24. hxg6 Qxg5 {isinsufficient;} (24... Z0)) 23... Re2 24. Qc3 ({no better is} 24. Qd5 Nxh4 $125. Rxh4 $2 Re1+ 26. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 27. Qd1 Qxh4) 24... Qe3+ 25. Qxe3 Rxe3 26. h5Ne5 {would leave Black two pawns up.}) 22. h4 c6 {EXERCISE: Black is planningto play 23...d5, eliminating the pressure on f7. How do you think Laskerresponded? --- ANSWER:} 23. g6 $1 {From the practical point of view this isthe only chance, although objectively it might not be the best move.} ({The alternatives were} 23. Kb1) ({and} 23. Rfg1 {, both of which would beanswered with} d5 {and ...Re8, or ...Ng6, and the white position would be verydifficult to defend. It's a decision similar to the one Lasker took with 20Rdf1. --- "There now begins a sequence of irrational play, in which Lasker,as it transpires, is superior to his opponent. The problem of this position isthat in nearly all variations Black is close to a win, but everywhere Whiteretains some counter-chances. To evaluate where there are more of them, andwhere there are less, is not easy, and for more than a dozen moves Steinitz isobliged to solve a rather ticklish problem: how not to lose his decisiveadvantage?" (Kasparov).}) 23... d5 $2 {Let's let Nunn speak: "When youalready have a material advantage, it's always hard to say whether you shouldgrab more or decline further sacrifices; there's no general rule, sinceeverything depends on the exact position. Here, however, Steinitz makes aserious mistake after which White is no longer worse. The move played appearssuspect as it allows White both to remove one of the defensive kingside pawnsand to reposition his bishop with gain of time".} ({Steinitz himself latersuggested} 23... hxg6 $1 {, to answer} 24. h5 {with} g5 {.} ({Nevertheless,more than a hundred years of analysis has established a better, more concreteway: Black can play} 24... gxh5 $1 {, and repulse the attack after} 25. Rxh5Re5 $1 {, and if the white rook retreats then 26...Qg5, so White is forced toplay} 26. Rxh8+ Kxh8 27. Qh2+ Kg8 28. Bxf7+ Qxf7 29. Rxf7 Kxf7 {, and Black'stwo rooks should constitute a winning material advantage after, for instance,}30. Qf4+ Ke7 31. Qh4+ Kd7 32. Qg4+ Re6 33. Qxg7+ Re7 {(Nunn).})) 24. gxh7+ Kxh725. Bd3+ Kg8 26. h5 Re8 27. h6 ({This advance is consistent with White'sprevious energetic play, but once again it was objectively better to maintainthe tension and add force to a future h6 with} 27. Qf2) ({or} 27. Rfg1) ({or by strengthening the position with} 27. Kb1 {and 28 a3. Meanwhile Black hasno clear way to win, since after all he is playing practically without hisknight.}) 27... g6 $1 {This looks strange, but it's best in the long run.} ({Instead, after} 27... gxh6 $5 28. Rfg1+ Ng6 29. Bxg6 fxg6 30. Rxg6+ Kf7 {, White can play} 31. Rgg1 {, and although he is two pawns down, the blackking is very exposed.} (31. Rgxh6 {is also possible, and the rook endingarising after} Re1+ 32. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 33. Qxe1 Rxe1+ 34. Kd2 Rg1 {(to defend with...Rg7)} 35. b4 {, with the idea of a4-a5, appears tenable.})) 28. h7+ Kg7 29.Kb1 {In a way this is similar to the earlier suggestion of 27 Kb1. Laskerdecides to keep the tension for now, considering that Black can't noticeablyimprove his position, and he postpones entering any complications until he hasimproved the situation of his monarch. --- At some point Black will have todisturb his kingside to let the knight back into the game, and any pawnadvance will create a weakness. --- As Kasparov put it: "In this game thereis something of the 'Tal' element: White's attack is rather abstract, but itwill not come to an end - all the time some threats arise!"} Qe5 30. a3 {"Lasker's last two quiet moves were completely inexplicable to hiscontemporaries: how can you play this way when two pawns down?!" (Kasparov)--- However, having played Kb1 and given his king an escape square, White cannow use his queen to attack, since giving up control of e1 no longer resultsin mate. This will considerably increase his attacking possibilities.} c5 {Black is threatening to weaken the white king with ...c4 and ...c3.} 31. Qf2 {With the idea of 32 Qh4.} (31. c3 $2 {was not possible due to} c4 32. Bc2 {and with the bishop on d3 under attack Black can play} f5 $1 {, followedquickly by ...Nf7.}) 31... c4 {This was the idea;} ({but it was preferable totake into account the threat of Qh4, which could have been neutralized with} 31... f5 $1 {Instead, if} 32. Rfg1 {it would be good to overprotect g6 with} ({and after} 32. Qh4 Nf7 $1 33. Rhg1 Qf6 {, Black has regrouped, with a bigadvantage.} (33... Z0)) 32... Re6 {(with the possibility of a timelycounterattack with ...Rb6)} 33. Qh4 Qf6 34. Qf4 R6e5 {, and there is no clearway for White to make progress with his attack.}) 32. Qh4 f6 (32... f5 {is not possible here, because White can destroy Black's defences with} 33. Bxf5$1 gxf5 34. Rfg1+ Ng6 ({or} 34... Kf7 35. Qh5+ Ke7 {and White's attack isirresistible}) 35. Rxg6+ $1 Kxg6 36. Rg1+ Kf7 37. Qh5+ Ke7 38. Rg8 {and theh-pawn queens.}) 33. Bf5 $1 {This 'loss' of a piece was planned.} ({Thealternative was} 33. Bxg6 $5 {, which seems sufficient to equalize the gameafter} Nxg6 ({not} 33... Kxg6 $2 34. Qh6+ {and Rhg1}) 34. Rfg1 {and the gamewill probably end in a draw after} Kf7 35. Qg4 Qg5 36. Qd7+ R3e7 $1 37. Qh3 Qh438. Qxh4 Nxh4 39. Rxh4 Rh8 40. Kc1 Ke6 41. Rgh1 {, followed by Kd2, and Blackcan't make progress. Lasker's move is in no way inferior and it againmaintains the tension.}) 33... Kf7 ({Instead,} 33... gxf5 34. Rhg1+ Kf7 ({since} 34... Kf8 $2 {allows White to promote the h-pawn after} 35. Rg8+ Ke7 36. Rfg1$1 {, followed by Rxe8 and Rg8}) 35. Qh5+ {transposes to the game.}) ({Nobetter is} 33... Qg3 34. Qh6+ Kf7 {nevertheless the zwischenzug} 35. Bd7 $1 {keeps the balance, since} ({when although} 35. Rhg1 {, fails to} Re1+ 36. Ka2Qxg1 $1 (36... Z0)) 35... Rd8 $2 {, loses to} ({as such, he has to play} 35...R8e7 {and the game is likely to end in a draw after} 36. Rxf6+ Kxf6 37. Qf8+Kg5 38. Qh6+ {, etc}) 36. Rh3 $1 Re1+ 37. Ka2 Qe5 38. Rxe1 Qxe1 39. Re3 {and Black must give up his queen. --- The position is very complex, and thereare other lines, but none give Black the advantage.}) 34. Rhg1 $1 {Now Blackmust defend against the threat of 35 Bxg6+, as well as 35 Qg4, or thepreparatory move 35 Ka2.} gxf5 ({The most practical and the best. Black can'tmake progress: for example, if} 34... b5 {then White's attack is very strongafter} 35. Bxg6+ $1 Nxg6 36. Qg4 $1 Nh8 37. Qg7+ ({or} 37. Qd7+ Re7 38. Qc8 Re839. Qb7+ Re7 40. Qxa6) 37... Ke6 38. Qb7 {, with the ideas of 39 Rg8, 39 Rg7and 39 Qxa6+.}) 35. Qh5+ Ke7 36. Rg8 Kd6 $6 {The first step towards theprecipice. It's natural to want to keep d5 protected, but this move isinaccurate.} ({It was better to play} 36... Kd7 {(or 36...Kd8)} 37. Rxf5 Qe638. Rxd5+ Kc7 {, when the play is still complicated, but Black is holding after} 39. Qh2+ Re5 40. Rc5+ Kb8 41. Qg3 Ka7 42. Rxe5 Qxe5 {(Nunn). Of course, itwas very difficult to play accurately with the onset of tiredness and aftersuch complicated play.}) 37. Rxf5 Qe6 $2 {Black was already worse, but thismove makes White's task easier. --- EXERCISE: What did Lasker play now?} ({It was preferable to play} 37... Re1+ 38. Ka2 Qe2 {, with advantage to Whiteafter} 39. Rxd5+ Kc6 40. Rc5+ Kb6 41. Qxe2 R1xe2 42. Rxc4 {, since Black istied down by the pawn on h7, but 'a piece is a piece' and it isn't at allclear how White can increase his advantage.}) 38. Rxe8 {ANSWER: Of course.With this exchange the f6-pawn falls and lines are opened against the blackking.} Qxe8 39. Rxf6+ Kc5 ({It was no better to play} 39... Kc7 40. Qxd5 {(threatening 41 Qd6+ or 41 Qc5+ followed by Rf8)} Re1+ 41. Ka2 Qd8 {, and hereNunn gives} 42. Qxc4+ Kb8 43. Rxa6 $1 bxa6 44. Qb4+ {and Qxe1, winning.}) 40.Qh6 {Threatening 41 Rf8; Black must prevent the h7-pawn from advancing and atthe same time defend the knight and his exposed monarch, which is animpossible task.} Re7 ({Chigorin suggested} 40... Qe7 {, but that fails todefend against} 41. Rf8 {: for example,} Re6 42. Qd2 $1 Qxh7 43. Qb4+ Kc6 ({no better is} 43... Kd4 44. Qc3+ Kc5 45. Rc8+ Rc6 46. Qb4+ Kd4 47. Rxh8 $1 {when capturing the rook loses to 48 Qc3+, but otherwise White has a winningattack with 48 Qxb7 or 48 Rh1, etc}) 44. Rc8+ Qc7 45. Rxc7+ Kxc7 46. Qc5+ {and nearly all the black pawns are falling.}) ({Another suggestion was} 40...Re2 {, but this fails to} 41. Qg7 Re7 42. Qg1+ Re3 ({if} 42... d4 {then} 43.Qg5+ Re5 44. Qg8 d3 45. cxd3 cxd3 46. Qb3 $1 {, with a decisive attack}) 43.Qg8 Re7 {and now one winning line is} 44. Rf8 Qg6 45. Rc8+ Kd6 {, andaccording to the 'old' engines (of about fifteen years ago) the game is aboutequal; today's engines quickly see that White's initiative is decisive, though:for instance,} 46. Qd8+ Ke6 47. Qb6+ Ke5 48. Qe3+ Qe4 ({or} 48... Kd6 49. Rd8+Rd7 50. Rxh8 {, threatening 51 Qb6+, with a winning attack}) 49. Qg5+ Kd6 50.Qf6+ Qe6 51. Qxh8 Rxh7 52. Qd8+ Ke5 53. Qg5+ Ke4 54. Rf8 {, and the black kingwill not survive.}) 41. Qh2 ({Not} 41. Rf8 $2 {because of} Rxh7 $1 {.}) ({Another way, though, was} 41. Qd2 $1 {and after} Qd8 {several moves win, suchas} 42. Qb4+ Kd4 43. Qc3+ Kc5 44. a4 $1 {(with the idea of 45 b4#)} a5 45. Qa3+Kd4 46. Qg3 $1 {, with a position similar to the game.}) 41... Qd7 ({Nunnindicates that the only chance was to play} 41... Re1+ 42. Ka2 Qe7 {, "butWhite has an attractive win":} 43. Qf4 {(with the idea of 44 Rf8, attackingthe knight and also preparing 45 Rc8+ and Qd4)} Qe5 44. Qh6 Qe7 45. Rf8 Re6 {, and the queen resumes the attack with} 46. Qd2 $1 Qxh7 ({if} 46... Qxf8 {then} 47. Qb4+ {wins}) 47. Rc8+ $1 {(to deprive the black king of the c6-square)}Rc6 48. Rxh8 $1 {and the black king is defenceless: for example,} Qf7 {(therook is immune from capture in view of 49 Qb4+ followed by Qc3+)} 49. Rf8 $1 {(increasing the mobility of the rook)} Qe7 50. Qb4+ Kd4 51. Rf1 {, with adecisive attack.}) ({Steinitz mentioned} 41... Re6 {, but this can be refutedwith} 42. Qg1+ $1 {, followed by Qg8 and Rf8, capturing the knight whilekeeping up the attack.}) 42. Qg1+ $1 {The strongest check, since from g1 thequeen has access to g5.} d4 {Forced;} (42... Kb5 {leads to mate after} 43. Qb6+{.}) 43. Qg5+ {Gaining a decisive material advantage.} Qd5 44. Rf5 Qxf5 45.Qxf5+ Kd6 46. Qf6+ {General opinion maintains that this game was to a largeextent the one that decided the match. Up to this point Steinitz was notinferior to Lasker, but this game represented a tremendous mental blow. Theage difference began to be more evident (Lasker was 25, as opposed to the48-year-old Steinitz), and Lasker made this more influential by opting forlong endgames on several occasions.} 1-0[Event "10: World Championship, Philadelphia"][Site "?"][Date "1894.??.??"][Round "9"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Steinitz, W"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C62"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "97"][EventDate "1894.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker won the eighth game, which was also played in New York. The match wasthen transferred to Philadelphia, with a 5-3 advantage to Lasker (+ 4 =2 -2).Three games were played there. Let's look at the ninth game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. Nc3 a6 ({In the eleventh game of the world title match inHavana in 1891, Steinitz played the more natural} 4... Bd7 {, and he wassuccessful, but everything indicates that he considered that this move was animprovement.}) 5. Bc4 ({QUESTION: What's this? Why doesn't he play} 5. Bxc6+ {, reaching a theoretical line with an extra tempo? --- ANSWER: It's true thatwith 5 Bxc6+ White would have the extra tempo Nc3 in comparison with the lineof the Steinitz Defence Deferred 1 e4 e5 2 Nf3 Nc6 3 Bb5 a6 4 Ba4 d6 5 Bxc6+bxc6, but this line became popular only some decades later; at the time thisgame was played there was no theory on it.}) ({Neither of the two championsconsidered that taking on c6 was promising. Steinitz commented: "White couldhardly exchange, and} 5. Ba4 {would have cut him off from the kingside. Blackhas therefore evidently gained a move in the development as compared withsimilar positions". Curiously, this very move was played by a candidate forthe world championship, Romanishin, against Nikolac in Amsterdam in 1978, andBlack ended up winning in 50 moves; his light-squared bishop helped to win thegame.}) 5... Be6 ({"Either this or} 5... Be7 {was now indispensable",commented Steinitz.}) ({On} 5... Nf6 {Black must consider} 6. Ng5 {, but itdoesn't seem to be worse for him after} d5 7. exd5 Na5 {; the move 4...a6being very useful here, since it prevents 8 Bb5+.}) 6. Bxe6 fxe6 7. d4 exd4 8.Nxd4 Nxd4 {This is the Steinitz recipe that we have already seen, and, despiteappearing dubious, as it helps the white queen to become active, it issatisfactory.} ({Nevertheless, afterwards Steinitz wasn't happy with theexchanges that ensued in the game and he suggested} 8... Qd7 {, and after} 9.Nxc6 Qxc6 10. Bg5 Be7 11. Bxe7 Nxe7 12. Qg4 Kd7 {if White accepts thesacrifice with} 13. Qxg7 {then Black has reasonable compensation after} Qb6 {, followed by bringing a rook to g8.}) 9. Qxd4 Ne7 ({It was also possible toplay} 9... Nf6 {, after which} 10. Bg5 Be7 11. O-O-O {was suggested, but here,instead of} O-O $2 ({Black can play} 11... Ng4 $1 12. Bxe7 Qxe7 {, with goodplay}) 12. e5 Ne8 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 14. f4 {with advantage to White.}) 10. Bg5 ({Redeploying the active queen with} 10. Qb4 {achieves little. After} Qc8 {, followed by ...Nc6, Black has few problems.}) 10... Nc6 11. Bxd8 {Aninteresting decision. Lasker opts to play the ending, not because objectivelyit is better than keeping the queens on, but due to trusting in his greaterskill in the endgame and fancying his chances in a prolonged struggle, inwhich the age difference might become a factor. As we remarked in the note tomove 8...Nxd4, Steinitz was not comfortable moving so soon into the ending.}Nxd4 12. O-O-O Nb5 {There is nothing wrong with this decision;} ({but Steinitzcriticized himself in his annotations: "As second player, Black should havebeen content with the slight advantage arising from doubling the pawns by} 12... Nb3+ 13. axb3 {followed by} Rxd8 {. In trying to do more he seriouslycompromises his position. Although he recovers the sacrificed pawn, hisdoubled b-pawns become the source of trouble".}) ({Almost any continuationby Black was playable here. The one in the game, the one mentioned by Steinitz,and also} 12... c5 {(suggested by Chigorin)} 13. Bg5 Be7 {, and now, forinstance,} 14. Be3 Rf8 15. f3 Bf6 {, followed by ...0-0-0.}) ({Also} 12... Rxd813. Rxd4 g5 $1 {is very interesting, fearing neither} 14. h4 {, on account of}Bg7 15. Rd3 ({nor} 15. Rb4 b5 {when} 16. hxg5 $2 {fails to} c5 17. Rb3 c4 18.Rb4 d5 {, threatening ...Bf8}) 15... g4 {.}) 13. Nxb5 axb5 14. Bxc7 Rxa2 {Consistent with opening the a-file and correct.} ({Also good was} 14... Ra6 {, threatening ...Kd7, and after} 15. e5 d5 16. a3 {the best line is Chigorin'ssuggestion} b4 $1 17. axb4 Bxb4 18. c3 Bc5 19. f3 Kd7 {, with a balancedendgame.}) 15. Bb6 Be7 ({Once again, unjustly, Steinitz criticizes his ownplay, preferring} 15... b4 {, which is good, but not better than what heplayed. An interesting response (to 15...b4) would be} 16. Kd2 {, and after}Rxb2 17. Bd4 Ra2 18. Ra1 {White quickly regains the pawn.}) 16. c3 {This iswhy Steinitz later suggested 15...b4. 16 c3 doesn't give White any advantage,but it livens up the position, and now Steinitz made an inaccuracy.} Kf7 $6 {"A grave error of judgment to which the loss of the game may fairly beascribed. --- EXERCISE (simple): What did Lasker play now?} ({Instead} 16...Kd7 {followed soon by ...Kc6, would have brought the necessary support to theweak pawns on the queenside" (Steinitz). It's not really so serious, but theposition is not yet equal; White stands a little better.}) ({Also good wasLasker's suggestion} 16... Ra4 17. f3 b4 {;}) ({and even the immediate} 16...b4 {was playable, since after} 17. cxb4 Bf6 18. Rhe1 Ke7 19. Bd4 Ra4 {Blackregains his pawn, with equality.}) 17. Kc2 $1 {ANSWER: Of course, Lasker wasconsistent with his idea of opening the route c2-b3 for his king.} Rha8 18. Kb3R2a4 19. f3 R8a6 ({Once again Steinitz criticized his own play and suggested} 19... g5 {.}) 20. Bd4 g6 ({Steinitz mentioned} 20... g5 {here as well, but itdoesn't offer stable equality. White could try breaking with h4, and since} 21.h4 {, can be answered with} ({it's interesting to preface this with} 21. g4 $1{, with the idea of 22 h4 gxh4 23 Bf2, opening up the game on the kingside toWhite's advantage}) 21... g4 {.}) 21. Rd3 {White also has many options. Laskerdecides first of all to exert pressure on the weak d6-pawn.} Ke8 22. Rhd1 e5 $2({White also has many options. Lasker decides first of all to exert pressureon the weak d6-pawn.} 22... Kd7 {for fear of} 23. Bc5 {, when} Kc7 {solvesnothing due to} 24. e5 $1 {, and the white rooks come decisively into play, sohe makes a seemingly 'ugly' move, one which weakens his pawn structure andalso d5; in this case the appearances are not deceptive.}) ({Steinitzattributed this decision to an error in calculation: "Black overlooked theforce of White's twenty-fourth move. The move} 22... g5 {was, under anycircumstances, much better".}) ({Chigorin suggested} 22... Rc4 {, with theidea of 23...Kd7 next.}) 23. Be3 Kd7 {EXERCISE: What was Lasker's strong movethat Steinitz had underestimated? --- ANSWER:} 24. Bc5 $1 {The bishop combineswith the rooks to attack the d6- pawn. An always generous Steinitz commented:"A beautiful key move to splendid ending play in a series of fine movescarried through by White in a style that can hardly be improved upon".} Ra125. R1d2 {It suits White to keep both rooks on the board; the one on d2 isputting pressure on d6, whereas the one on a1 is not fulfilling any importantrole.} Ke6 26. Ba3 g5 {Steinitz looks for counterplay, preparing the break ...g4.} 27. Rd5 $1 {Reminding Black that he has another important weakness aswell as the one on d6, and at the same time eliminating the eventualpossibility of a tactical ...d5 break.} Rb6 28. Kb4 $1 {"Now the kingactively enters into the fight" (Lasker).} g4 $1 {Lasker: "The initiationof a subtle counterattack, which nearly succeeded in turning the tables".--- EXERCISE: Concerning Lasker's response, Steinitz commented, "All ingrand style", so what did White now play? --- ANSWER:} 29. Ka5 $1 ({In hisannotations Lasker remarked that it would perhaps have been better to acceptthe pawn, but that's not clearly the case: if} 29. fxg4 Re1 30. Ka5 Bd8 31.Rxb5 {, Black seems to gain enough counterplay after} Ra6+ (31... Rc6+ 32. Ka4Bg5 33. Rd3 Rxe4+ 34. Bb4 Ra6+ 35. Kb3 Rxg4 36. g3) 32. Kb4 Rxe4+ 33. Kb3 {. Even though Lasker says that White has a clear advantage in that case, hispieces are left passive after} Bg5 $1 34. Rc2 {(to keep g2 protected)} b6 35.h3 ({or} 35. Rb4 Rxb4+ 36. Kxb4 Ra5 {, followed by ...d5}) 35... Re1 {.}) 29...Ra6+ ({If} 29... Bd8 {then} 30. Rxb5 $1 {is possible, and none of thediscovered checks are dangerous.}) 30. Kxb5 h5 $6 (30... Rh1 {gave moredrawing chances, according to Lasker, although he added that after} 31. fxg4Re1 32. h3 Rxe4 33. c4 Re1 {White's advantage is clear. --- "After the textmove there appears to be no hope and Lasker plays the ending with hisaccustomed accuracy", commented Steinitz.}) 31. Rd1 $1 {Now it definitelysuits White to exchange the black rook, before it becomes dangerous.} Rxd1 32.Rxd1 gxf3 33. gxf3 Ra8 {Heading for the g-file.} ({If} 33... Bg5 {it wouldhave been White who activated his rook with} 34. Rg1 {. Then if} Kf6 {thewhite king would improve its position with} 35. Kc4 {, followed by Rd5,leaving Black defenceless.}) 34. Kb6 {Of course, as the black rook has leftthe b7-pawn unguarded.} Rg8 35. Kxb7 Rg2 {EXERCISE: The endgame is winning forWhite, but still requires accuracy. Lasker now plays the most precise move -what was it? --- ANSWER:} 36. h4 $1 {This pawn cannot be saved in the long run,but to capture it the rook will have to give up the attack on the b2-pawn.} Rh237. Kc6 {The complement of the previous move. "This manoeuvre makes theblack game untenable" (Lasker).} Bxh4 ({Now if} 37... Rxh4 {then} 38. Bxd6 {wins.}) 38. Rxd6+ Kf7 39. Kd5 {With two extra pawns, both passed and connected,the ending should be won, but White needs to neutralize Black's passed h-pawn.}({There are several ways for him to proceed, for instance, with} 39. c4 {, but Lasker prefers something simpler.}) 39... Bf6 ({In the event of} 39...Rd2+ 40. Kxe5 Bg3+ 41. f4 Rxd6 42. Bxd6 h4 {White arrives in time to halt theh-pawn with} 43. Bc5 h3 44. Bg1 {, as indicated by Lasker;}) ({while if} 39...Bg3 40. Rd7+ Kf6 {there are several ways for White. With his two extra pawns,any queening race should favour him, and the simplest method seems to be} 41.b4 h4 42. b5 h3 43. b6 Rd2+ 44. Kc6 Rxd7 45. Kxd7 h2 46. b7 h1=Q 47. b8=Q {, with a winning ending.}) 40. Rd7+ Kg6 41. Ke6 h4 {EXERCISE: Here there areseveral winning moves, but the best, from the practical point of view, is thesafest. How did Lasker minimize the risks? --- ANSWER:} 42. Rd1 $1 {Beforeadvancing his passed pawns Lasker takes steps to neutralize Black's passedpawn, by bringing his rook back into defence.} h3 43. Rg1+ Rg2 ({If} 43... Bg5{there are several ways for White to win, and the simplest suffices:} 44. Be7Rg2 45. Rxg2 hxg2 46. Bc5 {: for example,} Bc1 47. b3 Bb2 48. Kxe5 Kg5 49. Be3+Kh4 50. Kd4 {, followed by the advance of his passed pawns.}) 44. Rxg2+ hxg245. Bc5 {This endgame is simpler than the one in the previous note.} Bd8 46. b4Kg5 47. Kd7 Bf6 48. b5 Kf4 49. b6 {Lasker also won the tenth game and theeleventh, so that the second stage of the match ended with the outcomepractically decided. Lasker was leading 8-3 (+ 7 =2 -2), and needed only threemore wins to become the new world champion. --- The match transferred toMontreal in Canada. Steinitz fought tenaciously. After drawing the twelfthgame, he won the next two, so the score became 8½-5½ in favour of Lasker.However, Lasker won the next two games and the score moved to 10½-5½ in hisfavour, meaning he needed only one more victory.} 1-0[Event "11: World Championship, Montreal"][Site "?"][Date "1894.??.??"][Round "19"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Steinitz, W"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D37"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "103"][EventDate "1894.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Steinitz won the seventeenth game, the eighteenth was drawn, and Laskerfinally achieved the tenth win that he needed in the nineteenth game.} 1. d4 d52. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. dxc5 dxc4 8. Bxc4 Qxd1+9. Kxd1 Nc6 10. a3 Bxc5 11. b4 Rd8+ ({Varying from the eleventh game, in whichhe played} 11... Bb6 {; Steinitz decides to keep his bishop on the a3-f8diagonal.}) 12. Ke2 Bf8 {Leaving the e7-square free for the c6-knight tomanoeuvre.} ({Another idea} 12... Be7 {"is fully as good, especially as itleaves the king untrammelled", wrote Steinitz.}) 13. Bb2 Bd7 14. Rhd1 Rac8 {Unlike in the eleventh game Black's pieces are not stepping on each others'toes. He has fewer problems here and the ending is balanced.} 15. Bb3 Ne7 {Heading for g6, not fearing 16 Ne5, because the black rook is on d8, not f8 asin the eleventh game, so here 16...Be8 is possible, without spoiling theharmony of his pieces.} 16. Nd4 Ng6 17. Rd2 e5 $6 {Black stands well and hehas no problems... but neither does White. This advance, giving greatermobility to his light-squared bishop, seems to indicate that Steinitz wasplaying for a win, but he was taking a risk.} ({In any case Steinitz, who wasnot averse to self-criticism, commented: "Hardly a commendable plan, as itweakens the centre. Far superior was} 17... Ne5 18. Rad1 Be7 ({Steinitz alsopointed out that} 18... Nc4 {, winning the bishop pair, was less precise,because after} 19. Bxc4 Rxc4 {White could play} 20. Nf3 $1 {, with the idea of21 Ne5 and then g4, taking the initiative}) 19. Ndb5 Ne4 {with an excellentgame".}) 18. Nf3 Bg4 {Consistent with 17...e5. Black is threatening to winwith 19...e4, but the threat is easily parried.} 19. Rxd8 Rxd8 {EXERCISE: Howdid Lasker continue here? --- ANSWER:} 20. h3 {'Putting the question' to thebishop. Lasker was willing to accept doubled pawns on f3, because heconsidered that here the bishop pair was more important than the structuralweaknesses, since Black is in no position to exploit them.} Bxf3+ $6 ({It wasdifficult to resign himself to waiting passively with} 20... Bd7 {. After} 21.Rd1 Be7 {Black would not yet have achieved comfortable equality and Whitecould continue with} 22. Nd5 {, for example. However, exchanging on f3 onlymakes Black's defence even more difficult.}) 21. gxf3 ({Of course, not} 21.Kxf3 {in view of} Rd2 {, followed by 22...e4+ and an attack on White's king byBlack's knights.}) 21... Be7 22. Rc1 {White doesn't want to exchange the rooksyet, because his rook will be able to infiltrate Black's queenside at somepoint, whereas the black rook can do little except defend.} Kf8 23. Na4 {With the idea of 24 Nc5, seeking to create further weaknesses.} b6 24. Nc3 {Now that White has provoked a weakness in Black's queenside, the knight has nofurther work to do on a4, so heads for b5.} ({Nothing is to be gained yet byplaying} 24. Rc7 {, on account of} Rd7 {.}) 24... Bd6 {To respond to 25 Nb5with 25...Bb8.} ({QUESTION: You told me that for the moment White doesn't wantto exchange the rooks. In that case, why doesn't Black restrain White'sexpansion a little by playing} 24... Rc8 {- ? --- ANSWER: Of course, 24...Rc8was possible, but it's not that White never wants to exchange the rooks.Moreover, in this case} 25. Nb5 {deserves consideration, so that after} Rxc126. Bxc1 a6 (26... a5 $2 {leads to the loss of a pawn after} 27. bxa5 bxa5 28.Bd2 Bd8 29. Nd6 Be7 30. Nc4) 27. Nc7 a5 28. bxa5 bxa5 {, and now perhaps} 29.a4 {, Black's difficulties would by no means have disappeared; the pawn on a5remains weak, and the white bishops are strong, added to which the whiteknight now has access to many squares.}) 25. Rd1 {This pin is unpleasant;} Ne8({The strength of the white bishops is apparent in a line such as} 25... Ke7 $226. Nb5 Bb8 27. Rxd8 Kxd8 28. Bxf7 {.}) 26. Nb5 Rd7 $2 {This is a seriouserror. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker bring the black position to the brink ofdefeat?} ({It was necessary to weaken his position with} 26... a6 {. White isbetter then, after 27 Nc3 with the idea of Nd5 or Ne4, or} 27. Nxd6 Nxd6 ({if} 27... Rxd6 {then} 28. Rc1) 28. h4 $1 {, but there is still a struggle ahead.})27. Bc2 $1 {ANSWER: With the tremendous threat of 28 Bf5, followed by Nxa7;there are also ideas of winning the e5-pawn with 28 Nxd6, followed by Bxg6 andBxe5.} Ke7 $6 {After the loss of the exchange all serious resistance will sooncome to end.} ({Black had to play} 27... a6 {, although White can then win thee5-pawn with} 28. Nxd6 Rxd6 29. Bxg6 {.} ({Possibly Lasker would have triedfor even more by playing} 29. Bd3 {, when after} b5 30. a4 bxa4 $2 {the move}31. b5 $1 {, threatening Ba3, is decisive.})) 28. Bf5 a6 29. Bxd7 Kxd7 30. Nc3({Faithful to his motto 'If you see a good move, look for an even better one',Lasker rejects the simplifying} 30. Nxd6 {and looks for more. Black must nowdefend against multiple threats: 31 b5 a5? 32 Nd5, 31 Ne4, 31 Nd5, etc.}) 30...f5 ({The position was bad, lost even, but as Steinitz commented: "Ifanything were yet to be done} 30... Ne7 {followed by 31...f6 furnishesundoubtedly a much better defence. The weakness of the e-pawn leaves a markfor the breaking in by White's combined forces, which soon renders resistancehopeless".}) 31. b5 axb5 32. Nxb5 Ke6 33. Bc3 Ne7 34. Nxd6 {Finally Whiteexchanges his knight for the bishop, but under more favourable conditions thanon move 30. Now there are more open lines for his rook.} Nxd6 35. Bb4 Nd5 36.Rc1 Nf7 37. Bd2 Nd6 38. Kd3 Kd7 39. e4 Nf6 40. Be3 fxe4+ 41. fxe4 b5 42. f3 Nc443. Rc3 Ne8 44. Bc1 Ncd6 45. Rc5 Nc7 46. Rxe5 {Black could well have resignedseveral moves ago, or at this point.} Ne6 47. Rh5 h6 48. Re5 g5 49. h4 gxh4 50.Rh5 Kc6 51. Rxh6 Nc5+ 52. Kc2 {. And after this move Steinitz got up from hischair, shook Lasker's hand and declared out loud, "Three cheers for the newworld champion!".} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "2: Selected Games: 1895-1900"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{After winning the world title Lasker returned to London, where he gave aseries of lectures formulating his chess credo. The content of these lectureswas later published in the book Common Sense in Chess.} 1. Z0 {Even thoughLasker was now the world chess champion, he did not really have a veryimpressive record of successes. Indeed, he needed some victories in order tobe considered a 'real' world champion.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Hastings 1895"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The Hastings and St. Leonards Chess Club organized one of the strongesttournaments of the nineteenth century, which was at the same time Lasker'sfirst big tournament. It took place from the 5th of August to the 2nd ofSeptember 1895 in Hastings. --- "Just the fact that the tournament includedthese four stars - Lasker, Steinitz, Tarrasch, Chigorin - gives itchessically historical significance," wrote the Deutsche Schachzeitung. ---The list of twenty-two participants included veterans such as Blackburne, vonBardeleben, Burn, and the oldest participant, Bird, aged 65, as well as youngplayers from whom great things were expected, the Austrian Carl Schlechter andthe American Harry Nelson Pillsbury.} 1. Z0 {Lasker began with only two pointsout of four, but he later recovered and after 18 of the 21 rounds he was theoverall leader and the favourite to win. However, Lasker's finishing run wentbadly for him. The winner was Pillsbury, on 16½ points; second was Chigorinwith 16, and trailing in third place the world champion with 15½, ahead ofTarrasch in fourth place with 14 and Steinitz in fifth with 13. --- This was adisappointment for Lasker, who came very close to winning, but on the otherhand, it wasn't a disaster; it simply delayed his demonstration that he wasthe strongest player in the world. --- In the second round Lasker playedagainst Mikhail Chigorin for the first time, in a game which was veryimportant for the final classification. The battleground was Chigorin's owndefence to the Queen's Gambit, in which Black gives up both his bishops inexchange for knights. It was an intense struggle from which Chigorin emergedthe winner. In the third round, with Black, Lasker defeated a futurechallenger for the title, Carl Schlechter, but in the fourth he was beaten byvon Bardeleben. --- At this stage he had only two points, but he then embarkedon a series of five successive victories. Despite his impressive score of 7/9,this was only enough to put him in fourth place behind Chigorin's 8/9, andPillsbury and von Bardeleben on 7½ points (see the following game).} *[Event "12: Hastings"][Site "?"][Date "1895.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Janowski, D"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D55"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "71"][EventDate "1895.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Be7 5. Nf3 O-O 6. e3 b6 7. Rc1 Bb7 {Decades later this position was more frequently reached with the inclusion ofthe moves ...h6 and Bh4.} 8. cxd5 {A good choice, even if the order used byWhite allows 8...Nxd5. As we have seen in a similar position, this can beavoided by preceding the exchange 9 cxd5 with 8 Bxf6.} ({QUESTION: And what'swrong with just continuing development with} 8. Bd3 {- ? --- ANSWER: Nothing,of course. It allows} dxc4 {, and White takes two moves to capture on c4, butthis just leads us to another kind of position; Black opens the diagonal forhis b7-bishop, at the cost of exchanging a centre pawn for a wing pawn.}) 8...exd5 9. Bd3 c5 10. O-O Nbd7 11. dxc5 Nxc5 ({More usual is} 11... bxc5 {, butit isn't clear that Black's choice was really bad. It's more a question oftaste; with the move played, the knight becomes active and the black pieceshave greater mobility.}) 12. Bb1 Rc8 13. Bf5 Ne6 14. Bh4 Kh8 $6 {QUESTION:What? I can't believe that there wasn't a better move than that! --- ANSWER: Isee that you almost agree with the pessimistic Teichmann, who also criticized11...Nxc5 in his annotations, and commented here: "This is certainly aweakening move, but the position is very delicate and Black is at a loss forwhat to do". --- It's not so bad, in fact. Even though it seems a strangemove, it prepares for an opportune ...Ng8, offering an exchange of bishops inorder to gain greater freedom of movement.} ({It was not possible to play} 14... Ne4 $2 {with the same idea, because of} 15. Bxe7 Qxe7 ({or, even worse,} 15... Nxc3 16. Bxd8 Nxd1 17. Rxc8 Bxc8 18. Be7 {, with the idea of Ba3}) 16.Nxd5 {.}) ({However, there were certainly better moves, and with} 14... g6 $1 {Black could have obliged the f5-bishop to choose a diagonal. After, for example} 15. Bh3 Rc5 {, defending d5, Black would be ready to play 16...Nfe4, withgood play.}) 15. Ne5 ({Lasker wants more than the minimal advantage that hecould obtain with the natural} 15. Nd4 {. With the text move he tries to takeadvantage of the fact that after 14...Kh8 the f7-pawn has been weakened.})15... Qe8 ({QUESTION: Once more, is there really nothing better? --- ANSWER:No, not this time, as} 15... Ng8 $2 {would be met with} 16. Nxf7+ $1) ({and White wins material, while} 15... Qd6 $2 {was also bad due to} 16. Bg3 {.})16. Qf3 {Lasker tries to take advantage of his current greater mobility. AsTeichmann pointed out, White is "Threatening now 17 Qh3, followed by 18Bxf6".} Ng8 {This was the idea.} ({Also playable was} 16... g6 17. Bc2 Kg7 {, and after} 18. Rfd1 {Black is fine after, say,} Rc7 {.}) 17. Bg3 {Avoidingthe exchange of bishops and momentarily leaving the black pieces awkwardlyplaced.} ({This is the best move from the practical point of view, although itwas also interesting to allow the exchange with} 17. Qh3 {, when after} Bxh418. Qxh4 {Black can't play 18...Nf6? due to 19 Ng4, while after} Nh6 19. Bh3 ({not} 19. Bc2 d4 $1 20. exd4 Qd8 {), with the idea of Rfd1, White standsslightly better.})) 17... Nh6 {It's true that here too the knight stands in anawkward position. Black hasn't gained the good piece play he was hoping for,when accepting an isolated pawn, and the ...d4 advance is impossible for themoment. However, White has nothing concrete either; he lacks a blockadingpiece at d4, and if Black manages to recycle the h6-knight, his position willbe quite reasonable.} 18. Bb1 f6 {"A good move, chasing the white knightaway from the e5-square and giving the h6-knight a route back to the centrevia f7" (Nunn).} 19. Nd3 Qd7 {Black continues to improve his pieces. Nowthat the bishop on b7 is defended, advancing with 20...d4 becomes apossibility.} 20. Qd1 Rfd8 $6 {QUESTION: Why is this dubious? It looks verylogical. --- ANSWER: Yes, and so it is, placing the rook on a useful file andpreparing ...d4, but sometimes logical is not synonymous with best. ---EXERCISE: How did Lasker respond to 20...Rfd8 - ?} ({It's possible that theimmediate} 20... d4 {is playable. After} 21. Nf4 Nxf4 22. Bxf4 {White isthreatening the pawn on d4, as well as Bxh6, but Black has} Ba6 $5 {and after}23. Bd3 {(otherwise 23...d3 would follow)} Bxd3 24. Qxd3 Rfd8 25. Qxd4 Qxd4 26.exd4 Rxd4 {, damaging Black's pawn structure with} 27. Bxh6 {fails to achievemuch, because in such an open position the bishop is better than the knight,and the black rooks are active.}) ({Nevertheless, it's more attractive tofirst solve the other, more serious, problem, the 'knight on the rim'. Thiscould be achieved with} 20... Nf5 $1 {, which not only supports the ...d4advance, but also enables Black to exchange the g3-bishop at an appropriatemoment.}) 21. Nf4 $1 {ANSWER: With the exchange of the knights it will be moredifficult for Black to play ...d4, and the bishop is going to f4, after whichBxh6 will now be a threat, because we are still in the middlegame, not theendgame.} Nxf4 ({Teichmann suggested} 21... Nf8 {, but of course such apassive move isn't to everyone's taste;}) ({and} 21... d4 $2 {is not playable,due to} 22. Nxe6 Qxe6 23. exd4 {.}) 22. Bxf4 g5 $2 {This move is either veryoptimistic or else a reaction borne of panic. It radically prevents the threatof 23 Bxh6 and does so with gain of time, but the cost of weakening thekingside should have been weighed up more carefully. --- For once it's easy toagree with Teichmann, who commented: "And this premature advance compromizeshis kingside irretrievably. An attack on the kingside is, on the face of it,without prospect".} ({Parrying the threat with} 22... Nf5 {isn't convincingdue to} 23. Qh5 ({or} 23. Qg4 {, when} Nd6 24. Qxd7 Rxd7 25. Bxd6 Rxd6 {(forced)} 26. Nb5 {is uncomfortable}) 23... g6 24. Bxf5 {, weakening Black'spawn structure.}) ({Instead,} 22... Nf7 $2 {isn't good either, due to} 23. Qh5{;}) ({but with} 22... Ng4 $1 {Black could have prevented Qh5 and prepared ...Ne5, with a satisfactory position.}) 23. Bg3 Bf8 ({Since} 23... Nf5 $2 {fails to} 24. Qd3) ({and} 23... Nf7 $2 {to} 24. Qh5 {, Black overprotects h7,to allow him to play ...Nf5.}) ({The more active bishop move} 23... Bc5 {could have been answered with} 24. Qh5 Nf5 25. Rfd1 {, putting pressure on thed5-pawn and with Ne4 a possibility.}) ({Something similar would have occurredafter} 23... Ng4 24. h3 Ne5 25. Qh5 {, followed by 26 Rfd1.}) 24. Qd3 {Laskerprevents the h6-knight from becoming active and prepares to play Rfd1.} f5 {Blocking the b1-h7 diagonal and preparing ...Bg7 or, perhaps better, ...Qg7 (which would keep h7 defended and permit a ...f4 at an appropriate moment),with the idea of ...d4. Of course this comes at price, and once againTeichmann gives us his pessimistic view: "Creating another weakness. Eitherthe f-pawn or g-pawn must fall in a few moves." --- EXERCISE: How did Laskernow continue?} ({Naturally the knight can't go to f5 or f7, while} 24... Ng4 $2{fails to} 25. Qf5 $1 {, and White wins material.}) 25. Ne2 $1 {ANSWER!} ({Not content with the natural and good move} 25. Rfd1 {, which would have beenanswered with} Qg7 {. Now the ...d4 advance has been restrained and after afuture Nd4 the f5-pawn will suffer.}) ({The alternative route} 25. Nb5 {was less effective in view of} Ba6 {.}) 25... Bg7 ({Now} 25... Qg7 $2 {wouldhave been answered with} 26. Nd4 {.}) 26. Nd4 Rf8 27. Rxc8 Qxc8 28. Qd2 $1 {Preparing Rc1. Teichmann commented, "Very subtle. The queen is excellentlyposted here and the rook can now take possession of the important c-file".}Rf7 {This defends the second rank, but, of course, it's proof of the failureof Black's strategy; the isolated queen's pawn hasn't provided the activepiece play that he sought.} 29. Rc1 Qe8 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker now increasethe pressure? --- ANSWER:} 30. h4 $1 {Opening more lines, providing luft forhis king, and gaining the f4-square for his bishop. It's interesting to notethat Lasker could have played h4 on move 25, instead of Ne2, which would havebeen good, but he decided postpone it until he had improved his pieces, andnow it's even stronger.} gxh4 {Sub-optimal;} ({but the weakening move} 30... g4{isn't satisfactory either. White can play} 31. Bf4 {, threatening Bxh6;} {while after} Qd7 {,} ({when} 31... Bc8 {loses to} 32. e4 {;} (32. Z0)) 32. Rc7{is strong; in both cases Black would be left paralyzed.}) 31. Bxh4 {With theidea of 32 Bg5 and capturing the pawn on f5.} Bc8 {Black defends tenaciously,but it's clear that a position condemned to such passivity will not be able tohold out for long.} 32. Bg3 ({There were several attractive moves here, such as} 32. Bg5 {, threatening 33 e4 and forcing Black to go 33...Ng4. This was good,but Lasker prefers not to help the knight redeploy to the good square on e5.})32... Ng4 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker demonstrate that it was better to reachthis position with his bishop on g3 rather than on g5? --- ANSWER:} 33. Nb5 $1{Now this comes with much more force. --- As Teichmann pointed out, "Thispowerful move leaves Black defenceless. The whole game was very well played byMr. Lasker, and it's a good specimen of this variation of the Queen's Gambit.White maintained an advantage throughout by combining direct attacks on theking with continuous pressure on the weak isolated d-pawn". --- QUESTION:Let's go back, if we may. If this move was so strong, why didn't Black preventit with 32...a6 - ? --- ANSWER: Black's position is so delicate that it's notenough to prevent one strong move from his opponent; ...a6 also weakens thequeenside and White could respond, for instance, with 33 Qb4, attacking b6,when 33...b5 34 Qc5 Be6 35 Qd6 would leave Black defenceless.} Rf8 ({After} 33... Qxb5 34. Rxc8+ Bf8 35. Qd4+ Kg8 ({or} 35... Nf6) {, White wins with} 36.Bxf5 {.}) 34. Nd6 Qe6 35. Rxc8 $1 {Thanks to having played 32 Bg3, the knighton d6 is defended and now White gains a decisive material advantage with thissimple sequence.} Rxc8 36. Bxf5 {Lasker continued in his dominating stride forthe next nine rounds, in which he scored seven and a half points. He was nowin first place with 14½/18, followed by Chigorin on 14 and Pillsbury on 13½;only these three were within sight of the title. --- Then came the fatefulnineteenth round, where Lasker lost a won ending against Tarrasch. With tworounds to go Chigorin took the lead with 15/19, followed by Lasker andPillsbury with 14½. Lasker still had chances of winning the tournament, but acrushing defeat against Blackburne in the penultimate round put an end to hishopes. --- Lasker soon received some consolation for his disappointing finalresult; he would not have to wait long for an opportunity for revenge. At theclosing banquet in Hastings, Chigorin announced: "There is something I wouldlike to mention: the chess club of St. Petersburg is going to organize atournament at the end of this year, where five or six of the most prominentchess masters will be invited. Among them will be Pillsbury, the outstandingrepresentative of America".} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "St. Petersburg 1895/96"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{In the end, those invited were the first five from Hastings, but Tarrasch wasunable to take part due to his professional commitments. The six-roundquadrangular event took place in St. Petersburg from the 13th of December 1895to the 28th of January 1896.} 1. Z0 {Lasker achieved an extraordinary victory,showing great superiority over his rivals, who were the best chess players inthe world. He racked up 11½/18, followed by Steinitz with 9½, Pillsbury on 8and Chigorin 7. --- Lasker made another bad start, losing with White toPillsbury, who roundly punished Lasker's weak play in the opening. However, inthe second round Lasker defeated Steinitz, and in the third round he gainedanother important victory (see the following game).} *[Event "13: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1895.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Chigorin, M"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C52"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "52"][EventDate "1895.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. b4 Bxb4 5. c3 Bc5 {To reach the 'LaskerDefence'.} ({It's more accurate, though, to play} 5... Ba5 $1 {;}) ({sincewith the} 5... Bc5 {move order White can play} 6. d4 {, when} d6 {isimpossible.}) 6. O-O {Now it just amounts to a transposition.} d6 7. d4 {With the bishop on a5, Steinitz played 7...Bg4 several times against Chigorinin their 1890 match for the world championship in Havana, as well as 7...Bd7in their 1892 encounter, with a negative score. --- At that time the 'normal'continuation was 7...exd4 8 cxd4, with countless games by De la Bourdonnais,Anderssen, Morphy, Zukertort and Chigorin himself, among many others.} Bb6 $1 {The 7...Bb6! variation is called the 'Lasker Defence', "which put the Evansout of commission last century", according to Fischer, confirming its statusas one of Emanuel Lasker's greatest contributions to opening theory. ---Nevertheless, as Kasparov remarked, there were antecedents: "The value ofthis move, which was tried back in one of the match games McDonnell-De laBourdonnais (London 1834/35), went unnoticed until Lasker played it". ---Black refrains from opening lines and plans to continue with his development,returning the pawn if necessary, relying on his better pawn structure. ---QUESTION: OK, but in what concrete variation is this a useful move? --- ANSWER:As we know, one of the basic ideas in the Evans Gambit is to play Qb3,attacking f7.} 8. a4 {This impetuous attempt, seeking tactical chances againstthe bishop on b6, hasn't passed the test of time, despite several tries onChigorin's part.} ({Black has ruled that out by vacating the a5-square, so that} 8. Qb3 $2 {now runs into} Na5 $1 {, exchanging the dangerous bishop on c4after} 9. Qa4+ ({since} 9. Bxf7+ $4 {loses to} Kf8 10. Qd5 {and now, forinstance,} c6) 9... Bd7 10. Bb5 {.}) ({The main line became} 8. dxe5 dxe5 {and now there are two branches:} {Exchanging queens doesn't seem attractive,but Chigorin played this way several times. After} 9. Qxd8+ ({White can keepthe queens on the board with} 9. Qb3 {, after which Black plays} Qf6 {, andnow, for example,} ({following the exchanges on e5,} 9... Na5 {is lessconvincing due to} 10. Qb5+) 10. Bg5 Qg6 11. Bd5 Nge7 12. Bxe7 Kxe7 13. Bxc6Qxc6 14. Nxe5 Qe6 15. Nc4 Rd8 {, about which Kasparov wrote: "Regarding this,the main variation of the defence, the two players conducted a lively disputeon the pages of the magazines that they edited. Chigorin believed in White'sattacking resources, whereas Lasker considered that Black's two bishops andthe absence of any weaknesses in his position promised him the advantage -for example, after} 16. Qa3+ Ke8 {".}) 9... Nxd8 10. Nxe5 Be6 {White hasregained his pawn, but is left with the worse pawn structure.}) 8... Nf6 ({Two years later, in an informal game, also in St. Petersburg, Lasker played} 8... exd4 {and after} 9. cxd4 ({the sacrifice} 9. a5 Nxa5 10. Rxa5 Bxa5 11. Qb3{doesn't appear to be sound after} Qd7 12. e5 d5 13. Bxd5 c6 14. Bc4 b5 15. e6fxe6 16. Bxe6 Qxe6 17. Re1 Qxe1+ 18. Nxe1 {, with advantage to Black, J.Blackburne-I.Gunsberg, London 1900}) 9... Bg4 {, Chigorin opted for} 10. Bb5 $6{, and after} (10. Bb2 {seems necessary}) 10... a6 11. Bxc6+ bxc6 12. a5 Ba713. Be3 Ne7 14. Nc3 O-O {he had no compensation for his sacrificed pawn.}) 9.Bb5 {EXERCISE (simple): What did Lasker play here?} ({Chigorin also failed toobtain good results with} 9. Bd5 {. There are several good replies, but in M.Chigorin-P.Lipke, Vienna 1898, Black played in a simple and effective way:}Nxd5 10. exd5 Na5 11. dxe5 O-O $1 12. Bg5 Qd7 13. Re1 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Qf5 15. Bh4f6 16. Nf3 Bd7 {with advantage to Black, who has the bishop pair and thebetter structure.}) 9... a6 {ANSWER: Of course, 'putting the question' to thebishop and obtaining a7 as a retreat square for his b6-bishop.} ({Instead,} 9... O-O $2 {loses to} 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. a5 {.}) 10. Bxc6+ bxc6 11. a5 Ba7 12.dxe5 ({In the event of} 12. Nbd2 {Black has time to play} exd4 13. cxd4 O-O {, and having brought his king into safety, he places the onus on White tojustify his pawn sacrifice, which he failed to do in the game E.Schiffers-G.Marco, Vienna 1898.}) ({If} 12. Qa4 {then} exd4 {is good:} {nor is the quietercontinuation} 13. cxd4 ({and after} 13. Qxc6+ Bd7 14. Qxa6 Nxe4 {White has tofight for equality, possibly with} 15. Qe2 d5 16. Nbd2 {.} (16. Z0)) ({Theviolent} 13. e5 dxe5 14. Ba3 e4 15. cxd4 Bd7 16. Qc4 c5 {is no better for White}) 13... Bd7 14. e5 Nd5 {, followed by 15...0-0. Black can even return thepawn then with} 15. exd6 O-O 16. dxc7 Qxc7 {, since he is left with the bettergame; his pieces are well placed and the weaknesses at d4 and a5 are moreimportant than the one on c6.}) 12... Nxe4 13. Qe2 $2 {This can be answeredwith natural moves and Black is just fine. It would seem that White evaluatedbadly the complications that he was planning.} ({His position is alreadyslightly worse, so he should have aimed for equality and chosen another path.Not with} 13. exd6 {though, since after} O-O $1 14. dxc7 {Black can play notonly} Qxc7 {,} ({but also} 14... Qxd1 15. Rxd1 Nxf2 16. Rf1 Nd3+ 17. Kh1 Nxc118. Rxc1 f6 19. Rd1 Bc5 {, with the idea of 20...Ra7, in both cases withadvantage to Black.})) ({It seems that greater chances to equalize wereoffered by} 13. Qa4 {, and after} Nc5 14. Qxc6+ Bd7 15. Qd5 O-O 16. Bg5 Qe8 17.exd6 {White appears to be in no great danger, but of course hoping to equalizeisn't the idea that inspired the Evans Gambit, and Chigorin prefers to chancehis arm. However, after the text move the balance tilts in Black favour.})13... d5 14. Nd4 $2 {This was the idea, but it will be severely punished.} ({However, after, say,} 14. Ba3 Bg4 {White is already running out of usefulmoves; the attack on c3 hinders} 15. Nbd2 {;} ({but} 15. h3 $2 {loses to} Ng3)({and} 15. c4 Bd4 16. Ra2 c5 {fails to inspire much hope.})) ({Kasparovmentions} 14. Be3 {, but goes on to say that after} c5 {things are still noteasy for White} (14... Bg4) ({and} 14... O-O {are also good.})) 14... Nxc3 $1 {And why not? This wins another pawn and simplifies.} ({Admittedly Black wouldalso be better after other moves, such as the simple} 14... Bd7) ({or} 14...Qd7 {, planning 15...0-0 or 15...c5, but his central domination allows him tokeep his king in the centre, quite safely, and make his extra material count.})15. Nxc3 Bxd4 16. Qd3 ({If} 16. Bb2 {then} O-O {is good enough,} ({but evenstronger is to preface castling with} 16... Rb8 $1 {, since after} 17. Rfd1 c5{White has nothing.})) 16... c5 17. Qg3 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker respond tothe attack on g7? --- ANSWER:} Be6 $1 18. Bg5 ({Simply continuing withdevelopment, without fear of} 18. Qxg7 {In this line} Bxc3 {is not as strong,not because of} ({because Black's king is safe enough in the centre with} 18...Kd7 $1 {, and after} 19. Qg3 {he can make favourable use of the half-openg-file with} Rg8 ({or} 19... Qg8 20. Qf3 Qg4 {, winning.})) 19. Qxh8+ $2 ({but White has a better move in} 19. Bg5 $1 {, and after} Qc8 20. Rac1 {Blackmust play} Kd7 $1 {when following} 21. Rxc3 {the position is far from clear})19... Kd7 {and White has to exchange queens, leaving him with a lost endgameafter} 20. Qxd8+ Rxd8 {and 21...Bxe5.}) 18... Qd7 19. Rac1 {EXERCISE: Theblack king is still in the centre, but there are no immediate threats. Theengines indicate that there are several good moves for Black now. It's verypossible that Lasker took the most 'human' decision here. What do you think heplayed? --- ANSWER:} f6 $1 {The clearest idea, opening the g-file withdevastating effect.} 20. exf6 gxf6 21. Bf4 Rg8 22. Qf3 O-O-O {Black brings hisking to safety and has two extra pawns, for which White has no compensation.}23. Rfe1 ({After} 23. Ne2 {the simplest is} Bg4 24. Qd3 Bxe2 25. Qxe2 c4 {, planning 26...Qg4, 26...Rde8, etc.}) 23... c4 {Threatening to win with 24...Bg4 25 Qg3 Bh3.} 24. Qe2 {Sounding the retreat.} ({If} 24. Bg3 {then, amongstother things, Black can play} Bg4 25. Qf4 Be5 {, winning material.}) 24... Bf525. Qa2 $6 {Sending the queen away doesn't bode well; it threatens nothing ofimportance. However, there was already no defence; Black's central pawns areunstoppable. He just needs to take care not to expose his king prematurely.--- EXERCISE: Lasker now finished the game in the quickest possible way. Whatdid he play?} ({A sample continuation is} 25. Bg3 Bxc3 26. Rxc3 Rde8 27. Qd2Rxe1+ 28. Qxe1 Bd3 29. Rc1 d4 30. Qd2 Re8 {(Kasparov).}) (25. Qd1 {is moretenacious, but then Black could play} Bd3 26. Bg3 Rde8 27. Qd2 Rxe1+ 28. Rxe1Re8 29. Rxe8+ Qxe8 30. h4 ({or} 30. Nxd5 Qb5) 30... Qe6 {, etc.}) 25... Rxg2+$1 {ANSWER: The quickest and most attractive finish.} 26. Kh1 (26. Kxg2 Bh3+27. Kh1 ({or} 27. Kg1 Qg4+ 28. Bg3 Qf3) 27... Qg4 {forces mate.}) 26... Rxf20-1[Event "14: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Pillsbury, H"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "D50"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "62"][EventDate "1895.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{After the first half of the tournament Pillsbury was in the lead with 6½/9,followed by Lasker with 5½, Steinitz on 4½ and Chigorin just 1½. --- Laskerhad only managed to score half a point from his three games so far againstPillsbury, whom he faced in the first round of the second half of the St.Petersburg tournament. A further defeat for Lasker would have given Pillsburyan almost unassailable advantage in it, but let's see what happened.} 1. d4 d52. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Nf3 c5 5. Bg5 ({Subsequently the main lines became} 5.cxd5) ({and} 5. e3 {, which is still the case today.}) 5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nc6 ({Black could have avoided possible complications with} 6... Be7 {, according toLasker.}) 7. Qh4 $6 ({Pillsbury's idea was to castle queenside and attack.Since this met with no success, the conclusion was reached that the correctcontinuation was} 7. Bxf6 {. Pillsbury himself beat Lasker with this atCambridge Springs 1904; after} gxf6 8. Qh4 dxc4 9. Rd1 Bd7 10. e3 {while inhis Manual of Chess, Lasker suggested} f5 {, reaching the conclusion thatBlack is not worse "since the doubled pawn is compensated for by the twostrong bishops and good development, for instance,} (10... Ne5 11. Nxe5 fxe512. Qxc4 Qb6 13. Be2 $1 {, Lasker didn't manage to bring his into safety andwent down under a spectacular attack.} (13. Z0)) ({Nevertheless, thisevaluation may not be definitive. Euwe suggested} 10... Be7) 11. Qg3 (11. Qxc4{has also been played, but with} Bg7 {has also been played, but with}) 11... h512. Bxc4 h4 13. Qf4 Rg8 14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 a6 ({this opinion hasn't beenquestioned until now either by practice or analysis, but} 15... Bg7 {seemseven better, since} 16. Qf4 $2 {allows} Qa5 {, with the idea of ...Be5 and ...Bc6, with a strong initiative, while if} 17. Qd6 {then} Bc6 {, with good play})16. O-O Rc8 {".}) 7... Be7 8. O-O-O $6 {Consistent,} ({but} 8. e3) ({or "} 8. cxd5 exd5 9. Rd1 {is perhaps more solid", according to Kasparov, who thenadded, "but it was not for this that Pillsbury played 5 Bg5 and 6 Qxd4".})8... Qa5 9. e3 Bd7 10. Kb1 {EXERCISE: With 8...Qa5 and 9...Bd7 Lasker madeuseful developing moves without compromising the security of his king. Now hecould continue in the same spirit with 10...Rc8, which is good, but in fact hechose something slightly better. What did he play? --- ANSWER:} h6 $1 {"Thuseither the bishop must be exchanged or the white queen stay where it is" (Lasker), and Black still retains ...Rc8 as a possibility, such as after 11Bd3.} 11. cxd5 exd5 12. Nd4 ({QUESTION: Instead of moving an already developedpiece, why didn't White pursue his attacking plans with one developing move,such as} 12. Bd3 {- ? --- ANSWER: Because his own king would be in danger after} Rc8 {, threatening ...Nb4, and if} 13. a3 {then} Rg8 $1 {is very strong,forcing White into} 14. Bxf6 {, which would spell disaster for the white kingafter} Bxf6 {.}) 12... O-O ({Black could continue to wait with decent movessuch as} 12... Rc8) ({or} 12... Rd8) ({or perhaps} 12... Nxd4 {, but tacticalfactors allow him to make this more useful move, even though it looks risky.})13. Bxf6 ({Of course conceding the bishop pair wasn't part of the plan, butWhite didn't continue with his aggressive idea with} 13. Bxh6 $2 {, becausethen simply} gxh6 ({and} 13... Ne4 $1 {is even stronger, since after} 14. Qh5Nxc3+ 15. bxc3 Nxd4 16. Rxd4 {Black has} Qb6+ {and ...Qxh6, winning}) 14. Qxh6Ng4 {would be good.}) 13... Bxf6 14. Qh5 {Black is better. White has had toexchange his dark-squared bishop and soon it will be clear that his king is inmore danger than Black's.} Nxd4 {A good move, saddling White with a weak pawnon d4, but for tactical reasons it's perhaps not the more precise.} ({It waspossible to play} 14... Be6 {immediately to defend d5, since White can'tseriously consider} 15. Nxe6 $2 fxe6 {, when there would be no good defenceagainst 16...Bxc3 and 17...Rxf2, or 16...Nb4.}) 15. exd4 Be6 {Lasker's ideaseems very provocative, inviting a quick f4-f5, but he had a clear idea inmind.} 16. f4 {Pillsbury needs no provocation to launch the attack; he isplanning f5, maybe followed by Qf3, attacking the weakness on d5 again.} ({However, in the light of the eventual result, it's logical to think that itwas preferable to focus first on defence. Now that Black has played 14...Nxd4,it was possible for White to go} 16. Bc4 {, followed by 17 Bb3, giving hismonarch more protection and putting pressure on d5 more quickly. Black'sposition would still be somewhat preferable after} Rad8 (16... Qb4) ({and} 16... Rfd8 {are the alternatives}) 17. Bb3 Qb4 $1 {, threatening 18...Bxd4,when} 18. Ne2 $6 {wouldn't be good due to} a5 {.}) 16... Rac8 17. f5 {EXERCISE:What was the idea that Lasker had prepared? --- ANSWER:} Rxc3 $1 {"A fine,deeply calculated combination, which any grandmaster could be proud of eventoday. It's beyond the powers of even a strong computer - here additionalforces are needed..." (Kasparov).} ({It's also much better than} 17... Bd718. Qf3 Bc6 {, which was slightly better for Black. Regarding Lasker'sdecision to sacrifice when he had a good alternative, Nunn commented: "Toembark upon a sacrificial combination when there's no choice is not especiallybrave, but to do so when you have a perfectly good positional alternativerequires courage," and he added, "Nevertheless, this is one of the keys tosuccess in chess. If you genuinely believe that a particular continuation isbest then you should have the self-confidence to play it even if it involves adegree of risk".}) 18. fxe6 {EXERCISE: What had Lasker planned to play here?}({In the event of} 18. bxc3 {but more crushing is the immediate} Rc8 $1 {and after} ({the simple} 18... Bd7 $1 {is good, followed by 19...Rc8;} 19. Z0 (19. Z0)) 19. fxe6 Qxc3 20. exf7+ Kf8 {Black's attack is decisive:} 21. Be2 ({or} 21. Qe2 Bxd4) 21... Qb4+ 22. Ka1 Rc1+ $1 {and mate with ...Bxd4+.}) 18... Ra3$3 {ANSWER: Marvellous. This move unsurprisingly attracted great admirationand praise. It's hard not to have the same reaction as upon seeing a move like11...Na4!! in D.Byrne-R.J.Fischer, New York 1956, or 18 Rxf7!! in M.Botvinnik-L.Portisch, Monte Carlo 1968, or the sequence beginning with 24Rxd4!! in G.Kasparov-V.Topalov, Wijk aan Zee 1999, to quote just a fewexamples of the highest expression of the art of chess. --- Nunn wrote:"This is the difficult move to see. The threat to the a2-pawn forces Whiteto take the impudent rook, exposing his king to a check along the b-file.However, the queen and bishop by themselves cannot press the attack home andthe key factor is whether Black can include his remaining rook in theattack". --- "The point of the combination! This paradoxical rooksacrifice forces the white king to begin a fight for its own existence",commented Kasparov, while Amos Burn called it "The finest combination everplayed on a chess board", while it's noteworthy that Lasker commented simply,"This was the point".} 19. exf7+ $2 {This capture reduces the tension inthe position and makes Black's task easier, since it activates the rookimmediately.} ({Lasker commented: "Or} 19. e7 Re8 20. bxa3 Qb6+ 21. Kc2 ({if} 21. Ka1 {, Black would soon win by} Bxd4+ 22. Rxd4 Qxd4+ 23. Kb1 Rxe7) ({in the event of} 21. Bb5 {here, Black could play} Qxb5+ 22. Ka1 Rxe7 {, withhuge compensation for the small material investment}) 21... Rc8+ 22. Kd2 Bxd4 {and White has no defence". --- After 19 e7 Lasker preferred 19...Re8 to themore active move 19...Rc8, because White could then exploit the fact that therook was unprotected with 20 Qg4! and at the same time defend d4, enabling himto capture the rook on a3 under more favourable conditions.}) ({White had toplay} 19. bxa3 {, to which the reply would be} Qb6+ {.} {As such, the onlyviable option for White would be to return some of the material with} 20. Bb5$1 {, although after} ({Then} 20. Ka1 $2 {loses to} Bxd4+ 21. Rxd4 Qxd4+ 22.Kb1 {, after which the f8-rook would join in the attack with} fxe6 $1 {,threatening ...Rf2, amongst other things. Then after} 23. Be2 Qe4+ 24. Ka1 Rf2{Black is winning: for example,} 25. Re1 Qd4+ 26. Kb1 Qd2 {etc.} (26... Z0)) (20. Kc2 $2 {also loses:} Rc8+ 21. Kd2 Qxd4+ 22. Ke1 (22. Bd3 {allows mate with}Rc2+ $1 23. Kxc2 Qb2#) 22... Qe3+ 23. Be2 fxe6 {, and despite White's extrarook, with his king stuck in the centre, his position is indefensible after,say,} 24. Qh3 Bc3+ 25. Kf1 Rf8+ 26. Bf3 Ba5 27. Qg3 Bb6 {, followed by 28...e5and 29...e4.}) 20... Qxb5+ 21. Ka1 fxe6 {Black's compensation for the exchangeshould be more than sufficient.}) 19... Rxf7 20. bxa3 Qb6+ {EXERCISE: Whatshould White now try? --- ANSWER:} 21. Bb5 $1 {As in some lines we've alreadyseen. "Against other moves the attack becomes overwhelming" (Lasker).} ({Indeed,} 21. Kc2 $2 {loses quickly after} Rc7+ 22. Kd2 Qxd4+ 23. Ke1 Qc3+ 24.Rd2 ({or} 24. Kf2 Bd4+) 24... Re7+ ({not} 24... Bg5 $4 25. Qe8+) 25. Be2 Bg5 {.}) 21... Qxb5+ 22. Ka1 Rc7 $2 ({"Fifteen moves an hour were prescribed and Ihad consumed nearly two hours. Thus I have to make these moves in a hurry;} 22... Qc4 {was the logical continuation. It would have made it impossible forWhite to guard his second rank" (Lasker). The rook could become active oneither the f-file or the e-file, while with 22...Qc4! the threat is to take ond4 with decisive effect, and after} 23. Qg4 Re7 {, Black threatens both 24...Re2 and 24...Re4. There is no better defence than} ({or the curious computersuggestion} 23... Be5 $1 {, with the threat of 24...Rf2}) 24. Qh3 Bxd4+ 25. Kb1Re2 26. Qb3 Rb2+ 27. Qxb2 Bxb2 28. Kxb2 Qe2+ {and 29...Qxg2, with a winningendgame, in view of the material advantage and White's exposed king.}) 23. Rd2$1 {"Now White can breathe again" (Lasker). White defends against theinvasion of his second rank and gains a tempo to bring the h1-rook into play.}Rc4 {Attacking d4, and with the idea of ...Qc6.} 24. Rhd1 $2 {It'sunderstandable to want to bolster the defence, but this gives Black thepossibility of becoming more active.} ({With the more active defence} 24. Re1$1 {White defends d4 indirectly, due to the threat to invade on e8, and thiswould have been sufficient to draw the game, although White would have had toshow some ingenuity. --- EXERCISE: How can White equalize after} Qa5 25. Re8+Kh7 26. Qf5+ g6 {- ? --- ANSWER: Only one move draws,} 27. Re7+ $1 {, andthere is perpetual check after} Bxe7 28. Qf7+ Kh8 29. Qe8+ {.}) 24... Rc3 $2 {Black also misses the most active move and gives White a free hand.} (24... Qc6$1 {was winning. After} 25. Kb1 Bg5 {Black regains the exchange, as with} 26.Re1 Kh7 $1 27. Qe2 Bxd2 28. Qxd2 Qb6+ 29. Ka1 Rxd4 30. Qc2+ Qg6 {, and Blackemerges with a winning rook ending, in which he is a pawn up with betterpieces.}) 25. Qf5 $1 {Exploiting the fact that there is no very strong threatat present, White's queen takes up a more active position.} Qc4 {Threateningto win with 26...Rc1+.} 26. Kb2 {"A mistake. 26 Kb1 was indicated" (Lasker). --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue?} ({It's quite surprising thatPillsbury's move loses, whereas with} 26. Kb1 $1 {he could have retained theadvantage after, for example,} Rxa3 27. Rc1 $1 (27. Qc2 Rc3 28. Qb2 b5 29. Rc2Bxd4 30. Rxc3 Bxc3) 27... Qb5+ {and now White can either keep the queens onwith} 28. Ka1 ({or head for the ending with} 28. Rb2 Qd3+ {(forced)} 29. Qxd3Rxd3 30. Rxb7 Bxd4 31. Rd7) 28... Re3 {(forced, due to the threat of 29 Rc8+,forcing Black to go 29...Kf7, after which 30 Rb2 wins)} 29. Rb2 ({now} 29. Rc8+Kf7 30. Rb2 {fails to} Re1+) 29... Qe8 30. Qxd5+ {.}) 26... Rxa3 $3 {ANSWER:"This is some kind of mysticism: the second rook is also sacrificed on thevery same square! I think that Pillsbury must have been unable to believe hiseyes..." (Kasparov).} 27. Qe6+ ({If} 27. Kb1 {then Black can play} Bxd4 28.Re1 Qb4+ 29. Kc1 Qc3+ 30. Qc2 Qa1+ 31. Qb1 Rc3+ 32. Rc2 Be3+ 33. Rxe3 Qxb1+ 34.Kxb1 Rxe3 {, and the rook ending should be a win for Black.}) 27... Kh7 ({Quicker was} 27... Kh8 28. Qe8+ Kh7 29. Kb1 Bxd4 {, but there is nothing wrongwith repeating moves.}) 28. Kxa3 ({"If} 28. Kb1 Bxd4 29. Qf5+ ({in this line} 29. Qe2 {is no better, in view of} Qb4+ $1 {regaining the exchange, with adecisive advantage}) 29... g6 30. Qd7+ Bg7 {wins" (Lasker).}) ({Instead, if} 28. Qf5+ {Here Lasker would have repeated moves with} Kg8 $1 {, and now if} ({Black should avoid} 28... Kh8 $2 {because of} 29. Kb1 $1 {and as 29...Bxd4??loses to 30 Qf8+ and Qxa3, he must play} Rxa2 30. Rxa2 Qb3+ 31. Kc1 {, when}Qxa2 $2 {, when} ({so Black must force a draw with} 31... Bg5+ 32. Rad2 Qc3+33. Qc2 Qa1+) 32. Qc8+ Kh7 33. Qc2+ {.}) 29. Kb1 {, then} ({while} 29. Qe6+ Kh8{transposes to the line given in the note to move 27, above}) 29... Bxd4 {is winning, since with the king on g8 there is no 30 Qf8+.}) 28... Qc3+ 29. Ka4{EXERCISE: How Lasker finish off this impressive game? --- ANSWER:} b5+ $1 {It's mate in three moves.} 30. Kxb5 Qc4+ 31. Ka5 Bd8+ {. Later Lasker calledthis game the best of his career. --- "Too many mistakes, you say? Pleasedon't rush to write off this game, and just remember its unique historicalimportance! That day Caissa chose Lasker, and as we know today, the chessgoddess did not err. Her cruel decision marked a fork in the lives of bothplayers. --- "Lasker, inspired by this victory, won the tournamentconvincingly. Later that year he crushed Steinitz in a rematch and kept histitle for 25 more years, while Pillsbury, after the above disaster, collapsedand lost five games out of the remaining eight, ending up third behindSteinitz. He never achieved the same peak of playing strength as in thatmagnificent year and died eight years later at the age of 34. --- "Who knowhow often Harry Nelson Pillsbury remembered that traumatic day in St.Petersburg and the chances he had missed - chances that would have changedhis entire life and the course of chess history" (Kasparov). --- The causeof the collapse of the only 23-year-old Pillsbury in the second half wasapparently that he had contracted syphilis, an illness which began to becurable only in 1908. He scored only one and a half points from the final ninegames, whereas Lasker continued playing at the same, very high level andscored 6/9.} 0-1[Event "15: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Chigorin, M"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D02"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "109"][EventDate "1895.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 Nf6 3. Bf4 Nbd7 4. Nc3 {Lasker decides to leave the usualchannels, which would involve playing e3 and Nbd2.} c6 ({QUESTION: Wouldn'tthe natural} 4... e6 {be better? --- ANSWER: Possibly. The motivation for thismove is that after 4...e6 White can to try to take advantage of his atypicaldevelopment by playing} 5. Nb5 {, when after the forced} Bb4+ 6. c3 Ba5 {, followed by a quick ...a6, forcing Na3, it remains to be seen which piece isworse placed, the bishop on a5 or the knight on a3.}) 5. e3 e6 6. Bd3 {Withthe idea of breaking with 7 e4, which could be played after 6...Be7.} Bb4 7.O-O h6 ({A bit mysterious as Black rejects} 7... O-O {. One might think it wasto be able to play 8...Nh5 and exchange knight for bishop, since it preventsBg5, but if that were the case then Chigorin changes his mind. In any casesince the position is a closed one, the 'waste' of a tempo isn't anythingserious.}) 8. Qe2 {Lasker insists on preparing the e4 break. An eventual ...Bxc3 is, of course, nothing for White to be afraid of, because his dominationof the dark squares would be more than sufficient compensation. Nor does hefear 8...Nh5, or else he would have played the thematic move 8 h3 to give thebishop an escape square on h2.} O-O ({It seems that Chigorin rejected} 8... Nh5{because of} 9. Be5 {when if} Nxe5 {, as well as} 10. Nxe5 {followed by f4,} ({White can play more strongly with} 10. dxe5 {and the black knight will not bewell placed on h5.})) 9. e4 Bxc3 10. bxc3 dxe4 11. Bxe4 Nxe4 12. Qxe4 {QUESTION: I find it surprising that Lasker not only lets his pawn structure bedamaged, but also allows opposite-coloured bishops. That doesn't seem the bestway to play for a win, does it? --- ANSWER: Yes, 9 e4 is a notable move, butdon't be in any doubt that Lasker was playing for a win. --- 'It's better tobe rich and healthy than poor and sick', is a Russian saying that Dvoretskyused to quote, but it is rare to have a choice between these extremes. Usuallyto gain something, you have to concede something else. In this case, as youmentioned, Lasker concedes the worse structure and the risk of a draw in thelong term due to the opposite-coloured bishops. --- The 'something' that Whitegains in this case consists of the possibility of occupying the half-open b-and e- files, as well as an advantage in space and development. Meanwhile,with respect to the bishops of opposite colour, at least for a while thef4-bishop will be much more active than the one on c8, and, furthermore, thereare still a lot of pieces on the board and the endgame is a long way away.} Nf613. Qd3 Nd5 ({QUESTION: Moving the knight? Isn't it better to think aboutdevelopment and play} 13... b6 {, with the idea of ...Bb7 - ? --- ANSWER:Apparently Chigorin considered 13...b6 inadequate because of} 14. c4 Bb7 15.Rfd1 {, with the idea of Qa3, when Black is passive, his bishop is inactive,and, for instance, the try} c5 16. dxc5 Qxd3 17. cxd3 Bxf3 18. gxf3 bxc5 {isn't at all satisfactory due to} 19. Rab1 {, with unpleasant pressure;Black's weakness on c5 looks more important than any of White's. --- The blackknight on f6 has no clear future after c4, while the one on f3 can go to e5 atan opportune moment; hence Chigorin wants to find a useful job for his knight.}) 14. Bd2 Ne7 {This is Black's idea; the knight is heading for g6, to parryWhite's possible Ne5.} 15. Rfe1 {Lasker brings a piece into play, using one ofhis half-open files, not changing his central formation with c4 yet.} Ng6 {EXERCISE: White has several ideas at his disposal here. What do you thinkLasker played in this position? --- ANSWER:} 16. Ne5 $1 ({QUESTION: Exchangingthe knights as well? You told me that this was exactly what Black wanted tohinder with his ...Nd5-e7-g6 manoeuvre. How do you explain this? --- ANSWER:In this position there are no immediate tactical issues, so it's possible toindulge in making long-term plans. Probably Lasker considered focusing on thequeenside with natural moves such as} 16. Rab1 {, for instance, occupying theother half-open file;}) ({or} 16. a4 {, another move which might be useful, tobe able to break with a5 when Black plays ...b6. --- Let's hand over to Nunnto explain why the world champion opted to play on the other wing: "Laskercame up with what is undoubtedly the strongest move, which provides an exampleof how thinking clearly about a position can lead you to the correct choicewithout any analysis. White potentially has threats against Black's kingsidesince his queen and bishop are well placed to attack the enemy king, but atthe moment Black's knight is a good defender. White's most logical plan istherefore to exchange the knight, leaving Black's kingside without any pieceprotection". --- After the exchange of knights, the bishops of oppositecolour will become more relevant, but not in the sense that they will bringthe game any nearer to a draw. Instead, they will favour White's futureoffensive against the black monarch, since even after Black's passivelight-squared bishop comes into play, it won't be an effective kingsidedefender. Of course this is only a small advantage, and Black still hassufficient defensive resources.}) 16... Nxe5 17. Rxe5 {White is planning toplay Re3-g3, as well as to include the other rook in the attack with Rae1,which would be the response to the natural move 17...b6.} f6 {This is a smallconcession. Black regains control of some important dark squares, but at thecost of weakening his pawn structure and saddling himself with a weakness one6 that will tie down his bishop to its defence. --- QUESTION: But what's hesupposed to do then? If he can't touch his pawns or develop the bishop, howcan he parry the coming offensive? --- ANSWER: Well, this move isn't a clearmistake and Black's position continues to be only a bit worse. It's just thatit isn't necessary at this stage, because there's a curious alternativedefensive method, using the queen as a shield, to disrupt White's plan ofattack.} ({The move is} 17... Qf6 {, with the idea of answering} 18. Re4 ({or} 18. Re3 {with} Qf5) 18... Qg6 {, and afterwards develop his queenside. LaterBlack might even be able to think about counterattacking with ...c5.}) 18. Re3{With the crystal-clear idea of playing 19 Rg3.} f5 $6 {This is definitely amove that makes the situation worse for Black, who loses control of someimportant dark squares.} ({It looks like a panicking reaction to prevent thewhite queen coming to g6: for instance, after} 18... c5 19. Rg3 {(threateningBxh6)} Kh8 20. Bxh6 $1 {(anyway), and now if} gxh6 {then} 21. Qg6 {winsquickly, since if} Qe7 22. Qxh6+ Qh7 {then White has} 23. Qxf8+ {, winning.}) (18... Bd7 {looks better, developing and connecting the rooks, but in that caseafter} 19. Rg3 Kh8 20. Bxh6 $1 gxh6 {White wins with} 21. Rg6 $1 {and there isno defence; for example,} ({not} 21. Qg6 $2 {this time, since after} Qe7 $1 22.Qxh6+ Qh7 {the f8-rook is defended}) 21... Rf7 ({or} 21... Qe7 22. Rxh6+ Kg823. Qg3+) 22. Rxh6+ Kg8 23. Qh3 {.}) ({However, there was a less weakening wayto defend against an invasion on g6, and that was with} 18... Qe8 {and after}19. Rg3 {, as well as} Kh8 {,} ({it's possible to play} 19... Qh5 {, (usingthe queen in similar fashion to 17...Qf6 above), replying to} 20. Rh3 {with}Qf5 21. Qg3 h5 $1 {and the defence holds.})) 19. Rg3 $6 {Logical;} ({but fortactical reasons it was better to play} 19. Rae1 {, with a clear advantage toWhite.}) 19... Qh4 $2 {Black fails to take advantage of White's lapse.} (19...Qf6 {was no good either, because of} 20. Bf4 {;}) ({but White last moveallowed Black to free his position with} 19... f4 $1 {Neither of these linesgives White any advantage, but he could also try} 20. Rh3 ({and the bishops ofopposite colour start to favour Black after, say,} 20. Rf3 e5 21. dxe5 Qxd3 22.cxd3 ({or} 22. Rxd3 Bf5) 22... g5 23. h3 Be6 24. c4 Rad8 {.}) {However, Blacktoo can improve with} 20... Qe8 $1 {:} ({with the idea of answering} 20... e5 {with} 21. Rh5 $1 {and the rook escapes, leaving White with slightly the betterprospects.} (21. Z0)) {or} 21. Rh4 ({for example,} 21. Re1 e5 22. Rxe5 Qf7 {, attacking a2, with the idea of ...Bf5, and after} 23. Rh4 Bf5 24. Qe2 Qxa2 {Black equalizes;} (24... Z0)) 21... e5 22. dxe5 Bf5 23. Qe2 ({or} 23. Qc4+ Be6{when} 24. Qb4 $2 {is met with} Qd8 $1) 23... f3 $1 {with sufficientcounterplay. --- There are other lines, but in all cases Black manages toactivate his pieces and gain adequate compensation.}) 20. Rh3 Qe7 21. Re1 {The advantage has shifted back to White's side, with attacking ideas thatinclude Bf4-e5 and Rg3.} ({It was also good to begin with} 21. Bf4 {.}) 21...Rf6 ({Now if} 21... f4 {there is time to play} 22. Rf3 g5 23. g3 $1 {, and therook avoids imprisonment. After} fxg3 24. Rxg3 {Black's kingside weaknessesare more serious than White's, since all the white pieces are aiming towardsthe black king, with the 25 h4 break in the air.}) 22. Bf4 Bd7 23. Rg3 ({Another idea was} 23. Qg3 Kf7 ({if} 23... Kh7 $2 {then} 24. Bg5) 24. Bd6 {, followed by c4, planning to regroup, but with the bishop placed veryunpleasantly for Black on d6, where it can be supported with c5.}) 23... Be824. c4 Qd7 25. Rge3 ({There are several interesting ideas here, such as thefamiliar one of securing a good post for the bishop on d6 with} 25. c5 {, which naturally is still not ruled out.}) 25... b6 26. Be5 {Black hasmanaged to manoeuvre his bishop to defend the kingside, but all the same we'vereached one of those situations in which the presence of bishops of oppositecolour favours the attacker, who will have virtually an extra piece as thestruggle develops.} Rg6 {A difficult decision. Black defends g7 with an activerook move, eyeing g2, but we shall see that everything is not all positiveabout this move.} ({It's understandable that he didn't want to play the passive} 26... Rf7 {, giving White a free hand. Nunn commented: "[26...Rf7] wouldhave given White a strong attack after} 27. Rg3 Kh7 28. Qd2 Rd8 29. Rh3 {, followed by playing the other rook round to g3."}) 27. f3 {The rook on g6has succeeded in making Black's kingside safe, but now it can't influenceevents on the other wing, which means that Lasker will have a big advantage inany operations on the queenside. The text move prevents a future ...Rg4.} Bf728. Qa3 {With the idea of playing 29 c5 and Bd6.} b5 29. cxb5 {Lasker decidesto open the game.} ({Less promising was} 29. c5 a5 $1 {;}) ({but keeping thetension with} 29. Qa6 {was also interesting.}) 29... cxb5 30. Rc3 Rc8 {Itwould be hopeless to allow 31 Rc7, followed by Qc5, paralyzing Black's game,so Chigorin decides to exchange the rook. --- EXERCISE: There are severalmoves that give White the advantage, but what do you think Lasker chose here?--- ANSWER:} 31. Ree3 $1 {The most precise move, guaranteeing the presence ofa white rook on the queenside, which will mean that Black will have difficultymaintaining the material balance.} Rc4 32. Rxc4 bxc4 33. Qb4 {Now Black willlose the pawn on c4 and White will thus gain a passed c-pawn, while the rookon g6 remains out of play. White's advantage is decisive.} Qd8 34. Qxc4 Qa5 35.Rc3 {Preventing ...Qd2 in the most active way.} Kh7 36. h3 {Correct. Beforeinvading the black camp, White gives his king an escape square.} ({However,White could also employ his monarch more actively, preventing the black queenfrom entering with} 36. Kf2 {, followed by a3, Qb4 and Rc7, when Black wouldbe defenceless;}) ({he could also initiate this plan with} 36. a3 {.}) 36...Be8 37. a3 Bb5 38. Qb4 Qa6 {Black is unwilling to wait passively and prepares39...Bf1.} 39. Rc7 $1 Bc6 {EXERCISE: Black has several threats here: 40...Bxf3,40...Rxg2+ and 40...Qe2, with sufficient counterplay to draw. How did Laskerdefend?} ({Now in the event of} 39... Bf1 {the manoeuvre} 40. c4 ({but it isquicker to play} 40. Qf8 $1 {, and after} Rxg2+ 41. Kh1 {the desperate resource} Rh2+ {fails to} 42. Bxh2 Bg2+ 43. Kxg2 Qe2+ 44. Kg3 Qe1+ 45. Kf4 {and theking escapes}) 40... Bxg2 41. Qf8 {is satisfactory, since the black queen isunable to join in the attack.}) 40. c4 $1 {ANSWER: The only move, and a goodone; the loss of the f3-pawn isn't serious. The main thing is to ensure thatBlack's queen can't enter play, as on their own the rook and the bishop arenot dangerous, so White has time to make progress with his own attack.} Bxf341. g3 $6 {This is a winning move; the threat of 42 Qf8 is tremendous andforces Black to enter a very bad endgame. However, it isn't the quickest wayto win.} ({The most 'human' way to win was with} 41. Kf2 $1 Bc6 {, and nowWhite should first block the bishop's attack on g2 with} ({if} 41... Bxg2 {then} 42. Qf8) 42. d5 $1 {, when there is no defence after} exd5 43. Qf8 {.}) ({The computer's winning method is to play} 41. Qf8 $1 {, allowing} Rxg2+ {, since White eventually wins after the long sequence} 42. Kf1 Kg6 43. Rxg7+Kh5 44. Qf7+ Kh4 45. Rxg2 Qxc4+ 46. Kg1 Bxg2 47. Bf6+ Kg3 48. Qg7+ {and 49Qxg2.}) 41... Qb6 42. Kf2 Be4 {Black manages to avoid defeat in the middlegameand, although the ending is losing, he can still resist.} 43. Qxb6 axb6 44. a4h5 45. h4 {Of course, preventing ...h4 and keeping Black's rook out of play.There is no need to give the opponent unnecessary chances.} Rg4 46. Ke3 {Lasker opts to head with his king to the queenside, to support the advance ofhis pawns, or ideally to first capture the one on b6. The black rook has morefreedom, but remains tied to the defence of g7.} Bg2 47. Kd3 Kg8 48. Kc3 Kf849. Bf4 $6 {An odd decision; it isn't necessary to imprison the rook.} ({Lasker could have continued with his idea,} 49. Kb4 $1 {. Now the win becomesslightly more complicated, for tactical reasons.}) 49... Ke8 {EXERCISE: Whiteis still winning, but now care is required to avoid giving the opponentexcessive counter-chances. How should White continue here?} 50. Ra7 $6 {This move 'passes', but there is a price to pay.} (50. Kb4 {was better,although not the strongest.}) ({ANSWER: The most convincing was the manoeuvre} 50. Rc8+ $1 Kd7 51. Rh8 $1 {, with which White would have suppressed theunnecessary counterplay that now ensues.}) 50... g5 $1 {The black rook finallygains some activity.} 51. Bxg5 (51. hxg5 h4 {is no better.}) 51... Rxg3+ 52.Kb4 Rxg5 $4 {Tiredness begins to affect Chigorin too.} ({He had to play} 52...Rg4 $1 {, attacking the d4-pawn. It's true that objectively he would still beconsiderably worse after} 53. Re7+ Kd8 $1 54. Rxe6+ Kd7 55. Re7+ Kd6 56. Re8Kc6 57. Bf6 {, but there would still be a struggle.}) 53. hxg5 h4 {The pawnsare easily stopped.} 54. Rh7 h3 55. g6 {The threat is 56 Rh8+, followed by g7;}({and after} 55. g6 Kf8 56. c5 bxc5+ 57. dxc5 f4 58. Kb5 {, there is no wayfor Black to carry on the fight.}) 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Nuremberg 1896"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker's superiority at St. Petersburg was unquestionable; only Tarraschremained unconvinced that Lasker was truly the world number one. In order totest this, a "second Hastings" was organized in Nuremberg, with most ofthe Hastings participants present, and this time also the young Geza Maróczyand Rudolf Charousek from Austro-Hungary.} 1. Z0 {However, the tournament didnot turn out as Tarrasch hoped. Lasker had another clear victory, scoring 13½/18; in a surprising second place came Maróczy, with 12½, while Tarrasch tiedfor third and fourth place with Pillsbury, on 12 points. --- Lasker racedahead with six points from his first seven games, scoring five wins and twodraws. Let's look at part of this crushing start (see the following game).} *[Event "16: Nuremberg"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Porges, M"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C67"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "66"][EventDate "1896.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 ({"Lasker's favourite defence, in place ofthe alternative} 3... d6 {", commented Tarrasch in the tournament book.}) 4.O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7 (5... Nd6 {was Kramnik's invincible weapon against Kasparovin their 2000 match in London, opening a new field in the theory of theopenings. It was not really new though. Lasker himself had used it more than ahundred years before; his dramatic defeat against Tarrasch in Hastings 1895,the final part of which we examined in an earlier extract, began the same way.After} 6. Bxc6 dxc6 7. dxe5 Nf5 8. Qxd8+ Kxd8 9. Nc3 h6 10. Bd2 Be6 11. Ne2 c512. Bc3 g5 {Black obtained a satisfactory position, although after acomplicated struggle, Lasker ended up losing, as we saw.}) 6. Qe2 Nd6 7. Bxc6bxc6 {Now the knight must retire for a while to a very uncomfortable positionon b7, since placing it on a more active square doesn't inspire muchconfidence.} ({After} 7... dxc6 8. dxe5 Nf5 {White can play} 9. Rd1 Bd7 {and now there are several possibilities:} 10. Nc3 {seems better, keeping theg4 advance in reserve.} ({The violent} 10. e6 {, which after} fxe6 11. Ne5 {looks good, but after} Bd6 12. Qh5+ g6 13. Nxg6 Ng7 14. Qh6 Nf5 15. Qh3 Rg8 16.Qxh7 Rg7 17. Qh5 Qf6 {, already played in K.Lepge-L.Paulsen, Leipzig 1863, andmore recently in P.Svidler-A.Morozevich, Wijk aan Zee 2005, White was unableto prove any advantage; the active black pieces, with the bishop pair,compensate for the pawn.}) ({Tarrasch praised Showalter's idea} 10. g4 {, which gives White the advantage after 10...Nh6 11 Bxh6, but not after} Nh4 $1{, when a key line is} (10... Nh6 11. Bxh6) 11. Nxh4 $1 Bxh4 12. g5 {, and nowBlack should rescue the trapped bishop with the manoeuvre} Qe7 $1 ({not} 12...Bxg5 $2 13. e6 $1) 13. Qh5 Qb4 {, with a playable game.})) 8. dxe5 Nb7 {This line was played many times by Lasker, which is evidence that it can't beso bad; nowadays it is still considered playable, although a little passive.White has a space advantage and the better pawn structure, to which we can addhe bad position of the knight on b7, but the pair of bishops gives Black hopesfor the future. Nevertheless, Tarrasch's opinion was very scathing: "If aknight has invested four moves out of eight in the opening to end up in suchan incredible position, I cannot consider this anything less than ridiculous;neither can I understand why this manner of development was accepted as normalfor so many years".} ({The alternative} 8... Nf5 {has never been popularbecause of} 9. Qe4 {, although it has been much less explored. After} g6 {White can play} 10. Nd4 (10. Nc3) ({and} 10. b3 {are other good options}) 10...Nxd4 11. Qxd4 O-O ({or} 11... d5 $1 {, "As my former assistant, grandmasterVladimirov liked to play"; this move was also employed by Spassky}) 12. Bh6Re8 13. Nc3 {, S.Tarrasch-J.Taubenhaus, Monte Carlo 1903, which ended in awhite victory after the weak move} Bg5 $4 {;} ({although White's advantage isminimal after} 13... c5) ({or} 13... d5 {.})) 9. b3 {"You should develop theknights before the bishops," recommended Lasker, although he had also playedthis move, six years before. --- QUESTION: Yes, I've heard that advice ofLasker before. What does he mean exactly? --- ANSWER: What Lasker is gettingat is that generally where the knights should go is clearer than where toplace bishops. This position is a case in point; is b2 the best location forthe bishop? That can't be asserted with any certainty, whereas it would behard to find a better square for the queen's knight than c3.} ({9 Nc3 is themain line, while} 9. c4 O-O 10. Nc3 {is a good alternative.}) ({After} 9. Nc3O-O {there are several possibilities:} {The most promising move is} 10. Re1 {, an idea of Pillsbury's, to make it more difficult for Black to break with ...d5, by preventing him from recapturing with the pawn on d6 after White playsexd6. This was played in the world championship match between Lasker andTarrasch in 1908.} ({Further on we'll see} 10. Nd4 {played in Winawer-Laskerfrom this same tournament.}) (10. Rd1 {doesn't give White much after} d5 {, M.Tal-L.Pachman, Moscow 1967,} ({or} 10... Nc5 11. Bf4 Ne6 12. Bg3 d5 $1 {, A.Shirov-J.Timman, Dordrecht 1999.}))) 9... O-O 10. Bb2 d5 {Of course, andwhy not? This regains one degree of space and mobility. And now 'the ball isin White's court'; should he take on d6 or not?} 11. exd6 {QUESTION: So,clarify for me, is it better to take on d6 or not?} ({"This dissipates theadvantage gained by White in the opening, at the same time as it consolidatesthe game of the opponent," commented Tarrasch, who suggested} 11. Nbd2 {, which was played by a young Lasker, and which won quickly,} {The gamecontinued, instead:} c5 ({although Black should be fine after} 11... a5 {, a typical and good move, when if} 12. a4 {the knight can recycled with} Nc5 {.} (12... Z0)) 12. Rfd1 Bf5 13. Rac1 Qc8 14. Nf1 Qe6 15. Ne3 Be4 16. Nd2 Bg617. f4 f6 $2 18. Qf3 $1 fxe5 19. Qxd5 Qxd5 20. Nxd5 Bd8 21. Bxe5 c6 22. Ne3 Bb623. Ndc4 {1-0 Em.Lasker-O.Müller, London 1891.}) ({We shall examine} 11. Nd4 {in Game 17, Teichmann-Lasker.}) 11... cxd6 {ANSWER: It's possible that there'sreally no definite answer; both moves have their advantages and disadvantages.Exchanging pawns can favour the black bishops, but it also clears the way forthe b2-bishop and opens the d-file in White's favour, while keeping the pawnon e5 keeps the position closed and restricts the mobility of the black pieces,but the b2-bishop is left staring at its own pawn on e5.} ({Recapturing withthe bishop,} 11... Bxd6 {, doesn't look very nice and is not good in fact;after} 12. Nbd2 Re8 13. Qc4 Re6 14. Rfe1 {the white position is superior. Thiswas played by... can you guess? It appeared in the game G.Marco-S.Tarrasch,Vienna 1898, and Tarrasch even played this "ridiculous" variation with theknight on b7 a second time in the same tournament, winning again, but with 11...cxd6 that time, against Schiffers; he won an endgame with his pair of bishopsafter also gaining the better pawn structure. That seems to show us two sidesof the same coin; although Tarrasch was very categorical in his opinions, hewasn't totally inflexible and was capable of changing his mind.}) 12. Nbd2 {EXERCISE: What did Lasker play here? --- ANSWER:} Re8 $1 {"From this square,the rook threatens the white queen, and it is interesting to see how thisindirect threat gives Black one decisive advantage", commented Tarrasch,although, of course, at the moment there is no such clear advantage.} ({Lasker had chosen} 12... Bf6 {against Pillsbury in St. Petersburg a few monthsbefore; he lost that game, although after} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Rfe1 Nc5 15. Ne4Nxe4 16. Qxe4 Bd7 17. c4 Rfe8 18. Qd4 Rxe1+ 19. Rxe1 Qxd4 20. Nxd4 Kf8 {Black's position was not worse.}) 13. Rfe1 Bd7 ({There were several attractivemoves here, such as} 13... Nc5) ({or} 13... d5 {, but Lasker prefers to defendhis rook on e8, postponing any decisions about his centre and the destinationof b7-knight.}) 14. Ne4 $2 {This, played almost automatically, is a definiteblunder.} (14. Nf1 {was better;}) ({or} 14. Nc4 {and if} d5 {, the knightretreats safely to e3;}) ({while Tarrasch faced} 14. Qf1 {in theaforementioned game against Schiffers, but this isn't very convincing.}) 14...d5 {Of course. Now Tarrasch's premonition about the 'X-ray' pressure of thee8-rook against the white queen on e2 becomes reality and the white positionstarts to collapse.} 15. Ned2 ({Not} 15. Ng3 {because of} Bb4 {, winning theexchange.}) 15... Ba3 {Forcing White to move his bishop to a very awkwardsquare. Admittedly Black's bishop is loose on a3, which allows a timely Qa6,unpinning and attacking the bishop at the same time, but this will prove to bean ineffective defence, as Lasker will demonstrate.} 16. Be5 {EXERCISE (simple): How did Lasker exploit White's careless play? --- ANSWER:} f6 $1 {Thisdoesn't win a piece, as we know, but Black will gain a very strong centre.} (16... Bb2 {wasn't winning either, because after} 17. Rab1 Bxe5 18. Nxe5 f6 {White still has the resource} 19. Qa6 $1 {.}) 17. Qa6 {The only move.} fxe5 18.Qxa3 {Once again the only move;} (18. Qxb7 $2 {loses to} e4 19. Nd4 Bb2 {.})18... e4 19. Nd4 Qf6 ({Activating the queen with a gain of time, although itwas perhaps slightly better to play} 19... a5 {first.}) 20. c3 $2 {Verypassive.} ({It was essential to play} 20. Qb4 $1 {, bringing the queen backinto the defence, even though it would be exposed to a quick ...c5; Blackwould be better after} Rf8 ({or} 20... Rab8 {, threatening ...c5, but itwouldn't be simple.})) 20... Rf8 21. f3 {This isn't very pleasant. ---EXERCISE: How now to best increase the pressure?} ({But after} 21. Rf1 {Black can continue powerfully with} Qg5 $1 {, attacking the d2-knight andthreatening 22...Bh3.}) 21... Qg5 $1 {ANSWER: "One blow after another.Lasker plays the attack with great energy" (Tarrasch).} 22. Qc1 {Forced;} (22. Re2 {loses to} c5 23. Nc2 exf3 {.}) 22... Nc5 $1 {The threat of 23...Nd3is decisive;} ({whereas now} 22... Bh3 23. Re2 c5 24. Nc2 exf3 {isn't soeffective, because after} 25. Nxf3 {White doesn't lose any material.}) 23. Nf1Qg6 24. Re3 Nd3 {The knight joins the attack with gain of time.} 25. Qd1 Nf426. Ng3 h5 $1 27. Nde2 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker finish off the game?} ({The pressure on g2 can't be relieved with} 27. Qf1 {, since Black can continuesimply with} Rae8 ({or} 27... h4) ({but the strongest is} 27... Qg5 $1 {, exploiting the tactical weakness of the loose rook on e3; then after} 28.Ree1 {Black wins with} c5 {, eliminating the second defender of f3.})) 27...Nxg2 $1 {ANSWER: Tarrasch continued with his praises: "Speeding up thefinish with an elegant combination".} 28. Kxg2 exf3+ 29. Rxf3 Bh3+ ({Betterthan} 29... Rxf3 {.}) 30. Kxh3 $1 ({Now if} 30. Kf2 {it is stronger for Blackto have the bishop on h3 after} Rxf3+ 31. Kxf3 h4 {.}) 30... Qg4+ 31. Kg2 Qxf3+32. Kg1 (32. Kh3 {can also be answered with} h4 {, and if} 33. Kxh4 {thenBlack wins with} Rf6 {.}) 32... h4 33. Nh1 Qe3+ ({White resigned;} 33... Qe3+34. Nf2 {is forced;} ({since} 34. Kg2 {allows mate in one with} h3# {.})) (33... Z0 {Tarrasch took a degree of small revenge in the tournament book byincluding a 'table of fortune' in which he demonstrated the "accidental goodfortune" received by each of the ten highest-placed players in thetournament. It was no surprise that he included Lasker as the one mostfavoured by the "gifts" presented to him by good fortune in five gamesthat he should have lost. --- It's likely that Tarrasch really believed whathe asserted, but the picture he paints is an incomplete one, unworthy of atop-class player. It reminds me of a present-day football manager, blaming histeam's defeats on the poor performance of the referee, but quoting only thedecisions which went against his team. --- It's not enough to play better thanthe opponent in just one phase of a game to mathematically win. Nobodywillingly draws or loses a much superior or winning position; it's almostalways the result of the difficulties that the opponent has set, involvingsurprising defences, superior calculation, etc, leading one to make mistakes.In this respect Lasker was unbeatable. --- Lasker had the bye in the seventhround, and after his impressive start, he went through a bad patch, losing twoconsecutive games. In Round 9 he lost to Pillsbury in an extraordinary gamewhich won the Beauty Prize, and in Round 10 he succumbed to Janowski afterspoiling a very advantageous position.}) 0-1[Event "17: Nuremberg"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Teichmann, R"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C67"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "98"][EventDate "1896.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{After ten rounds Steinitz was leading with 8/10, while Lasker, with 6/9, wasnow only in sixth place. But he recovered immediately, achieving fiveconsecutive wins. Let's look at part of what happened.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O Nxe4 5. d4 Be7 6. Qe2 Nd6 7. Bxc6 bxc6 8. dxe5 Nb7 9. b3 O-O 10.Bb2 d5 11. Nd4 $6 {EXERCISE: How should Black respond to the attack on thec6-pawn?} ({In the previous game we saw} 11. exd6 cxd6 12. Nbd2 {, which wasfollowed by} Re8 $1 {, with a good position for Black. White can't hope formuch more, since, as we indicated, 9 b3 isn't the most challenging move in theposition.}) 11... Qd7 $1 {ANSWER! --- QUESTION: Hmm, OK, but isn't the queenawkwardly placed on d7?} ({But not} 11... Bd7 $2 {because of} 12. e6 $1 {, winning a pawn;}) ({nor} 11... c5 {, since after} 12. Nc6 {White exchangesthe e7-bishop and thus Black loses one of the factors that compensate for hisworse structure, namely the pair of bishops.}) 12. Nd2 $6 {ANSWER: Certainly,but White can't force it to stay there for very long; it will soon move to abetter square. --- Another automatic move.} ({Instead,} 12. f4 {would at leastjustify the previous knight move.}) 12... c5 {Of course, driving back theknight and gaining space. We can see that White's last two moves were'routine': one activated a piece and the other was a developing move; but theyweren't the best and Black's position already starts to be superior.} 13. N4f3{QUESTION: You just said that White's last two knight moves aren't the best,but is White's play really so bad? As far as I can see, he only needs todevelop his rooks, whereas Black still has to develop his c8-bishop andredeploy his b7-knight, etc. So why do you say that Black is slightly better?--- ANSWER: What you say is quite correct. White's minor pieces are alreadydeveloped, and Black is poorly coordinated. This would be favourable to Whitein most cases, when his dynamic advantage (supposed in this case) could beexploited. --- The problem is the lack of a plan; what can White really do?It's very difficult to imagine a productive plan for him, since his minorpieces have no promising squares to head for, and as regards his pawns,although he can attack the centre with c4, to try to force Black to move ...d4and give White the e4-square, Black doesn't have to co-operate. Instead ofadvancing with ...d4, he can even turn a weakness into a strength by playing ...c6, supporting the centre and making productive use of his doubled pawn. ---In contrast, Black, with no immediate defensive worries, can regroupeffectively and activate his pieces. He also has the typical plan of ...a5,with the idea of ...a4 and getting rid isolated pawn at the most appropriatemoment.} Qf5 {Of course, activating the queen with tempo, by attacking thepawn on c2.} 14. Rac1 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue his regrouping? ---ANSWER:} c6 $1 {QUESTION: What's so good about this move? Why not improve theknight with ...Nd8 and ...Ne6 - ? --- ANSWER: Let's hand over to Nunn: "It'ssmall finesses such as this that make the difference between good players andgreat players. Black would prefer to keep the queens on the board as White'sposition is rather cramped and there are attacking chances on the kingsidebased on ...Qh5, ...Bg4 and ...Ne6-f4. By defending the d5-pawn in advance,Black ensures that he can avoid the exchange of queens in the event of Qd3 byWhite.} ({If Black plays immediately} 14... Nd8 {, then} 15. Qd3 {attacks thed5-pawn and so forces Black either to retreat his queen or to allow a queenswap".}) ({We can add that if Black starts with} 14... Qh5 {then White canplay} 15. Nd4 {. Then, since Black would prefer not to exchange queens, theonly choice is to play} Bg4 16. f3 Bd7 {, but after} 17. f4 Bg4 {White cancounter attack with} 18. Qb5 {, and his prospects have clearly improved;} Nd8 {can be answered with} 19. Ba3 {.}) 15. Rfe1 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker continuenow? --- ANSWER:} a5 $1 (15... Nd8 {was also good, improving the worse placedpiece;}) ({as was} 15... Qg6 {, making way for the c8-bishop, but beforecommitting any of his pieces, Lasker creates the possibility of playing ...a4,and then infiltrating along the a-file. He also creates the possibility of ...Ba6, once his knight has started its manoeuvre.}) 16. a4 {This radicallyprevents Black's idea, but it isn't cost-free; the white pawn structure losesmobility.} Nd8 {Finally there is nothing better than improving the placementof the knight.} 17. Nf1 Ne6 18. Ng3 Qg6 {There is a big difference betweeneach side's knight manoeuvres. While the b7-knight is much better on e6, withchances to become active on f4, bringing the d2-knight to g3 has notnoticeably improved its prospects.} 19. Qd2 {EXERCISE: And now how did Laskercontinue? --- ANSWER:} h5 $1 {Showing the negative side of the Nf1-g3manoeuvre; White's knight helps Black make progress.} 20. Ne2 {White has tochoose between two evils: allowing Black to make progress with ...h4, orpreventing it with the weakening move 20 h4; neither option is pleasant.} ({Nunn indicates that in the event of} 20. h4 {Black can win a pawn with} Qg4 21.Ba3 Bxh4 22. Nxh4 Qxh4 {, but} 23. Nf5 {"gives White excellent counterplaysince his pieces have come to life and his dark-squared bishop in particularstarts to look menacing. Therefore, Black would have to proceed more slowly".}) {White is now planning to exchange the knights with 21 Nf4.} 20... Qf5 {Before playing ...h4 Lasker wants to prevent the exchange of knights. Thisisn't an obvious choice, because it allows White the option of playing 21 h4,but everything indicates that Lasker wasn't afraid of this defence.} ({Nevertheless,} 20... h4 {was good. After} 21. Nf4 Nxf4 22. Qxf4 {Black can play} Bh3 23. g3 hxg3 24. hxg3 Qh5 {and White's kingside has been weakened.}) 21.Ba3 ({After a neutral move such as} 21. Red1 {Black can play in various ways:}h4 {,} (21... Ba6) ({and a 'new', promising idea:} 21... g5 {.})) ({With} 21.Ng3 Qg4 22. h3 Qg6 23. h4 {there would be a transposition to the possible linewith 20 h4, examined above.}) 21... Re8 {Lasker's move 21...Re8 defends hisloose bishop on e7 and neutralizes the pressure exerted by White's a3-bishop.}(21... h4 {was playable, but not clearly advantageous. The move 21 Ba3contained some venom, enabling White to go} 22. Ned4 {, with the possiblecontinuation} Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Bg5 24. Nxf5 Bxd2 25. Ne7+ Kh7 26. Bxc5 {, andthanks to his extra pawn and domination of the dark squares, White hascompensation for the exchange.}) ({On the other hand,} 21... g5 $2 {seriouslyweakens Black's position and} 22. Ned4 $1 {is even stronger than after 21...h4;following} Nxd4 23. Nxd4 Qd7 {, White has the winning shot} ({instead of 23...Qd7,} 23... Qg6 {allows} 24. e6 $1 fxe6 25. Nxc6 Bd6 26. Re5 $1 {(or 26 c4),with advantage to White}) 24. Bxc5 $1 {with the idea of} Bxc5 25. Qxg5+ Kh7 26.Qxh5+ Kg7 {, and after clearing the ground for the arrival of the rook with}27. Qg5+ Kh7 28. Qh4+ Kg7 {, White plays} 29. Re3 {, winning.}) 22. Qe3 ({Teichmann still refrains from playing} 22. h4 {, and Black's next move rulesit out indefinitely.}) 22... h4 {Threatening to break up White's position with23...h3.} 23. h3 {EXERCISE: What now?} ({In the event of} 23. Qd3 {, seekingto weaken Black's attack by exchanging the queens, Black would happily play}Qxd3 24. cxd3 Rb8 {, since after} 25. Rb1 Ba6 {the weaknesses in White'sstructure are brought to light and after} 26. Red1 {Black can simply play} Rb7{, with the plan of doubling rooks. White would then be tied down to thedefence of his weak pawns, as well as paralyzed by having to prevent ...Nf4 or...Bg5; Black could then consider opening lines at the right moment with ...f6.} ({However, as Nunn pointed out, Black can also strike immediately with "} 26... Bxd3 $1 27. Rxd3 c4 28. Rdd1 Bxa3 29. bxc4 dxc4 30. Nxh4 Bb2 {and thec-pawn is extremely dangerous".}) (26... g5 $1 {would also be good, with theidea of answering} 27. h3 {with the same combination, but under even betterconditions, since the possibility of Nxh4, as in Nunn's line above, isprevented.})) 23... Ba6 {ANSWER: Controlling d3 and putting pressure on thee2-knight, with the idea of 24...d4 25 Qd2 Red8, when ...d3, activating theblack forces even more, can't be prevented.} 24. Kh1 {QUESTION: What's goingon? Black has a clear plan, yet White simply says 'pass'? --- ANSWER: In thiscase appearances are deceptive. Observe that the e2-knight has no moves;White's king move frees g1 for the knight, so that after ...Red8 the knightcan retreat there, enabling White to answer ...d3 with c4, keeping linesclosed. --- "It's an ingenious defence, but the fact that this clumsymanoeuvre is White's best option says a great deal about his position" (Nunn).} d4 25. Qd2 Red8 {'The threat is stronger than the execution'; 25...d3 wasgood, but now this lends it even greater force.} 26. Neg1 {White continueswith his plan of evacuation, parrying the threat of 26...d3 27 cxd3 Rxd3 28Qc2 Rxf3! 29 gxf3 Qxh3+ 30 Kg1 Ng5, winning.} Nf4 {Black occupies the groundthat White has conceded, and he stands better, but there is nothing concreteyet.} 27. Bxc5 $2 {A mistake in calculation. White thinks he can exploit thefact that the e7-bishop and the black queen are overloaded.} ({It was betterto continue to wait with} 27. Rcd1 {, after which there are severalpossibilities: one is to manoeuvre in pursuit of a kingside breakthrough with ...g5 and a timely ...g4, for which it is useful to start with} Bc8 {.}) 27...Bxc5 28. Nxh4 Qg5 29. Ngf3 {EXERCISE: White seems to be regaining the piecewith advantage. How did Lasker refute Teichmann's combination? --- ANSWER:} Bb4$1 {The white queen can't retreat and at the same time maintain the attack onthe f4-knight, so Black will emerge with an extra piece, for two pawns.} 30.Qxb4 Qxh4 31. Qd2 Qh6 32. Re4 Ne6 33. Qe1 d3 ({Black could prepare thisadvance with} 33... c5 {, but this isn't necessary.}) 34. cxd3 Nf4 ({It wassimpler to play} 34... c5 {, followed by 35...Rxd3, but the text move is alsogood. Black is winning and that evaluation holds true for many moves.}) 35. Qe3Nxd3 36. Qxh6 gxh6 37. Rc2 Bc8 38. Nd4 c5 39. Nb5 Be6 40. Nd6 Rab8 41. f4 Bxb342. Rd2 c4 43. f5 Nc5 {This wins, but it isn't the strongest move.} ({It wasbetter to play either} 43... Rb4 {, threatening 44...c3;}) ({or the combination} 43... Nxe5 $1 44. Rxe5 c3 45. Rd4 c2 46. Re1 Bxa4 47. Rxa4 Rb1 {, as givenby Tarrasch.}) 44. Rg4+ Kh7 45. Nxc4 Rxd2 46. Nxd2 Re8 {Lasker has had severalopportunities to shorten White's sufferings. Although in this case objectivelythe win was never in danger, what happens in practice is that the longer youtake to finish off a won game, obviously the more chances of salvation yougive the opponent.} ({Here the quickest way was to play} 46... Rb4 47. Rg3 Bd5{, followed by capturing the a4-pawn, preventing any white counterplay.}) 47.Nf3 $6 {Now though, the win is easy.} ({Better practical chances were offeredwith} 47. Nxb3 Nxb3 48. f6 {Nunn indicated another way:} h5 ({but with} 48...Rg8 49. Rc4 h5 {Black could slowly reel in the win: for example,} 50. Rc6 {(threatening 51 Rb6 Nc5 52 Rb5)} Rb8 {, followed by ...Kg6 and at the rightmoment ...Rb4, capturing the a4-pawn.} (50... Z0)) 49. Rg7+ Kh6 50. Rxf7 Rxe5 {, pointing out that although Black is winning, given how little materialremains, he will need to play with the utmost care. As a sample winning line,Nunn gives: "} 51. Rf8 Nd4 52. Rd8 Ne6 53. Rg8 Ng5 54. h4 Nh7 55. f7 Rf5 56.Ra8 Kg7 57. Ra7 Nf6 58. Kh2 Ng4+ 59. Kg3 Nh6 {and the f-pawn falls".}) 47...Nd3 48. Rg3 Bd5 49. e6 fxe6 0-1[Event "18: Nuremberg"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Tarrasch, S"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C68"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "81"][EventDate "1896.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{After the fifteenth round Lasker was now leading the tournament with 11/14,followed by Maróczy with 9½. --- In the 18th round there came the encounterbetween Lasker and Tarrasch. Lasker was in the lead with 12½/16, followed byTarrasch himself and Pillsbury, with 11. Let's see what happened in this greatduel.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {Lasker used the Exchangevariation in many important games, and generally with success. He didn'tnecessarily reach advantageous positions, but his skill in the endgame, bothsimple and complex ones, was often sufficient to overcome the majority of hisopponents, especially in the so-called "queenless middlegames", asKasparov categorized the 'Berlin endgame'; that label could also be applied tomany endgames arising from the Exchange variation.} dxc6 5. Nc3 {"For achange, Lasker does not adopt here his usual variation 5 d4", commentedTarrasch. However, this was only the third time that Lasker employed theExchange variation in a serious game.} ({Lasker had played} 5. d4 {, and lost,against Steinitz in the thirteenth game of their 1894 world championship match;}) ({and, curiously, on his debut with the Exchange variation, againstMortimer in London 1892, for the only time in his career he played 'Fischer'smove'} 5. O-O {. We can deduce that Lasker didn't like to decide the locationof his monarch so soon, and subsequently he alternated between 5 Nc3 and 5 d4.--- Capablanca, annotating his win against Janowski in St. Petersburg 1914,wrote that he and Alekhine had analyzed this position on several occasions.Alekhine considered at that time that 5 Nc3 was superior to the more popular 5d4, and in the St. Petersburg event he played it against Lasker himself,"And gained a superior position, and if he subsequently lost, it was due toa serious error on his part", according to Capablanca.}) 5... Bc5 {QUESTION:But 5...Bc5 is a developing move, and it prepares castling. What can possiblybe wrong with it?} ({As 5 Nc3 does not threaten anything, there are many waysto reply. All of} 5... Bg4) (5... Bd6) ({and} 5... Qd6 {have been played;}) ({but both Tarrasch and later Capablanca stated that} 5... f6 {was the mostprecise, and that remains the main move.}) 6. d3 {ANSWER: Yes, it's adeveloping move, but that's not the priority in this position. The snag isthat after a later Be3 by White, if the bishops are exchanged, Black loses oneelement of his compensation for his damaged pawn structure, which is thebishop pair.} (6. Nxe5 {gives White no advantage because of} Bxf2+ {,regaining the pawn after} 7. Kxf2 Qd4+ {.}) 6... Bg4 7. Be3 {I recall that inmy youth the Argentinean master, Gregorio Lastra, emphasized to me thatFischer "always" put the question to the bishop in such situations, toforce a decision: either exchange or have just one diagonal.} ({In the event of} 7. h3 Bh5 {White has gained the extra possibility of playing g4 at somepoint.}) 7... Qd6 ({Tarrasch was convinced that this was the best moveavailable to Black, since} 7... Bxe3 8. fxe3 {"would have opened the f-file,giving White chances for future operations". After} Qe7 9. O-O {Black made amove that Capablanca described as "bold play, typical of Janowski", whichcuriously reduced the opening of the f-file to merely secondary importance; heplayed} O-O-O {, and after} 10. Qe1 Nh6 {, we now challenge you with anexercise which for once isn't drawn from one of Lasker's games. --- EXERCISE:What would you play with White? --- ANSWER: Let's hand over to Capablanca:"The problem for White now is to advance his b-pawn to b5 as fast as he can.If he plays an immediate b4, Black will take it. If he plays first a3 and thenb4, he will have to protect his b-pawn before he can go on and play a4 and b5.Here White played a quite unusual move, but which, given the circumstances,was the best, since White can play b4 and a4 right away, to continue with b5." --- The continuation was} 11. Rb1 $1 f6 12. b4 Nf7 13. a4 {, 1-0 in 31moves, J.R.Capablanca-D.Janowski, St. Petersburg 1914.}) 8. Bxc5 Qxc5 {Tarrasch considered that Lasker's decision to exchange pieces came aboutbecause this was the final phase of the tournament and "he preferred not torun any risks"; it is difficult to agree that this was the only reason.Lasker was an excellent endgame player and it can't be ruled out that he wasrelying on his strength in that area.} 9. Qd2 {Lasker's move threatens to winwith 10 Qg5 Bxf3 11 Qxg7. It's easily prevented, but it also gives Black thechance to damage White's pawn structure. But is this really good for Black?Lasker thought not.} ({QUESTION: What? Letting his pawns be doubled? Why notthe natural} 9. h3 {- ? --- ANSWER: We can suppose that Lasker considered that}Bxf3 10. Qxf3 Ne7 {wasn't very promising and in fact it's hard to see anyproblems for Black here. He can castle on either wing, he has no problems ofmobility and there is no obvious plan by White that Black needs to fear.}) 9...Bxf3 $6 {As in similar positions from the Exchange variation, this damage tothe white structure isn't disadvantageous for White if can play a later f4,getting rid of the pawn in order to end up with more pawns in the centre.} ({After the game Tarrasch criticized his decision: "A grievous misjudgement,bringing disadvantage to Black.} 9... f6 {was indicated".}) ({The threat of10 Qg5 can also be parried with} 9... Ne7 {, since then} 10. Qg5 {can beanswered with} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Ng6 {.}) 10. gxf3 Ne7 {EXERCISE: How to continuenow as White? --- ANSWER:} 11. O-O-O {A really surprising decision; Laskerlets the opportunity to play f4 slip by. This advance would have given Whitethe advantage in the centre.} Ng6 12. Qe3 $1 {Tarrasch: "An excellent movewhich accentuates all Black's weaknesses".} Qxe3+ {This is a clearerinaccuracy; now White's task of playing f4 is made easier, and Black iscompletely passive. --- Tarrasch admitted his error: "Not good, because itstrengthens White's centre. But after 12...Qe7 Black could not have castledQ-side on account of Qa7, whereas castling K-side would have been dangerous onaccount of the open g-file. Black is paying the penalty of his mistake on the9th move."} ({Everything indicates that this evaluation is too pessimistic.In this line with} 12... Qe7 {, followed by 13...0-0, Black isn't obliged toawait execution along the g-file, but instead can react with ...f5, reaching areasonable position: for example, after} 13. Ne2 O-O 14. f4 {, Black can play}({or} 14. Rdg1) 14... f5 $1 {, and isn't worse after} 15. fxe5 fxe4 16. dxe4Nxe5 ({or} 16... Qf7 {. The resource ...f5 is something that we should keep inmind for the rest of the game.})) ({Preparing queenside castling wasn't badeither, in this case with} 12... Qd6 {, and after} 13. Ne2 c5 $1 {(preventingthe incursion Qa7) and 14...0-0-0, Black doesn't stand badly.}) 13. fxe3 {"The exchange of queens has also allowed White to restrict the enemy knightand prevented it from jumping to the square f4", commented Tarrasch. ---Nunn described the position in this way: "White's advantage in thisqueenless middlegame may be slight, but it's permanent. Black has few activepossibilities, while White can easily play f4 and this, when combined with theaction of his rooks on the f- and g-files, will put Black's kingside underpressure".} Rd8 {As in the most endings, although this is a 'queenlessmiddlegame', the king is fine in the centre.} ({QUESTION: I understand, butwouldn't it also be good here to play} 13... O-O {, to look for counterplaywith ...f5 - ?} {However, before defining his central structure White can play}14. h4 $1 {, answering} ({ANSWER: That was possible, but wouldn't equalize.White shouldn't rush to play} 14. d4 $6 {because, as you say, Black has} f5 $1{, and White can't keep his structure intact; it can be considered neitherweak nor strong.} (14... Z0)) 14... f5 ({or} 14... h5 {with} 15. Rdg1) 15. h5Ne7 {and, say,} 16. Rh3 {, defending f3 to be able to recapture with theknight on e4, when White can continue to improve his position with Kd2, Rg1,etc, before eventually advancing in the centre.}) 14. Ne2 $1 ({There wereseveral attractive moves here, such as} 14. h4 {, but Lasker first makes the'obligatory' move, the most flexible one, which will be useful for advancinghis pawns either with f4 and/or d4. --- Tarrasch praised his move: "Theappropriate strategy for White is to play f4".}) 14... f6 ({After} 14... O-O{White could also continue with} 15. f4 {, and if} ({another option is} 15. h4f5 16. h5 Ne7 17. f4 {, with a preferable position in each case}) 15... exf416. exf4 f5 {he could obtain a passed pawn with} 17. e5 {.}) 15. Rhg1 Kf7 {"Here the king is too exposed against the possible opening of the f-file.Therefore castling would have been preferable", according to Tarrasch.Curiously today's engines disagree; it's true that in the game having the kingon the f-file was decisive in the end, but only due to an error by Tarraschlater.} 16. Rdf1 {Lasker continues to prepare f4; he wants to advance onlywhen he has all his pieces in the best positions.} Rhe8 {Tarrasch: "Blacktakes precautions against the advance of White's centre pawns after theeventual advance of the f- pawn". --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue? ---ANSWER:} 17. Ng3 $1 {Once again Lasker is in no hurry.} ({He postponed hisbreak because after} 17. f4 {Black is well placed to blockade the passed pawnthat could be created after} exf4 18. exf4 f5 19. e5 {with} Nf8 {and ...Ne6,so first Lasker controls f5.}) 17... Nf8 {The knight retreats before beingdislodged with h4-h5. "With the hope that the knight will obtain a dominantposition, but it will be demonstrated that this isn't feasible." (Tarrasch).}18. f4 {Now, finally, after all the preparations, Lasker carries out hisplanned break, with a concrete threat that Tarrasch overlooks.} c5 $2 {Atactical error, which allows White to exploit the 'X-ray' pressure of thef1-rook against the black king. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker now gain adecisive advantage?} ({Playing} 18... exf4 19. exf4 {would be a concession;White would have improved his central structure.}) ({It was better to playeither} 18... Nd7 {, in order to recapture on e5 with the knight;}) ({or else} 18... g6 {, when} 19. fxe5 Rxe5 20. d4 Re6 21. e5 {, threatening Ne4, looksvery good, but after} Nd7 22. Ne4 Kg7 {it isn't clear that the inevitableexchanges will be in White's favour. In both cases it would be better forWhite to advance 19 h4!, increasing the pressure on the black position beforeadvancing the d- and/or f- pawn(s).}) 19. Nh5 $1 {ANSWER!} (19. h4 {waspossible, with advantage, but Lasker's move is crushing. --- "Lasker hasplayed admirably since move 12 and now forces a decisive gain of material",commented Tarrasch.}) 19... g6 {There is nothing better;} (19... Ne6 {isanswered with} 20. f5 Ng5 21. h4 {.}) 20. fxe5 $1 {Tarrasch overlooked this'petite combinaison'.} Rxe5 {Resigning himself to the loss of a vital pawn.} ({Instead,} 20... gxh5 $2 {allows mate with} 21. Rxf6+ Ke7 22. Rg7# {.}) 21. Nxf6Kg7 22. Rf2 h5 {EXERCISE: White's advantage is decisive. The advance of hiscentral pawns can't be prevented. Among several good moves here, Laskerselects the best one - what is it? --- ANSWER:} 23. Nd5 {Before the knightis immobilized with 23...c6. --- Going back, 22...c6 was more tenacious,preventing Nd5; 22...h5 prevented Ng4, but from d5 the knight has greatermobility.} c6 24. Nf4 c4 {This exchange of pawns doesn't change the situation,there is no way to put pressure on the white centre.} 25. Rfg2 Rd6 26. h4 {Lasker continues to prepare the advance of his centre pawns; first he improveseverything as well as he possibly can.} cxd3 27. cxd3 Kf7 {EXERCISE: How didLasker now continue to make progress? --- ANSWER:} 28. Rg5 $1 {The exchange ofrooks removes the obstacle preventing the vital advance of the e4-pawn.} Rxg529. Rxg5 Rf6 30. e5 Rf5 31. Rxf5+ gxf5 32. d4 {White has an ideal position,with an extra pawn and a dominating knight, which is also attacking the pawnon h5.} Ke7 33. Kd2 {One of the ideas is to play 34 Ke2 and 35 Kf3, when hewould be ready to play 36 Nxh5, since after 36...Ng6 the h4-pawn could bedefended with 37 Kg3.} c5 {This break grants White two connected passed pawns,but by now there was no defence.} 34. Kd3 cxd4 35. exd4 Kd8 36. d5 Kd7 37. Kd4Kc7 38. b4 Kd7 39. Kc5 Kc7 40. d6+ Kd7 41. Kd5 {With this game Lasker won thetournament earlier than expected, but he lost in the last round to the youngCharousek. Lasker was impressed with his talent and prophesied a great futurefor him. He forecast that Charousek would be challenging him for the worldtitle within a few years, a prophecy that could not be fulfilled, because ofthe (at that time) fatal illness tuberculosis which 'Comet Charousek' caughtshortly after.} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Second Steinitz-Lasker match"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Immediately after losing the world title to Lasker, in the middle of 1894,Steinitz challenged him to a return match, which Lasker accepted, but he didnot want to play immediately. --- The match, also to the first to win tengames, began in Moscow on the 7th of November 1896 and ended on the 14th ofJanuary 1897. In the two years that had gone by since the first match,Steinitz had not clearly got the better of his rivals, but neither had he donebadly in any of the tournaments in which he competed.} 1. Z0 {Lasker was thefavourite, but the overwhelming superiority he showed was rather unexpected.Lasker won by 10 wins to two, with five draws. --- After six games the matchalready stood at 5-0, so that the final result was already in very littledoubt. --- Why was Lasker so superior? It's true that Steinitz was ill forquite some time, but he responded in sporting fashion, as he had done with hisprevious defeat. In the first place he said concerning his health problems:"During the match, a chess master has no more right to be ill than does ageneral on the field of battle". --- And on the chess front he replied,"Why was I defeated so clearly? Because Lasker is the greatest master I haveever faced, possibly even the greatest who ever existed".} *[Event "19: World Championship, Moscow"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "1"][White "Steinitz, W"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C54"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "90"][EventDate "1896.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 ({The Italian Opening has comeback into fashion recently (2018) and is in the repertoire of the currentworld champion and of almost all the world's best players, but these days theplay is more positional, with} 5. d3 {.}) 5... exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nxe4 8.O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 ({The continuation which subsequently displaced thiscomplicated variation is} 9. d5 {.}) 9... d5 10. Ba3 dxc4 {In his annotationsto the aforementioned game Lasker wrote that the sacrifice had to be accepted,and for several moves the game follows his analysis.} ({This sacrificial line,aimed at preventing the black king from finding shelter in the near future,was a novelty in the game W.Steinitz-C.Schlechter, Hastings 1895, where Blackresponded with} 10... Be6 {, and after} 11. Bb5 Nd6 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Ne5 O-O14. Nxc6 Qf6 {, he had survived the initial surprise and emerged with equalchances.}) 11. Re1 f5 ({Lasker is consistent in following his publishedanalysis, but in the third game of the match (see Game 20), he gained thebetter position in a less complicated manner, and with considerably lessdanger to his king, with} 11... Be6 $1 12. Rxe4 Qd5 {.}) 12. Nd2 Kf7 $1 ({Chigorin had suggested that it was better to play} 12... Be6 13. Nxe4 (13. f3Nxc3 14. Rxe6+ Kf7 15. Qe1 Qxd4+) 13... fxe4 14. Rxe4 Qd7 {Indeed, White hasanother way to create problems for the black king, which is} 15. Qh5+ $1 ({since} 15. Qe2 {is parried with} Kf7 {, when} 16. d5 Bxd5 17. Rd1 {achievesnothing for White after} g6 $1 {, and the black king reaches safety, with ...Rhe8 on the agenda.} (17... Z0)) ({However, 15 Qe2? isn't the best move, andwe can also rule out} 15. d5 $2 O-O-O 16. Rxe6 {.}) 15... g6 {is better, butthen, unlike in Chigorin's line, here White is able to activate all his forceswithout allowing the black pieces to become organized: for example,} ({when} 15... Kd8 $2 {, is bad due to} 16. d5 $1 Bxd5 17. Rd1 {.} (17. Z0)) 16. Qg5 Kf717. Rf4+ Kg7 18. Qf6+ Kg8 19. Re1 {, and now 19...Bf5 is answered with 20 g4,while} Re8 20. Bf8 Qf7 21. Qxf7+ Bxf7 22. Rxe8 Bxe8 23. Bh6 Bf7 24. Re4 {"leads to a curious endgame in which Black actually stands slightly worsedespite being a whole piece up" - Nunn.}) 13. Nxe4 fxe4 14. Rxe4 {EXERCISE:What had Lasker planned (and published) as a way for Black to defend? ---ANSWER:} Qf6 $1 {This defends against the immediate threats, which were 15Qf3+ Kg8 16 Rf4, and 15 Rf4+, and he plans to bring his king into safety after15...Rd8 and...Kg8.} ({If} 14... Bf5 {White can play} 15. Qf3 $1 Qd7 16. Rf4 {;}) ({while, as Lasker pointed out,} 14... Re8 $2 {is clearly bad due to} 15.Qh5+ {and after} g6 16. Qxh7+ {, the black king remains exposed, as shown by}Kf6 17. Rxe8 Qxe8 18. d5 Ne5 19. Bc5 $1 {, and the bishop joins in the attackwith decisive effect after Bd4 and f4.}) 15. Qe2 {White is preparing to tripleon the open file, while also threatening the pawn on c4, but the game is stillfollowing Lasker's analysis.} Bf5 $1 {Best, speeding up his development andignoring pawn on c4.} ({Lasker indicated that} 15... Be6 $2 {fails to} 16. Re1Rhe8 17. d5 {, "and wins". Perhaps this is not decisive, but there can beno doubt that White is better after regaining the piece and seizing theinitiative.}) ({The bishop is better on f5 than d7 after} 15... Bd7 16. Qxc4+Kg6 {.}) 16. Qxc4+ ({Finally Steinitz diverges from Lasker's analysis, whichcontinued: "} 16. Rf4 h5 17. Qxc4+ Kg6 18. d5 Ne5 19. Qxc7 {and althoughBlack is two pawns behind for the piece, and may lose a third, his attack isexcellent", which is undoubtedly true after} Rhe8 {, followed by ...Rac8.--- As we can see, Lasker always had in mind that he should be prepared toreturn part of the extra material, or even all of it, to obtain otheradvantages.}) 16... Kg6 17. Re3 {EXERCISE: Steinitz can't afford to give Blacktime to bring his king easily to safety. How should Black defend now againstthe threat of 18 Rg3+ Kh5 19 Qe2+ - ?} Rae8 $6 {Lasker opts to control e2,preventing Qe2+ in the line quoted above, but it isn't the most precise move.--- ANSWER: It was better to provide the black king with some shelter bymoving his h-pawn, either with 17...h6 or 17...h5.} ({Analysis indicates that} 17... h5 $1 {was best. This wasn't obvious, especially not at the board. Itrequired deep calculation to find a precise series of moves and to concludethat Black would emerge with advantage; the engines indicate that after} 18.Rae1 {Black's best course is to play} Kh7 $1 19. d5 Nb8 $1 20. Qxc7 Nd7 21. Re7Rhc8 22. Qf4 Bg6 23. Qd2 Nb6 $1 24. R1e6 Qf5 {, and although White has managedto activate his pieces to the maximum, Black has also achieved his objectives:his king has found shelter and almost all his pieces are active. Moreover,Black still has an extra piece for only two pawns, and the d- and c- pawnslook vulnerable, although, of course, the position remains complicated.}) 18.Rae1 $2 {A weak reply, inconsistent with White's previous play, but it iseasier to say that than to calculate accurately to reach the conclusion thatthere was something better. --- QUESTION: Agreed, allowing the exchange ofpieces doesn't looks right. Why did Steinitz do this? I don't understandeither why Lasker didn't safeguard his king with 17...h6 or 17...h5, as youmentioned - these are very logical moves. --- ANSWER: This type of positionis so complicated that just following the general rules (which would suggest17...h5, or here 18 Rg3+, as you indicated) isn't enough; precise calculationis required, because a move may look good, but in fact be bad for sometactical reason.} ({Analysis indicates that it was better to play} 18. Rg3+ Kh5{, and now not} 19. Rf3 $2 ({or} 19. Qd5 $2 {, which can both be answered with}Qe6 $1 {, taking advantage of White's weak back rank}) ({but} 19. h3 $1 {, with the threat of 20 Rf3 and 21 g4+}) ({or} 19. Qb5 $1 {, also with theidea of 20 Rf3; in both cases the position would remain complicated, withchances for both sides.})) 18... Rxe3 {This is logical; exchanging a rook andthen sheltering the king gives Black a clear advantage and from the practicalpoint of view is unobjectionable.} ({However, there was an objectively evenbetter move,} 18... Qf7 $1 {; exchanging queens is even better for Black thanexchanging rooks, and this move prepares to play 19...Rxe3, followed by ...Re8.If White declines the queen exchange with} 19. Qb5 $2 {, then} ({while if} 19.d5 {then after} Rxe3 20. Rxe3 h5 21. h3 Rd8 {the situation starts to clarifyand after, for instance,} 22. g4 Rxd5 23. gxf5+ Qxf5 24. Qe2 Re5 {Black isleft with an extra pawn and the better structure}) 19... Rxe3 20. Rxe3 Qxa2 {, and White's back-rank weakness is decisive.}) 19. Rxe3 h5 20. h3 {Black isleft with an extra pawn and the better structure.} ({Here White could havetried to win another pawn with} 20. d5 $2 {, but after} Ne5 21. Qxc7 $2 Ng4 {, followed by ...Re8, or ...Rc8, depending on where the white rook goes, Blackseizes the initiative decisively.}) 20... h4 {A good move, preventing thecheck on g3.} (20... Rd8 {was also good, indicated by Chigorin, when after} 21.d5 {, as well as other good moves, such as} Na5 {,} ({it is possible to play} 21... Qf7 22. g4 Rxd5 23. gxf5+ Qxf5 {, which transposes to the note toBlack's 18th move.})) 21. d5 Ne5 22. Qxc7 {EXERCISE: With 22...Ng4 ruled out,how did Lasker continue? --- ANSWER:} Nd3 $1 {Freeing the queen from thedefence of the knight and threatening to win with 23...Rc8, followed bycapturing on c3.} 23. Qxb7 {White has three pawns for the piece, but for nowthey aren't dangerous.} Bc8 $6 {This retreat reveals an attack on f2 andforces White to exchange queens under favourable conditions for Black, leadingto a position in which 'only two results' are possible.} ({However, in thisposition it would have been stronger to be materialistic and play} 23... Qxc3$1 {, threatening the bishop.} {so} 24. g4 {is almost forced and after} ({Then if} 24. Qxa7 {Black wins with} Qa1+ 25. Kh2 Nxf2 {;} (25... Z0)) 24...hxg3 25. Rxg3+ Kh5 {the threat of 26...Qe1+ prevents White from takingadvantage of the exposed position of the black king;} 26. Qe7 {is answered with} Qd2 $1 {, defending g5 and attacking f2, when, since} 27. Rg2 ({White wouldhave to try} 27. Bc5 {, but there is insufficient compensation for the twopieces after} Nxc5 28. Qxg7 Rh7 29. Qe5 Rf7) 27... g6 {, planning ...Qe1+,would be hopeless. --- Of course, once again, from a practical point of viewit is more dangerous to play like this, with the black monarch on edge of theprecipice.}) 24. Qc6 Qxc6 25. dxc6 Nf4 26. Re7 a6 {With so little materialleft, the value of each pawn increases; on a6 the pawn is well defended fornow.} 27. c4 Kf6 {Thanks to the exchange of queens the black king can now takeup an active role.} 28. Ra7 $6 {Steinitz wants to keep his rook active on theseventh rank. He is threatening 29 Bb2+, but it was better to try to keep theblack king cut off from the centre with 28 Re3, when there would a very goodchance of the game ending in a draw.} Nd3 {Restricting the mobility of White'sbishop.} 29. Be7+ Ke6 30. Rc7 Ne5 $1 {Demonstrating that 30 Rc7 wasn't a gooddecision; the knight attacks the pawns on c6 and c4, and defends against 31Bxh4?, which is answered with 31...Kd6!, winning more material.} 31. Bg5 {EXERCISE: White's rook attacks the g7-pawn while his bishop maintains thepressure on the h4-pawn. How did Lasker respond? --- ANSWER:} Rg8 $1 {Defending the g7-pawn directly, with the idea of 32...Kd6, winning White'smost dangerous pawn.} ({The immediate} 31... Kd6 {was not as strong, due to}32. Rxg7 Kxc6 33. Re7 {, and Black is tied down to the defence of the h4- pawn,with very few winning chances.}) 32. Be7 ({Lasker realizes that} 32. Bxh4 {is nothing to fear, due to} Kd6 33. Ra7 Nxc6 34. Bg3+ Kc5 35. Rc7 Be6 {and thec4-pawn is lost.}) 32... g5 {With the aid of tactics Black has made clearprogress; now he is planning, among other things, 33...Kf5, with ideas of 34...Nxc4 or 34...Be6.} 33. c5 Nf7 {Lasker continues unhurriedly, defending g5 inorder to free his rook.} ({There were other ways too: for instance, Blackcould exploit the fact that d5 is now accessible by playing} 33... Kd5 {, with good chances after} 34. Bxg5 Bxh3 35. f4 Be6 36. Ra7 Bc8 {.}) 34. f3 Re835. Kf2 Rxe7 36. Rxc8 Kd5 37. Ra8 $2 {This looks active, but once againSteinitz falls prey to Lasker's superior tactical skills. --- EXERCISE: Howdid Lasker now take another step forward?} ({Nunn indicated that Black's taskwould have been more complicated after} 37. g3 Kxc5 38. gxh4 gxh4 39. c7 Nd640. Rh8 Rxc7 41. Rxh4 {, since he would only have one pawn left.}) 37... Ne5 $1{ANSWER: Threatening 38...Nd3+, followed by ...Nxc5.} 38. Ke3 $6 {This failsto present Black with any difficulties. Black is able to preserve his a-pawnunder much better conditions, and the rest is simple.} ({Now after} 38. Rxa6Nd3+ 39. Kg1 Nxc5 40. Ra3 Rc7 41. g3 Rxc6 {with his active pieces Black wouldhave good winning chances, despite having only pawn left. Nevertheless, thiswas White's best chance.}) 38... Nxc6+ 39. Kd2 a5 40. Rf8 Re5 41. f4 gxf4 42.Rxf4 Rh5 43. Ke3 Ne5 44. Ra4 Nc4+ 45. Kf4 Kxc5 0-1[Event "20: World Championship, Moscow"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "3"][White "Steinitz, W"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C54"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "78"][EventDate "1896.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bc4 Bc5 4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 Bb4+ 7. Nc3 Nxe4 8.O-O Bxc3 9. bxc3 d5 10. Ba3 dxc4 11. Re1 Be6 $1 ({Instead of the moreambitious, but riskier} 11... f5 {, as Lasker played in the first game, inwhich he was unable to hang on to the extra piece, he now plays thisimprovement, which continues his development and prepares to bring his kinginto safety.}) 12. Rxe4 Qd5 {Preparing queenside castling, remaining with anextra pawn, but without taking any risks. --- QUESTION: This seems obvious.Why didn't Lasker play this in the first game? --- ANSWER: Yes, now it seemsobvious! It wasn't so clear, seeing the position for the first time. Besides,it's more attractive and better to be up a piece rather than a pawn. To arriveat the conclusion that this is the best line is only possible through analysis,which when games of the highest level are involved is rarely simple.} 13. Qe2O-O-O 14. Ne5 Rhe8 {Lasker continues to play simple chess; the idea is 15...Bf5, followed by exchanging on e5 and infiltrating down the d-file.} 15. Nxc6 ({After} 15. Re1 Bf5 16. Re3 Nxe5 17. Rxe5 Rxe5 18. Qxe5 Qxe5 19. Rxe5 Be6 20.f4 g6 {White would have the ungrateful task of trying to hold an inferiorending, a pawn down and with zero counterplay.}) 15... Qxc6 16. Re1 {Black canbe satisfied with the outcome of the opening: he has an extra pawn and noproblems; furthermore, the a3-bishop is now a piece with poor prospects.Black's task now is to try to increase his advantage, taking into account thatthe exchange of all the major pieces could possibly lead to a drawn ending,due to the presence of bishops of opposite colour. On the other hand, tryingto advance the queenside pawn majority is not advisable as long as the majorpieces remain on the board. --- EXERCISE: What did Lasker play here? ---ANSWER:} Rg8 $1 ({There were several good moves, in a general sense, such as} 16... Rd5) ({or giving the king an escape square with} 16... b6 {, but thetext move is more concrete. The rook abandons the e-file, since it no longerfulfils any purpose there and merely restricts the movements of its own bishopon e6; finally, it prepares a timely ...g5.}) 17. Re5 b6 {Naturally it isalways essential to take into account the opponent's ideas or threats, andideally make a move that is preventative and at the same time beneficial; nowRc5 is ruled out, while ...b6 is useful in any case.} ({The immediate} 17... g5$2 {was unwise due to} 18. Be7 {.}) 18. Bc1 {Steinitz tries to improve thepassive position of his bishop and at the same time tries to restrain 18...g5.--- EXERCISE: What do you think Lasker played now? --- ANSWER:} g5 {Asurprising move, untypical of Lasker; objectively it is dubious at least, but... since White fails to respond in the best way, it is transformed into a goodmove. --- Lasker doesn't lose all his advantage with this pawn sacrifice, buthis usual practice was to keep manoeuvring, so as to execute this advance atthe best moment, and that would also have been the objectively better courseof action in this case. White isn't threatening anything dangerous, so Blackhas at his disposal all time he wants.} ({Lasker had various playablealternatives: for instance,} 18... h6 {is a natural suggestion;}) ({while} 18... Kb7 {could be a useful prophylactic move.}) 19. Rxg5 $2 {JustifyingLasker's decision; opening the g-file, and ending up, after exchanges, with ablack rook on g8, is very dangerous, and it wasn't necessary.} ({Even worse was} 19. Bxg5 $2 h6 {.}) ({However, with} 19. Qh5 $1 {White would attack theh7-pawn and threaten 20 Bxg5 (since now 20...h6? can be answered with 21 Qxh6),as well as 20 Rxg5, eventually recapturing on g5 with the queen, thushindering ...Rg8.} {So perhaps Black should play} g4 {, followed by ...Rg6, ...Kb7, ...Bd5, etc, but White could respond with Bf4, eyeing c7, and there wouldstill be a tense struggle ahead} (19... Kb7 {After} {, White could play} 20.Bxg5 {without any great problems.} (20. Z0))) 19... Rxg5 20. Bxg5 Rg8 21. f4 {EXERCISE: White's reply was forced, to defend g2 with the queen. What didLasker play now? --- ANSWER:} Bd5 {Forcing another weakness in White's castledposition, due to the threat of 22...f6 or 22...h6.} 22. g3 Kb7 {A useful move,preventing any tactics based on a check on the back rank.} ({Nunn gave asample line:} 22... Qd7 23. Bh4 {There were other options: for instance,} Kb8 {, with the plan of ...Bb7 when as well as ...Qd5, Black has the extra optionof ...Qc6; the black king could also shelter on a7 after ...a5. In any case,the plans ...Qd7-h3 and ...Bc6 with ...Qd5 are all latent in the position. Wecan see that the bishops of opposite colour work in Black's favour in thisposition.} (23... Qh3 24. Qf1 {and now} Qxh4 $2 {fails to} 25. Re8+ {.} (25. Z0))) 23. h3 {Steinitz has anticipated one of the ideas mentioned above; with 23h3 and Kh2 he rules out the possibility of ...Qd7-h3, and furthermore it isnow simpler for White to defend the h1- and g2-squares. --- EXERCISE: How didLasker continue? --- ANSWER:} Qb5 {Lasker continues with the plan of ...Bc6,followed by ...Qd5.} ({Another idea was possible, taking into account that theexchange of rooks can favour Black if his queen manages to infiltrate; so} 23... Qg6 {was possible, trying to put more pressure on the white king with ...f6 and ...h5:} {As Nunn indicated, after "} 24. Qe5 ({which would be lethalin the event of} 24. g4 f6 25. Bh4 h5 {, for example.} (25... Z0)) ({Alsoafter, for instance,} 24. Kh2 f6 25. Bh4 h5 {White is almost paralyzed, andBlack can continue with ...Qf5, followed by activating the rook via the routed8-d6-e6. It's worth noting that with the bishop banished to h4, the exchangeof rooks would bring the added threat of ...Qd3, since the exchange of queenswould lead to the promotion of Black's pawn.}) 24... Kc6 {(threatening ...Qc2,so White must retreat)} 25. Qe2 h5 26. Qd2 Qf5 27. Kh2 Rg6 {followed by ...Ke6White's position collapses}) ({Not} 23... Rg6 $2 {due to} 24. Qe8 {.}) 24. Kh2Rg6 {Lasker isn't content to play good moves, such as 24...h5 or 24...Bc6, andtries to play ...f6 to displace the white bishop. This is a good plan, butrequires a degree of care.} ({The idea behind} 24... h5 {is a good one, tohinder g3-g4.}) (24... Bc6 {is also good, since} 25. g4 {can be answered with}h5 {, when the pawn is taboo due to ...f6, while after} 26. Qe5 Qb2+ 27. Re2Qb1 {Black has successfully infiltrated and the white position is left veryweak. --- Lasker's chosen plan is good, but it requires precision, since oncethe bishop has been forced back to h4 he will have to bear in mind White'spossible idea of playing g4, followed by f5, when the bishop can bereactivated on g3, attacking the weak point on c7, and finally the bishops ofopposite colour would give White some help.}) 25. Qc2 f6 26. Bh4 Bc6 $2 {Lasker continues with the idea of playing ...Qd5; the idea is a good one, butthe move is bad because in this position there are other priorities. The textmove allows White to regroup and noticeably improve his situation.} ({Heshould have prevented the white bishop from becoming active, which could havebeen achieved with} 26... Rh6 $1 {, and only afterwards ...Bc6.}) 27. g4 $1 Qd528. Qf2 $2 {A surprising lapse.} ({QUESTION: Why not} 28. f5 {- ? --- ANSWER:}{If} Rg8 {instead, then after} ({Then} 28... Rh6 $2 {is bad; White simplyretreats with} 29. Bg3 {and the rook on h6 can't move.} (29. Z0)) 29. Bxf6 Qf330. Be5 {White is over the worst. The pressure that Black exerts is sufficientfor equality, but not for any advantage: for example, if} h5 {White can play}31. Qe2 hxg4 32. hxg4 {, when} Qxc3 $2 {loses to} 33. d5 {.}) 28... h5 $2 {An unusual case of mutual chess blindness. Once again, it was necessary toprevent White's from activating his bishop with f4-f5.} ({Much better than theimmediate 28...f5 is} 28... Rh6 $1 {and after} 29. Bg3 f5 $1 30. g5 Re6 {the bishops of opposite colour once more favour Black, and all the more so inthat the bishop on g3 has no future. In that case Black could then think aboutadvancing on the queenside with ...a5, ...b5, etc.}) 29. g5 $2 {A bad decisionwhich opens up the position of his monarch and also misses his lastopportunity;} ({which consisted of playing} 29. f5 $1 Rg8 30. Kg3 $1 {(theonly move)} hxg4 31. hxg4 {, when the pressure on f6 prevents Black from doingjust as he likes. White also has the possibility of playing Re6 at the rightmoment (another possibility presented by the plan of 24...Rg6 and 25...f6).})29... fxg5 30. Bxg5 {EXERCISE: There are several good moves here; Lasker madethe strongest one - what is it?} ({After} 30. fxg5 Rg7 {Black would continuewith 31...Rf7 and White must wait passively while Black keeps making progressuntil the game is decided. White has to defend g2 and h1, as well as the pawnsat a2 and c3, which can be attacked at an opportune moment with ...Qa5; healso has to try to prevent an invasion by the black rook. It isn't possiblefor White to cope with all Black's possible threats.}) 30... h4 $1 {ANSWER:Now the white king can't go to g3, as the tactical ideas increase and now allBlack needs to do is to bring his rook into play.} 31. Rf1 Rg8 32. Qd2 a5 {Playing like Petrosian would many years later as White is defenceless; thismove isn't necessary, but neither does it spoil anything.} 33. a4 Re8 $1 {With the idea of 34...Re3 and ...Rg3.} 34. f5 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker nowstrike the decisive blow?} ({If} 34. Rg1 {then} Qf3 {wins,}) ({while} 34. Bxh4{loses to} Re3 {followed by ...Qe4 or ...Rxc3.}) 34... Rg8 $1 {ANSWER: Thismove paralyzes the white position; White will soon be in zugzwang. The bishopcan't move due to ...Rg2+, the king can't move either, due to ...Qh1+, thepawn on f5 can't advance because of ...Rxg5, the queen has to defend g2 and g5,and the rook must defend h1 and the f5-pawn. Within a few moves it won't bepossible for White to keep everything protected.} 35. Re1 {The loss of thepawn was inevitable. Now everything speeds up, because there are now morelines opened in Black's favour.} Qxf5 36. Re5 Qf3 37. d5 Qg3+ 38. Kh1 Qxe5 39.dxc6+ Kxc6 {. According to 'La Strategie', the game lasted three hours and 40minutes, of which Lasker consumed only 58 minutes.} 0-1[Event "21: World Championship, Moscow"][Site "?"][Date "1896.??.??"][Round "10"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Steinitz, W"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C68"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "81"][EventDate "1896.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{After the sixth game, with the score 5-0 in Lasker's favour, the match wasadjourned for ten days, as had been agreed. --- When the match resumed,Steinitz proved to be in rather better health, and the next three games allended in a draw. Let's see what happened in the tenth game.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. Nc3 Bg4 {A move that 'dries out' the position;it reduces White's chances of achieving active play, but on the other handBlack concedes the pair of bishops, which was his main compensation for thedamage to his pawn structure.} 6. h3 Bxf3 7. Qxf3 Ne7 8. d3 c5 {Blackradically rules out the possibility of White playing d4, but at the cost ofconverting his bishop into a purely defensive piece.} 9. Qg3 ({Naturally} 9.O-O {was also possible, but Lasker prefers to postpone committing his kinguntil he sees how Black deploys his pieces.}) 9... Ng6 ({Here Fine preferred} 9... Nc6 {, which seems more consistent with 8...c5, but of course in thatcase White would play f4, either right away or when it suited him.}) 10. Be3Bd6 11. O-O-O O-O {EXERCISE: What did Lasker play here?} ({Fine criticizedthis, noting: "} 11... Qd7 {followed by 12...0-0-0 would have been safer".}) 12. h4 {ANSWER: When he castled queenside it was with this idea in mind;Lasker wants to gain ground on the kingside, all the more so now that theblack monarch is on that wing. --- Going back to Fine's suggestion of 11...Qd7followed by queenside castling, White could still continue with 12 h4 andafter 12...h5 there are several possibilities, including 13 f3, with the ideaof breaking with g4 after Qf2 and Rdg1.} Nf4 {The knight jumps before it ispushed, and in fact it's well placed here, since although it can be dislodgedby an eventual g3, it can then move to e6, closer to the fine outpost on d4.}13. Kb1 {A typical consolidating move, not strictly necessary at the moment,but appropriate in the long term; the king is generally slightly safer on b1and here it moves 'out of range' of the knight on f4.} Ne6 {A strange decisionon Steinitz's part; the knight was well placed on f4, and it was unnecessaryto retreat it so soon, since Bxf4 wasn't to be feared, as that would increasethe scope of the d6-bishop. So it was better to make some other useful moveand wait for the knight to be dislodged with g3.} ({Here} 13... b5 {was moreattractive, starting a pawn storm; in that case Black's attack appears to beno slower than White's.}) 14. Qg4 {The queen must retreat to make way foradvancing with g3 and f4; this move also prepares to play a future Ne2, tochallenge the black knight when it comes to d4.} Qe8 ({Instead,} 14... b5 {was still worth considering;}) ({while Nunn points out a neat tactical detail:after} 14... Nd4 15. h5 c6 16. Ne2 Qc8 {it's not bad to exchange the queens,followed by Ng3, but in fact this isn't forced. Instead,} 17. Qh4 $1 {ispossible, since if} Nxe2 $2 {then} 18. h6 {, and Black can't defend his kingsatisfactorily, but otherwise the knight goes to g3, joining in the attack.})15. Ne2 Nd4 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker now continue? --- ANSWER:} 16. Nxd4 $1 {An original decision; Lasker exchanges on d4 at a moment when 16...cxd4? isn'tpossible due to 17 Bh6. By forcing Black to capture with the e-pawn, Whiteacquires a kingside pawn majority, which can soon begin to advance.} ({HereLasker was faithful to his motto 'when you see a good move, look for a betterone', because} 16. Ng3 {was also advantageous. The attack can be parried with}Qc8 {, but after} 17. Nf5 Nxf5 18. exf5 {the white queen would have a goodsquare on e4, and the white pawns would be ready to advance, with the additionof g2-g4.}) 16... exd4 17. Bh6 {The point of this is to draw the black bishopto e5, so that later f2-f4 will come with tempo.} Be5 18. Bc1 {Retreating thebishop, in order to play f4 under better conditions.} ({For instance, asChigorin pointed out,} 18. f4 {can be answered with} Qe6 {, and the endgameafter} 19. Qxe6 fxe6 20. fxe5 gxh6 21. Rdf1 Rxf1+ 22. Rxf1 Rf8 23. Rf3 Rf7 {is nothing Black need fear.}) 18... Qe6 19. Qe2 {Naturally White isn'tinterested in an exchange of queens; he is planning to play 20 f4, followed byg4, when the attack 'plays itself'.} f5 {With this Black ends up cedingterritory, which isn't pleasant, but at least he deprives White of an easyattack.} 20. f4 Bd6 21. e5 Be7 22. h5 {The plan now is to play g4, andconcentrate White's fire against g7. This move prevents Black from solidifyinghis kingside pawn structure and at the right moment the advance h6 will comeinto consideration.} Rad8 23. g4 b5 {Black seeks counterplay on the queenside,which is logical, although subsequently this boomerangs.} ({Tarrasch suggestedthe line} 23... fxg4 24. Rdg1 Rf5 25. Rxg4 Bf8 {, defending g7 first.}) 24.Rdg1 c4 25. Rg2 ({Threatening to double rooks; this is better than} 25. gxf5Rxf5 {, which helps Black, because Black needs to move his rook from f8 anyway,to be able to play ...Bf8 to defend g7, once White doubles his rooks on theg-file.}) ({25 Rg2 is the most 'human' move in the position; the enginesevaluate it similarly to almost any move designed to double the rooks, such as} 25. Rh3 {,}) (25. Rg3 {, etc.}) 25... cxd3 26. cxd3 fxg4 27. Rxg4 Rf5 (27...Rf7 28. Rhg1 Bf8 {was suggested by Chigorin, but it's not really animprovement, because the rook on f7 gives rise to some tactical motifs. Asample continuation is} 29. Rg5 Kh8 30. Qe4 {(with the idea of f5)} Rd5 ({or} 30... Re8 31. Rg6 $1 Qf5 32. Rxa6) 31. Rg6 hxg6 32. hxg6 Kg8 {, and now thestrongest move is} 33. Qh1 $1 {, winning.}) 28. Rhg1 Bf8 29. Rg5 $1 {Thanks tothe rook exchange, the white pawns once more become mobile.} Rxg5 30. Rxg5 {EXERCISE: White's position is better, but he is still far from achieving aclear advantage. How do you think Black should defend now?} Rd5 $6 {Black hastwo ways to hinder f5; he needs to keep White's e5-pawn under attack and hecan do this with either 30...Re8 or the move chosen in the game, 30...Rd5. Atfirst glance it isn't easy to decide which is better. This requirescalculation, naturally, and consideration of how White can prepare to play f5,since once White achieves that, the black position collapses.} ({ANSWER: Therook looks more active on d5, but Lasker will demonstrate that in fact it isworse there, and so} 30... Re8 {was the better choice.}) 31. Qf3 (31. Qe4 {was also good. With 31 Qf3, White threatens 32 f5 Qxe5 33 f6, which enableshim to play Qe4 with a gain of time.}) 31... Rd7 32. Qe4 Rd5 {EXERCISE: Howdid Lasker continue to make progress?} ({In the event of} 32... Qd5 {Whiteplays} 33. e6 $1 Qxe4 34. dxe4 Rd8 35. f5 {, and his mobile pawn mass is muchstronger than Black's (even though Black's could produce two passed pawns!),because White can combine the threat of advancing his pawns with pressureagainst g7: for example,} Re8 36. Bf4 $1 c5 37. Be5 h6 38. Rg1 Kh7 {, and thewhite king can join in the struggle with} 39. Kc2 {. Then, as Nunn points out,"If Black waits then White wins by activating his king; for example,} a5 ({moving the rook anywhere along the first rank loses to 40 e7, while if} 39...Re7 {White can play} 40. Bd6 Re8 41. e5 {, threatening 42 Bxf8 and 43 e7, aswell as invading with the king after 42 Kd3}) 40. b3 a4 41. bxa4 bxa4 42. Kd3Kg8 43. Kc4 Kh7 44. Rg3 Kg8 45. Ra3 Ra8 46. f6 {and Black's positioncollapses".}) 33. Rg2 $1 {ANSWER: This shows why the correct continuationwas 30...Re8 and not 30...Rd5. --- The white rook has achieved all it can onthe g-file and now heads for e2; White needs to overprotect the e5-pawn tofree the f5-pawn to advance. If Black had played 30...Re8 he could havedefended against this plan by playing ...Re7 followed by ...Rf7. White wouldstill be better, but his plan would be less clear.} c6 {Black protects therook, allowing his queen more freedom, but of course any move of the queenrelaxes the blockade and then the advance e6 comes into consideration.} 34. Re2Qg4 {EXERCISE: How to continue now?} ({This attempt at a counterattack willnot be successful, but trying to restrain f5 with} 34... g6 {would have beenequally futile, since lines would open decisively after} 35. Rg2 Kf7 36. hxg6+hxg6 {.} {but White can prepare the breakthrough with} 37. Qe2 $1 {(threatening 38 Rg5 Be7 39 f5) when} ({Now} 37. Rg5 {can be answered with} Be7{;} (37... Z0)) 37... Be7 {, is met with} ({other moves also fail to halt thewhite offensive: for example,} 37... Bg7 38. Rg5 Rd7 39. Qe4 c5 40. f5 gxf5 41.Rxf5+ Ke8 42. Bg5 {, with a winning attack; the black position has too manyaccess points}) 38. f5 $1 Qxe5 39. fxg6+ Kg7 40. Qg4 Qf5 41. Qg3 {and theg6-pawn is of great assistance to White's invading forces.}) 35. e6 $1 {ANSWER: Of course. The threat of e7 prevents any counterplay.} ({There wasanother way, which was to play} 35. h6 $1 {, hammering in a deadly wedge on h6,which would make its presence felt after} gxh6 36. e6 Be7 {. Now} 37. Rc2 $1 {wins the c6-pawn since after} Rd6 {, as well as} 38. Rxc6 {(winning),} ({White has the even stronger move} 38. Qe5 {, with a quick mate.})) 35... Be736. Rc2 Qxh5 37. Rxc6 Rd8 ({According to Schiffers, the counterattack} 37...Rc5 38. Rxa6 Qd1 {would not have worked, because White can exploit the factthat the rook on c5 is loose with} 39. Ra8+ Bf8 40. Rxf8+ $1 Kxf8 41. Qa8+ Ke742. Qa7+ Kxe6 43. Qxc5 {and after} Qxd3+ 44. Ka1 $1 {although there is stillwork to be done, with an extra piece White's win is not in doubt.}) 38. Rxa6 (38. f5 {was also good and after} a5 39. Rc7 {, followed by Qb7 or Qg2, theblack position collapses, but this capture is simpler.}) 38... Qe8 ({After} 38... Qd5 {White could still play} 39. Ra7 {, with a winning endgame.}) 39. Ra7h5 40. f5 h4 41. Qg4 {. The most serious threat now is 42 Bg5. Black isdefenceless.} ({If he tries to counterattack with} 41. Qg4 Rc8 {Instead, Whitecan first play} 42. a3 {, when Black is helpless:} ({then White should refrainfrom playing} 42. Bg5 $2 {due to} Qc6 $1 43. a3 Bxg5 44. Qxg5 Qh1+ 45. Ka2 Qd5+{with a draw.} (45... Z0)) 42... Qc6 {is met with} 43. Rxe7 Qxc1+ 44. Ka2 Qh6 {and now the quickest is} 45. Rf7 {, threatening f6.}) (41. Z0 {Lasker also wonthe eleventh game, but lost the twelfth and thirteenth, at which point thescore was 7-2, and at that point Steinitz's fight-back came to an end. Laskerwon the fourteenth game, after which he only needed a further two games foroverall victory. Of course, he also had games with a dose of the "luck"that Tarrasch talked about, as in the sixteenth game, after which the finalwin needed for overall victory was achieved already in the very next game. ---After retaining his title, Lasker withdrew from active play temporarily fortwo years to resume his studies in Mathematics and Philosophy. Beforecompleting them, he received an invitation to play in a great double-roundtournament in London, in May 1899, where all the greatest chess players in theworld were to take part, except for Tarrasch.}) 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "London 1899"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The London 1899 tournament, played from the 30th of May to the 9th of July1899, was a double round event of 15 players, which went down to 14 whenTeichmann withdrew after playing four games. --- As we have noted, the bestplayers in the world, with the exception of Tarrasch, all took part once,namely Pillsbury, Janowski, the old greats Chigorin and Steinitz, the risingstars Maróczy and Schlechter, etc.} 1. Z0 {Lasker's start was not good. Aftertwo draws he gained his first win, but then he lost in the fourth round to abrilliant attack by Blackburne. In contrast, Janowski got off to a dazzlingstart, scoring seven and a half points from his first eight games. Pillsburyalso began well. --- However, Lasker's defeat against Blackburne was the onlyone he suffered; from then on he moved up the rankings, leading on his ownwith 9/12, and he never relinquished the lead after that. From the fifth roundonwards he gained some seventeen wins and five draws, finishing clear firstwith 22½ points, no less than four and a half points ahead of Janowski,Pillsbury and Maróczy on 18, while Schlechter was fifth with 17 points. ---Teichmann's withdrawal makes the final classification rather confusing, as hewas only counted as having withdrawn after the first cycle. In other words,having played four games (from which he scored two points), he was counted ashaving ten losses by default, and of the top five finishers, he only playedPillsbury, drawing. --- Let's look at a few examples of Lasker's performance (see the following game).} *[Event "22: London"][Site "?"][Date "1899.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Lee, F"][Result "1-0"][ECO "B19"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "77"][EventDate "1899.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Nf3 Nd7 7. h4 h6 8. Bd3({QUESTION: What? Why didn't Lasker play} 8. h5 {, gaining a tempo, and then 9Bd3 - ? --- ANSWER: This variation, which we see so often these days, was onlyin its infancy when this game was played. But I agree, it is noteworthy thatLasker abstains from interpolating} Bh7 {before playing} 9. Bd3 {, which isthe most usual continuation at the present time.}) 8... Bxd3 {I recall that inthe 1980s Bent Larsen, in one of the magnificent articles that he wrote forthe Argentinean newspaper Clarin, wrote that Seirawan agreed with him thatplaying h5 wasn't good for White; the loss of elasticity was more importantthan the tempo gained with h5 to fix Black's kingside, and also the pawn couldbecome weak on h5. --- Who's right here? For now it's impossible to give amathematically correct response; it's just question of taste and fashion.} 9.Qxd3 Ngf6 10. Bd2 e6 11. O-O-O Qc7 12. Rhe1 {QUESTION: This move seems logical;is it still played? --- ANSWER: To be precise, 12 Rhe1 is not played much;developing this rook is not treated as a priority.} ({Much later, severalimportant games were played with this line. Some featured} 12. Ne4 {;}) ({but, among others, Smyslov versus Botvinnik and Spassky against Petrosian, inmatches for the world title, preferred the most popular line} 12. Kb1 O-O-O 13.c4 {, when in most cases Black responds by challenging the white centre with}c5 {.}) 12... O-O-O 13. Qb3 ({One again Lasker refrains from playing} 13. c4 {, which became a very common move in this type of position, controlling d5 andpreparing a later Bc3, if appropriate.}) 13... Bd6 14. Ne2 {This isn't a veryattractive move, but Lasker has emerged from the opening without the slightesthint of advantage. In a way, this move is a backward step.} ({However, Laskerprevents the exchange of bishops with 14...Bf4, and refrains from exchangingknights with} 14. Ne4 Nxe4 15. Rxe4 c5 {, when Black has a free game. White'stactical weakness on f2 gives Black various options for deploying his piecesand a choice of pawn breaks, ...c5 or ...e5.}) 14... Ng4 {A good move;} ({an alternative was to attack f2 with} 14... Ne4 {, which allows} 15. Be3 {, but then Black can return to the idea of ...Ng4 with} Ndf6 {.}) ({Possibly amodern Caro-Kann player would also seriously consider playing} 14... c5 $1 {.})15. Rf1 Ndf6 {EXERCISE: What do you think Lasker played in this position? ---ANSWER:} 16. Qa4 {Creating his first threat of the game, attacking a7, andforcing Black to take a decision: how to defend the pawn? In addition, eventhough it might not be important just now, this move sets up a favourable'X-ray' situation between the white queen and Black's knight on g4.} Kb8 {The king is no worse on b8 than c8, and Lasker has gained no advantage, butwith his next move he sets up some tactical possibilities, based on theposition of Black's king and queen on the same diagonal.} 17. c4 $1 {Now thisadvance converts the position of Black's king and queen into a tacticalweakness with the threat of 18 c5 Be7 19 Bf4, winning;} ({while} 17. c4 e5 $2 {is not playable due to} 18. c5 Be7 19. dxe5 Nxe5 20. Nxe5 Qxe5 21. Bf4 {.})17... Qe7 $6 {Black loses the game through playing far too tentatively.} ({It was better to make room for the bishop with} 17... Qc8 {, followed by ...c5,}) ({but there was no reason to refrain from} 17... c5 $1 {, when} 18. Nc3 {In the tournament book, the annotator mistakenly suggests} Bf4 $2 {. Then after} ({is answered with} 18... a6 {with a good game.} 19. Z0 (19. Z0)) 19. Nb5Bxd2+ {However,} 20. Nxd2 $1 {is better; after} ({the book considers only} 20.Rxd2 $2 {, which after} Qb6 {gives Black a good position; the pressure on f2is unpleasant and restricts White's mobility.} (20... Z0)) 20... Qb6 21. dxc5Qxc5 {, since c4 is now defended by the knight, White can expand with} 22. b4$1 Qb6 23. c5 Qa6 24. Qxa6 {, with advantage.}) 18. Nc3 Qc7 $6 {Veryoptimistic, wagering that the loss of two tempi can't be exploited, given theclosed or semi-closed character of the position.} ({It was still possible toplay} 18... e5) ({or even} 18... c5 {, since after} 19. Nb5 a6 20. Nxd6 Qxd6 {, Black's active play compensates for the loss of the dark-squared bishop.})19. g3 $1 {Preventing exchanges with 19...Bf4 and renewing the threat to winwith 20 c5, followed by Bf4.} Qc8 {The queen makes room for the bishop. ---EXERCISE: What do you think Lasker played now?} ({Now} 19... c5 $2 {fails to}20. Nb5 Qb6 21. Nxd6 Rxd6 22. Bf4 {;}) ({while} 19... e5 $2 {loses to the ideawe've already seen:} 20. c5 Be7 21. dxe5 {.}) 20. b4 $1 {ANSWER: Setting upthe possibility of 21 c5, followed by b5. This still doesn't give White anobjective advantage, but it proves devastating, because it quickly provokesBlack into making an error, on seeing that White has been making progress,while he has been shifting his pieces to and fro.} e5 {Finally Black reacts,not at the best moment, and not in the best way, since he will need tocontinue accurately, but this isn't a bad move.} ({Black could bring all hispieces into play with} 20... Rhe8 $1 {Instead, the preparatory} 21. Kb1 $6 {gives Black time to play} ({when} 21. c5 {can be answered with} Bc7 22. b5 Qd7{, and White hasn't achieved much.} (22... Z0)) 21... e5 $1 {, under goodconditions, and after} (21... b5 $5 {was also playable, since with White'sking on c1, it would be unsound to play} 22. Nxb5 $2 cxb5 23. Qxb5+ Ka8) 22.dxe5 Nxe5 23. Nxe5 Bxe5 24. Be3 b6 {, Black stands well, as the white positionis overexposed.}) 21. dxe5 Nxe5 $2 {This is a definite mistake. --- EXERCISE:How did Lasker exploit the Black's error?} (21... Bxe5 {was necessary, eventhough it wasn't attractive to give up the bishop with} 22. Nxe5 Nxe5 23. Bf4 {, but tactics appear to come to the support of the black position after} Nfg424. f3 g5 25. hxg5 hxg5 26. Bxg5 Rd3 {, and the position is rather unclear.From the practical point of view, though, this is much more dangerous forBlack than the position arising after 20...Rhe8!.}) 22. Be3 $1 {ANSWER:Suddenly there is no good way to defend a7.} Nxc4 $2 {Now the black king can'tbe saved.} ({Also bad were} 22... b6 23. Rxd6) ({and} 22... Nxf3 {, when Whitecan win with} 23. Qxa7+ ({or} 23. Bxa7+ Kc7 24. Bb6+ $1 Kd7 25. Bxd8 {and 26c5.})) ({The only way to avoid serious losses was} 22... a6 {, when after} 23.Rxd6 Nxf3 24. Qd1 $1 Rxd6 ({not} 24... Ne5 $2 25. Bf4 {, creating seriousthreats along the h2-b8 diagonal}) 25. Qxd6+ Qc7 26. Qc5 {Black's position isweak and his dark squares are at White's mercy, but he can fight on after, say,} Re8 {.}) 23. Bxa7+ Kc7 {EXERCISE: There's more than one favourablecontinuation here. What do you think Lasker chose? --- ANSWER:} 24. Rd4 $1 ({The most direct; the other winning moves,} 24. Nd4) ({and} 24. b5 {, were evenstronger, though, as the pressure on the black king is irresistible. Laskeropted for a move with an immediate threat.}) 24... b5 {Unpleasant, but therewas nothing better;} (24... Ne5 {loses to} 25. Nxe5 Bxe5 26. Qa5+ {;}) ({while} 24... Qe6 25. Re1 {is decisive.}) 25. Nxb5+ $1 {Of course; this is the onlyplayable move. Now the black king will be stripped of its defences and at themercy of the white pieces.} cxb5 26. Qxb5 Na3 {EXERCISE: What's the winningline now? --- ANSWER:} 27. Qa5+ $1 {Once again the only move. Even though theblack king is able to retreat with check, it gains no respite.} Kb7+ 28. Bc5 $1Bxc5 29. bxc5 {Threatening not only 30 Qb6+ followed by 31 Ra4+, but also 30Rb4+, etc, with a quick mate, not to mention that the a3-knight remains enprise.} Rxd4 {The rook has to be eliminated.} ({If} 29... Qa8 {the quickestway is} 30. c6+ $1 {: for example,} Kxc6 31. Ne5+ Kb7 32. Rb4+ {, etc.}) 30.Nxd4 Qd8 (30... Qa8 {loses to} 31. c6+ Kb8 32. Qb6+ Kc8 33. Nf5 {.}) 31. c6+Kc8 32. Qa8+ {White is now able to capture the a3-knight with check, emergingtwo pawns up with a winning attack.} Kc7 33. Qa7+ $1 Kd6 34. Qxa3+ {The whiteattack is very easy to conduct and, furthermore, White has a materialadvantage.} Kd5 35. Rd1 $1 {Lasker plays the strongest move, and Black couldeasily have spared himself the rest.} Qb6 36. Nf3+ Ke6 37. Qd6+ Kf5 38. Qd3+Kg4 39. Ne5+ ({It's mate after} 39. Ne5+ Kh5 ({or} 39... Kh3 40. Rh1+) 40. Qf3+{.}) 1-0[Event "23: London"][Site "?"][Date "1899.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Steinitz, W"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C29"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "60"][EventDate "1899.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. f4 d5 4. d3 {Steinitz employed this move several times,but everything indicates that it gives White no chances of advantage.} ({The usual move is} 4. fxe5 {.}) 4... Nc6 ({Steinitz faced} 4... d4 {severaltimes, with scant success after} 5. Nce2 Nc6 6. Nf3 Bd6 {. The black positionis sound and White has to solve the problem of how to deploy his pieces, whichare in each others' way. Now it seems best to play} 7. fxe5 ({althoughSteinitz preferred to play} 7. c3) 7... Bxe5 {, with an approximately equalgame.}) ({He had much more success against} 4... dxe4 5. fxe5 Ng4 6. Nxe4 Nxe5{, when with} 7. d4 Ng6 8. Nf3 {White's central domination gives him theadvantage.}) ({Lasker himself played something stronger against Spielmann inSt. Petersburg 1909 with} 4... exf4 $1 {Lasker's game against Spielmanncontinued} 5. Bxf4 ({when} 5. e5 $6 {, with the idea of 6 Bxf4, can beanswered with} d4 $1 {, as Lasker indicated in the tournament book, withadvantage to Black, as was confirmed, for example, in W.Lombardy-V.Smyslov,Teesside 1975, which continued} 6. Nce2 Nd5 7. Nxf4 Bb4+ 8. Kf2 Nc6 9. Nf3 O-O10. Be2 Ne3 $1 {, with a very strong initiative.} (10... Z0)) 5... Bb4 $1 6.exd5 Nxd5 7. Bd2 Bxc3 8. bxc3 O-O 9. Nf3 Re8+ 10. Be2 Qe7 {, when the whiteking's difficulties give Black the advantage and now after} 11. c4 Nf6 12. Bg5{, instead of} Nc6 ({it was stronger to play} 12... Nbd7 $1) 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14.O-O {, which allowed White to solve his problems.}) 5. fxe5 Nxe5 6. d4 Ng6 7.exd5 {This simplification poses no problems to Black, who can develop hispieces without any difficulties.} ({It was more ambitious to play} 7. e5 Ne4 8.Nxe4 dxe4 9. Bc4 {, followed by Ne2 and 0-0, and on completing his developmentWhite will be in good shape, due to his central control.}) 7... Nxd5 8. Nxd5 ({Reinfeld and Fine criticized this move, which facilitates Black's development,and suggested} 8. Bc4 Nxc3 ({Black isn't forced to play an ending, though.Instead, he could play} 8... Bb4 $1 {, and after} 9. Nge2 Be6 {White'sproblems continue; Black threatens 10...Nxc3 and the check on h4 remains inthe air}) 9. bxc3 Qh4+ 10. g3 Qe7+ 11. Qe2 Qxe2+ 12. Nxe2 Bf5 13. Bb3 {"withonly a minimal disadvantage for White".}) 8... Qxd5 {Nunn commented:"Steinitz liked this line because White ends up with an extra centralpawn", but he also noted that the Black's advantage in developmentcompensated for that static advantage. "These days, players put much moreemphasis on dynamic factors such as piece activity and development,recognizing that static advantages often mean little if there is not time toexploit them", he concluded.} 9. Nf3 ({The move order} 9. Be2 {, and onlythen 10 Nf3, was interesting;} {or} Be7 {, with only a minimal advantage.} (9... Qxg2 $4 {, fails to} 10. Bf3 {, so Black would be forced to playdifferently from the game;} (10. Z0)) ({perhaps with} 9... Bd6)) 9... Bg4 10.Be2 {After this logical move Black develops smoothly and the his dynamicadvantage continues to increase.} ({Nunn suggested entering an endgame with} 10. h3 {, even at the cost of weakening the pawn structure, and he consideredthat White's two bishops would provide compensation after} Bxf3 11. Qxf3 Qxf312. gxf3 {.}) 10... O-O-O 11. c3 {Steinitz continues to rely on his centralsuperiority as he bolsters his centre. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue?}({He has not ruled out fighting for the initiative, but, as with 10 h3, it wasperhaps more precise not to reject the equality offered by} 11. O-O {. Blackcould continue with} Bxf3 {and after} 12. Bxf3 ({Schlechter preferred} 12. Rxf3{and Rxf7 after the exchange of queens}) 12... Qxd4+ 13. Qxd4 Rxd4 14. Be3 Rd815. Bg4+ {and Rxf7 the position is equal. Possibly Lasker wouldn't have optedfor this and instead would have maintained the tension, as with 11...Kb8 or 11...f6.}) 11... Bd6 $1 {ANSWER!} ({With another developing move, a novelty atthe time and an improvement on W.Steinitz-D.Thompson, Philadelphia 1883, whichcontinued} 11... Bxf3 12. Bxf3 Re8+ 13. Kf2 {. Steinitz had no great problemsin leaving his king in the centre; in this case his central superioritysheltered it from any danger.}) 12. O-O ({The advance c4 is something that hadto be considered, but not right away, since after} 12. c4 $2 Qh5 {the whiteking has problems.}) 12... Rhe8 $1 {A simple move, bringing his last pieceinto play, after which "Lasker has obtained a beautiful position whileSteinitz has not yet had an opportunity of completing his development" (Fineand Reinfeld).} 13. h3 (13. c4 $2 Qh5 {was still inadequate; then after} 14. h3{Black's concentration of pieces on the kingside gives him a choice betweenseveral moves, such as} Bxh3 {,} (14... Nh4 $1) ({and} 14... f5 $1 {.})) 13...Bd7 14. Ng5 $2 {This is Steinitz's first serious mistake, based on a tacticaloversight, and it is already decisive. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker refuteWhite's erroneous 14th move?} ({Possibly he should have played} 14. Bd3 {, although after} f6 $1 {, controlling e5 and g5, and with the idea ofreplying to} 15. Qb3 {with} Qh5 {, Black is slightly better.}) 14... Nh4 $1 {ANSWER: "Sometimes the simple moves are the best" (Nunn).} ({Steinitz hadexpected} 14... f6 $6 {, which he planned to answer with} 15. Bf3 {, followedby 16 Ne4, substantially repairing his position.}) 15. Nf3 {A sad retreat;} ({but after} 15. Bf3 {Black's lead in development would make itself felt after}Nxf3+ 16. Nxf3 ({no better was} 16. Qxf3 Qxf3 17. Nxf3 Bb5 $1 18. Re1 Rxe1+ 19.Nxe1 Re8 {, followed by 20...Re2}) 16... Bb5 17. Re1 Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Re8 {, followed by 19...Be2 or 19...Re2.}) 15... Nxg2 $3 {Crushing;} ({and muchstronger even than the positional continuation} 15... Qe6 16. Nxh4 ({not} 16.Bd3 Nxg2 $1) 16... Qxe2 17. Qxe2 Rxe2 18. Nf5 Bxf5 19. Rxf5 f6 {, withadvantage to Black, since White is still unable to complete his development:for example,} 20. Rf2 {can be answered with} Re1+ 21. Rf1 Bh2+ 22. Kf2 Bg3+ 23.Kg1 Rde8 {.}) 16. Kxg2 Bxh3+ $1 ({EXERCISE: This beautiful continuation,destroying the white king's defences, brought about a quick victory. It's good,but there was an even better line - can you find it? --- ANSWER: It was evenstronger to play} 16... Re6 $1 {, when the participation of the rook isdecisive after, for example,} 17. Bd3 Rf6 {(with the ideas of 18...Qh5 or 18...Re8, among others)} 18. Bg5 ({or} 18. Rf2 Qh5 {followed by capturing on h3 and/or ...Bc6, winning}) 18... Rxf3 19. Rxf3 Qxg5+ 20. Kf2 {and now both} Bc6 ({and} 20... Re8 {give Black a decisive attack.})) 17. Kf2 {The bishop is immunefrom capture.} ({After} 17. Kxh3 $2 Qh5+ 18. Kg2 Qg4+ 19. Kh1 (19. Kf2 $2 Qg3#)19... Qh3+ 20. Kg1 Qg3+ 21. Kh1 Re4 $1 {(the only winning move, with the ideaof 22...Rh4+)} 22. Bg5 Rg4 {, there is no defence against 23...Qh3+, winning.})17... f6 $1 ({Black's light-squared bishop is a very strong piece; after} 17...Bxf1 18. Qxf1 {Black has some advantage, but not much. It would beuncharacteristic of Lasker to relax the pressure to gain a small advantagewhen could aspire to much more. --- With the text move Lasker prepares tobring his pawns into the attack by playing ...g5. The position is verydifferent, but for some reason, declining the exchange reminds me of a classicgame R.Byrne-R.Fischer, New York 1963 (See the following game).}) 18. Rg1 $2 {A very passive defence, doing nothing to oppose the advance ...g5.} ({The onlymove to offer some resistance was} 18. Rh1 $5 {, and then} Qf5 $1 19. Bd3 $1 {. --- EXERCISE: How would you now continue the attack as Black? --- ANSWER:Black needs to continue energetically, without wasting any time, so} Bg3+ $1 {is indicated. Now taking the bishop allows mate, so} 20. Kg1 {is forced andafter} Qg4 {the threat of mate in two moves by retreating the g3-bishop forces}21. Rxh3 {, when after} Bd6+ 22. Kf2 Qxh3 23. Qg1 g5 {Black has a clearadvantage and objectively his winning chances are great, although there isnothing immediately decisive.}) 18... g5 19. Bxg5 {Returning the piece andopening more lines against his own king, while he still has a rook inactive ona1, isn't a solution, but by now there was nothing better in the face ofBlack's various threats, both immediate, such as 19...g4, and more gradualones, such as 19...h5, 19...Qe6, or 19...Qe4, with the idea of 20...g3+.} fxg520. Rxg5 Qe6 {Threatening 21...Qe3+ 22 Ke1 Qxf3.} 21. Qd3 Bf4 22. Rh1 ({If} 22.Ra5 {there are several strong responses, such as} Bg4 {(with the idea of ...Qh6); for instance,} 23. Rh1 ({or} 23. Rxa7 Kb8 24. Ra5 Qh6 {, with a decisiveinvasion}) 23... Be3+ 24. Kf1 Bxf3 25. Bxf3 Rf8 26. Kg2 Qg8+ {, winning;}) ({and} 22. Rh5 {is worse, in view of} Qg4 {.}) 22... Bxg5 23. Nxg5 Qf6+ 24. Bf3Bf5 {The exchange down, with a very weak king and the g5-knight in jeopardy,Steinitz could well resign here, but he staggers on for a few more moves.} 25.Nxh7 Qg6 26. Qb5 c6 27. Qa5 Re7 28. Rh5 Bg4 29. Rg5 Qc2+ 30. Kg3 Bxf3 {. Thisgame gained the First Brilliancy Prize.} 0-1[Event "US Championship, New York"][Site "?"][Date "1963.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Byrne, R"][Black "Fischer, RJ"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r2qr1k1/p4pbp/bp4p1/3p4/8/BPN1n1P1/P2QN1BP/R2R2K1 b - - 0 18"][PlyCount "1"][EventDate "1963.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]18... Z0 ({After the expected} 18... Nxd1 19. Rxd1 {, White has no problems;})({but Fischer played} 18... Nxg2 $1 {. "Removing this bishop leaves Whitedefenceless on his light squares" (Fischer), and the game ended} 19. Kxg2 d4$1 20. Nxd4 Bb7+ 21. Kf1 Qd7 $1 {0-1; Fischer had envisaged} 22. Qf2 Qh3+ 23.Kg1 Re1+ $3 24. Rxe1 Bxd4 {and mate.}) *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Paris 1900"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The Paris 1900 tournament was another monumental demonstration of Lasker'sstrength. It took place from the 17th of May to the 20th of June 1900. Oncemore the strongest masters on the planet were assembled, albeit once againwithout Tarrasch. --- Lasker gained first place with 14½/16, followed byPillsbury on 12½; Maróczy and Marshall finished tied for third with 12;fifth was Burn with 11, and further behind trailed Chigorin, Schlechter, Marco,Mieses, Janowski, etc.} 1. Z0 {It was the first tournament in which drawngames were replayed. Lasker had to do so only twice: against Marco, in theeighth round, whom he defeated, and in the final round, with the tournamentalready won, against Chigorin, when the game was drawn again. --- Lasker beganwith five wins, but lost in the sixth round to Marshall. Janowski began with 7/8, and he was the only serious opponent for Lasker until that round. However,while Lasker went on to win all his games, Janowski collapsed. --- Let's lookat one example of Lasker's play in Paris (see the following game).} *[Event "24: Paris"][Site "?"][Date "1900.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Pillsbury, H"][Result "1-0"][ECO "A83"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "169"][EventDate "1900.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 f5 2. e4 {Lasker played the Staunton Gambit in the last two officialgames in which he faced the Dutch Defence;} ({previously he had played} 2. c4)({and} 2. g3 {. In any case, few of Lasker's opponents played this defenceagainst him and he employed it only once himself, albeit in an important gamein his match for the world title against Marshall in 1907.}) 2... fxe4 3. Nc3Nf6 ({On the other occasion when Lasker played the Staunton Gambit, not longbefore this game, against Bird in London 1899, Black responded weakly with} 3... e6 4. Nxe4 Nf6 5. Nxf6+ gxf6 $2 {, allowing} ({instead of} 5... Qxf6) 6.Qh5+ {, and after} Ke7 7. Bd3 Qe8 8. Qh4 {, although Black's king didn't comeunder direct attack, his forces remained uncoordinated and White won in 38moves.}) 4. Bg5 c6 5. f3 exf3 {Accepting the sacrifice naturally comes at acost; White's development is speeded up and Black will need to employ all hisingenuity to find a safe haven for his king.} ({Instead,} 5... d5 {is a lessdemanding continuation;}) ({while on the one occasion when Lasker defendedthis position with Black, he played} 5... Qa5 {and the game F.Marshall-Em.Lasker, World Championship (Game 11), Chicago 1907, continued} 6. Bxf6 (6. Qd2{is the other critical continuation}) 6... exf6 7. fxe4 Bb4 (7... Ba3 {is thetop choice of the engines, and seems to equalize more easily}) 8. Qf3 d5 9.Nge2 O-O 10. exd5 Qxd5 11. Qxd5+ cxd5 12. O-O-O Rd8 {, and Black reached areasonable position.}) 6. Nxf3 e6 7. Bd3 Be7 {EXERCISE: After accepting thepawn Black has slipped behind in development and now there are severalpossibilities for White - what do you think Lasker chose? --- ANSWER:} 8. Ne5$1 ({The main alternative was the natural} 8. O-O {, to which Black would reply} d6 {, preventing this knight jump, followed by ...Na6, with the idea of ...Nb4 or ...Nc7, heading for d5. However, castling can wait. White can andshould try to exploit his greater dynamism. Lasker's move is more energeticand sets up several threats, the most pressing one being 9 Bxf6 followed byQh5+ with a attack decisive.}) 8... O-O ({It's not possible to drive back theknight with} 8... d6 {, in view of} 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Qh5+ g6 11. Bxg6+ Ke7 {, when the strongest continuation is} 12. Bxh7 $1 {, and after} dxe5 13. dxe5Bxe5 14. Qxe5 {White emerges with an extra pawn and the better position, sinceif} Rxh7 {then} 15. Qg5+ Ke8 16. Qg8+ {wins.}) 9. Bxf6 Rxf6 ({Instead,} 9...Bxf6 $2 {loses easily to} 10. Qh5 g6 ({or} 10... h6 11. Qg6 {, with a decisiveattack}) 11. Nxg6 {.}) ({Even worse is} 9... gxf6 $2 {owing to} 10. Qg4+ Kh811. Ng6+ $1 hxg6 12. Bxg6 f5 13. Qh5+ Kg7 14. Qh7+ Kf6 {, and mate in threemoves with} 15. Ne4+ fxe4 16. O-O+ Kg5 17. Qh5# {.}) 10. Qh5 g6 (10... h6 {is hardly an improvement, since White has several advantageous continuations,such as} 11. Ne4 (11. Ng4) ({or} 11. g4) ({but the most crushing is toeliminate the black rook, which is preventing Qg6, with} 11. Rf1 $1 {, and theinvasion on g6 is cannot be averted: for instance,} Qf8 12. Rxf6 Qxf6 13. Qe8+{and after the forced move,} Qf8 {, White can play} 14. Qg6 {.})) 11. Nxg6 $1Qe8 ({White regains the pawn, since if} 11... hxg6 {then} 12. Bxg6 {,threatening mate in two moves;} Rxg6 {is no better; White continues with} ({and after} 12... Bb4 {, vacating e7 for the king, White can play} 13. Qh7+ Kf8{, when once again the strongest continuation is to exchange the defendingrook with} 14. Rf1 $1 {, with the threat of Qh8+.} (14. Z0)) 13. Qxg6+ Kh8 14.Qh6+ Kg8 15. O-O {and the black monarch is defenceless against theintroduction of the white rook via f7 (after Qg6+), or f3.}) 12. Nxe7+ Qxe7 {White has now the pleasant, but difficult task of choosing between severalvery promising continuations of similar strength.} 13. O-O-O ({Thealternatives were the wild} 13. g4) ({and the more positional} 13. Ne4 {, transferring the knight to the kingside before Black plays ...d5.}) 13... d5{EXERCISE: Once again there are several attractive moves; what would youchoose? --- ANSWER:} 14. Rde1 {Lasker plans to bring his rook to the kingsidewith Re3, at the same time putting pressure on the weakness at e6.} ({This isgood, but perhaps even stronger is the continuation suggested by Reinfeld andFine:} 14. Rhf1 {, because exchanging the black rook is still a good decision,as White can include his other rook in the struggle, which is something Blackis unable to do. After, say,} Nd7 15. Rf3 {White threatens to play 16 Rdf1,but exchanging on f3 opens the g-file, and interpolating} Qf7 16. Qh4 {bringsno relief. There is no apparent way for Black to defend against White's attack;the threats include 17 Rdf1 as well as 17 Rxf6, followed by 18 Rf1, etc.}) ({Another good idea, already mentioned, is} 14. g4 {, with the idea of openingmore lines against Black's king.}) 14... Nd7 15. Re3 {Lasker presses on withhis plan.} ({The alternatives} 15. g4) ({and} 15. Rhf1 {were still very strong,which provides proof of the scale of White's advantage; he can afford to losea tempo, yet still maintain a very advantageous position.}) 15... Rf7 16. Rg3+Kh8 17. Bg6 {EXERCISE: After this move Lasker still has the advantage, but itisn't the most energetic. Your task here is nothing less than to improve onthe play of the world champion! Can you find a better move?} ({ANSWER: Onegood possibility was} 17. Re1 {, leaving Black virtually paralyzed. Perhapshis best course then would be to sacrifice a pawn with} e5 {, in order todevelop his pieces, but, of course, this isn't very encouraging.} ({It wouldbe worse to play} 17... Nf6 {allowing} 18. Qe5 {: for example,} Bd7 19. Rf1Raf8 {and now, amongst other things,} 20. Ne2 $1 {is strong, followed by Nf4,with Rgf3 in reserve.})) ({Possibly even better was our by now familiar recipeof exchanging the defending rook with} 17. Rf1 $1 {, and the remoteness orcomplete absence of the a8-rook and c8-bishop from the struggle would soon befelt.}) 17... Rg7 18. Rf1 Nf6 19. Qh4 ({The exchange of queens relieves theblack king of his greatest problems, but White can't avoid it now:} 19. Qe5 {would be met with} Nd7) ({and} 19. Qh6 {with} Ng8 {.}) 19... Ng8 20. Qxe7 Rxe721. Bd3 Bd7 {EXERCISE: What do you think Lasker played in this position?} 22.Nb1 {A very surprising decision; Lasker allows Black to free his position with...e5, in exchange for activating his only prospectless piece, via a scarcelyobvious route. This move was much praised, but objectively it might not havebeen the best.} ({ANSWER: It was possible to keep the backward e6-pawn inplace with} 22. Rg5 $1 {, since} Rg7 $2 ({while after} 22... Rae8 23. Re5 {Black remains bottled up; and after that White could focus on including thec3-knight in the struggle}) {, isn't possible due to} 23. Rxg7 Kxg7 24. Bxh7 {.}) 22... Rae8 23. Nd2 {The threat of 24 Nf3 forces Black's next move, whichbrings his bishop to life, but also gives the white knight the possibility ofbecoming active with gain of time.} e5 24. dxe5 Rxe5 25. Nf3 Re3 $6 {Thisloses a pawn in a few moves.} ({The alternative was} 25... R5e7 {, when after}26. Ng5 Re1+ 27. Rxe1 Rxe1+ 28. Kd2 Re7 29. Rf3 {White still has a slightinitiative, but nothing too worrying for Black.}) 26. Ng5 Rxg3 27. hxg3 h6 ({The defensive try} 27... Re7 $2 {allows} 28. Nxh7 $1 {and the knight is immunefrom capture, since after exchanges on h7, 30 Rf7+ would follow.}) 28. Nf7+ Kg729. Nd6 Re7 30. Nxb7 Nf6 31. Nc5 {Lasker has won a pawn, not a very valuableone, but "better a pawn up than a pawn down", as Najdorf's wise old auntused to say, according to her nephew Don Miguel.} Bg4 {EXERCISE: With 31...Bg4Pillsbury was planning to play 32...Nh5 or 32...Re3. How do you think Laskerresponded?} (31... Nh5 {was premature due to} 32. Nxd7 Rxd7 33. g4 Nf6 34. Bf5{, when} Rf7 {is answered with} 35. Rf3 $1 {(preventing ...Nxg4), and Whitekeeps his advantage (Reinfeld and Fine).}) 32. Rf4 $1 {ANSWER: The rookbecomes active along the fourth rank, preventing both Black's ideas for themoment; 32...Re3 would be answered with 33 Ra4.} Bc8 33. Ra4 Ng4 34. Ba6 $6 {In the next phase of play Lasker loses his small advantage.} ({Instead,} 34.Kd2 {was interesting, not fearing} Ne3 {, which could be answered with} 35. Nb3$1 Nxg2 36. Nd4 {, when Black would be unable to keep all his queenside pawnssafe and at the same time maintain an escape route for his knight.}) 34... Bf5({In general it is better for Black to keep his bishop, so as not tofacilitate the attack on his two weaknesses at a7 and c6, and, concretely,} 34... Bxa6 $2 {would lose a piece here after} 35. Rxg4+ {.}) 35. Rf4 $6 {The rook returns to the centre.} ({Another possibility was} 35. Kd2 {, aspreviously mentioned, intending to answer} Ne3 {with} 36. Bd3 {: for example,}Bxd3 37. Nxd3 Nxg2 38. Nb4 {and White regains his extra pawn.}) 35... Ne3 36.c3 Kg6 37. Rf2 Be4 ({Here} 37... Nc4 $1 {was very interesting, since after} 38.Bxc4 dxc4 {Black's pawn structure is 'ugly' but the white knight is left badlyplaced and Black's bishop is now active.}) 38. b3 {Returning the pawn, butruling out ...Nc4, and giving the king an escape route via b2.} ({It wouldhave been difficult to opt for} 38. Nxe4 dxe4 {, granting Black adangerous-looking passed pawn, but it is possible that White could have keptit under control with} 39. Kd2 $1 {, after which Black can't just cheerfullyadvance it with} Nf5 40. Rf4 e3+ {, since after} 41. Ke1 Kg5 42. Rf3 {, withBd3 to follow, White would be left with a clear advantage.}) 38... Bxg2 39.Bd3+ Kg5 $2 {EXERCISE: White's advantage has evaporated, but still Laskermanaged to keep his practical chances alive. How did he do it?} ({HerePillsbury missed his best defence,} 39... Be4 $1 {, after which it is notapparent how White can gain any advantage. After, for instance,} 40. Bxe4+ dxe441. Rf4 Nd5 42. Rxe4 Rxe4 43. Nxe4 Kf5 {, Black activates his king, regainsthe pawn and equalizes the game.}) 40. Rf8 $1 {ANSWER: By activating his rook,in order to harass the black king and to be able to attack Black's weak pawns.}Kg4 41. Rg8+ $6 ({The immediate} 41. Rf6 {offered more practical chances;after Lasker's move Black can equalize.}) 41... Kf3 42. Rg6 Ng4 43. Bf5 h5 44.Rg5 Re1+ {The start of a bad plan. Black activates his rook, but with amistaken idea.} ({In itself the move isn't bad, but it was better to prefaceit with} 44... Nf6 $1 {, defending the h5-pawn, and only after that try toinfiltrate with the rook, with ...Ne4 also on the agenda.}) 45. Kb2 Rh1 {This was the idea;} ({but since the h5-pawn will soon be lost anyway, asimpler way to equalize was} 45... Kxg3 {. However, it is quite possible thatfor the last few moves Pillsbury has been playing for a win.}) 46. Bg6 Kxg3 $6{Now this leads to a worse endgame.} ({It was preferable to seekcounter-chances through piece activity with} 46... Ke3 47. Bf5 Nf2 {, with theidea of ...Ne4.}) 47. Bxh5 Bf3 48. Bxg4 Bxg4 49. Rg6 Rh2+ 50. Ka3 Rc2 {EXERCISE: The material is equal once more, but with his next move Laskermanaged to regain the advantage. How did he do it? --- ANSWER:} 51. Nd3 $1 {Winning a vital pawn.} ({In contrast,} 51. Rxc6 $2 {would have allowed} Rxc3 $1{, since after} 52. Ne4+ dxe4 53. Rxc3+ Kf2 {, the passed pawn will be enoughto save Black.}) 51... Kh4 ({Here} 51... Rxc3 {is impossible due to} 52. Ne5Kf4 53. Nxg4 Rg3 54. Ne5 $1 {and White wins.}) 52. Ne5 Bf5 53. Rxc6 {Finallythe scales are tipped clearly in Lasker's favour. The ending should be won forWhite, but there are still technical problems to overcome. First White needsto shake off the pressure exerted by the black rook.} Kg3 54. Rc5 $1 {Laskeris able to achieve this quickly; now defending the pawn with 54...Be4 (to keepthe rook active) is answered with 55 Nc6!, followed by Nd4.} Rd2 55. Nc6 Kf456. Nb4 d4 57. cxd4 Rxd4 58. Ra5 Rd7 59. Nc6 ({In fact} 59. Nd5+ $1 {wasquicker, and in view of the possibility of 60 Nf6, Black is forced to play} Kg5{, which allows White to simplify to a trivial pawn ending with} 60. Ne3 Rf761. Nxf5 Rxf5 62. Rxf5+ Kxf5 63. Kb4 {. Nevertheless, Lasker's move also winswithout trouble.}) 59... Be4 60. Nxa7 Rd1 61. Nb5 Rd5 62. Kb4 Bd3 63. Nc7 Rxa564. Kxa5 Ke5 65. Kb4 Kd6 66. Nb5+ Kc6 67. a4 Kb6 68. Na3 Be2 69. Nc4+ Ka6 70.Kc3 Bd1 71. Nb2 Bh5 72. b4 Be8 73. Kb3 Bc6 74. Kc4 Bd7 75. Kc5 Bg4 76. Nc4 Bd177. b5+ Ka7 78. a5 Bf3 79. Ne5 Bb7 80. Nc6+ Ka8 81. Kb6 Ba6 82. Nb4 Bb7 83. Na6Bf3 84. Nc7+ Kb8 85. a6 {After his two magnificent victories in London 1899and Paris 1900, Lasker once more stopped playing serious chess, this time fora longer period, some four years, not competing again until the CambridgeSprings tournament of 1904.} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "3: Selected Games: 1901-1910"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "29"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{During Lasker's four years' abstention from playing competitive chess hedevoted himself mainly to the study of mathematics. In January 1902 Laskerreceived "with great distinction" his degree as Doctor of Mathematics andPhilosophy, from Erlangen University on the theme 'On Series at ConvergenceBoundaries' ("Über Reihen auf der Convergrenze"). --- In 1905 Laskerwrote 'On the theory of modules and ideals', and also published works ofphilosophy. As regards chess, he gave lectures on chess topics and gavesimultaneous displays. He did play a six-game exhibition match in Brighton in1903, against Mikhail Chigorin. The match was played with an obligatoryopening, the Rice Gambit, invented by the philanthropist and professor IsaacRice (1850-1915), who sponsored the contest. --- Chigorin won 3½-2½ (+2,-1, =3). --- The more-than-dubious gambit in question arises after} 1. e4 e5 2.f4 exf4 3. Nf3 g5 4. h4 g4 5. Ne5 Nf6 6. Bc4 d5 7. exd5 Bd6 {, when the RiceGambit is constituted by the piece sacrifice} 8. O-O $6 ({instead of the usual} 8. d4 {.}) 8... Bxe5 {The following moves, up to White's 15th, are more orless forced.} 9. Re1 Qe7 10. c3 f3 11. d4 Ne4 12. Rxe4 Bh2+ 13. Kxh2 Qxe4 14.g3 O-O 15. Bf4 {. In this position Black is the exchange up and has a clearadvantage, so that the result (2½/6) achieved by Lasker, who had to playall six games with White, is actually very praiseworthy.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Cambridge Springs 1904"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{In the early spring of 1904 Lasker returned to competitive play, in thestrongest tournament played in the USA until that moment, in Cambridge Springs.The event ran from the 25th of April to the 19th of May. --- The grouprepresenting Europe was made up of Lasker, Janowski, Chigorin, Schlechter,Maróczy, Mieses and Teichmann, while the USA's contingent was headed byPillsbury, Marshall and Showalter. The natural favourite was Lasker, but hislack of serious match practice made itself felt. He finished in second place, (+ 9, =4, -2), equal with Janowski on 11/15, but two points behind the overallwinner, Frank Marshall, who achieved the greatest success of his career inthis event. --- Let's take a quick overview of how Lasker played. His startwas acceptable; after five rounds he had four points and was in joint secondplace. We saw his win against Napier in the introduction. In the sixth roundagainst Pillsbury he was left with his king exposed and Pillsbury won with anice mating attack. After this defeat Lasker slipped to fifth place, behindJanowski (5½/6), who had a very good tournament with a spectacular start,Marshall and Teichmann (5), and Mieses (4½).} 1. Z0 {Marshall and Janowskibegan to leave the rest behind. After eight rounds they had seven points andLasker was trailing in third a point and a half in arrears. Lasker scored twoand a half points in the final three rounds and managed to catch up withJanowski in the last round by defeating him in a complex and very difficultgame. --- After that Lasker was busy with Lasker's Chess Magazine, and didn'tfor a while play in any serious events again, only taking part in a smalltournament organized by the New York State Chess Association in July 1906,which he won with +5, =2, against young hopefuls of the United States. --- Insix years Lasker played in only one important tournament, but this period ofvirtual inactivity as regards serious games was about to change radically overthe next four years, beginning precisely in January 1907.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1907 WCh against Marshall"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Frank Marshall was the first to challenge Lasker after Steinitz. The matchtook place between the 26th of January and the 8th of April 1907 in a numberof cities in the USA: New York, Philadelphia, Washington DC, Baltimore,Chicago and Memphis. The winner would be the first player who scored eightwins. --- Marshall had finished ahead of Lasker in the Cambridge Springstournament in 1904, and he had also won the strong Nuremberg tournament, inJuly-August 1906, well ahead of Duras, Schlechter and Chigorin, as well as apoorly performing Tarrasch, among others. Marshall also had a favourable scoreagainst Lasker, although based only on two games: +1, =1. --- However, asTarrasch had already demonstrated in their 1905 match, although Marshall was asuccessful tournament player, he didn't perform as strongly in matches.Tarrasch had defeated Marshall 12-5 (+8 -1 =8).} 1. Z0 {As Tarrasch had statedat the time: "After my latest performance which is my greatest ever, I haveno reason to acknowledge anyone in the chess world as being superior to me. Itcertainly was more difficult to beat the young Marshall than the old Steinitz.I am ready to play a match against Lasker under inexpensive conditions, but Iwill not challenge him, for this is the duty of the player of less reputationand successes." Therefore, Lasker was about to play two matchessimultaneously, one across the board against Marshall and the other in thearena of public opinion against Tarrasch. --- Lasker responded to thechallenge with full force; he defeated Marshall convincingly, 11½-3½ (+8 =7),and thus also won the parallel contest against Tarrasch. The first game of thematch is well known, a formidable struggle, with errors of course, in whichLasker outplayed Marshall in all respects: in positional play, in the endgameand also in the complications.} *[Event "25: World Championship, New York"][Site "?"][Date "1907.??.??"][Round "1"][White "Marshall, F"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C65"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "98"][EventDate "1907.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d4 {A continuation which has been more orless abandoned as harmless; White derives no benefit from this early openingof the game, which only leads to simplification.} exd4 5. O-O Be7 6. e5 ({The alternative is to prevent the knight from coming to e4 with} 6. Qe2) ({or} 6. Re1 {before playing e5, but after} O-O {the black knight has a good retreatsquare on e8, after which Black can play ...d6 or ...d5.} ({After 6 Re1 Blackalso has the option of transposing to one of Lasker's favourite lines, theSteinitz Defence, with} 6... d6 {.})) 6... Ne4 7. Nxd4 {EXERCISE: How shouldBlack deal with White's idea of playing 8 Nf5 - ? --- ANSWER:} O-O $1 ({It isn't advisable to prevent the threat with} 7... Nxd4 $6 8. Qxd4 Nc5 {, since this helps White's development; after, for instance,} 9. Rd1 O-O 10.Nc3 d6 11. Be3 {White's game is the more comfortable.}) ({Also,} 7... Nxe5 $4 {isn't playable due to} 8. Qe2 {, winning a piece.}) 8. Nf5 d5 $1 {"The keymove, after which White has nothing better than to exchange a number of minorpieces" (Nunn).} 9. Bxc6 (9. Nxe7+ Nxe7 {is a playable option. White doesgain the bishop pair, but this isn't an advantageous factor for the moment,since the bishops have no prospects of developing any dangerous activity.Black's pieces develop easily and soon the e5-pawn will need protectionfollowing ...Ng6, when playing f4 would leave White's dark-squared bishoprestricted.}) 9... bxc6 10. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. Re1 Qh4 {QUESTION: Is this the bestmove, as the attack on f2 can be parried with a useful move?} ({Doesn't theimmediate} 11... f6 {look more logical? --- ANSWER: Réti was of the sameopinion: "The positional requirement here was ...f6, and it would have beensimplest and best to make this move at once", but he justified Lasker'schoice by its practicality: "Chess today however has reached a stage ofdevelopment where it has become very difficult to win a game with the best andsimplest moves [...] Lasker however is a master of the art of creatingcomplications, and of blending the requirements of a position with thesecomplications [...] In the present position, Lasker evolves an idea from thefact that White has played Re1, thus depriving the f2-square of a guard, andthat it is Black's intention of playing f6, in order to open the f-file, andso begins a complicated attack against f2". --- Let us examine this moredeeply. After 11...f6 Black is fine; a possible continuation is} 12. f3 Ng5 13.Bxg5 ({another possibility, also acceptable for Black, is} 13. exf6 Qxf6 14. c4Qg6) 13... fxg5 14. Nd2 ({if} 14. Nc3 {Black can quickly become active byplaying} Rb8 15. Rb1 Rb4 {, with the idea of 16...g4}) 14... Be6 {.}) ({Finally, another typical idea is} 11... Re8 {, to answer} 12. f3 {with thegood retreat} Nd6 {.}) 12. Be3 {Logical and good;} ({it was also possible toplay} 12. f3 {immediately, preventing the game continuation, but this was nobetter.}) 12... f6 {This looks obvious, but it's more complicated afterinducing 12 Be3. As Réti said, Lasker is trying to complicate the gameprecisely by exploiting the placement of the bishop on e3. --- QUESTION: Butis it correct to provoke a developing move in order to subsequently make amove which could have been made earlier? --- ANSWER: You're making it looklike something bad, but it all depends on the tactics. Objectively there issomething in what you say, but let's not forget that chess is a struggle, andnot a branch of mathematics. On occasion, as long as the disadvantage is nottoo great, the winner will not be the player who stands better objectively,but the one who handles his chances better.} ({Returning to objectivity, sinceWhite could have gained some advantage after Lasker's move, Nunn suggested} 12... f5 {, with the plan of ...f4, and if} 13. f4 {then Black can open thingsup with} g5 $1 {, with complex play after} 14. g3 Nxg3 15. Bf2 gxf4 {.}) 13. f3({In the event of} 13. exf6 {Black would obtain the d6-square for his knightto retreat.}) 13... fxe5 {This was Lasker's idea, to complicate the game.} ({Objectively it's possible that} 13... Ng5 {was preferable, admitting thatWhite is slightly better after, for instance,} 14. Qd2 {, but, as Kasparovcommented: "Lasker makes a psychologically wise choice. It's doubtfulwhether the World Champion calculated all the variations; he more probablysensed that the character of the positions arising after the piece sacrificewould be quite comfortable for him, and that for Marshall they would beunpleasant".}) 14. fxe4 d4 15. g3 $6 {And Lasker's choice passes the firsttest.} ({It wasn't possible to preserve the bishop with} 15. Bd2 $2 {, sinceBlack can play} Bg4 16. Qc1 Rf2 $1 {, with the idea of 17...Bf3, and then} 17.Bg5 {fails to} Rxg2+ $1 18. Kxg2 Bh3+ 19. Kh1 Qf2 {followed by mate.}) ({However, Marshall could have played the simple} 15. Qd2 $1 {, and after} dxe316. Qxe3 {, followed by Nd2, heading for f3 or c4, Black would be hard pressedto justify his very poor pawn structure.}) 15... Qf6 16. Bxd4 $2 {Marshall sawthat keeping the extra piece would grant Black a very strong attack, and hepreferred to give the piece back.} ({After weakening his kingside,} 16. Qe2dxe3 17. Qxe3 {was less attractive now due to} Bh3 {.}) ({Objectively,according to analyzes that have been refined over many years now, and in whichit is very easy to get lost, it was better to retreat the bishop with} 16. Bd2{, when the main line runs} Qf2+ 17. Kh1 Bh3 18. Rg1 h5 $1 {, with the idea of...Bg4. Obviously then} 19. Qxh5 $2 {, allows mate with} ({but White can dobetter with} 19. Na3 Bg4 20. Rf1 Bxd1 21. Rxf2 Rxf2 22. Rxd1 {, when Nunn'sanalysis concludes that with} Re2 {Black can reach a slightly better ending})19... Qxg1+ 20. Kxg1 Rf1# {, as Réti indicated long ago.}) 16... exd4 17. Rf1{EXERCISE: How did Lasker proceed now? --- ANSWER:} Qxf1+ $1 {Generallyspeaking, in such positions it is preferable to keep the queens on to try toexploit the weaknesses of White's castled position, but here there is no goodway to do so.} ({After, for instance,} 17... Qe5 18. Rxf8+ Kxf8 19. Qf3+ {, followed by Nd2 or Qf4, White has no problems;}) ({or} 17... Qg5 18. Rxf8+Kxf8 19. Qd2 {, followed by Qf2+ and Nd2. --- As regards the endgame we areabout to reach, Capablanca evaluated it like this: "To a beginner, theposition can seem drawn, but an experienced player will immediately spot thegreat winning possibilities that Black has, not only because he has theinitiative, but also because White's queenside is completely undeveloped; andbesides, in such positions the bishop is superior to the knight. White willneed some time to bring his knight and rook into play, and Black will use thattime to obtain a certain advantage."}) 18. Qxf1 Rxf1+ 19. Kxf1 {EXERCISE:"When he avoided the dangerous 16 Bd2 Marshall probably considered thisending to be drawn, but Lasker is of another opinion", commented Kasparov.What step did Lasker now take to demonstrate that different opinion? ---ANSWER:} Rb8 $1 {This is the most flexible move; it activates the rook withoutdefining yet the destiny of the bishop.} ({"} 19... Bh3+ {with 20...Rf8+,leading to development with a gain of time would have been more obvious atthis point. Most chessplayers would probably have made this move, since it isa common failing to consider only the new field of action of a piece after ithas been moved while neglecting or completely overlooking the field of actionwhich has been given up as a result of the new move. In the position in thetext, Black's bishop can become effective in two directions, a6 and h3, bothof which in fact subsequently become important. With commendable self-controlLasker therefore refrains from gaining a tempo by ...Bh3+" (Réti). ---Capablanca gave a rather different opinion; he quoted another plan: "Themost obvious [way], and the one that most players would have adopted, consistsin immediately advancing with ...c5 and ...c4, in conjunction with the checkby the bishop on a6 and whatever other move that it might b necessary to makewith the rook. The other, more subtle [way], was the one adopted by Black."})20. b3 Rb5 $1 {The plan, as outlined by Capablanca, "Consists in using therook to force White to constantly defend some point in his position, thusrestricting the action of his knight and rook, while one's own pieces retainall their freedom of action." This move threatens 21...Rc5, amongst otherideas.} 21. c4 $2 {White gets rid of his backward pawn, but it is not withoutcost, as we shall see; the position is now more difficult to defend. ---EXERCISE: How did Lasker respond now?} ({The best defence was} 21. Nd2 $1 {, which would have led to a more balanced position. Let's take a look:} Rc5 22.Nc4 $1 Ba6 23. Ke2 Bxc4+ 24. bxc4 Rxc4 25. Kd2 {, and 'all rook endings aredrawn'. White threatens to become active with Rb1, and after} Rb4 {he usesanother method,} 26. Rf1 {and there is no advantage:} {or finally} c5 ({for example,} 26... Rb5 27. Kd3) (26... Ra4 27. Rb1 Rxa2 28. Rb7 {;} (28. Z0))27. Rf5 Rb5 {, and here White introduces another important factor, his passedpawn. After} 28. e5 c4 29. Rf4 c5 30. e6 {(planning Rf5)} g6 {one of manylines that are sufficient to equalize is} 31. a4 Rb7 32. c3 {and Black has nowinning chances. There are other lines, but in all cases the white rook isable to become active.}) 21... Rh5 $1 {ANSWER: "In this game the rook trulyperforms miracles" (Kasparov). Black keeps his active rook with a gain oftime.} 22. Kg1 ({Now} 22. h4 $2 {fails to} g5 $1 23. hxg5 Rh1+ {, paralyzingWhite.}) 22... c5 {Reinforcing the new element that appeared after 21 c4, thepassed d-pawn, and also opening the h1-a8 diagonal.} 23. Nd2 Kf7 {Blackactivates his king, which can advance to put pressure on the e4-pawn, etc,which indicates that White is worse; not by much, it's still possible toequalize, but he will need to play with great accuracy.} 24. Rf1+ $2 {Thisobvious move is an error, curiously not a tactical error, but one ofevaluation. Marshall didn't realize that it was imperative for him to findcounterplay.} ({For that purpose it was better not to move the rook yet andinstead to play} 24. a3 $1 {, as suggested by Capablanca, trying to play b4.If Black responds with after} a5 {White should prepare the b4 break further byplaying} 25. Rb1 $1 {and, as shown by the analyses of Kasparov and Nunn, Whitehas enough counterplay to equalize.}) 24... Ke7 25. a3 $6 {EXERCISE: Marshallexecutes the correct idea, but at the wrong moment, with his rook misplaced.How did Lasker punish him?} ({More tenacious was} 25. Nf3 {, with advantage toBlack, but there would still be play.}) 25... Rh6 $1 {ANSWER: The rook headsfor the queenside, taking advantage of the absence of the white rook from a1and exploiting the weakness created by 25 a3.} 26. h4 ({The tacticaljustification is that now} 26. b4 {is met with} Ra6 $1 {, and there is nosatisfactory defence: for instance,} 27. Rf3 Bg4 28. Rb3 cxb4 29. axb4 Ra2 ({or} 29... Ke6 {, and the defensive task is unpleasant.})) 26... Ra6 27. Ra1 (27.a4 {is no better; Nunn then suggests the immediate} Rf6 {, because the endingof knight versus bishop is hopeless for White, due to the weakness of b3, andthe imminent attack with ...Ke6-e5, followed by ...d3 and ...Kd4.} ({It's alsopossible to preface the rook exchange with} 27... Bg4 28. Rf4 h5 29. Kf2 {and now} Rf6 {is one of several strong moves.})) 27... Bg4 $1 {Activating thebishop and controlling f3 before activating the king. There is no defence.} 28.Kf2 Ke6 29. a4 ({The ending after} 29. Nf3 Bxf3 30. Kxf3 Ke5 {is also lost forWhite.}) 29... Ke5 {With the plan of 30...Rf6+, followed by 31...d3 and ...Kd4.} 30. Kg2 Rf6 31. Re1 d3 32. Rf1 Kd4 33. Rxf6 gxf6 34. Kf2 c6 35. a5 ({Or} 35.Nb1 a5 36. Ke1 Kxe4 37. Kf2 Kd4 {.}) 35... a6 {Now White is in zugzwang, sothe e4-pawn falls and the rest is simple.} 36. Nb1 Kxe4 {Marshall continuesplaying, but there is really no chance of salvation.} 37. Ke1 Be2 38. Nd2+ Ke339. Nb1 f5 40. Nd2 h5 41. Nb1 Kf3 42. Nc3 Kxg3 43. Na4 f4 44. Nxc5 f3 45. Ne4+Kf4 46. Nd6 c5 47. b4 cxb4 48. c5 b3 49. Nc4 Kg3 {Lasker also won the next twogames, which were played in New York, also outplaying Marshall in everyrespect. He won the second game in the ending, and in the third, whereMarshall had very good chances of drawing, Lasker used the defence that bearshis name: after 1 d4 d5 2 c4 e6 3 Nc3 Nf6 4 Bg5 Be7 5 e3 he played 5...Ne4.--- The match stood at 3-0 to Lasker and seemed to be heading for a speedyconclusion, but this was not to be; between the fourth and the eleventh gameLasker managed only one win. After that second phase of the match, in whichMarshall resisted stubbornly, Lasker, now leading with four wins to zero withseven draws, showed Marshall no mercy and won the next four games, runningaway with the match.} 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1908 WCh against Tarrasch"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The long delayed match for the world title between Lasker and Tarraschfinally took place. It was played in Germany, in Dusseldorf and Munich, fromthe 17th of August to the 30th of September 1908. --- There had been anarrangement to play it in 1904, but Tarrasch had a skiing accident whichprevented it happening. Much earlier, in 1892, Tarrasch had refused to playagainst Lasker, because he considered his early victories to be of littlevalue, and later he undervalued other more significant achievements by Lasker,beginning with his coronation as world champion against Steinitz.} 1. Z0 {Victory in the 'Match of the Century', as it was called at the time, wouldagain go to the first player to score eight wins. After winning the first game,which had seemed to be heading for a draw, Lasker won again in the second. Itwas a dramatic encounter, commented on and analyzed in depth by masters frommany different eras, ranging from the players themselves to Réti, laterKorchnoi, Dvoretsky and Kasparov, among others, and more recently by Nunn. ---Lasker landed in a losing position, but especially against Lasker that wasrarely the end of the story. It was unthinkable that he should passively awaithis execution. Indeed, Lasker decided to complicate the play, at the cost ofweakening his own king. Tarrasch's position remained objectively winning, butit required precise play to prove this, and the challenger was not up to thetask. Lasker went over to the counterattack and won with energetic play. ---As regards the influence of the psychological element in Lasker'sdecision-making, the analysts are not unanimous in their opinions; someconsider it of great importance, others not. Incidentally, Korchnoi'sannotations, dating from the 1970s, are admirably accurate, not only instrategic evaluation, which is to be expected, but also in analysis of thetactics. More than forty years on, today's analysis engines find few faultswith his analysis.} *[Event "26: World Championship, Dusseldorf"][Site "?"][Date "1908.??.??"][Round "2"][White "Tarrasch, S"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C66"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "82"][EventDate "1908.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O d6 5. d4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Re1 exd4 ({EXERCISE: Let's put your knowledge to the test:} 7... O-O {is a well knownerror, but why? --- ANSWER: Because it loses a pawn to the so-called 'Tarraschtrap' after} 8. Bxc6 Bxc6 9. dxe5 dxe5 10. Qxd8 {No better is} Rfxd8 (10...Raxd8 11. Nxe5 {and here} Bxe4 $2 {makes things worse, losing a piece after}12. Nxe4 Nxe4 13. Nd3 f5 14. f3 Bc5+ 15. Nxc5 Nxc5 16. Bg5 Rd5 17. Be7 Re8 18.c4 {1-0, S.Tarrasch-G.Marco, Dresden 1892.} (18. Z0)) 11. Nxe5 Bxe4 12. Nxe4Nxe4 13. Nd3 f5 14. f3 Bc5+ 15. Kf1 {, etc, winning material. --- This is awell known trap, dating from the nineteenth century. It's surprising thereforethat a world championship candidate should fall for it so many years later,with just a slight difference, having interpolated the moves 3...a6 4 Ba4,which don't change the situation. In the game M.Tal-B.Ivkov, Belgrade vs.Moscow 1974, Black played 11...Raxd8 12 Nxe5 Bd7, but was unable to save thegame.}) 8. Nxd4 O-O (8... Nxd4 {was Lasker's choice in the fourth game; Blackremained rather passive after} 9. Qxd4 Bxb5 10. Nxb5 {.}) 9. Nxc6 {Doublingthe pawns is always tempting. --- QUESTION: But didn't you just tell me thatexchanging two pieces with 8...Nxd4 wasn't very good?} (9. Bxc6 bxc6 10. Qf3 {is of similar strength, with ideas such as 11 Nf5 and 11 e5 followed by Nxc6.})({Another idea is} 9. Bf1 {, avoiding exchanges, which is advisable when youhave more space, leaving the opponent with his mobility problems.}) 9... Bxc6 {ANSWER: The suitability of exchanging pieces when you have less space is ageneral rule which is valid in most positions, but of course it depends on theconcrete situation; if it leads to weakening the king or a passive position,then it's more debatable. There is no consensus in this case; Nunn prefers theexchange of knights, since it reduces White's options.} (9... bxc6 {is alsosatisfactory, as played several times by Steinitz and Euwe. After} 10. Bd3 Re8{, with the idea of ...Ng4-e5, the strongest move is considered to be} 11. h3 {. S.Tarrasch-W.Steinitz, Vienna 1898, continued} {At the end of the twentiethcentury the position was handled differently:} h6 $5 {was played several times,with the idea of 12...Nh7 and 13...Bf6; the h7-knight can go to f8, or g5 ifthis is accessible, and Black's results were quite reasonable.} (11... Bf8 12.Bg5 h6 13. Bh4 Rb8 14. Rb1 g5 $6 15. Bg3 g4 $2 16. Bh4 $1 {, punishing Black'srisky play.} (16. Z0))) 10. Bxc6 bxc6 11. Ne2 {QUESTION: What a strange move!Isn't it better to play, for example, 11 b3 and 12 Bb2 - ? --- ANSWER: It'snot the first move that comes to mind, not even to Lasker, who commented:"This manoeuvre was new to me, though Tarrasch had used it previously.Obviously the e-pawn must not be captured because of Nd4. Hence, White gainstime to place the knight advantageously so as to dominate the f5-square,either on d4 or on g3." --- The knight is heading for f5 or h5, which,together with Lasker's suggestion of b3, followed by Bb2, threatens to createstrong pressure on Black's castled position.} ({As is almost always the case,the move order is important. Let's hand over to Korchnoi, who mentions for thefirst time the psychological factor, in this case employed by Tarrasch:"There is also an element of psychology in the move chosen by White, whoprevents Black from following the natural plan of development for his pieces.If, for example, White plays the natural} 11. b3) ({or} 11. Bf4 {then Blackreplies} Nd7 {and 12...Bf6.}) ({The knight move to d7 is normal, but after} 11.Ne2 {it is no longer sufficient:} Nd7 $2 12. Nd4 c5 13. Nc6 Qe8 14. e5 {and White has a clear advantage".}) 11... Qd7 $2 {QUESTION: A mistake? Itcompletes Black's development, so how can it be bad? --- ANSWER: The shortanswer is the one given by Kasparov: "This square is for the knight!".Moreover, Black is planning to play ...d5 at an opportune moment afterpreparing it with ...Qd7 and ...Rad8, but this proves to be a faulty plan. Themain drawback of this move is the one mentioned above: it occupies the naturalsquare of the f6-knight. Also it isn't very flexible: if Black is unable tocarry out his idea, his pieces will be badly coordinated and his position willgradually deteriorate.} ({Korchnoi suggested} 11... Re8 {, which threatens tocapture on e4, and after} 12. Nd4 c5 13. Nf5 Nd7 {Black has a reasonableposition; Dvoretsky then suggested} 14. a4 {, with the idea of Ra3 followed bytransferring the rook to the kingside, which is an interesting manoeuvre and afavourite of the world champion Magnus Carlsen in similar positions, althoughin this case Black appears to have time to strengthen his position with themanoeuvre 14...Re6, followed by ...Kh8 and ...g6.}) ({Since moving the knightfrom c3 has reduced White's control of the centre, a move to be considered isthe central strike} 11... d5 {, on the merits of which there is no consensus:for instance, Korchnoi disliked it in view of the continuation} {Thealternative} 12. e5 (12. Nd4 Qd7 13. Nf5 Bc5 14. Qf3 {, but current enginesconsider the black position satisfactory.} (14. Z0)) 12... Ne4 {wasn'tconsidered dangerous for Black, despite White having the better structure,with just two 'pawn islands' against Black's three. Nevertheless, White'sposition seems more pleasant after, for instance,} 13. c3 {, followed by Be3,Qc2, Rad1, etc, with a timely f3 to evict the knight from e4.}) 12. Ng3 Rfe8 {"A mistake. If the rook moves at all it must go to d8. The knight at f6should have a retreat open" (Lasker).} ({Réti recommended} 12... Rfd8 {, with the plan of playing ...Rab8, followed by implementing the ...d5 break,reserving the e8-square for the eventual retreat of the f6-knight.}) 13. b3Rad8 ({Here "turning round and going back" with} 13... Qc8 {has beensuggested, something that is always very difficult in practice; the idea is torespond to} 14. Bb2 {with the regrouping} Nd7 15. Nf5 {is not as strong,because Black can reply with} ({but White's initiative is very dangerous after} 15. Nh5 {, forcing the weakening move} g6 {,} ({since} 15... Bf8 $2 {loses to} 16. Bxg7 $1 Bxg7 17. Qg4 {etc.})) 15... Bf6 $1 {;} ({once again though,} 15... Bf8 $2 {loses to} 16. Bxg7 $1 {.})) ({This last line suggests that} 13...Qd8 {should be considered, so that after Nh5 Black can play ...Nf6 or ...Bf6without the kingside pawns being doubled, but this move would be even moredifficult to play than 13...Qc8.}) 14. Bb2 {EXERCISE: The white knight willsoon jump to f5, which combined with Qf3 looks very threatening. What do youthink Lasker played here? --- ANSWER:} Ng4 $1 {Objectively this is a bad move,but if we add the human factor to the mix, it may well be the most promisingoption. Korchnoi expressed it thus: "Lasker's vast tactical talent finds theonly possible way of complicating the game. An astute psychologist, he doesnot mind material loss in order to escape from the positional pressure beingexerted by Tarrasch. True, it is dangerous: White might gain a strong attack,but then Tarrasch is by no means as strong an attacking player as he is apositional player!" --- According to Richard Réti, Lasker deliberatelyplayed doubtful variations in order to "force" his opponent to playpositions which were not to his liking, even though they were objectivelyfavourable. This view was often repeated, although later opinion began to turnagainst it, and now it's an explanation which is not taken very seriously.} ({In any case this is not an example of voluntarily playing a weak move; theproblem is that there is no satisfactory continuation for Black. Returning topurely chess matters, Lasker would have been very reluctant to opt for} 14...g6 {, since this would create glaring weaknesses in Black's kingside and Whitewould have the advantage after} 15. Qd4 $1 {.}) ({Instead,} 14... Qe6 {looksmore tenacious, defending the f6-knight so as to be able to retreat the bishopfrom e7, although is clear that Lasker didn't relish Black's prospects in a'quiet' position. White can play} 15. Qd4 $1 {, attacking the pawn on a7; andafter} ({as well as} 15. Nf5 Bf8 16. Qf3) 15... c5 16. Qc3 {there is a threatof Qa5 and Black faces an unpleasant defensive task}) 15. Bxg7 $1 {Of course.}({Now} 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 $2 {is unplayable due to} 16. Nf5+ {and Qxg4.}) 15... Nxf2$1 {Now the white king will also be exposed, but as Korchnoi pointed out, theg-pawn is the most important of the three kingside pawns, and White should beable to take advantage of this in some way. --- EXERCISE: White now has morethan one tempting continuation; which is the best?} 16. Kxf2 $2 {Objectivelythis is correct; White wins a pawn and gains a big advantage. Nevertheless,Tarrasch was criticized for relaxing the pressure on the black king.} ({ANSWER: Possibly slightly stronger, and above all much more dangerous from thepractical point of view was} 16. Qd4 $1 {, not simplifying prematurely.} {In the event of} Ng4 ({Then if} 16... c5 {one good continuation is} 17. Qxf2 ({but even stronger is} 17. Qc3 $1 {, keeping more pieces on the board}) 17...Kxg7 18. Nh5+ Kh8 19. Nf6 Bxf6 20. Qxf6+ Kg8 21. Re3 {.}) 17. Nf5 Qe6 {Whiteshould first neutralize Black's tactical resources:} {and there is also} 18.Qc3 $1 {, with the awful threat of 19 Qg3} ({instead of rushing ahead with} 18.Re3 $2 c5 19. Qc3 Bf6 $1 (19... Z0)) ({or} 18. h3 $2 Bf6 $1 {, and in bothcases Black is over the worst.}) ({Instead,} 18. Qxa7 {is stronger, asKorchnoi pointed out}) {That leaves} 18... Ne5 {, but then all the whitepieces would attack the black king with, for example,} ({preventing} 18... Bf6$2 {, because of} 19. Bxf6 Qxf6 20. Qg3 Qg6 21. Qxg4 $1 {, which is possibleprecisely due to the disappearance of the g-pawn.} (21. Z0)) ({Another virtueof 18 Qc3 is that it attacks Black's weak queenside pawns, which is decisivein the event of} 18... Qg6 19. h3 Bf6 20. Bxf6 Nxf6 21. Qxc6 d5 22. Qxc7 Rd723. Qf4 {, etc.}) 19. Re3 $1 f6 20. Rg3 Ng6 21. Rf1 {, etc. --- According toRéti, Lasker wouldn't have played 14...Ng4? against an attacking player, andhe did so against Tarrasch in view of the latter's preference for meticulousand orderly play, and reluctance to enter unfathomable tactical complications.As we'll see at the end, in a way Lasker proves him right. --- "The movechosen by Tarrasch also wins a pawn, but after the exchange of the importantbishop on g7 for the knight, Black succeeds in creating counterchances" (Korchnoi).}) 16... Kxg7 17. Nf5+ Kh8 18. Qd4+ f6 19. Qxa7 {White has won apawn and has a big advantage, but the greatest threat to the black king,namely White's dark-squared bishop, has disappeared. White will need to employgood technique to realize his extra pawn.} Bf8 {Unlike the situation a fewmoves ago, Black's king is now out of danger, at the cost of a pawn, and hehas a clear plan, which is to apply pressure to the isolated pawn on e4 bydoubling rooks on the e-file, with the idea of an eventual ...d5.It shouldalso not be forgotten that the white king remains somewhat exposed.} 20. Qd4Re5 {QUESTION: Despite seemingly not playing the best moves, White still haseverything in his favour: centralized pieces, passed pawns, etc. What problemcould there possibly be? --- ANSWER: Let's see what Dvoretsky thinks: "Itlooks as though White has succeeded, and the assessment of the position isobvious: he's a pawn up, and his knight is far more active than the opposingbishop. In this kind of situation, it's a very difficult task psychologicallyto pull oneself together, and examine the contours of the opponent'sthreatened counterplay, in order to take accurate measures to neutralize it [...] Clearly, it's not yet time to shepherd the a-pawn to the queening square:first White must consolidate. And if he succeeds in this, then he mustsimplify. But it's not that obvious precisely what plan White should follow".} 21. Rad1 {White had used up a lot of his time and had seen the prospects ofa victorious attack after 15 Bxg7! disappear. Now, as Dvoretsky pointed out,White needs to adapt to the new situation.} ({Taking into account Black's plan,White might have considered trying to anticipate it by reducing the impact ofthe ...d5 break and overprotecting the e4-pawn, starting with} 21. g4 {However,the exposed situation of the white king can be highlighted by} d5 $1 ({withthe idea of answering} 21... Rde8 {with} 22. Re3 {, followed by Rae1.} (22. Z0)) {After 21...d5! it is unclear whether White can simply ignore the pawn andplay} 22. a4 {, since with} ({and if} 22. exd5 $6 {then} Rxf5+ $1 23. gxf5Qxf5+ 24. Kg2 Bd6 $1 {provides Black with enough counterplay to equalize.} (24... Z0)) 22... h5 $1 {The engines at first show a clear advantage to Whiteafter} 23. exd5 {, but they soon change their mind and shows the amazing line}(23. h3 Qh7 {Black can demonstrate that 21 g4 wasn't entirely cost-free.} (23... Z0)) 23... Rxf5+ 24. gxf5 Bc5 $3 25. Qxc5 Qxf5+ 26. Ke3 Rxd5 {, withequality after} 27. Qxd5 ({or a draw by perpetual check starting with} 27. Qf8+) 27... cxd5 28. Kd2 {.}) 21... Rde8 22. Qc3 {Korchnoi assessed the positionthus: "And so White has an extra pawn and central squares for his pieces,and that amounts to good winning chances. It's true that Black also has someadvantages: his rooks are actively placed on the e-file, attacking the weakpawn on e4, and the position of the powerful white knight on f5 is unsafebecause of the threat of d6-d5. With his last move White declared hisintentions: he will try to tie Black down to the defence of the weak pawns onc6 and f6, transfer the knight to a safer position on f3 or c4, and finally atan appropriate moment begin to advance the passed pawn. Yet in the game itselfall this never happens. Tarrasch apparently was short of time, met a stubbornand resourceful defence, and played very weakly in the endgame part of thegame, gradually conceding the centre."} Qf7 $1 {Tarrasch probably thought hehad prevented this. It's easy to understand how disconcerting thus must havebeen for him;} ({now the capture} 22... Qf7 23. Qxc6 {wouldn't represent aclear profit, since after} Rc5 24. Qa6 Rxc2+ 25. Re2 Rc5 {, although Black isstill a pawn down, at least he has exchanged a doubled pawn for the healthierone on c2.}) 23. Ng3 $6 {Korchnoi: "There is no point in retreating theknight to a passive position". White begins to lose the thread of the game;the retreat of this dominating albeit slightly insecure knight represents aconcession. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker respond?} ({As Korchnoi pointed out,White could have defended e4 in a better way with} 23. Qf3 $1 {, and in theevent of} d5 24. exd5 cxd5 25. Rxe5 Rxe5 26. Re1 Bc5+ 27. Kf1 Qe6 28. Rxe5 Qxe5{the exchanges have helped White, whose king is now much safer. He can nowstart to think about advancing his passed pawn with} 29. a4 {, with advantage,}({or perhaps prefacing this with} 29. c3 {, preventing the entry of the blackqueen on a1, as suggested by Dvoretsky.})) 23... Bh6 {ANSWER: With the mostannoying move. Finally, this bishop is able to become active.} 24. Qf3 $6 {It's always difficult to admit a mistake and 'take the move back', but asKorchnoi pointed out "Both now and on the following move it is possible toreturn the knight to f5 with chances of a win. But one has the feeling thatTarrasch has lost the strategic thread of the game".} ({After} 24. Nf5 $1 {there was no need to fear} Qh5 {due to} 25. Qf3 $1 {.}) 24... d5 25. exd5 $2 {Another inaccuracy.} (25. Nf5 $1 {was appropriate, forcing Black to retreatthe bishop or enter a worse endgame after} Qg6 26. Nxh6 Qxh6 27. exd5 Qh4+ 28.Qg3 {, etc.}) 25... Be3+ 26. Kf1 cxd5 27. Rd3 $2 {This is a clear mistake,handing the advantage to Black; all the black pieces will soon begin to worktogether in perfect harmony. --- Lasker meanwhile considered that after thetext move White is lost. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker set about proving thecorrectness of his assessment?} (27. Nf5 {was still preferable, as mentionedby the players, after which Korchnoi suggested} d4 {, when "The activepositions of the black pieces would be enough for equality. Now, despiteWhite's material advantage, his position is very difficult".}) 27... Qe6 {ANSWER: The powerful f5-knight is now a thing of the past and the white kingwill begin to feel more and more uncomfortable.} 28. Re2 f5 $1 {The blackpawns on f5 and d5 will advance to cement the strong bishop in place, as wellto harass the knight, which has suddenly become a piece lacking any goodprospects.} 29. Rd1 ({t isn't possible to provide a good square for the knightwith} 29. Ke1 {, since Black wins material with} f4 30. Nf1 Bf2+ $1 {, etc.})29... f4 30. Nh1 d4 31. Nf2 Qa6 $1 {"Lasker conducts the attack with greatenergy. First he gains control of the centre, and now he wins back a pawn, atthe same time effectively breaking into the enemy camp" (Korchnoi). Blackthreatens to win with 32...Bxf2.} 32. Nd3 $6 {EXERCISE: What now? White isvery cramped, but how can Black infiltrate the white position? What is thebest square for the attacked rook?} ({It was preferable to play} 32. Kg1 $1Qxa2 33. Kh1 {.}) 32... Rg5 $1 {ANSWER: Not only eyeing the g2-pawn as afuture target, but with an even stronger idea also in mind.} 33. Ra1 (33. a4 {could have been answered with} Reg8 {, followed by the move that Black nowmakes.}) 33... Qh6 $1 {The complement to 32...Rg5; the h-pawn is much moreimportant than the a-pawn.} 34. Ke1 ({If} 34. h3 {Black opens lines decisivelyagainst the white king with} Rg3 ({for instance,} 34... Kg8 35. Qd5+ Kg7 36.Rxe3 fxe3 37. Qb5 Rg8 {and the game isn't over yet}) 35. Qd5 {and now} f3 $1 ({rather than the spectacular but erroneous} 35... Qxh3 $2 {, which would allow}36. Qxd4+ $1 {, after which the position becomes unclear.})) 34... Qxh2 35. Kd1Qg1+ 36. Ne1 Rge5 $1 {The pressure along the e-file grows stronger andstronger, and White, in time trouble, is unable to mount much resistance.} 37.Qc6 R5e6 ({Another way to win was with} 37... R8e7 {: for example,} 38. a4 Kg8$1 {(threatening 39...Bf2, because now there is no 40 Qf6+, with check), withthe idea of answering} 39. Qf3 ({or} 39. Qb7 {with} h5 $1 {, preventing theannoying check on g4 and thus renewing the threat of 40...Bf2.})) ({It wasalso good to pre-empt the check on f6 by playing} 37... Rg8 {, threatening 38...Bf2, but Lasker's move is also winning.}) 38. Qxc7 R8e7 ({In time pressure itwasn't easy to decide about} 38... f3 $1 {. If} 39. gxf3 {then} Qg6 $1 {is very strong, preparing to move the bishop or play 40...Qh5,} ({but not} 39... Bg5 $2 40. Rxe6 Rxe6 41. Qc8+ {, picking up the rook. However, the textmove also wins and with fewer complications.})) 39. Qd8+ $6 ({"} 39. Qc8+ {was a little better. But Black places his rook upon e5 and finally forces thegame by ...Bf2, or ...d3, followed by ...Bd4, or by the advance of the h-pawn,according to circumstances" (Lasker).}) 39... Kg7 40. a4 f3 $1 {Openinglines and preparing the decisive infiltration.} 41. gxf3 Bg5 $1 ({After} 41...Bg5 42. Rxe6 Rxe6 43. Qa5 {,} Qe3 {wins.}) (41... Z0 {Here's what the playersthought of the game: Tarrasch: "I should be ashamed of this game. As farback as the 15th move, after the stroke on g7, my advantage was so great thatLasker, who had a habit of walking around the hall, told the spectators, whileI was considering my moves, that 'I always lose the second game'. --- "Buthere, the effects of my previous loss came to bear. On the 16th move, I couldnot decide whether to play for a continuation of the attack or the win of apawn, and chose the second possibility, telling myself that my opponent mightbe able to withstand the attack, and then I would regret not taking an easypawn, which would be enough to secure me the win. Had I not lost the firstgame, I would certainly have played for the attack, since even if I had notwon the game, I would not have been in an inferior position. But the concernwas to equalize the match score and catch up with my opponent. On the otherhand, this plan should also have been enough for victory. But myindecisiveness about which was the best defensive plan, and the terribletime-pressure it induced, led to my making a whole series of weak moves, whichruined a won position". --- And Lasker: "With my back to the wall, Idecided to allow a powerful attack against the position of my king, intendingto seek compensation in other factors. Had I hesitated, I would have lost theinitiative completely. Tarrasch took the opportunity offered him, drove myking to an exposed square, maintained his threats, and even gained thematerial advantage of a pawn. He thought that he had assured himself anadvantage sufficient for victory; but in fact, as later became clear, he hadonly equality at best. Had he, like Pillsbury or Steinitz, taken himself inhand, refused the insignificant material advantage, and thrown himself intothe whirlwind of attacking combinations, he would have won. He was not to beallowed the quiet, risk-free exploitation of his material advantage. I gavehim a choice, and he made a mistake. His pieces were driven back from theirstrong positions, and by the 41st move, he was beaten".}) 0-1[Event "27: World Championship, Dusseldorf"][Site "?"][Date "1908.??.??"][Round "4"][White "Tarrasch, S"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C66"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "82"][EventDate "1908.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Tarrasch recovered to win the third game. Untypically Lasker declined to winback a pawn he had sacrificed; in an equal position he threw himself into theattack, which was accurately rebuffed. --- Kasparov commented: "Thechallenger had raised his head! Now much depended on which of the two playerswould succeed in landing the next blow. And at this moment was played one oftheir most famous games, determining the outcome of the match". --- This winby Lasker was also analyzed by every generation of grandmasters from the earlytwentieth century to the start of the twenty-first century. It's another oneof Lasker's best known games.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. O-O d6 {Lasker and Tarrasch had opposing opinions about the Steinitz Defence. Laskerwas attracted by its solidity; Tarrasch, on the other hand, did not approve ofit. One of his most famous sayings is: "Every cramped position harbours thegerm of defeat".} 5. d4 Bd7 6. Nc3 Be7 7. Re1 exd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4 ({In thesecond game, as we have already seen, Lasker played} 8... O-O {, although hismistake came later. As Kasparov has pointed out, Lasker returned successfullyto 8...0-0 in his matches with Janowski (1909), Schlechter (1910) andCapablanca (1921).}) 9. Qxd4 ({The alternative is} 9. Bxd7+ Nxd7 10. Qxd4 {and although White is able to emerge with a bishop against a knight after} O-O11. Nd5 {, he appears to have no advantage after} Bf6 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 {.}) 9...Bxb5 10. Nxb5 {QUESTION: Explain to me once again the motivation for theseexchanges? I can see that there is no divergence of opinion here and Laskeropted to exchange. --- ANSWER: In this case it is easier to reach agreement.Once the first exchange has taken place, activating the white queen, Blacksolves his mobility problems with this second exchange of pieces; in contrast,9...0-0 would allow 10 Bf1.} O-O 11. Bg5 {A logical developing move.} ({A drawback mentioned by Nunn is that it can lead to an exchange of bishops, sohe suggested} 11. Bf4 {instead.}) ({It's worth noting too that here it isn'tappropriate to employ the dangerous plan with} 11. b3 {used in the second gamesince White's slower development allows} d5 $1 ({as well as} 11... Nd7 {), and White gains no advantage.})) ({Capablanca suggested} 11. Qc3 {Anotherpossibility is} d5 {(Nunn), and if} ({and in the event of the natural} 11... c6{White plays} 12. Nd4 {, and the knight heads for f5.}) ({As such, Kasparovsuggested that Black should avoid weakening the d6-pawn and instead play} 11...a6 {, since the pawn on c7 is immune from capture and after} 12. Nd4 Nd7 13.Nf5 Bf6 14. Qg3 Kh8 ({or} 14... Re8 {, Black is fine.})) 12. e5 {the key isthe counterblow} c6 $1 {, and after} 13. exf6 Bxf6 14. Qb3 (14. Nd4 $6 {runs into} Qb6) 14... cxb5 15. Qxb5 {, despite Black's isolated queen's pawn,his advantage in development and his greater piece activity guarantee him anequal game; he can continue, for instance, with} Rc8 16. c3 d4 17. cxd4 Bxd4 {, with the idea of ...Rc2.}) 11... h6 12. Bh4 Re8 ({Since the b5-knight can'tgo to d4, it's worth considering} 12... c6 {, followed by 13...Qb6 (Nunn); theexchange of queens doubles the pawns, but opens the a-file and allows a future...b5.}) 13. Rad1 {EXERCISE: White is first to centralize his rooks,preventing the aforementioned manoeuvre with ...c6 and ...Qb6. What would youplay here? --- ANSWER:} Nd7 {Lasker parries the threat of 14 e5 with athematic response, offering an exchange of bishops to relieve the pressure.} ({Nunn suggested seeking counterplay with} 13... a6 14. Nc3 b5 {, to which apossible response is} 15. Ne2 {, intending Ng3-f5.}) 14. Bxe7 ({QUESTION: Butif it suits Black to exchange pieces, why doesn't White just retreat hisbishop? --- ANSWER: This is a general rule, but its appropriateness needs tobe judged in each concrete case. Tarrasch didn't consider that White's chanceswould be improved with} 14. Bg3 {, since Black's pieces 'wake up' with, forinstance,} Bf6 15. Qc4 a6 $1 16. Nd4 (16. Nxc7 $2 {fails to} Nb6 $1) 16... b517. Qc6 Bxd4 18. Rxd4 Ne5 19. Qc3 Qb8 {.}) 14... Rxe7 15. Qc3 {The most direct,attacking c7 and with the familiar plan of Nd4-f5. --- EXERCISE: As Kasparovpointed out, "Tarrasch must have been happy with the outcome of the opening:White has a slight but enduring advantage, and chances of increasing itwithout any risk". How did Lasker prevent Tarrasch prevent Tarrasch fromincreasing his advantage without any risk?} ({In the event of} 15. f4 {Blackcan play} a6 16. Nc3 Re6 {, not fearing} 17. e5 {because of} Qe8 $1 {.}) ({Another plan, completely different, apparently slower, but in view of whathappens in the game, slightly better, is} 15. c4 {, gaining more space andpreparing the pawn break c5, not forgetting e5. This was played in J.R.Capablanca-F.Marshall, fourth matchgame, New York 1909, which quickly ended ina draw, but after} Re6 16. f4 a6 17. Nc3 {White's position is slightly betterand it isn't easy for Black to gain any counterplay.}) 15... Re5 $1 {ANSWER: Abrilliant response and the start of another of Lasker's spectacular rookmanoeuvres. --- QUESTION: This isn't the first move that springs to mind. Howdid Lasker come up with it? --- ANSWER: We can only speculate, but it ispossible that it was because he didn't find the alternatives convincing, or asKasparov puts it, "Lasker realized perfectly well that his only chance ofavoiding a prolonged and gruelling defence was to dislodge Tarrasch from hisconfident state. To do this he had to create something unusual, contrary toall the positional rules and standards of chess wisdom!".} ({Let's considerit concretely: the natural moves fail to prevent the Nd4 manoeuvre, with theidea of Nf5, with pressure on g7; preventing Nf5 with ...g6 naturally weakensBlack's castled position. Meanwhile} 15... Nf6 $2 {was impossible due to} 16.e5) ({so the main alternative was} 15... Nc5 {, when} 16. e5 $6 (16. f3 {is better, when Black can frustrate the threat of Nd4 with} Ne6 {, but heremains rather passive after} 17. Qd2 {, preparing Nc3-d5, or perhaps 17 c4first}) {, can be answered with} 16... Qd7 $1 {(Kasparov): for example,} 17.Nd4 Rxe5 18. Rxe5 dxe5 19. Qxc5 Re8 $1 {(Nunn).}) 16. Nd4 (16. Nxc7 $4 {loses to} Rc5 {;}) ({while} 16. Qxc7 $2 {is inadvisable due to} Rxb5 17. Qxd6 {and now} Rc8 $1 {threatening ...Rc7} ({and better than the immediate} 17...Rxb2 18. e5 $1 {, with the idea of e6}) 18. Qxd7 Qxd7 19. Rxd7 Rxb2 {, withthe better ending.}) 16... Rc5 $1 {Continuing with the idea of changing thenatural course of the game. Of course this unusual rook manoeuvre requirescareful calculation, because the rook is more exposed than in 'normal'positions.} ({In the event of} 16... Nc5 {(or 16...Nf6)} 17. f3 {White canproceed unhindered; he has Nf5 available and can also prepare c4 with b3 ifnecessary.}) 17. Qb3 ({If} 17. Qg3 {, still hoping to attack g7, Black can play} Qg5 {.}) 17... Nb6 {This prevents c4 and defends b7;} ({another idea was} 17... a5 {, with the plan of ...a4, which would give the c5-rook more room.}18. Qxb7 $2 {would not be good in view of} Rb8 {and ...Rxb2, and Black becomesactive at no cost to himself.}) 18. f4 {Cutting off the retreat of the blackrook. As Dvoretsky pointed out, White "prepares to cramp the opponent by Qf3,b2-b3 and c2-c4".} Qf6 19. Qf3 Re8 {Lasker plays the most natural move,which is to bring into play the only inactive piece.} ({Subsequently hesuggested another way to do this, with} 19... a5 {, which is the ideamentioned above, but with the knight in b6. Now after} 20. b3 a4 21. c3 ({more flexible than} 21. c4 {, which can wait till later}) 21... axb3 22. axb3Rca5 {the a-file doesn't seem to compensate for White's central domination andprospects of kingside activity.}) ({However, even more precise is the ideafound some years ago by one of Dvoretsky's students, Ilya Makariev:} 19... Na4$1 {, which tries, successfully, to make use of the intrepid black rook, butof course it would require deep calculation.} {and neither does the moreviolent try} 20. e5 ({The attack on b2, despite appearances, can be answeredwith} 20. b3 {, leading to a complicated position after} Nc3 21. Rd3 Nxa2 22.e5 dxe5 23. Qxb7 Rd8 24. Qxa7 {, where Black is fine after} Nb4 {;} ({or themore colourful line} 24... Qb6 25. Ne6 {(forced)} Qxa7 26. Rxd8+ Kh7 27. Nf8+ {, with a draw by perpetual check.})) ({Alternatively, after} 20. Qb3 {Blacksimply goes back with} Nb6 {.}) ({Instead,} 20. Qa3 b5 {gives White noadvantage}) 20... dxe5 21. Qxb7 Rd8 {while} 22. Nb3 $6 {isn't advisable due to}({when} 22. Qxa7 {can be met with} Nxb2 ({or} 22... Rxd4 23. Rxd4 exd4 24. Qxa4Qxf4)) 22... Rxd1 23. Rxd1 Rc4 $1 ({more ambitious than the also good} 23...Rxc2 24. Qe4 {) and White's position is very shaky; Black's pieces are veryactive and the white king is weak. --- It's worth noting that although 19...Na4! is immediately suggested by today's analysis engines and is in a wayconsistent with 15...Re5!, it isn't a move that would be easy to play over theboard. Indeed, it would require Black to enter complications with a rook outof play and would involve the careful calculation of many lines. Such a moveis much easier to find in later analysis.})) 20. c3 $1 ({One of the ideas of19...Re8 was preventing} 20. b3 {. After that, with the idea of 21 c4, Blackwould have played} Nd5 $1 21. Ne2 ({not} 21. exd5 $2 Rxe1+ {followed by ...Qxd4+}) 21... Nc3 ({or} 21... Nb4 {, with a good position.})) 20... a5 {The pawn not only comes to the aid of the c5-rook, as we have seen above, butit also plans to keep advancing, to open up the queenside, even though thereis no longer a rook on a8.} 21. b3 {The most logical reply, seeking to stifleBlack's pieces with c4.} a4 22. b4 $5 ({Tarrasch wants to drive the rook to aworse position and he rejects the more routine continuation} 22. c4 axb3 23.axb3 {, which would guarantee some advantage, since the b6-knight would berestricted and White would be ready to play Nb5.} {As such, best seems to be}Nd7 {, trying to recycle the knight, but after} ({In that case although thec5-rook has more scope,} 23... Ra5 {would be inappropriate due to} 24. Nb5 $1Qe7 25. Qf2 {(threatening Nxd6)} Rd8 26. Qd4 {, with the idea of e5 or Nc3-d5.}) ({If} 23... c6 {instead, then} 24. Qf2 ({or} 24. Nf5 {and if} d5 25. Qf2 Nd7{when Black is in difficulties}) 24... Nd7 25. e5 dxe5 26. Nf3 {, winningmaterial.}) 24. Qf1 {, with the threat of b4,} Ra5 25. Nb5 Qd8 {, White hassome advantage. --- Tarrasch's move was condemned by annotators, although itisn't clear that it is objectively worse. However, as we know, something thatis objectively certain can be less important in practice. --- As Dvoretskypointed out: "After 22 c4 the position is clear and established, and White'ssubsequent play is simpler. After 22 b4 the position is more complicated, moreunusual. Lasker was superior to his opponent in tactics, and was better atfinding his way in dynamic positions. In addition, he was significantlyyounger than Tarrasch, more robust and with greater stamina. It's clear whowas favoured by the further complication of the play."}) 22... Rc4 {"Although the rook is trapped, it is exerting constant pressure on c3, sothat it is now doing some work!" (Kasparov).} 23. g3 {Strengthening f4 withthe idea of Nb5.} ({On the other hand,} 23. Nb5 {immediately would allow goodcounterplay with} g5 {: for example,} 24. g3 gxf4 25. gxf4 Rexe4 $1 26. Rxe4Qg6+ 27. Qg3 Rxe4 28. Nxc7 Nc4 {.}) ({Another possibility was to first to playthe cautious} 23. a3 {, and later g3, since Black has no immediate threats.})23... Rd8 $6 ({Since} 23... c5 $2 {allows} 24. Nb5 {, Lasker defends d6, to beable to answer 24 Nb5 with 24...c6; at the same time he prepares ...c5.}) ({EXERCISE: Nevertheless, there was an alternative which was more consistentwith Black's previous play, but which would require tactical justification.What was the move? --- ANSWER: Black could have played} 23... a3 $1 {,preparing ...Na4. It's important that} 24. Nb5 {, can be met with} (24. Qd3 Qg6) 24... Na4 25. Re3 d5 $1 26. Rxd5 {and now according to Nunn,} Qb6 $1 {"is likely to lead to a draw by perpetual check after} 27. Kg2 c6 28. Re5Rxe5 29. Nd6 Rxc3 30. fxe5 Qxe3 31. Qxf7+ {". If, instead, 24 Qd3, tyingdown the b6-knight, Black can play 24...Qg6!, with the idea of ...d5, or ...c5,with sufficient counterplay.}) 24. Re3 $2 {Tarrasch is beginning to losecontrol of the position. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker punish White's move?} ({His move b4, evicting the black rook from the fourth rank and provoking theretreat of the e8-rook, could have been fully justified with} 24. e5 $1 {and after} dxe5 25. Rxe5 {, with the idea of Rde1, White's pieces would bebetter placed and he would have the advantage.}) ({There were other goodoptions, such as} 24. a3 {(Tarrasch)}) ({and} 24. Rd3 {(Makariev); we shallsoon see the difference this rook move makes, compared with 24 Re3. ---Tarrasch explained his decision thus: "Up until now I had conducted the gameirreproachably, but here I was seized by the unfortunate idea of a rooksacrifice, which in view of time-trouble I was unable to calculate properly."}) 24... c5 $1 {ANSWER: Now this counterblow works. After 24 Rd3 it would havebeen less good because White could then play 25 bxc5 Rxc5 26 Rb1, whereas now,with the rook on e3, Black would have 26...Nc4.} 25. Nb5 $2 {Tarrasch puts hisfaith in the combination he has prepared, but Lasker will refute itbrilliantly.} (25. Nc2 {was better;}) ({although the most precise move waspossibly} 25. bxc5 {(Teichmann): for example,} Rxc5 26. Rb1 Nc4 27. Rd3 b6 {, with equal chances.}) 25... cxb4 26. Rxd6 $2 {This combination, which is thekey to Tarrasch's previous play, is the decisive error.} ({Much more tenaciouswas} 26. Red3 {, and after} d5 27. e5 Qc6 28. Nd4 Qc5 29. cxb4 Rxb4 30. Kh1 {Black has an extra pawn and the slightly better position, but for now the pawnis unimportant and White can seek counterplay with Nf5, e6 or f5, followed bye6.}) 26... Rxd6 27. e5 {As a matter of fact, White's combination, although itlooks attractive, is unsound for more than one reason. It's possible that, asDvoretsky would suggest, the age difference influenced matters. Lasker hadmore energy than Tarrasch in this decisive phase following such a complexstruggle involving a good deal of physical and mental exhaustion. --- EXERCISE:What is the most precise way to refute White's idea? --- ANSWER:} Rxf4 $3 (27... Qf5 {was also good, the key being} 28. Nxd6 Qb1+ 29. Kg2 Rxc3 $1 {: for instance,} 30. Rxc3 bxc3 31. Qxc3 Qxa2+ 32. Kh3 Qb3 {, but thisspectacular counterblow is the best move.}) ({QUESTION: Spectacular, certainly,but what is surprising is that this combination is good. How did Lasker findit? --- ANSWER: Let him speak for himself: "To understand the motifs of thiscombination one must dig deep. White is attacking the queen and rook with hise-pawn; hence both are desperadoes: they look for checks, for an attack on thequeen, for captures, for strong threats regardless of the sacrifice involved;27...Rd1+ suggest itself, but that check is adequately guarded by the whitequeen. Here is the function motif holding the white queen. The white queenguards the f-pawn, which is also guarded by the g-pawn, and that g-pawn has toguard against the check of the black queen. Considering the functions of thewhite queen and the g-pawn, the white f-pawn is not defended at all. Hence 27...Rxf4 and everything else follows easily. Black wins". --- Let's expandthings a little. Clearly} 27... Rd1+ $2 28. Qxd1 Qc6 {doesn't work, since itleads to a draw after} 29. Qd8+ Kh7 30. e6 $1 fxe6 31. Qd3+ Kg8 ({or} 31... g632. Nd4) 32. Qd8+ Kh7 33. Qd3+ {. Meanwhile in the third book of 'Lasker'sManual of Chess', Lasker emphasizes that once the tactical motifs that canlead to a combination have been detected, it is important to find theappropriate move order, the one which allows the destruction of possibledefences in the most efficient manner.}) 28. gxf4 ({Equally futile is} 28. exf6Rxf3 29. Rxf3 Rd5 30. Nc7 Rd1+ {and the b-pawn wins for Black.}) 28... Qg6+ {As Lasker pointed out, this is the decisive check, enabled by the sacrifice ofthe rook. Now after 29 Rf1 the simplest is 29...Nc4, threatening ...Nd2+.} 29.Kh1 {This allows a decisive invasion.} Qb1+ 30. Kg2 Rd2+ (30... Rg6+ {was alsowinning. The rest is very easy.}) 31. Re2 Qxa2 32. Rxd2 Qxd2+ 33. Kg3 a3 34. e6Qe1+ 35. Kg4 Qxe6+ 36. f5 Qc4+ 37. Nd4 a2 38. Qd1 Nd5 39. Qa4 Nxc3 40. Qe8+ Kh741. Kh5 a1=Q {"In this game, as in many others, I dug my own grave" (Tarrasch). Moreover, several masters believe that this game had a seriouseffect on Tarrasch; that it undermined his confidence, although Tarraschblamed his poor result on the weather conditions. --- With Lasker leading by3-1 the match was transferred from Dusseldorf to Munich. If one takes asuperficial look at those opening four games, that is to say, taking intoconsideration only a few moments from each game, we can see that Tarraschshould not have lost the first game and should have won the second and thefourth; this means that of three and a half possible points, he had onlyscored one. Obviously that is only part of the story; you also have to includein the equation the difficulties that Lasker continually posed, whether hisposition was bad, dubious or equal, as well as his ability to counterattackand to capitalize on his opponent's mistakes. --- After the Dusseldorf stageLasker explained it thus: "The two players have gained some knowledge of theforce opposing them [...] In a match it is necessary to understand thepsychology of the opponent, in order to decide how to conduct the furtheroffensive. Almost sub-consciously, sometimes even involuntarily, each createsin his mind a plastic image of the opponent. This work is necessary, since theconcept of playing strength is a highly complex matter. --- "How theopponent conducts himself in joy and grief, in simple and complex situations,in dubious and safe positions, in the moments of origination and ruining ofhopes - all this forms his style of play. It consists of many differentcomponents. And therefore to compile the psychological resources of the twosides one has to examine a number of games, where the opponent finds himselfin a variety of situations [...] This knowledge is bound to come in useful inthe subsequent battle." --- In Munich the progress of the match did notchange; in the fifth game Lasker repeated the line of the Ruy Lopez he hadplayed in the third game, in which he was defeated, but this time achieving astrong attack very early, and he won decisively. The score now stood at 4-1 (wins). --- Lasker defended himself with the French Defence in the sixth game.He had a good position, but then he was outplayed by Tarrasch, who squandereda winning advantage in the ending; it finished a draw. Lasker scored anotherwin in the seventh game and at 5-1 the contest now seemed practically decided.This game had a strange finish; Tarrasch also chose the French Defence, but hemade a serious error as early as the eighth move. Lasker kept increasing hisadvantage and by move 56 he reached a rook ending with two extra connectedpassed pawns and Tarrasch having no pawns left. It was a trivial win, butTarrasch continued playing for another twenty moves, almost until mate. ---Lasker won the eleventh game to lead 6-1, but in the twelfth game Tarraschgained an advantage and managed to win after a long endgame. Then in thethirteenth game Tarrasch played the variation which bears his name against theQueen's Gambit. He achieved a good position, in an Isolated Queen's Pawnstructure, but Lasker outplayed him in the complications and with the scorestanding at 7-3 he needed just one more win to retain his title. ---Nonetheless, Tarrasch continued to fight and he gained a winning advantage inthe fourteenth game, but he didn't manage to convert it. "I won a piece, butnot the game", as Tarrasch said, and although he tried to win the endgame ofrook and bishop against rook, he had to concede the draw after 119 moves. ---In the fifteenth game Lasker was a pawn up in a rook ending, but was unable torealize it, while in the sixteenth game Tarrasch, in time trouble and with avery bad position, lost a piece without compensation. This was Lasker's eighthwin and with that he managed to win the match.} 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Saint Petersburg 1909"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Three months after retaining his title against Tarrasch, Lasker played ashort match against the Dutch master Abraham Speyer on the occasion of thethirtieth anniversary of the Amsterdamsch Schaakgenootschap. Lasker won 2½-½. Around the same time Lasker agreed to play a match for the world titleagainst the Viennese master Carl Schlechter in 1910 in Berlin. --- Lasker'sfirst serious commitment arrived very quickly. He took part in the St.Petersburg tournament, played between the 22nd of February and the 12th ofMarch 1909. There he came face to face with the new generation, led by AkibaRubinstein. The tournament became a race between Lasker and Rubinstein, whofinally shared first place with 14½/18, after taking turns to be leader andchaser. A long way behind came Spielmann and Duras with 11 points.} 1. Z0 {Lasker wrote a book about the tournament and annotated all the games. In thefirst round he had a winning advantage against Schlechter and in his bookLasker showed the various winning chances that he wasted. It was a draw. ---In the third round Lasker lost to Rubinstein in a model game which is one ofRubinstein's best. Rubinstein continued playing impeccably until the eighthround, when he was leading with 7/8, followed by Lasker with six points.Lasker managed to catch up with him in the ninth round by defeating Speijer,benefiting from Rubinstein's defeat by Dus-Khotimirsky. --- Let's look atthree of Lasker's games from this stage of the tournament.} *[Event "28: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1909.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Salwe, G"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C66"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "129"][EventDate "1909.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3 Nf6 6. O-O Be7 7. Bg5 {Lasker,who defended this position with Black innumerable times, introduces a new idea.} ({One might think that it is less precise than the more usual} 7. Re1 {, since the bishop has other development options, but of course Lasker wasaware of this and didn't consider it important: "This move appears strongerthan the usual 7 Re1", he commented in the tournament book.}) 7... exd4 {Black decides to release the central tension, arriving at a structure typicalof the Steinitz Defence.} ({It was also possible to delay the capture with} 7... O-O {, which, as we know, isn't possible after 7 Re1, since it loses apawn.}) 8. Nxd4 O-O 9. Bxc6 ({With} 9. Re1 Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bxb5 11. Nxb5 {we would have a transposition to Game 33.}) 9... bxc6 10. Qd3 Re8 {EXERCISE:Here we can see one of the reasons behind the move 7 Bg5. What do you thinkLasker played now? --- ANSWER:} 11. Rae1 {Since White is planning to expand onthe kingside with a timely f4, Lasker decides to keep his king's rook on f1,where it can be useful, and place the other rook on e1.} c5 {A thematic move,driving the knight from the centre to be able to play ...Bc6, putting pressureon the e4-pawn.} 12. Nb3 {The knight retreats from the centre to a somewhatpassive position, but, as Lasker generally preferred, the tension ismaintained.} ({He was unconvinced by} 12. Nf5 Bxf5 13. exf5 {, when after} h614. Bh4 {Black can play} c6 {, with the idea of ...d5, without fearing} 15.Bxf6 Bxf6 16. Rxe8+ Qxe8 17. Qxd6 {, since Black gains compensation with} Rb8 {: for example,} 18. Nd1 Bxb2 19. Qxc5 Qd7 {and the white pieces are verypassive.}) 12... Ng4 $6 {This simplification is typical of the whole line (sometimes it is achieved by playing...h6 and then answering the Bh4 with ...Nh7), although here it leads to a slightly inferior position.} ({Thissimplification is typical of the whole line (sometimes it is achieved byplaying...h6 and then answering the Bh4 with ...Nh7), although here it leadsto a slightly inferior position.} 12... Rb8 {in order to impede the knight byan attack on the b-pawn, White can play} 13. Bc1 {. White will always (in somecases, when Black has attempted attacks by ...Rb4 or ...Bc6, only after thenecessary defensive measures) succeed in establishing a centre by playingf2-f4".}) ({This leads on to the idea of playing} 12... h6 {first, so thatin the event of} 13. Bh4 {White would no longer have Bc1 available. After} a5 {, White wouldn't play} ({or in the event of the immediate} 13... Rb8 {Whitecould play} 14. f4) 14. a4 {, since that would lend more force to the} Rb8 {and ...Rb4 manoeuvre, but since b2 is not attacked, White would be able toplay Nd2-c4. Nevertheless, in the light of Lasker's comment above, it ispossible that he would have played 13 Bc1. In all cases the position isapproximately equal.}) 13. Bxe7 Rxe7 ({The alternative was} 13... Qxe7 {, although after} 14. f4 {the situation would be similar and the only movethat might change the situation is} Qh4 {. After} 15. h3 {, unlike the otherlines in which the knight is forced retreat to h6, here} Nf6 {is possible, butafter} 16. Qf3 {, preparing e5, it isn't clear that the queen is bettersituated on h4 than d8.}) 14. f4 {White's novelty has brought some success; hehas the advantage on the kingside.} Rb8 15. h3 {Lasker prefers to maintain theposition, forcing the knight to go to h6, after which White stands slightlybetter.} ({A good alternative was the immediate} 15. e5 {Instead, Black shoulddefend his attacked pawn with the rather artificial} Re6 {. Then after} ({since after} 15... dxe5 $6 16. h3 Nh6 17. Nxc5 {White has a big advantage.} (17. Z0)) 16. h3 Nh6 {there are various possibilities, such as} 17. Na5 {, when White's better development should give him the better chances in theevent of complications: for instance,} ({Nunn mentioned} 17. Re2 {with theplan of Rd1}) 17... c6 18. f5 Rxe5 19. Rxe5 dxe5 20. f6 $1 {, with a verystrong initiative.}) 15... Nh6 ({If} 15... Nf6 {then} 16. e5 {is very strong.})16. f5 {QUESTION: That's an unusual move, isn't it? It doesn't seem to matchWhite's earlier play, keeping all the options open. --- ANSWER: Lasker himselfwas critical of his move, but of course it wasn't a decision to be takenlightly. This is how he explained it: "White could have achieved more by 16g4 as he would then not have abandoned the squares e5 and g5 to his opponent.He was tempted into the actual continuation by the consideration that an entryremained for the rook via f4 and the g-file was open to the queen". ---Nevertheless, this kind of advance, which gains space on the kingside, givingup some squares to gain others, wasn't unusual in Lasker's practice. One ofhis most famous victories, against Capablanca in St. Petersburg 1914 (Game 38),was based precisely on the very same advance f4-f5, giving up control of thee5-square, and a move of which Capablanca disapproved.} f6 {The threat of 17f6 forces this move, after which it's not only White who has given up squares,since now Black loses control of e6.} 17. Nd5 Re8 18. c4 {Bolstering thedominating knight. Admittedly it can be evicted with ...c6, but only at thecost of leaving a backward pawn on d6. It's impossible to tell whether ...c6is a good move or not. Nunn commented: "It's not necessary for White to knowthe answer to the question himself, since Black is the one who has to resolveit. Therefore it is Black who has to use time on the clock thinking about it,while White can just wait and see what he decides", emphasizing thepragmatism that was characteristic of Lasker's play.} Nf7 {EXERCISE: Theposition presents no immediate opportunities, so the appropriate course ofaction is to engage in manoeuvres, a long series of which is about to begin.What did Lasker play here? -- ANSWER:} 19. Qc3 {This defends b2, in order toliberate the knight on b3.} Re5 {A move which prepares ...c6, to be followedby exerting pressure on the e4-pawn by doubling rooks on the e-file.} (19...Bc6 {was possibly better, seeking the best moment to eliminate the knightwithout weakening Black's pawn structure.}) 20. Nd2 c6 $6 {This was the idea,but as we'll soon see, the result isn't encouraging; both of Black's minorpieces lose some mobility, and the pressure on e4 is insufficient compensation.} 21. Nf4 Qb6 22. b3 Rbe8 {EXERCISE: Black has completed his idea, so how didLasker proceed? --- ANSWER:} 23. Qg3 {This move is also consistent with hisprevious play (16 f5), manoeuvring with threats against Black's castledposition. There is an immediate threat to win with 24 Nh5.} Kh8 24. Nh5 {It was difficult to decide from the many ways available to improve theposition.} ({It was difficult to decide from the many ways available toimprove the position.} 24. Nf3 $1 {, when} Rxe4 $2 (24... R5e7 {is thereforeessential, when White would still play} 25. Nh5) {, loses to} 25. Rxe4 Rxe4 26.Nh5 {.}) ({A third very good possibility is} 24. Qh4 $1 Nh6 25. Nh5 {,threatening 26 Nf3, and if 26...R5e7 27 Nxf6!, but Lasker wanted to reserve h4for his rook. --- It's possible that the move played is not as strong as thealternatives, but it does keep the advantage.}) 24... Rg8 25. Rf4 {This wasthe idea, and it's a dangerous one.} ({Once again,} 25. Qh4 {was worthconsidering.}) 25... Qd8 {The queen joins the defence, specifically to bolsterthe tactical weakness on f6. It also parries the threat of 26 Rg4?! which cannow be answered with 26...g6!.} 26. Nf3 {White continues to push Black'spieces back.} Re7 ({The counter-blow} 26... g5 $6 {weakens the structure andallows a later pawn break with h4.} {Lasker would have played} 27. Rg4 {and after} ({It does prevent} 27. Nxe5 $2 {though, as} Nxe5 28. Rff1 Be8 $1 {wins material.} (28... Z0)) 27... Ree8 {, instead of} 28. h4 ({it's better toplay} 28. Qf2 $1 {, threatening h4, or Rd1 followed by h4. This involves anexchange sacrifice, but after} Ne5 29. Rd1 $1 Nxg4 30. hxg4 Qe7 31. Qg3 $1 {White captures the d-pawn and the weakness of f6, created by 26...g5, isexposed}) 28... Nh6 {.}) 27. Rh4 Qe8 {QUESTION: I'm not understanding much ofwhat's going on here. I can see that the pieces are coming and going, butthere is nothing specific, is there? --- ANSWER: We're in a manoeuvre phase.Let's see what Lasker wrote about it: "Black is cramped, but a winningcontinuation is not easy to see. White must, therefore, try to carry disorderinto Black's ranks by new attacks, and afterwards return to take up the oldattack again." --- With reference to this game in particular, Nunn pointedout: "The key lesson here is that to manoeuvre successfully, you must lookfor ways to improve your position, even if the value of these improvementsisn't immediately obvious. At the same time, it's important to be alert to anytactical possibilities for the opponent, so that they can be nullified in goodtime. Manoeuvring is a difficult subject to teach due to its amorphous nature.Lasker's games provide an excellent basis for understanding manoeuvring, butif you have little patience then you are unlikely to make a success of it."}28. Qf2 {The manoeuvring phase continues. In addition to the pressure on thekingside, Lasker is going to attack the weakness created on d6 and keep alookout for an opportunity to make the sort of exchange sacrifice that we'vealready seen above.} ({The move order} 28. Nf4 {, threatening Ng6 mate, andonly after} Nh6 29. Qf2 {, would have reduced Black's options.}) 28... Rf8 ({More tenacious was} 28... Ng5 $1 29. Nd2 Re5 {, when White can't manoeuvrequite so easily. His best option then would be to play} 30. Rd1 $1 {, planning31 Nf4, followed by Nd3; there would be no need to fear} Nxe4 {, because after}({the weakness of Black's centre would also be noticeable after} 30... Rf8 31.Nf4 Kg8 32. Nd3 Nxe4 33. Nxe4 Rxe4 34. Nxc5) 31. Nxe4 Rxe4 32. Rxe4 Qxe4 33.Rxd6 Bxf5 34. Ng3 Qb1+ 35. Kh2 {, the c5-pawn will fall and White will remainwith the more active pieces and the better structure.}) 29. Qd2 Qb8 30. Kh1 {Another waiting move. For now there is not much difference between having theking on g1 or h1, but in the future this could be important.} ({Since theattack on Black's king has come to a halt, another idea would be to regroupwith} 30. Rg4) ({and} 30. Rd1 {, or the other way round.}) 30... Rfe8 $2 {A blunder, allowing White to exploit the fact that the black queen is a longway from the defence of the kingside.} 31. Rg4 {Lasker continues with his plan.Curiously his choice of 30 Kh1 rather than 30 Rg4 could have paid offimmediately after Black's blunder. --- EXERCISE: There was a much bettercontinuation. What was it?} ({ANSWER: The black rook no longer defends f6 andthis could have been exploited with} 31. Qc3 $1 {, threatening to demolishBlack's kingside defences with either 32 Nxg7 or 32 Nxf6:} {After} Ne5 {then after} ({for instance,} 31... Qb4 {would lose immediately to} 32. Nxf6 $1{.} (32. Z0)) 32. Nxe5 $1 {none of the possible recaptures is adequate. If}Rxe5 {, then White can strike quickly and decisively with} ({if} 32... fxe5) ({or} 32... dxe5 {instead, then} 33. Qg3 $1 {is decisive, with the idea of 34Qg6!, and the black queen can no longer help the defence by coming to e8,because of Black's last move, 30...Rfe8}) 33. Nxg7 $1 Kxg7 34. Qg3+ Kh8 35.Rxh7+ $1 Kxh7 36. Qg6+ Kh8 37. Qxf6+ Kh7 {, and now the arrival of the rook isdecisive:} 38. Re3 {, (with 39 Rg3 as the main threat)} Rf8 ({or} 38... Rg8 39.Qh4+ Kg7 40. Rg3+ Kf7 41. Qh7+ Kf6 42. Rxg8) 39. Qg6+ Kh8 40. f6 {and toprevent mate Black has to return all the extra material.}) 31... Rg8 32. Rd1 {Although White didn't play the best moves at various points and could havegained a bigger advantage, nevertheless the evaluation of the position hasn'tchanged. White has the advantage, because Black has no counterplay and musttry to cope with two weaknesses: the backward pawn on d6 and the insecurity ofhis king. --- We've already seen that one error on White's part will generallynot be fatal, but in contrast a mistake by Black will significantly worsen hisposition.} Qb4 {Black isn't content with a passive role and tries to createcounterplay with his queen, although we've already seen how dangerous it canbe for the defender's queen to stray too far from the kingside.} 33. Qf2 {Heading for g3 or h4.} Qc3 {Black continues with his idea of shifting thefocus of the struggle; while overprotecting f6, the black queen tries to reachc2, where it would annoy White by attacking e4 and the rook on d1.} 34. Qh4 $6{Once again Lasker fails to play a very strong continuation.} ({The immediate} 34. Qg3 $1 {was decisive; there is simply no good way to defend the weaknessesof g7, d6 and f6.} {Finally, the idea of} Qc2 ({If} 34... Nh6 {then} 35. Qxd6)({while if} 34... Ne5 {White can win with} 35. Nxf6 $1 Nxg4 36. Nxg8 {.} (36.Z0)) 35. Rg1 Ne5 36. Nxe5 fxe5 {fails to} 37. Nf6 Rd8 38. Nxh7 $1 ({or} 38. Qh4{. In all these lines we should notice the remoteness of the black queen fromthe defence.})) 34... Nh6 35. Rf4 ({The weakness of the e4-pawn prevents Whitefrom playing the more natural} 35. Rg3 {due to} Qc2 {and although after} 36.Re1 d5 ({or} 36... Qb2 {first, White has no advantage}) ({while} 36... Bxf5 $2{loses to} 37. Nxf6 $1 {.})) ({Nevertheless} 35. Rxd6 $1 {, one of the latentideas in the position, was better, with good compensation for the exchangeafter} Nxg4 36. hxg4 {, threatening 37 e5 or 37 g5.}) 35... Nf7 $6 ({Blackcontinues to wait, when instead he had the opportunity to push back the whitepieces a little more with} 35... Be8 {, when} 36. Nxf6 ({while after} 36. Ng3 {it's possible to defend d6 with} Rd7 {, and White is forced to think again})36... Qxf6 37. Qxf6 gxf6 38. Rxd6 {achieves nothing after} Rf8 {.}) 36. Kh2 {Compared to White's earlier king move, 30 Kh1, the usefulness of this one iseasier to imagine; in some lines it might be possible now to respond to anattack by the black queen on the d1-rook with a blow on the kingside, withoutthe rook falling with check.} Rge8 37. Qg3 {A good reply; White still has abig advantage and is putting pressure on the black position.} ({Nevertheless,} 37. Rg4 $1 {was equally good, if not better, although after} Rg8 (37... Ne5 {loses prosaically to} 38. Nxe5 Qxe5+ 39. Qg3 Qxg3+ 40. Nxg3 {, since thed-pawn falls}) 38. Nf4 Nh6 {it's essential to have seen the attractive winningshot} 39. Rg6 $1 {(threatening 40 Rxd6 as well as 40 Rxh6 gxh6 41 Qxh6), when}Nf7 ({while after} 39... Rxe4 40. Rxh6 gxh6 41. Ng6+ $1 Rxg6 42. Qxe4 {followed by Rxd6 is decisive}) {, loses to} 40. Rg3 Nh6 41. Rxd6 {.}) 37... Rg838. Rh4 ({Another possibility was} 38. Rg4 {and if} Nh6 {then} 39. Qxd6 $1 {is very strong. "The text move 38 Rh4 threatens 39 Nf4 Nh6 40 Rxd6" (Lasker), and should win.}) 38... g5 ({The continuation} 38... d5 {would failon account of} 39. cxd5 cxd5 40. Nf4 {.}) 39. fxg6 {This capture is sufficientfor a big advantage; the position of the black king is weakened, as is hispawn structure.} ({EXERCISE: Lasker thought that} 39. Rg4 {"was uselessbecause of} Be8 {". Can you prove that this was a pessimistic evaluation?--- ANSWER: Once again the exchange sacrifice} 40. Rxd6 $1 {is decisive, sinceafter} Nxd6 41. Qxd6 Rf7 {, the advance} (41... Bxh5 {isn't any better,because after} 42. Qxe7 Re8 43. Qxc5 Bxg4 44. hxg4 {White has two pawns forthe exchange and prospects of winning more pawns or attacking with e5 at anopportune moment; meanwhile the white king is safe and White is in fullcontrol of the situation}) 42. e5 fxe5 43. Nf6 {is winning.}) 39... Rxg6 40.Qf2 f5 {This move weakens the position even more, but there was no gooddefence for Black. According to Lasker, "If he allows White to move Rf4before this, he will ultimately lose the f-pawn." We should also mention 41Nf4 as a possibility.} 41. Nf4 ({Opening the game up with} 41. exf5 Bxf5 42.Rf4 {, followed by 43 Nh4, was also strong.}) 41... Rf6 {Lasker now chooses awinning method which isn't the quickest but is perfectly safe.} 42. Ne2 Qb2 43.Rd2 Qa1 44. Ng3 ({"By} 44. Ng3 {White threatens} Z0 45. exf5 Bxf5 46. Nxf5Rxf5 47. Rxh7+ {," commented Lasker; if} Kxh7 {then} 48. Qh4+ {.}) 44... Kg845. exf5 Bxf5 46. Nd4 ({"Decisive," wrote Lasker, and more elegant thanthe simple} 46. Nxf5 Rxf5 47. Qg3+ Kf8 ({or} 47... Kh8 48. Qg6) 48. Rxh7 {.})46... cxd4 47. Nxf5 Kf8 {This loses;} ({as does the counterattack} 47... Re148. Rf4 Rh1+ 49. Kg3 Qc3+ {, "which at least might have given White ascare", according to Nunn, who added "Although if he finds the continuation} 50. Kh4 (50. Rf3 $4 {loses to} Rxf5) 50... Kf8 51. Qxd4 Qxd4 52. Rdxd4 {then he still stands to win the endgame thanks to his extra pawn."}) 48. Qxd4{The endgame is very comfortable for White; he has an extra pawn, the moreactive pieces, and there are weaknesses in the enemy camp.} ({Lasker couldalso have tried to win in the middlegame with} 48. Rf4 {, and if} Re1 49. Ng3Rxf4 50. Qxf4 {, with threats of 51 Rf2 as well as taking on d4, with an extrapawn and the attack.}) 48... Qxd4 49. Nxd4 Ne5 50. Rh5 Ref7 51. c5 $1 {Theensuing simplification allows White's rooks to attack Black's weaknesses,while easily defending his own weak points on g2 and a2.} dxc5 52. Rxe5 cxd453. Rxd4 Rf2 54. Rd8+ Kg7 55. Ra5 Rc2 56. a3 ({Lasker defends his a-pawnagainst the threat of ...Rff2, attacking the g- and a- pawns, but} 56. Ra8 {was also strong, not fearing} Rff2 {, since then} 57. R5xa7+ Kh6 58. Rg8 Rxa259. Rc7 Rac2 60. Rgg7 {wins another pawn.}) 56... c5 ({Although} 56... Rb7 {was more tenacious and would have prolonged the game, the result would havebeen the same after} 57. b4 {, threatening Ra8. Then after} Kf6 {, one goodcontinuation would be the quiet move} 58. Rd4 {, preventing} Rg7 {due to} 59.Rd6+ {and 60 Rxa7+.}) 57. Rc8 Rb2 58. Rb5 Rff2 59. Rb7+ Kg6 (59... Rf7 {wouldn't have helped Black, since after} 60. Rxf7+ Kxf7 61. Rxc5 Rxb3 62. Rc7+{he would be two pawns down.}) 60. Rc6+ Rf6 61. Rxc5 Ra6 62. a4 Rf6 ({"If now} 62... Rxa4 {then} 63. Rc6+ Kg5 64. Rb5+ {followed by 65 bxa4" (Lasker).}) 63.Rc3 a6 64. Rg3+ Kh6 65. Rgg7 {"This example clearly demonstrates the idea ofprobing both enemy weaknesses, as Lasker first threatens Black's king, andthen switches to pressure against the d-pawn. When manoeuvring, it's alwaysgood to introduce a new element into the mix and the possibility of anexchange sacrifice on d6 was probably the factor that induced Salwe to lashout, fatally weakening his own position", commented Nunn. This longmanoeuvring battle lasted seven and a half hours.} 1-0[Event "29: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1909.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Tartakower, S"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "A22"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "106"][EventDate "1909.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. c4 e5 2. Nc3 Nf6 3. g3 Be7 {Although it wasn't a regular part of hisrepertoire, Lasker sometimes used the Old Indian Defence, to which this offersto transpose.} 4. Bg2 O-O 5. Nf3 d6 6. O-O Nbd7 7. d3 ({Tartakower prefers tostay within in the English Opening and rejects} 7. d4 {.}) 7... c6 8. Ne1 $6 {White has relaxed after Black's apparently passive play in the opening. ---EXERCISE: How did Lasker reply?} ({The idea seems be to play e4 and then f4,but if so it was better to start with} 8. e4 {.}) 8... Nb6 $1 {ANSWER: Takingadvantage of the fact that the e1-knight is no longer putting pressure on e5,Black prepares to play ...d5.} 9. e4 d5 10. cxd5 ({QUESTION: Is it good toexchange and leave oneself with a backward pawn? --- ANSWER: I'll letTartakower answer: "He allows a weakness to emerge at his d3 as he foreseesits speedy elimination. Otherwise} 10. exd5 cxd5 11. Qe2 {would be to thepoint".}) 10... cxd5 11. exd5 Nfxd5 12. Nxd5 Nxd5 13. d4 {This was the ideamentioned above, which Tartakower also approved of in his annotations afterthe game.} exd4 14. Qxd4 $6 {This is consistent with White's plan, but thequeen will remain exposed. It's true that it attacks the knight on d5, butBlack responds with a useful developing move and White, with his pieces backon the first few ranks, is unable to increase the pressure.} ({It was betterto play} 14. Nf3 {in order to recapture on d4 with the knight.}) 14... Be6 15.Nc2 {Releasing the f1-rook, without obstructing the work of the g2-bishop.} Bf616. Qe4 {EXERCISE: How should Black respond to the threat of 17 Rd1 - ?} Qa5 $2{Anticipating the pin is correct, also preparing the centralization of therooks, but Lasker makes an inaccuracy.} ({ANSWER: It was stronger to play} 16... Qb6 $1 {, which as well as preventing White's next move puts pressure onb2; Black would then have a small advantage.}) 17. Nd4 {Winning the bishoppair.} Bxd4 {It isn't pleasant to give up this strong bishop, but it'sunderstandable that Black doesn't want to be left with a weakness on e6 byallowing 18 Nxe6 fxe6.} 18. Qxd4 Rfd8 {Although White has gained the bishoppair in an open position, his advantage isn't great, due to the strongposition of Black's knight on d5, where it is well protected and in a wayprevents White's dark-squared bishop from taking up a dominating position.} 19.Bg5 $6 {QUESTION: How can this be dubious if it develops with gain of time byattacking the rook? --- ANSWER: The answer is similar to the one given after14 Qxd4. White also develops here with gain of time, but Black is able torespond with a useful move. The bishop is loose on g5 and as soon as itretreats from g5, Black will be able to double rooks on the central file.} ({It was better to play} 19. Bd2 {, followed by 20 Rfd1, preserving a smalladvantage. "Naturally I saw that after the simple move 19 Bd2 the game wouldbe perfectly level [...] but I felt that there was more than a draw in theposition," commented Tartakower.}) 19... Rd7 20. a3 {This prevents thethreat of 20...Nb4 and frees the rook from the defence of the a2-pawn; youmight think 'what more could you ask for?'. --- EXERCISE: How did Laskerdemonstrate that not all was positive for White?} ({From a practical point ofview it was very difficult to decide to prevent ...Nb4 by 'taking back themove' with the objectively superior} 20. Bd2 {, to be followed by Rfd1.}) 20...Nb6 $1 {ANSWER: The knight heads for c4 with gain of time; from there it willput pressure on b2. What's unusual about this case is that the knight willoccupy a very strong position without being supported by a pawn, becauseBlack's pieces are very well placed.} 21. Qh4 Nc4 {"This game is a splendiddemonstration of how it's sometimes possible to fight with a knight against abishop in an open position. The knight was already fairly well placed on d5,but has now arrived on the even more annoying square c4" (Nunn).} 22. b4 {A small concession, since now the knight cannot be evicted with b3 and theweakness of a3 will requires defence. Nevertheless, White still has his bishoppair so the position is about equal.} Qb6 23. Rfe1 {EXERCISE: How did Laskerreply?} ({"If} 23. Be4 h6 (23... f5 $2 24. Bxf5) 24. Bxh6 gxh6 25. Qxh6 f5 {and White's impetus is broken", commented Tartakower. We can see thatTartakower is seeking to exploit his bishop pair by means of an attack on theenemy kingside, taking advantage of the lack of defensive pieces on that wing.--- The rook is now putting pressure on the e6-bishop. Before starting anyaction, White can also interpolate Rac1, threatening Rxe6. White's play isambitious and logical, but its success depends on tactics, and if it doesn'twork, the control of the d-file might give Black the advantage.}) ({Thealternative was} 23. Rfd1 {, to which Black could reply with} Rxd1+ 24. Rxd1 f6{, followed by ...Rd8, with balanced play.}) 23... h6 {ANSWER: First of allBlack 'puts the question' to the bishop, preventing future sacrifices on h6under more dangerous circumstances. Tartakower commented: "An importantmeasure, which puts an end to an illusory attack."} 24. Be7 (24. Bxh6 $2 gxh625. Qxh6 {isn't dangerous due to} Qd4 {.}) ({The text move retains control ofthe d8-square. The alternative was} 24. Bf4 {, when} g5 $6 {, would be riskyin view of} ({instead, Black could keep the balance with} 24... Rad8) ({or} 24... Qd4) 25. Bxg5 hxg5 26. Qxg5+ Kf8 27. Qh6+ Kg8 28. Re4 Rd4 29. Rae1 {.})24... Qc7 $1 {First of all Lasker drives arrive the bishop.} 25. Bc5 Ne5 $1 ({Of course, not} 25... Rad8 $2 26. Rxe6 $1 {. The idea is to improve theposition of the knight, which was already well placed on c4, but will be evenbetter on d3; if the knight can be consolidated there it will be a verypowerful piece.}) 26. Be3 $6 {It can be difficult to perceive the moment whenone should abandon hopes of victory and be content with equality, because therisks outweigh the prospects of a win. It's easier to appreciate this afterthe game, naturally.} ({Here we still are far from the point of no return, butWhite could have ensured equality with the more modest} 26. Qf4 {, and after}Nd3 27. Qxc7 Rxc7 28. Reb1 ({or} 28. Red1 {he has no problems.})) ({Anothermore elegant way was with} 26. Qe4 Nd3 27. Red1 Rad8 28. Be7 $1 {(Nunn). ---At this point I think it's unnecessary to explain that if Lasker had beenWhite he would have not chosen one of these equalizing two moves either; hewould have continued trying to win.}) 26... Nd3 27. Red1 Bb3 {Forcing the rookto decide where it wants to go.} 28. Rf1 $6 {White's position is slightlyuncomfortable, but this retreat, giving up the d-file, gives Black a free hand.--- EXERCISE: What was the point of Lasker's idea of expelling the white rookwith 26...Bb3 - ?} ({It was better to play} 28. Rd2 {, and after} Qc3 29. Rf1 {Black is only slightly better; he should then choose between} Re8 (29... Ba4) ({or} 29... Bd5 {.})) 28... Bd5 $1 {ANSWER: "After much careful manoeuvring,he succeeds in eliminating the guardian of the white squares in the enemy camp,which White can ill afford, in view of his weakness at f3" (Tartakower). ---With the exchange of bishops, in the first place Black succeeds in eliminatingWhite's main trump, his bishop pair. He also weakens the position of the whiteking and, furthermore, gains access to a various light squares that he can useto manoeuvre with his major pieces.} 29. Bxd5 Rxd5 {"The occupation of the Qfile, the superiority of the Kt to the B, and the weakness of White's Q sidePs, give Black a decided superiority. Lasker's positional play in this game inunsurpassable" (Marco).} 30. Qe4 Qd7 ({Instead of doubling rooks on thed-file with} 30... Rad8 {, Lasker also wants to occupy the e-file with ...Re8,after which "All three open files are in Black's keeping" (Tartakower).})31. Ra2 $6 {Since there is no clear danger as yet, it would be more tenaciousto place a rook on d1, to contest the file, although then White would alwaysneed to calculate the blow...Nxb4.} ({After} 31. Rad1 {(or 31 Rfd1),} {Instead,Black could try} a5 {, before bringing his a8-rook into play with ...Rd8, or ...Re8 followed by ...Rd8; the same idea would also be good after 31 Rfd1,preserving some advantage for Black.} (31... Nxb4 {, wouldn't be advantageous,in view of} 32. Rxd5 Nxd5 33. Rd1 Rd8 34. Bxa7 {.} (34. Z0))) 31... Re8 32. Qg2({The queen has to swallow her pride and retreat a long way from herdominating central position, out of reach of a possible attack by the knightwith a gain of time, which is what would happen after} 32. Qf3 {.}) 32... b6 {Lasker rarely deviated from a promising and sound way of sacrificing material.}({In this case} 32... Ne5 {was interesting too, and if} 33. Bxa7 {then} Rd3 {would be strong. Lasker prefers to play in simple fashion, defending thea7-pawn with a move that restricts the movements of the bishop; this alsoguarantees that he can keep the advantage.}) 33. Rc2 ({White is no longer ableto contest the d-file:} 33. Rd2 $2) ({or} 33. Rd1 $2 {would allow} Nxb4 {.})33... Rd8 34. Qe4 {EXERCISE: Black dominates the d-file, which gives him adynamic advantage. He needs to manoeuvre to try to increase his advantage. Howdid Lasker proceed now? --- ANSWER:} b5 $1 {Securing the c4-square for theknight.} ({Another idea interesting was} 34... f5 {, but Lasker prefers not totake any radical measures on the kingside yet. Lasker's move also prevents Qc4and thus prepares a possible 35...f5, followed by ...f4.}) 35. f4 {Thisprevents the ...Ne5-c4 manoeuvre, but at the cost of weakening White on thekingside and in the centre. "A risky advance, but White is fighting forair" (Tartakower).} Re8 {Lasker immediately starts to exploit the newlyweakened e-file.} 36. Qf3 Qe6 37. Bf2 ({Not} 37. Bxa7 $2 {because of} Ne1 {.})37... Rd7 $2 {A natural move, but imprecise, since it allows White to almostequalize the game.} 38. Kg2 $2 {White lets the chance slip by. --- EXERCISE:What is the idea behind both 37...Rd7 and 37...Rd6 - ?} ({Black's advantagewould be insignificant after} 38. Qc6 $1 {; White's king will be a lot saferfollowing the forced exchange of queens, and after} Qxc6 39. Rxc6 {White isfine with 40 Rc3. --- Going back, we can see that Lasker's best move wouldhave been 37...Rd6!, with the same idea as in the game.}) 38... Qb3 {ANSWER:"Black stresses his opponent's weakness at b3. The harrying tactics employedby him from his 24th move onwards now give way to more concrete measures" (Tartakower).} ({It's a good move, although even better was} 38... Red8 {first, preventing White's next move.}) 39. Qc6 $1 Red8 40. Qc3 $2 {A passivedefence. The queen defends the pawns, but at the cost an important concession:it abandons its active position.} ({It was more tenacious to defend withoutyielding any ground with} 40. Re2 $1 {, when} Qxa3 {, could be answered with} ({instead, Black should play} 40... a6 {, but after, for instance,} 41. Bb6 Rd642. Re8+ Rxe8 43. Qxe8+ Kh7 44. Qe4+ g6 45. Bd4 {White is still resisting}) 41.Re8+ Rxe8 42. Qxd7 {and White's active queen guarantees that the balance canbe maintained.}) 40... Qd5+ {Here Black isn't forced to exchange queens;instead the queen commands the centre as Black's initiative becomes verystrong.} 41. Kg1 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker continue to make progress? ---ANSWER:} Qe4 $1 {The queen dominates the whole board, and now 42 Qc6? loses to42...Nxf2 43 Rfxf2 Rd1+. The queen also prepares a future attack on White'sweakened king position.} 42. Qb3 g5 $1 {Lasker wants to make a breach in thewhite king's defences and this advance serves that purpose.} ({In this regard} 42... h5 $1 {was also effective, with the idea of 43...h4 and ...h3, not tomention the sacrifice ...Nxf4 at an opportune moment, to allow an invasion byBlack's major pieces.}) 43. Qa2 {"The white f-pawn has the function ofguarding e5 and thus preventing ...Ne5" (Lasker).} ({Indeed,} 43. fxg5 {loses to} Ne5 44. Rc3 Rd3 {.}) 43... gxf4 {Black has obtained a winningposition; he has an extra pawn and the white king remains weak.} 44. Re2 Qg645. Qc2 {EXERCISE: There are several strong continuations here. What would youchoose? --- ANSWER:} Kh7 $1 {Vacating the g-file.} ({There were other ways towin, such as} 45... f3 $1 46. Re3 Qh5 {, with the idea of 47...Ne5, followedby 48...Qh3 or 48...Nxf2 and ...Rd1+.}) (45... Qh5) ({and even} 45... h5 {were also good.}) 46. Qc3 Rg8 {The white position is indefensible. Theremaining moves were superfluous.} 47. Kh1 Qh5 48. Rd2 fxg3 49. Bxg3 Rxg3 50.Qc6 Ne5 51. Qe4+ Kg8 52. Rdf2 Rg5 53. Rc2 Rd1 0-1[Event "30: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1909.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Vidmar, M"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C62"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "47"][EventDate "1909.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{After drawing with Bernstein in the tenth round Lasker fell back into secondplace, but after scoring five consecutive wins, in rounds 11 to 15, and withthe favourable assistance of Rubinstein's bye, after 15 rounds Lasker (whowould have a bye in the penultimate round) became the tournament leader with12½/15, followed by Rubinstein with 11/14. --- Let's see one example ofLasker's play in those rounds.} 1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6 4. d4 Bd7 5. Nc3exd4 6. Nxd4 g6 {QUESTION: This is not very common, is it? What's the idea?--- ANSWER: At the time of the game this approach was fairly new, but sincethen it has been played many times, even by Keres and Geller on occasion. ---Let's see what Lasker wrote about it: "A new attempt to shorten themanoeuvre ...Bf8-e7-f8, ...g7-g6 and ...Bg7, by the two apparently uselessmoves. But now White takes up a totally different formation, and takesadvantage of the weakness of Black's f6- and h6-squares in a more decisive waythan would be possible in the line of play mentioned".} 7. Be3 {Thedifferent formation to which Lasker refers is based on castling on thequeenside, instead of on the kingside, which was usual against ...Nf6 and ...Be7. --- From the practical point of view Lasker's plan is more unpleasant forBlack, since with the kings castled on opposite flanks it is likely that bothsides will launch attacks directed at the enemy king and thus the value ofeach move becomes greater. Nevertheless, 7 Be3 isn't, of course, objectivelybetter than castling short.} Bg7 8. Qd2 Nf6 ({"If} 8... Nge7 {the whiteh-pawn advances at once} 9. h4 {then to h5" (Lasker). The text move obligesWhite to move f3 to prevent ...Ng4, but 9 f3 isn't a waste of time, since itsupports a later g4. The similarities with the Dragon variation of theSicilian Defence are obvious.}) 9. f3 O-O 10. O-O-O a6 {QUESTION: If the kingsare castled on opposite wings, isn't it essential to speed up the attack? Thisdoesn't seem very aggressive to me. --- ANSWER: Don't forget that this was oneof the first games with this line. With 10...a6 Black wants to advance hisqueenside pawns after first driving away the bishop.} ({Later, games wereplayed in which the attack was launched in a way that left White with feweroptions, i.e.} 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 {There's another possibility here, onewhich is both more materialistic and more popular: the combination} Nxe4 ({and now} 11... c6 {, with the same idea as in the game. After} 12. Be2 {it's possible to play} b5 {, without fearing} 13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxd6 {due to}Qg5+ 15. f4 Qxg2 16. Qxd7 b4 {.} (16... Z0)) {Something similar occurs after}12. Nxe4 ({when} 12. fxe4 {is answered with} Bxd4 13. Qxd4 Bxb5 {, the pointbeing that if} 14. Nxb5 {, then Black regains the piece with} ({it is possibleto play more aggressively with} 14. Nd5 f6 15. h4 {, when White's compensationfor the pawn is insufficient for an advantage}) 14... Qg5+ {.}) 12... Bxb5 13.Bxg7 (13. Qc3 {has also been played}) 13... Kxg7 14. h4 {, and this seems abit more promising for White.}) 11. Be2 {QUESTION: The bishop simply retreats?Is this best? Neither side seems in a hurry to attack. --- ANSWER: White optsto keep pieces on the board and refrains from the exchange on c6, which wouldopen the b-file.} ({Nevertheless, it's a matter of weighing up whether thetime gained by playing} 11. Bxc6 bxc6 {and now} 12. Bh6 {, followed by h4,isn't more important. It's possible that objectively this is more precise. ---Lasker, with a decision that by now will come as no surprise, prefers to giveBlack more possibilities.}) 11... b5 12. h4 {Given your earlier grumbles, thismove will surely be more to your liking.} Ne5 $6 ({Since} 12... b4 13. Nd5 {isn't very attractive, Black wants to attack with his pawns by playing ...c5.})({Many years later, in the Sicilian Dragon, preventing h5 by playing} 12... h5{ceased to be regarded as heretical. Here too it would be a good choice.}) ({Another useful move is} 12... Re8 {After a move such as} 13. g4 {now} ({and, with the knight still on c6,} 13. Bh6 $4 {is impossible due to} Nxd4 14.Bxg7 Nxe2+ {and wins.} (14... Z0)) 13... b4 {is more attractive, since} 14. Nd5$2 {is bad because of} Nxd5 15. Nxc6 (15. exd5 $2 {loses a piece after takingtwice on d4}) 15... Bxc6 16. exd5 Bb5 {, and Black takes over the initiative.In this line too the usefulness of 12...Re8 is evident.}) 13. Bh6 {Now Whiteis able to eliminate the vital defender of Black's castled position. This isthe most natural move and it leaves Black with the dilemma of how to seekcounterplay. --- EXERCISE: White's last few moves were natural, exchanging thedefender's bishop combined with the plan to open the h-file. On the other hand,how Black should respond is less obvious. What would you play here?} ({Therewere alternatives, such as} 13. Bg5 $1 {, to bolster the threat of 14 h5, andthis seems very dangerous.}) ({It was also possible to offer the typicalsacrifice to open the h-file with} 13. h5 Nxh5 {and now} 14. Bh6 {, but thisisn't so clear.}) 13... Nc4 $2 {ANSWER: Black achieves very little for theconsumption of two tempi. It's true that the b-file becomes open, but thiswill be prove to be less important; White's attack will be quicker.} ({It'spossible that Black's original idea here was, as we indicated above, to play ...c5, and then ...c4, opening lines quickly. However,} 13... c5 {is answered with} 14. Bxg7 $1 {, when} cxd4 $2 ({it's better to play} 14... Kxg7 {, but after}15. Nb3 {the black pawns have lost their venom and the threat of 16 Qxd6 haltsthe black attack}) 15. Bxf6 dxc3 {fails to} 16. Qxd6 {.}) ({Despite theobvious risk of bringing the white queen to an aggressive position, the bestmove here was} 13... Bxh6 $1 {. With the white queen no longer on the d-file,Black, after} 14. Qxh6 {, can now play} c5 15. Nb3 b4 {, and if} 16. Nd5 {he has} Bb5 $1 {, gaining counterplay.} {the sacrifice} 17. h5 {can also bedeclined with} ({Let's analyze this a bit deeper: in the event of} 17. Bxb5axb5 18. h5 {Black has the defence} Ra7 $1 {;} (18... Z0)) 17... Ra7 {;} ({but it's not clear whether it would be worse to accept the piece with} 17...Bxe2 {: for example,} 18. hxg6 fxg6 19. Nxf6+ Rxf6 20. Qxh7+ Kf8 21. Qb7 {and here Black has the effective defence} Nf7 {.})) 14. Bxc4 bxc4 15. h5 c6 {There is nothing else; Black controls d5 and dreams of a counterattack basedon ...Qb6 and ...Rb8, admittedly at the cost of weakening d6. White's attackis further advanced; he is ready to open the h-file and exchange the g7-bishop.} ({Of course, if the h-file can be opened, that's the priority. Laskercommented: "If} 15... Nxh5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. g4 Nf6 18. Qh6+ Kg8 19. Nd5 ({or, stronger still} 19. g5 Nh5 20. Nd5 {and 21 Rxh5". The black positioncollapses.})) 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. hxg6 fxg6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker strike adecisive blow? --- ANSWER:} 18. Nde2 $1 ({There were several attractive moves,such as} 18. e5 dxe5 19. Ne6+ Bxe6 20. Qh6+ {, winning the queen for rook,piece and pawn, Lasker chooses something simpler, beginning with the win of apawn.}) 18... Rf7 19. Qxd6 Qb6 {White's position is winning and there is manygood continuations. Lasker chooses one of the more attractive plans andcarries it out accurately.} 20. Qd4 {First of all Lasker centralizes his queenand pins the f6-knight, relying on the fact that Black can't really exchangethe queens.} c5 21. Nd5 $1 {Lasker sticks to his plan.} ({Of course,} 21. Qxc4{was possible, but he wants to exploit the situation of the black king and thepin on the knight.}) 21... Qb7 22. Qc3 {Thus White has managed to keep hisqueen on the long diagonal; one of his threats now is 23 Nxf6 Rxf6 24 Rxh7+.}Raf8 23. Nxf6 Rxf6 24. Rd6 ({After} 24. Rd6 Z0 {, "Black resigned, as} 25.Rxf6 {was threatened, followed by} Rxf6 26. Rxh7+ ({and also} 26. e5 Re6 27.Nf4 {" (Lasker).})) (24. Z0 {In the sixteenth round Lasker's second defeatoccurred, against Dus-Khotimirsky; in the tournament book Lasker praised hisopponent's play. Next came a win against Cohn and Lasker then had the bye inthe eighteenth and penultimate round. At the start of the final roundRubinstein was in first place with 14/17, with Lasker right behind him with13½. In the final round Rubinstein drew with Tartakower, while Lasker managedto defeat Teichmann and was thus able to share first place.}) 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1909 Match against Janowski"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker and Janowski played a short four-game match in May 1909. It finished2-2 (+2, -2), which perhaps gave a false impression of the level of each ofthem. --- This led to a ten-game match, which took place in Paris between the19th of October and the l9th of November 1909. This wasn't a match for theworld title (unlike the one they would later contest in November 1910). The1909 match was regarded by Lasker as preparation for his official encounterwith Schlechter, which was to be played in January 1910. The result was adecisive victory for Lasker by 8-2 (+7 -1 =2).} 1. Z0 {After drawing the firstgame, Lasker won the next four. Janowski scored his only win in the sixth game,and of the remaining four he drew only the eighth. --- Let's take a look attwo games from this match (see the following game).} *[Event "31: Paris (match)"][Site "?"][Date "1909.??.??"][Round "2"][White "Janowski, D"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "C49"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "64"][EventDate "1909.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 d6 7. Bg5 {The FourKnights Game with 4 Bb5 was very popular a century ago. It was soon displacedby more open systems, and also Black began to avoid it by playing the PetroffDefence.} Bxc3 {This eliminates the threat of 8 Nd5, doubling Black's f-pawns.On the other hand, it concedes the bishop pair, so it is likely that Whitewill seek to open the game under favourable conditions.} 8. bxc3 Ne7 ({Themost usual move here is} 8... Qe7 {, one of the ideas of which is to solve theproblem of the pin by the g5-bishop by means of the manoeuvre ...Nd8-e6. ---The text move is less common, but is a good alternative.}) 9. Bc4 {QUESTION: Idon't know much about this line, but I'm surprised that instead of 9 Bc4,White didn't grasp the opportunity to weaken the position of the black kingwith 9 Bxf6. Didn't Black play 7...Bxc3 precisely to prevent White fromdoubling the f-pawns with 8 Nd5 - ? Black's doubled pawns look more seriousthan White's on the queenside, so why didn't White exchange on f6? --- ANSWER:Generally it is as you say: doubling the pawns on f6 when the black king iscastled kingside is usually a serious matter, but not in this case, becauseWhite is unable to attack Black's castled position quickly. White's pieces area long way from the kingside and, unlike with the threat of 8 Nd5, White wouldhave had to give up his bishop to double the f-pawns. Black would seek to playa quick ...f5 to eliminate the doubled pawns and allow more of his pieces tocome over to the kingside.} ({After, for instance,} 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nh4 Ng6 {White can prevent ...f5 with} 11. Nf5 {, but after} Bxf5 ({in simultaneousgames Lasker continued instead with} 11... Kh8 {, followed by ...Rg8, whichkeeps the position more complicated}) 12. exf5 Ne7 {Black has no problems.}) ({However, you're right in criticizing 9 Bc4. Lasker himself commented thatWhite should have played} 9. Nh4 {, with the idea of continuing with f4.}) 9...Ng6 ({In their short match played a few months before, Lasker stood slightlyworse in D.Janowski-Em.Lasker, 3rd matchgame, Paris 1909, after} 9... Be6 10.Bb3 Bxb3 11. axb3 Nd7 12. d4 f6 13. Be3 Ng6 14. Qd3 Kh8 15. Nd2 a6 16. f4 {. Later the game became equal, but ended in victory for Janowski.}) 10. Nh4 Nf4{Lasker awarded an exclamation mark to this move, previously played byPillsbury.} ({After} 10... Nf4 {, Black plans to play} 11. Z0 h6 {, forcingthe g5-bishop to commit itself; then} ({instead,} 11... Ne6 {is also playable})12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Ng6 $2 {would fail to} d5 $1 {, winning material.}) 11. Bxf4$6 {A strange decision; Janowski exchanges on f4 without waiting for ...h6.} ({Lasker suggested} 11. Bb3 {"since thus the advance of the black d-pawn isdeprived of some of its force"; this move also prevents} h6 $2 {, because now} 12. Bxf4 exf4 13. Ng6 {works, followed by 14 Nxf4. Black could play 11...Ne6,perhaps preceded by 10...a5, seeking to provoke 12 a4.}) 11... exf4 12. Nf3 {EXERCISE (simple): The knight was doing nothing on h4 and White must defendagainst the threat of 12...Nxe4, but this move has a drawback. What is it? ---ANSWER:} Bg4 {Of course. The pin is very unpleasant.} 13. h3 {Lasker wrote ofthis move: "An error, which weakens the King's side very much".} ({Reinfeld and Fine commented "If White intends to play Qd2, it would be wellto do so directly, as the text-move induces a critical weakness in his game".That was what Janowski played in the fourth game of the match and after} 13.Qd2 Bxf3 14. gxf3 Nh5 15. Kh1 Kh8 16. Rg1 Qd7 17. Rg4 Rae8 18. Rag1 {Laskergained a slight advantage with} f5 $1 19. Rg5 g6 {and eventually won.}) 13...Bh5 14. Rb1 b6 15. Qd2 ({The doubled pawn on f4 isn't a weakness and evenrestricts White's mobility, such that} 15. g4 fxg3 16. fxg3 {was worthconsideration. Lasker comments that the continuation would have been "} d5 $117. exd5 Nxd5 18. Qd2 f6 {soon to be followed by ...Bf7 and Black has the bestof it both for Middle and End-game." --- Lasker based his evaluation onWhite having the worse pawn structure and a weak king. With the text move,Janowski seeks to build up some force on the g-file.}) 15... Bxf3 16. gxf3 Nh5{A curious position. White has doubled pawns on both wings and Black only onone. Unlike other such positions, the white pawns aren't very weak at themoment, but nevertheless mean that Black has a slight advantage. --- QUESTION:Why does Black have even a slight advantage here? White's doubled pawnscontrol the centre and can advance, seeking to open the position. Also White'sbishop looks like it will strongly support action by the white rooks along theg-file. I can't see how Black can create any danger. --- ANSWER: Euwe gavethis explanation: "The Black doubled pawn blocks the White one, and producessuch an uncomfortable pressure that White's counteradvantages - centralmajority and open g-file - carry very little weight".} 17. Kh2 {Whitecontinues with the natural plan, but it will be seen that Euwe's evaluation iscorrect. Nunn suggested another plan, one which would be very difficult tocome up with over the board, since it would involve renouncing any attackingaspirations and instead focusing on defence. It is very difficult to thinkabout defence when the opponent is not threatening anything.} ({One of thedifficulties of mobilizing the white centre with c4 and d4, seeking to openlines, is that Black can play ...c5 at an opportune moment, so Nunn suggested} 17. Bd5 {, followed by Bc6, and only then playing d4 and c4. Admittedly on c6the bishop would not assist the attack, but it would be very difficult toevict from c6 and its main role would be to prevent Black from playing ...c5to blockade the white centre. That move and the associated plan could havebeen tried both here and over the next few moves.}) 17... Qf6 18. Rg1 Rae8 19.d4 {Tarrasch commented on this position: "White has an imposing centre, butthere is absolutely nothing to be done with it; the f4-pawn cripples hisgame". --- EXERCISE: Although Tarrasch's comment is accurate, as we saidearlier, Black is unable to do anything active as yet and instead must preparefor activity in the future, while also thinking about defence. What did Laskerplay here to combine those two ideas? --- ANSWER:} Kh8 {The king moves awayfrom the dangerous g-file and, as in the fourth game of the match, this is thefirst step towards being able to play ...f5 in the future.} 20. Rb5 {Whitecontinues with his idea and tries to implement it with a gain of time byattacking the h5-knight.} Qh6 ({QUESTION: I understand that Black is fine andprepared to parry the coming attack, but why not prevent it with} 20... c5 {, so as not to allow the rook to swing over to the kingside? --- ANSWER:Because playing ...c5 before White has played c4, weakening d4, doesn't reallyput pressure on d4 or close the position. White could then change plan andswitch his focus to the queenside by playing a4-a5, when the position wouldcomplicate to White's benefit.}) 21. Rbg5 f6 22. R5g4 {Reinfeld and Fine hadcommented several moves ago that after doubling rooks on the g-file Whitewould have achieved all he could, "while Black's game contains stores ofpotential energy", as Lasker now demonstrates.} g6 $1 {With the now familiarrecipe, one of flexibility, increasing the prospects of Black's pieces andmaintaining the tension until he is able to open the game under idealconditions. Black prepares a future ...Ng7-e6 (at a point when this wouldn'tlose the f4-pawn, naturally), and also the centralization of the queen via g7.}({Lasker commented: "Stronger than} 22... f5 {, whereupon White on the openfile would get counter-action. Black's advantage consists in White's inabilityof his own accord, to open lines; Black's task is therefore to select the mostfavourable time and opportunity for forcing the lines open." After 22...f5 apossible continuation is} 23. exf5 {followed by 24 Re1.}) 23. Bd3 Re7 {"Atypical Lasker manoeuvring move," commented Nunn. There is no clear way tomake progress yet, so Lasker 'passes' with a neutral move, and goes into acrouch.} 24. c4 $2 {EXERCISE: A mistake, as Lasker will demonstrate. Unlikethe world champion, Janowski lacks the patience to mark time with some neutralmove or other, and instead he changes the pawn structure. How did Laskerpunish him? --- ANSWER:} Ng7 $1 {The tactics help Black to improve his pieces.}25. c3 ({White is unable to capture on f4 with either piece, since} 25. Rxf4 {loses material after} Ne6 ({or} 25... Nh5 {;})) ({while} 25. Qxf4 Qxf4+ 26.Rxf4 Ne6 {leaves White with a disastrous structure.}) ({Playing} 25. d5 {would prevent ...Ne6, but White's structure would lose all mobility.}) 25...Ne6 {The knight is much better placed on e6 than h5; the threat is now 26...Ng5.} 26. Bf1 {By defending h3 White prevents 26...Ng5 due to 27 Qxf4.} f5 $1 {Now the moment to become active has arrived, taking advantage of the bishophaving left d3.} 27. R4g2 ({The alternative was to open up his king's defenceswith} 27. exf5 {,} {However,} gxf5 {seems even better, relying on theinitiative against the weak white king. After} ({when one possibility is tomaintain the structure by playing} 27... Rxf5 {, with ideas of ...Rh5 as wellas ...Ng5, or, after tying down White's forces, playing ...c5, followed by ...Qg7, hitting d4.} 28. Z0 (28. Z0)) 28. R4g2 {, while the opening of the g-filehas been of no benefit to White, it has given Black greater room for manoeuvrewith his major pieces and he can play} Ref7 {(the start of a transfer to theh-file), and then if} 29. c5 {, seeking counterplay} (29. Kh1 {transposes})29... Rf6 {(threatening mate in two moves starting with 30...Qxh3+!)} 30. Kh1 {(preventing 30...Qxh3+?? due to 31 Rh2 Qxf3+ 31 Bg2 Qg4 32 Bd5 and the blackqueen is trapped)} bxc5 ({perhaps slightly better than} 30... dxc5 {), Blackhas the advantage.})) 27... Rf6 {Now the idea is to continue with 28...g5,threatening the aforementioned mate with 29...Qxh3+.} 28. Bd3 $4 {Once againWhite doesn't want to wait and instead he seeks to counter-attack with 29 exf5,trying to make use of his doubled rooks, since Black couldn't reply with 29...gxf5?? due to the mate on g8. However, the bishop was needed on f1 for defence,as we'll see.} ({White needed to keep waiting with a move such as} 28. Qd3 {, although the defensive task is not pleasant (even less so after 28 Qc2).Black can exploit the absence of the white queen from the c1-h6 diagonal byplaying} fxe4 29. fxe4 f3 {and after} 30. Rg3 Ref7 {he plans to play 31...c5or first 31...Qf4, intending ...Ng5 or ...c5, and White is very passive,suffering from the pressure against his centre. --- Against 28 Qc2 Nunn givesother possibilities, but his final comment is instructive and also applicableto the line given above: "It's interesting to note how important the centreis, even though a lot of the play takes place on the kingside. White's bishopand rooks are tangled up and cut off from the other side of the board, soBlack's correct strategy is to exploit the absence of these pieces by playingin another part of the board."}) 28... g5 {Of course. "At this point thethreat is 29...Qxh3+" (Lasker). One is inevitably reminded of the game Y.Averbakh-A.Kotov, Zürich 1953.} 29. Rh1 {EXERCISE: Lasker played thestrongest move now. What is it?} ({Now} 29. Kh1 {doesn't work, because withoutthe bishop on f1 the black queen can't be trapped. A possible continuation is}Qxh3+ 30. Rh2 Qxf3+ 31. Rgg2 {and White is left with no threats and two pawnsdown; Black can then play} g4 ({or even} 31... fxe4 32. Be2 e3 {.})) 29... g4 {ANSWER!} ({This frees g5 for the knight and is quicker than} 29... Qxh3+ 30.Kg1 Qxf3 31. exf5 Ng7 {, followed by ...Nxf5, which also wins.}) 30. Be2 Ng5 {"The final break up of White" (Lasker).} 31. fxg4 f3 32. Rg3 fxe2 0-1[Event "32: Paris (match)"][Site "?"][Date "1909.??.??"][Round "10"][White "Janowski, D"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "B34"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "58"][EventDate "1909.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 c5 ({On most occasions Lasker played} 1... e5 {, but surprisingly hissecond choice was the Sicilian, a defence which had not been much explored inhis day.}) 2. Nf3 Nc6 {This was his favourite move, keeping open the optionsof playing the Sicilian Dragon or an ...e6 system, but he also played othervariations which are now popular, such as the Sveshnikov variation.} 3. Nc3 g6{Although he played other lines, the Accelerated Dragon was Lasker's mostfrequent selection.} 4. d4 cxd4 5. Nxd4 Bg7 6. Be3 Nf6 7. Be2 ({The main lineat present is} 7. Bc4 {. The text move is less challenging for Black, but ofcourse this was almost unexplored territory in those days.}) 7... O-O 8. Qd2 {EXERCISE: White has played natural developing moves, with the plan of castlingqueenside, but this isn't the most ambitious move here. Why? --- ANSWER:} d5 {One difference between the Accelerated Dragon and the normal Dragon with 2...d6 is that Black can play ...d5 in one move and sometimes, as in this case,this provides good play.} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 ({White rejects} 10. Nxc6 bxc6{, because then there is no better move than} 11. Nxd5 {, giving Black acentral pawn majority. With the text move he wants to gain a tempo on thequeen.}) 10... Qxd5 11. Bf3 {EXERCISE: Where do you think Lasker moved hisqueen?} ({It's uncomfortable to play} 11. Nxc6 Qxc6 {, when g2 and b2 are bothattacked, and after} 12. Bf3 {Black can play} Qc7 ({or} 12... Qb5) {If, on theother hand, White plays} 13. c3 {then follows} ({when} 13. O-O-O {would giveBlack a clear target and allow him to put pressure on White's king with} Bf5 {.} (13... Z0)) 13... Rd8 {, when White is forced to play the sub-optimal} 14.Qc1 ({since} 14. Qe2 $2 {loses to} Bxc3+ {.})) 11... Qc4 {ANSWER: The mostunpleasant, move for White to face, since it prevents kingside castling, whileafter 12 Be2 Black has the option to return to d5, repeating the position.Moreover, it would be unpleasant psychologically for Janowski to acquiesce toa draw in this last game without a fight, with the match already lost.} 12. b3$2 {Courageous, but objectively a mistake. White wants to be able to play Be2without the black queen being able to move to d5, but this comes at the costof weakening the white pawn structure. Lasker will demonstrate that this moveisn't an improvement on 12 Be2.} ({It's surprising that after so few moves,and without having committed any error, White's best course actually is toseek a draw. Admittedly Lasker wasn't forced to repeat moves; after} 12. Be2Qd5 13. Bf3 {he could vary with} Qe5 {, which is good, since if} 14. Nxc6 bxc615. c3 {then} Ba6 {is unpleasant for White.}) 12... Qa6 13. Be2 {This was theidea, but now the black queen can move to an even better square. It wasdifficult to find a satisfactory solution for White; it isn't possible tocastle and Black is planning to play 13...Rd8.} ({The alternatives are alldepressing though:} 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Rc1 ({or} 14. Rd1 {would mean giving upthe a2-pawn;})) ({while} 13. c3 Rd8 {also loses a pawn after} 14. Qe2 Nxd4 {,}({or perhaps even better} 14... Ne5 {.})) 13... Qa3 {Still preventing castling.} 14. c3 ({After} 14. O-O {Black wins a piece by capturing on d4 and thenplaying ...Rd8, or playing the immediate} Rd8 15. c3 e5 {.}) 14... Rd8 15. Rd1$6 {EXERCISE (easy): There are several good moves now. Lasker chose thestrongest, but what is it?} ({This prevents} 15. O-O $2 {since after} e5 16.Nb5 Rxd2 {the bishop on e2 is loose.}) ({The white position was unpleasantafter either} 15. Qc1 Nxd4 16. Bxd4 Qxc1+ 17. Rxc1 Bxd4 {, when Black wins apawn,}) ({or} 15. f4 Bf5 16. O-O Rac8 {and the white position is full ofweaknesses, but perhaps this, while not offering much hope, was the mosttenacious.}) 15... e5 {ANSWER: This advance doesn't win a piece now, but Blackwill gain a pawn and his pieces will remain well placed.} 16. Nb5 Rxd2 17. Nxa3Rxa2 18. Nb5 Bf5 {There were several attractive moves in addition to the textmove, which threatens 19...Bc2.} ({Also strong was} 18... e4 {, increasing thescope of the g7-bishop and freeing e5 for the knight.}) ({There was also} 18...a6 {, driving the knight from the defence of c3 and allowing 19...Be6 in theevent of 19 Nd6.}) 19. Bc4 Na5 {Driving the bishop off the f1-a6 diagonal.} 20.Bd5 Bc2 21. O-O {Janowski surrenders the exchange.} ({If} 21. Rc1 {Black wouldhave a pleasant choice between} Nxb3 {,} (21... Rd8) ({and the very strong} 21... Bd3 {.})) (21. b4 Nb3 22. Rd2 Rd8 $1 {was equally hopeless. AlthoughWhite can win material, he will have to give up more to be able to bring hish1-rook into play: for instance,} 23. Rxc2 Rxc2 24. Bxb3 Rb2 25. Bd1 a6 26. Na3e4 27. O-O Bxc3 {, and White is almost paralyzed.}) 21... Bxd1 22. Rxd1 {EXERCISE: Black has a winning position and there are a number of good andreasonable continuations, but it is best to conclude the game as soon aspossible. Lasker made the strongest move possible - what was it? --- ANSWER:}Rd8 $1 {Black exploits the weakness of White's back rank to bring his lastpiece into play. The threat is 23...Rxd5.} 23. g3 Nc6 24. c4 Nd4 {Simplifying,in order to deprive White of any chance to complicate the issue.} ({Objectively there was nothing wrong with} 24... Rd7 {, with the idea of 25...Nb4, but it's a matter of choice.}) 25. Nc3 ({The endgame a clear exchangedown arising after} 25. Nxd4 exd4 26. Bxd4 Bxd4 27. Rxd4 Kg7 {offered no hope,but of course the text move isn't any better.}) 25... Rb2 {Black wins theb3-pawn and the rest is very simple.} 26. Ne4 Rxb3 27. Bg5 Nf3+ 28. Kg2 Nxg529. Nxg5 Rd7 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1910 WCh against Schlechter"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker defended his title against Schlechter in a ten-game match played inVienna and Berlin, from the 7th of January to the 8th of February 1910. For along time afterwards there was speculation that Schlechter played under theobligation to win by two points (over just 10 games this was an excessiveadvantage), but the documents from the time fail to support this theory. ---Schlechter's modest result in St. Petersburg (joint eighth with 9/18) gave nowarning of what was about to happen. It was one of the hardest fought matchesand had an unusual finish. Schlechter entered the final game with a one-pointlead, where it is possible that he forced himself to try to win by two points,in order to consider himself a true world champion. He had chances ofachieving that, and he could also have drawn the final game, but he played onin search of victory, so that Lasker was able to turn the game around and withgreat difficulty retain his title. --- Before looking at the final game, let'shave a brief review of the preceding games. The first four games all ended indraws; in the first, as we saw in the introduction, Lasker had to use all hisdefensive resource and cunning to rescue an inferior position. In the thirdand fourth games there was no great imbalance; in the latter Lasker gained theupper hand, but Schlechter demonstrated his defensive abilities and managed todraw.} 1. Z0 {Lasker, after using his Steinitz Defence for the third time,played a large part of the fifth game brilliantly, and managed to obtain awinning advantage, first one pawn up and then two, at the cost of weakeninghis king. Objectively it should have ended in a win, but an inaccuracy wasfollowed by a serious error and suddenly Lasker was defenceless against amating attack and Schlechter was the winner. We are familiar with thisscenario and this account of the game, but this was one of the very rareoccasions when it was Lasker on the losing side. --- In the sixth game Laskertook the initiative and even won a pawn, but he was unable to realize it. Inthe seventh game Lasker resorted to the Dragon variation of the Sicilian inorder to try to complicate the game. He gained a good position, but thenSchlechter sacrificed a piece in order to get some counterplay and, after atitanic struggle, it ended in a draw. Schlechter was proving to be a worthyopponent. --- Despite the great struggle that took place in the next two games(Lasker played the Sicilian again in the ninth game, this time the variationknown today as the Pelikan or Sveshnikov), they were both drawn. So everythingdepended on the final game. --- Kasparov wrote of this game: "A titanicbattle! Of course, there were many mistakes, but what an intense struggle, andwith what inventiveness both sides played! The game was ahead of its time, andthe commentaries on it, even later ones, often don't sustain criticism: socomplicated and deep were the variations that occurred. --- "Its study,beginning with Schlechter's opening novelty, enables us to follow thedevelopment of chess thinking. Whereas nowadays independent play at the boardnormally begins from the 15th move at least, here it began much earlier, andthe value of every move was extremely high. The two players immediately beganplaying creatively, and the tension was incredible - the game had colossalcompetitive importance, and therefore all the mistakes, in my view, areexcusable."} *[Event "33: World Championship, Berlin"][Site "?"][Date "1910.??.??"][Round "10"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Schlechter, C"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D94"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "141"][EventDate "1910.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 ({For the first time in the match Lasker doesn't open with} 1. e4 {. He didn't want to face the Open Defence to the Ruy Lopez a fifth time, asystem that Schlechter handled with great skill in this match.}) 1... d5 2. c4c6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 g6 {QUESTION: How modern! I guess that this line wasalmost unknown at the time. This couldn't have been predicted, could it? ---ANSWER: Indeed, it would have come as a complete surprise. It was an unusualchoice, since this move was very rare. Schlechter's explanation was: "I didnot want to play for a draw in the last game and I chose a little-knowncontinuation, leading to interesting complications." --- With respect to its'modernity', Schlechter couldn't possibly have imagined the popularity thisline would acquire in later years. It was regularly played by Smyslov and atpresent features frequently in the practice of some of the top Chinese players,among others.} 5. Nc3 Bg7 6. Bd3 O-O 7. Qc2 {This isn't the best move, butlet's remember that Lasker was faced with something completely new and itwould be hard to anticipate what could possibly be wrong with a developingmove such as 7 Qc2, which neutralizes one of the ideas of the Slav Defence,namely the development of the c8-bishop outside the pawn chain; now 7...Bg4can be met with 8 Ne5.} ({It was better to play} 7. O-O {and answer} Bg4 {with}8. h3 Bxf3 9. Qxf3 {, when Black can choose between several moves, including}e6 ({and} 9... Qd6 {, intending ...Nbd7.})) 7... Na6 ({"Very boldly played;} 7... Nbd7 {is more solid", commented Schlechter, but the move he chose isthe better of the two. --- Years later, as this line and the related GrünfeldDefence grew in popularity, a standard reaction in such positions wasdiscovered, justified in the event of a move such as 7 Qc2, which can prove tobe a waste of time.}) ({EXERCISE: How should Black react instead of with 7...Na6 - ? --- ANSWER: The most energetic reply is} 7... c5 $1 {, and if} 8. dxc5{Black can play either} Qa5 ({or} 8... Na6 {, when} 9. cxd5 $6 {isn'tadvisable due to} Nb4 {: for example,} 10. Qd2 Nfxd5 11. Nxd5 Qxd5 12. Qxb4Qxd3 {, with advantage to Black.})) 8. a3 dxc4 $6 {"Schlechter here goesinto a series of moves which finally leave him with a weak isolated c-pawn,which cannot possibly be so good" (Capablanca).} ({Once again,} 8... c5 $1 {was more appropriate; the inclusion of the moves 7...Na6 and 8 a3 seems tofavour Black in comparison with 7...c5.}) 9. Bxc4 b5 $6 {Schlechter's choicehere is difficult to explain; it's aggressive, but only serves to weaken thequeenside.} ({Here} 9... c5 {could be met with} 10. d5 {;}) ({so Euwe suggested} 9... Nc7 10. e4 Bg4 {, with equality, "But from the perspective of the21st century we know that in such positions - after, say,} 11. Be3 {-White's chances are somewhat better" (Kasparov).}) 10. Bd3 b4 $6 {This was"Another nervy, impulsive decision" according to Kasparov. This wasBlack's idea, but after Lasker's good response the black position will be leftweakened, with nothing to show for it. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker neutralizethe premature black offensive?} ({It was more precise to play a developingmove such as} 10... Qa5 {, threatening 11...Nb4.}) 11. Na4 {ANSWER!} ({Ofcourse, not} 11. axb4 $2 Nxb4 {, allowing the exchange of the d3-bishop.Lasker's move nullifies all Black's activity and leaves him with the worry ofthe weak pawn on c6.}) ({Black's play would have been justified if White hadaccepted the offered pawn sacrifice with} 11. Bxa6 $6 {; then} bxc3 {, isplayable, when after} ({but on the basis of Schlechter's previous play, it isalmost certain that he would have preferred} 11... Bxa6 12. axb4 Qc8 $1 {, preventing White from castling, with ideas of 13...Qg4 or 13...Nd5. After,for instance,} 13. e4 Qg4 14. Rg1 {Black can play} Qc8 {, leaving White withthe problem of his king stuck in the centre}) 12. Bd3 {White is slightlybetter. --- Kasparov commented: "Now Black simply has a 'dead' knight at a6,a 'hole-ridden' queenside and a strategically lost position. The challenger'sopening experiment has been a failure, but, as we will soon see, that day thiswas of no significance."}) 11... bxa3 12. bxa3 ({Not the suicidal} 12. Qxc6$2 {, when Black has the even stronger option of} Qa5+ $1 {, and after} ({instead of} 12... Nb4) 13. Qc3 ({better than} 13. Nc3 $2 {, when Black winswith} Nb4) 13... Qxa4 14. Rxa3 Qd7 15. Bxa6 Bxa6 16. Rxa6 {Black takes chargewith} Rfc8 17. Qd2 Ne4 18. Qd1 Qb5 {.}) 12... Bb7 13. Rb1 {Castling was alsogood, but activating a piece with a gain of time is very tempting and possiblybetter.} Qc7 14. Ne5 {"Lasker begins deviating from calm and consistentdevelopment and nervously forces the attack, gradually allowing his opponentcounter-chances", commented Tarrasch. Kasparov was also critical: "Itwould appear that, having failed to win any of the previous nine games, Laskerhad partly lost confidence in himself.} ({In a normal situation Black'schronic weaknesses should have suggested to him the simple} 14. O-O $5 Nd7 15.Qe2 Nab8 16. Bd2 {with an overwhelming advantage". --- It's easy to see thatthey are both right, but Lasker's move doesn't lose the big advantage thatWhite has gained. Black still has his pieces badly placed on the queenside anda chronic weakness on c6 for which he has no compensation.}) 14... Nh5 {This response isn't anything to be feared, but it does prevent the threat of15 Bxa6, followed by 16 Qxc6.} ({Black's difficulties can be seen in that} 14... Nd7 $2 {loses material after} 15. Rxb7 Qxb7 16. Nxd7 {, followed by 17Bxa6;}) ({while} 14... Rac8 $2 {allows} 15. Bxa6 Bxa6 16. Nc5 Bb5 17. a4 {.}) ({Meanwhile Kasparov mentions} 14... Nd5 15. O-O {, and in his analysis Blackfails to solve his problems completely;} ({the natural} 15. f4 {seems evenslightly better.})) 15. g4 $6 {QUESTION: This may well be dubious, as youindicate, but it seems consistent with Ne5, since White wants to attack. Asthere is no obvious refutation in sight, what's bad about it? --- ANSWER: Theerror was of a practical nature, and in this game the practical aspect wasmore important than the objective truth of the situation. As Tarrasch pointedout, until a few moves ago the most important feature of the position was theweakness of Black's queenside, giving White a clear advantage. However, bycomplicating the game in this manner, unleashing violence on the kingside,White creates a situation where Black's queenside weaknesses are now only oneof the important factors. --- Lasker's 19th move was nevertheless a playableone and he himself explained the brutal handling of the struggle on the partof both players in this way: "When so much is riding on a single game, thatboth players should be in a heightened state is understandable. My fantasyveered towards the adventurous", and he added: "Had this position arisenin the beginning of the match, I would probably have refrained from such anidea".} ({There is nothing to be gained from} 15. Bxa6 $6 Bxa6 16. Qxc6 Bxe517. Qxa6 {, when Black can play} Bxh2 ({while} 17... Qc2 18. Ra1 Nf4 19. O-ONe2+ 20. Kh1 Rfc8 {was also interesting.})) ({If we accept Lasker'sexplanation, then at the start of the match he would have played} 15. f4) ({or} 15. O-O {, with advantage.}) ({Reinfeld and Fine suggested} 15. Nf3 {, whichis also good; this could hardly be counted as a waste of time because theh5-knight would also have to retreat sooner or later.}) 15... Bxe5 ({Kasparovcriticized this move: "This justifies Lasker's idea" and suggested} 15...Nf6 {instead, since "The advance of the g-pawn has spoiled White'sposition", but then he rather contradicts himself: "although after} 16. O-ONd5 {he retains some advantage."} {Alternatively, there is} 17. e4 ({Whiteappears to gain some advantage with} 17. Qe2 Nb8 18. e4 Nb6 19. Nc5 {: forinstance,} Bxe5 20. dxe5 Bc8 21. Bh6 {.} (21. Z0)) 17... Bxe5 ({if} 17... Nb6 {then} 18. Bf4) 18. dxe5 Nb6 19. Be3 {, with advantage to White. This indicatesthat Schlechter's move isn't inferior to 15...Nf6; the weakness of g4 isn't soimportant in that line. --- With regard to the phase which now begins,Kasparov commented: "Positional factors retreat into the background, givingway to calculation and intuition. There begins 'play without rules', in whichboth these outstanding players demonstrate exceptional flights of imagination."}) 16. gxh5 $6 ({Here Reinfeld/Fine and Kasparov agree in their disapprovalof} 16. dxe5 Ng7 {, followed by ...Ne6, which in fact isn't so clear; on e6the knight only lends greater force to f4-f5, and Black's queenside piecesremain badly placed. White's chances appear better after} 17. O-O {, followedby f4, with 18 Qc4 also in the agenda, forcing the bishop to retreat to c8. Assuch, 16 dxe5 might well have been an improvement, but Lasker had a particularline in mind and, as Kasparov pointed out, this game is being led bycalculation and intuition.}) 16... Bg7 17. hxg6 hxg6 {EXERCISE: The positionis now chaotic, but why do you think Lasker chose to complicate the game? ---ANSWER:} 18. Qc4 {This was the shot that Lasker was relying on; he threatensboth 19 Rxb7, followed by Qxa6, and 19 Bxg6.} ({After another attacking movesuch as} 18. h4 $6 {Black can counter-attack with} c5 $1 19. Rg1 Qh2 {;}) ({while if} 18. f4 {then again Black can play} c5 $1 {: for example,} 19. Rg1Rac8 20. Bxa6 ({there is no advantage either in} 20. Nxc5 Nxc5 21. Qxc5 Qxc522. dxc5 Rxc5) 20... Bxa6 21. Nxc5 Qd6 {, with adequate compensation for thepawn. Those two moves are slower than Lasker's choice, and allow Black tohighlight that the white king is vulnerable in the centre.}) 18... Bc8 {Kasparov criticized, and rightly so, the analyses of this great battle carriedout over the course of many years Computers are very useful in this kind ofposition where tactics are key. They have allowed many older lines to berefined, but even analyses made only a few years ago don't escape either fromthe refinements provided by better programs and more powerful computers. It'sforeseeable that the same thing will happen to present-day analyses within afew years.} ({The choice of 18...Bc8 was universally approved until veryrecently and it was considered that the thematic shot 18...c5 was bad. However,everything now indicates that the most precise evaluation is the veryopposite! 18...Bc8?! is weak and} 18... c5 $1 {was best. Let's just focus onthe key lines. After} 19. Rg1 {It isn't an easy position to analyze accuratelyand it would be an almost impossible task over the board, since this is justone of many possibilities. Instead, Black has a better move in} e6 $1 {,securing the position of his king. White can win material with} (19... Qxh2 $2{turns out to be bad due to} 20. Rxg6 Qh1+ 21. Kd2 Qf3 {(Kasparov)} 22. Rxb7 $1Qxb7 23. dxc5 Qf3 24. Bb2 $1 {, and White obtains a decisive materialadvantage: for instance,} Qxf2+ 25. Kd1 Qf3+ 26. Kc2 Qf2+ 27. Kb1 e5 28. Bxe5Rfb8+ 29. Ka1 Qe1+ 30. Ka2 Qd2+ 31. Bc2 {and wins.} Z0 (31... Z0)) 20. Rxb7Qxb7 21. Qxa6 Qxa6 22. Bxa6 {, but after} cxd4 {Black's disadvantage isminimal; the white pieces are very uncoordinated and Black's pieces are easilyactivated, so the chances are about equal}) 19. Rg1 {After the removal of theblack bishop from the long diagonal there were many attractive possibilitiesfor White. The text move is logical, bringing a piece into play with thethreat of Rxg6, but only tactics will dictate whether this is not only logical,but good. --- QUESTION: So the exchange of queens isn't good for Black?} ({Schlechter commented, "After} 19. Bxg6 Be6 20. Bxf7+ Bxf7 21. Qxa6 Bd5 {Black has a strong attack", and he was right. Kasparov thought that withprecise defence Schlechter's evaluation could be overturned with} 22. Rg1 Qxh2({but in fact instead of 22...Qxh2? Black has the much stronger} 22... Rxf2 $1{and after} 23. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 24. Ke1 Qxg1+ {Black is not only equal on material,but also has a very strong attack}) 23. Qf1 {.}) ({There are other moves toanalyze, and the position isn't clear, but 19 Bxg6, entering complicationswithout having much development, proves to be unpromising. The developing move} 19. Bd2 {, suggested by Tarrasch, has instead stood the test of time; afterthis the best seems be the violent} e5 {, recommended by Euwe, which aftervarious complications leads to a small advantage to White.}) ({As Kasparovhimself commented, the most promising move was} 19. h4 $1 {, "A logicalcontinuation of the assault", and White gains the advantage: for instance,}Qa5+ {(seeking to exchange queens to avoid falling under an attack)} 20. Bd2Qd5 21. Qxd5 cxd5 {, but the endgame is better for White, as shown by} 22. h5g5 23. Rg1 Bf6 24. e4 $1 {"winning a pawn with a continuing attack" (Zak).}) 19... Qa5+ $2 {ANSWER: With the exchange of queens both kings are moresecure, but in general, it's White who benefits more, since this tradeeliminates his only weakness, his king in the centre, which then turns into anadvantage; on the other hand, Black's queenside weaknesses remain and thewhite pieces are better developed. --- Seeking the exchange of queens, butthis isn't best, as we've already discussed.} ({It was possible to play} 19...e6 {, nullifying the pressure along the diagonal a2-g8, with the threat of 20...Qxh2, and after} 20. Rg3 Rb8 ({or} 20... Rd8 {White's advantage isn't great.})) ({It was also possible to play} 19... Qxh2 $1 {, which seems to lead to adraw, but we know that Schlechter didn't want a draw. After} 20. Rxg6 Nc7 $1 ({not} 20... Qh1+ $2 21. Kd2 Qf3 22. Bb2 Qxf2+ 23. Be2 {, followed by Rbg1 andWhite wins}) 21. Rg5 Qh4 {it's a draw with} 22. Rg3 ({or} 22. Rg1 Qh2) ({but not} 22. e4 $2 Ba6 23. Qc2 Bxd3 24. Qxd3 Ne6 {, with advantage to Black})22... Qh1+ 23. Ke2 Qh5+ 24. Kd2 Qh2 {.}) 20. Bd2 Qd5 21. Rc1 ({Here} 21. h4 {was also interesting, as we've already seen in a similar position.}) 21... Bb7{Exchanging on c4 naturally leaves the c6-pawn weak.} 22. Qc2 {Lasker wants towin by complicating the play; this retreat threatens 23 Rxg6 fxg6? 24 Bc4.} ({The world champion, forced to play for a win, isn't content with the advantageoffered by Euwe's suggestion of} 22. Qxd5 cxd5 23. f4 {, preventing the breakwith ...e5, after which the a6-knight remains out of play and White has theattractive plan of h4-h5 with an advantage in the endgame. Possibly thestrongest move was, though, once again 22 h4!, retaining the possibility ofexchanging queens.}) 22... Qh5 {Schlechter accepts the challenge andcounterattacks against h2. --- EXERCISE (difficult): There are many ways tocontinue the attack, but what do you think is the best move here?} ({Zakrecommended} 22... Qd6 {, but this doesn't seem to be an improvement; the bestreply is the same as against 22...Qh5, which we'll see on the next move.}) 23.Bxg6 $2 {"Lasker underestimates Black's counterplay along the openedf-file" (Kasparov).} ({Lasker subsequently suggested} 23. Rb1 {, but after}Qxh2 24. Rf1 {"the best defence is} Bc8 $1 25. Qxc6 Rb8 {", as Kasparovcorrectly indicates, and White has no advantage.}) ({More promising is Zak'ssuggestion to improve the placement of the white pieces with a gain of time bythe manoeuvre} 23. Bc4 e6 24. Qd3 Nc7 (24... Qxh2 {wins a pawn, but Whiteobtains excellent compensation after} 25. Rf1 $1 Nc7 26. Nc5 Rfb8 27. Qe4 {; this was the kind of position that Lasker was seeking}) 25. Nc5 Bc8 26. Ne4 {. After} Nd5 {White has some advantage, but with the a6-knight now betterdeployed on d5, Black doesn't stand so badly.}) ({ANSWER: Capablanca'srecommendation} 23. Qb3 $1 {seems best, resuming the attack along the a2-g8diagonal and the g-file, and after} Rab8 24. Rxg6 Qxh2 {, as well as} 25. Be4 {(Kasparov),} (25. Rg5 {is interesting, among other possibilities, with ideassuch as 26 Qd1-g4. The exchange of queens would favour White, because thec6-pawn would remain a serious weakness, in Kasparov's opinion: "In my viewWhite has strong pressure; the main thing is that Black is still suffering dueto his ill-starred knight at a6. In general it must once again be emphasizedthat without the queens White would have significantly fewer problems. As wewill now see..."})) 23... Qxh2 $1 {After a series of strong moves Blackleaves his previous passivity behind.} 24. Rf1 fxg6 25. Qb3+ Rf7 26. Qxb7 Raf8$1 {Black makes use of the newly opened f-file to parry the double attack.} 27.Qb3 {Lasker defends f2 for the moment with this pin, abandoning the attack onthe knight.} ({Now} 27. Qxa6 $4 {loses to} Rxf2 28. Rxf2 Rxf2 {.}) ({Herejected} 27. f4 {very probably because then Black, if he wishes, can force adraw with} Qh4+ 28. Rf2 ({after} 28. Kd1 Qg4+ 29. Kc2 Qf5+ {the king is unableto go to the b-file due to 30...Rb8}) 28... Qh1+ 29. Ke2 Qh5+ 30. Kd3 Qf5+ 31.Ke2 ({not} 31. Kc3 $2 Bxd4+ $1 32. exd4 Qh3+ 33. Kc2 Rb8 {and Black wins})31... Qh5+ {with a draw by perpetual check; it would be bad to avoid this with}32. Rf3 $2 {due to} e5 $1 33. Qxc6 exf4 34. e4 Nc7 {and all Black's pieces canjoin in the attack.}) 27... Kh8 {In some lines the king is better on h7, butit's difficult to know whether that's true of all lines.} 28. f4 g5 $5 {Opening lines against the white king, before undertaking any other measures.} ({There were other possibilities, of similar value, such as the other pawnbreak,} 28... e5 $5 {, when after} 29. dxe5 Qg3+ {(setting up a pin againstthe white queen along the third rank)} 30. Ke2 Rxf4 31. Rxf4 Rxf4 32. Rh1+ Rh433. Rxh4+ Qxh4 {the play is unclear, with chances for both sides.}) ({Theimmediate} 28... Qg3+ {was also possible and after} 29. Kd1 {, seeking refugeon the queenside, Black can break with} c5 $1 30. dxc5 Rxf4 {, again withreasonable play.}) 29. Qd3 ({Various annotators have suggested} 29. Rxc6 {here, which is ambitious but also risky. There are many complicated lines; themost precise seems to be to carry out the manoeuvre that we saw above, i.e.}Qg3+ 30. Kd1 Rxf4 31. Rxf4 gxf4 {, and Black's initiative is dangerous: forinstance,} 32. Rxa6 $2 {loses to} f3 33. Be1 f2 34. Bxf2 Rxf2 {.}) 29... gxf430. exf4 ({Of course, not} 30. Qxa6 $4 fxe3 {.}) 30... Qh4+ ({Not the passive} 30... Nb8 $2 {when among other things White can play} 31. Qf3 {, strengtheningthe defence of the king and at the same time threatening Rh1: for instance,after} Qh4+ 32. Ke2 Qf6 33. Nc5 {, followed by Rh1, Ne4, etc, White is now theone attacking in force.}) 31. Ke2 ({Avoiding the exchange of queens whichwould follow} 31. Kd1 Qg4+ 32. Kc2 Qf5 {, when there would be no winningchances for White.}) 31... Qh2+ 32. Rf2 Qh5+ {"Here (or a move earlier) thegame was adjourned, and resumed the following day. It was one of the mostdramatic adjournment sessions in the history of chess!" (Kasparov).} 33. Rf3$1 {Maintaining the tension.} ({It isn't possible to evade the checks andstrengthen the defence of f4 with} 33. Ke3 $2 {, since then Black has severalvery strong possibilities, the simplest being} Bh6 {, and the white positionis untenable.}) 33... Nc7 ({If} 33... Nb8 $2 {Lasker intended to play} 34. Rh1$1 {and after} Qxh1 35. Rh3+ Qxh3 36. Qxh3+ Kg8 37. Nc5 {the queen is worthmore than the two rooks, thanks to the weakness of the black king and thecollaboration of the knight in the attack, while the bishop plays its part asan excellent defender.}) 34. Rxc6 {This move drew criticism, which now appearsexcessive.} ({The natural} 34. Nc5 {was suggested instead, "in order after}Nd5 {to make the leap} 35. Ne6 {with very sharp play and, apparently, dynamicequilibrium" (Kasparov).}) ({With the black knight on c7 the manoeuvre} 34.Rh1 Qxh1 35. Rh3+ Qxh3 36. Qxh3+ Kg8 37. Nc5 {is less advantageous than after33...Nb8, because the knight can be activated with} Nb5 {; nevertheless,instead of} 38. Ne6 $6 ({it's better to exchange the bishop with} 38. Be3 $1Nxd4+ $6 39. Bxd4 Bxd4 40. Ne6 {, when White is better; so this was perhapsthe best option}) 38... Nxd4+ 39. Nxd4 Bxd4 {.}) 34... Nb5 $1 ({Schlechterevaluated} 34... Nd5 {as "very strong and probably decisive", but Laskerpointed out} 35. Qg6 $1 {, which leads to equality: for instance. the mainline is} Qxg6 36. Rxg6 Nxf4+ 37. Bxf4 Rxf4 38. Rh3+ Kg8 39. Rhg3 Re4+ $1 40.Kd3 (40. Re3 {, exchanging rooks, is just equal}) 40... Rxd4+ 41. Ke3 Rxa4 42.Rxg7+ Kh8 43. Ke2 Rxa3 {.}) 35. Rc4 $1 ({Of course, not} 35. Rc5 $2 Nxd4+ 36.Qxd4 {because of the zwischenzug} Qxf3+ $1 {.}) ({Also unsatisfactory is} 35.Be3 $2 Nxd4+ $1 36. Bxd4 Rxf4 {, when the best White has is} 37. Rh6+ Qxh6 38.Rh3 Re4+ 39. Kd1 Rxd4 40. Rxh6+ Kg8 41. Qxd4 Bxd4 {, with the better endgamefor Black.}) 35... Rxf4 $2 {A miscalculation. Black thought it led to awinning position, but it only yields a draw. As with so many of the positionsarising in this game, this one is very complicated and was subjected to agreat deal of analysis subsequently. Over the years the evaluation has oftenchanged.} ({Schlechter thought that} 35... Rd8 {would have been decisive, buthe didn't consider the best defence} 36. Ke1 $1 {(attributed to Minev byKasparov), with the threat of Rh3, and White's disadvantage is minimal after}Kg8 {.}) ({Capablanca suggested} 35... e5 {. "This leads to a crazy position,which does not lend itself to evaluation", commented Kasparov. After} 36.dxe5 Bxe5 37. Ke1 {Black can play} Bf6 ({or} 37... Rh7 {, when he is fine, butthere is no question of any clear black advantage.})) ({According to Kasparov,whose argument is convincing, from the practical point of view the best optionwould have been} 35... Nd6 $5 36. Rc5 Nf5 {, as suggested by Tarrasch, puttingpressure on the white position. "Thus, although Schlechter held anappreciable initiative, nowhere did he have a direct win. The play wasdouble-edged, and Lasker did not intend to give up his crown", commentedKasparov.}) ({To complete the list of possibilities, the preference of thecurrent (2018) engines isn't any of the above, but} 35... Qg4 $1 {, preparing36...Rf6, with the plan of ...Rh6, ...Nd6, etc, and Black has a slightinitiative.}) 36. Bxf4 Rxf4 37. Rc8+ Bf8 38. Kf2 $1 Qh2+ ({According toSchlechter, he based his combination beginning with 35...Rxf4 on the fact thathe thought he could win here with} 38... Qh4+ 39. Kg2 $1 ({not} 39. Ke2 $4 {due to} Nxd4+) 39... Qg4+ {, "noticing too late} 40. Rg3 $1 Qxc8 41. Qg6 {".}) 39. Ke1 Qh1+ $2 {This allows the white king to escape, after whichBlack's position deteriorates.} ({Instead,} 39... Qh4+ $1 {would have led toan equal endgame after} 40. Kf1 ({if} 40. Kd2 {then the drawing line is} Qh2+41. Ke1 Qh4+ {, and the white king is unable to evade perpetual check}) ({Lasker would have been unable to avoid the draw, either with} 40. Rg3 $4 {, due to} Qh1+ 41. Kd2 Rf2+) ({or with} 40. Kd1 $4 {when Black has} Qh1+ 41.Ke2 Rxf3 42. Qxf3 Nxd4+) 40... Qh3+ 41. Kf2 Rxf3+ 42. Qxf3 Qxc8 43. Qh5+ {.})40. Rf1 Qh4+ 41. Kd2 Rxf1 (41... Rxd4 $2 {fails to} 42. Rcxf8+ Kg7 43. R1f7+Kh6 44. Rh8+ {, followed by mate.}) 42. Qxf1 Qxd4+ 43. Qd3 {The mostcomplicated phase of the game is behind us and Lasker once more has theadvantage.} Qf2+ ({Exchanging the queens offers Black no hope now; after} 43...Qxd3+ 44. Kxd3 Kg7 45. Nc5 {the black position is untenable.}) 44. Kd1 Nd6 {"White's winning plan is to coordinate his forces, exchange queens, pick upthe a-pawn and advance his own passed pawn to the queening square. It's hardto prevent this plan, especially since the champion carries it out withmerciless consistency, whereas the challenger is clearly disheartened." (Kasparov).} 45. Rc5 {This threatens to win with 46 Rh5+;} ({but since thiscan easily be parried, it seems better to play} 45. Rd8 {, preventing thebishop from coming into play, followed by recycling the knight.}) 45... Bh6 46.Rd5 Kg8 47. Nc5 Qg1+ {This enables White to improve the position of his king.}({More tenacious was} 47... Qg2 {, "although this would have been unlikelyto make any fundamental difference after} 48. Re5 Bg7 49. Re1 {" (Kasparov).}) 48. Kc2 Qf2+ 49. Kb3 Bg7 50. Ne6 Qb2+ ({As Kasparov also pointed out,} 50...Qb6+ {was more stubborn, forcing the white king to return to the kingsideafter the sequence} 51. Kc2 Qb2+ 52. Kd1 Qa1+ 53. Ke2 Qb2+ 54. Kf3 Qf6+ 55. Nf4Nf7 {, although White could have continued to press for a win with} 56. Kg3 {.}) 51. Ka4 Kf7 ({EXERCISE: This was considered to be the final serious error,and} 51... Qg2 {was suggested instead. Prove that this is not an improvement!}{There is no defence after} 52. Ng5 $1 {, with multiple threats:} ({ANSWER:Instead of} 52. Nxg7 {, which is advantageous, it's much stronger to retainthe knight.} Z0 (52... Z0)) {If} 52... Qh2 {, controlling h7, the fastest winis with} ({such as} 52... Z0 53. Rxd6 ({or} 53. Qh7+ Kf8 54. Ne6+ {,simplifying, followed by capturing the a-pawn}) 53... Qxg5 (53... exd6 {allows mate after} 54. Qh7+ Kf8 55. Qf5+ Kg8 56. Qe6+ Kh8 57. Qe8+ {etc}) 54.Qd5+ {.}) 53. Rb5 $1 {, threatening Rb8+, and after} Qh4+ 54. Kb3 $1 {there isno good defence.}) 52. Nxg7 Qxg7 ({If} 52... Kxg7 {then} 53. Qd4+ {, and thereis no possibility of further resistance after} Qxd4+ 54. Rxd4 {: for instance,}Kf6 55. Rd5 Ke6 56. Ra5 Nc8 57. Rc5 Kd7 58. Kb5 {, and the white king headsfor b7.}) 53. Qb3 $1 {The most precise.} Ke8 ({The endgame after} 53... Kf6 54.Qb2+ Kf7 55. Qxg7+ Kxg7 {is easier now; White would continue with} 56. Ra5 Nc857. Rc5 Nd6 58. Rc7 {.}) 54. Qb8+ Kf7 55. Qxa7 {After the fall of the a7-pawnLasker's victory is no longer in any doubt, even though he has to show goodtechnique, and "Lasker proceeds towards his goal with confident manoeuvresof his heavy pieces" (Kasparov).} Qg4+ 56. Qd4 Qd7+ 57. Kb3 Qb7+ 58. Ka2 Qc659. Qd3 Ke6 60. Rg5 Kd7 61. Re5 Qg2+ 62. Re2 Qg4 63. Rd2 Qa4 64. Qf5+ Kc7 {This makes White's task easier;} ({but there is no defence after} 64... Kd8 65.Qe6 $1 {when "the exchange of queens would soon have been forced" (Kasparov).}) 65. Qc2+ Qxc2+ 66. Rxc2+ Kb7 ({If} 66... Kd7 {then} 67. a4 {, and White's king will support the advance of the pawn.}) 67. Re2 Nc8 68. Kb3Kc6 69. Rc2+ Kb7 70. Kb4 Na7 71. Kc5 {. "All in all, a great game, whichwill go down in the history of chess as a remarkable finish to the greateststruggle for the Chess Championship of the World", commented Capablanca.} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "1910 WCh against Janowski"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Rather surprisingly, after the overwhelming result of their previousencounter, Janowski played another match against Lasker, this time for theworld title. The match took place in Berlin, between the 8th of November andthe 8th of December 1910.} 1. Z0 {The winner would be the first to achieveeight wins. It took Lasker only eleven games to win the match (+8 =3). Laskerallowed Janowski no chance to demonstrate his combinative ability; he took thefight into positional channels, where he was far superior, although even whenthe position became very complicated (as in the fifth game, which we shallexamine), and despite being worse, he outplayed Janowski in the complicationsas well.} *[Event "34: World Championship, Berlin"][Site "?"][Date "1910.??.??"][Round "5"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Janowski, D"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D32"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "57"][EventDate "1910.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 c5 {The Tarrasch Defence was well suited to theaggressive and dynamic style of the challenger. Black acquiesces to a weaknesson d5 in return for good piece play. This defence is still played from time totime. Its eponymous creator played it many times, but it later fell somewhatinto disuse. However it had its glory days when played by two world champions,Boris Spassky and subsequently Garry Kasparov.} 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Nf3 Be6 {Overprotecting the weak pawn; the slight drawback is that this commits thebishop rather early, when subsequently it might be developed to g4, forexample.} ({Tarrasch used to play exclusively} 5... Nc6 {in this position, asdid Spassky and Kasparov. Capablanca also resorted to this early developmentof the bishop, but only after} 6. g3 {.}) 6. e4 {It was Rubinstein whodeveloped the most popular way of playing against the Tarrasch Defence, basedon a quick g3 and Bg2, putting pressure on the weakness at d5; naturally thatcould also be played here.} ({Instead, in a rather surprising manner, Laskergives the game a violent turn at the first opportunity. He was criticized forthis, but today's engines approve of his choice, which seems a goodalternative to the more positional} 6. g3) ({or} 6. e3 {.}) 6... dxe4 $2 {A reply which immediately justifies Lasker's decision; Janowski fails torespond in the best way.} ({Instead of opening the game, he should have playedthe natural developing move} 6... Nf6 {, with only a slight advantage to Whiteafter} 7. Bb5+ ({or} 7. exd5 Nxd5 8. Bb5+ Nc6 9. Qa4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 {; the bishop pair gives sufficient compensation in the event of} 11. Bxc6+ bxc612. Qxc6+ Bd7 {, followed by 13...0-0}) 7... Nc6 8. Qa4 {.}) 7. Nxe4 $2 {Lasker lets Black's mistake go unpunished, as he weakens White's defencesalong the e1-a5 diagonal, which is of no importance right now, but which Blackis able exploit later, after another error on Lasker's part.} ({It's strangethat Lasker failed to play} 7. Bb5+ $1 {, a natural move, developing with again of time. Then after} Nd7 8. Ne5 Ngf6 ({if} 8... a6 {then} 9. Bxd7+ Bxd710. Qb3) 9. Bg5 cxd4 10. Qxd4 Be7 11. Rd1 O-O 12. Bxd7 Nxd7 13. Nxd7 {Whitewins material for insufficient compensation. It's curious that this correctmethod exploits Black's weakness along the a4-e8 diagonal.}) 7... Nc6 8. Be3 $6{This isn't a mistake, but it's an inaccuracy; the white king is still in thecentre.} ({It was better to play} 8. Bb5 Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nf6 10. O-O Be7 11. Qe2 {, when the position is fairly level, although White's game is slightly thefreer and} O-O $2 {isn't possible yet due to} 12. d5 {.}) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4Qa5+ 10. Nc3 $4 {Nunn had something to say about this move: "An absolutelydreadful move leaving White hopelessly lost."} ({Lasker could have reachedan equal position with} 10. Qd2 Bb4 11. Nc3 {, when the problems created inthe game by the pin on the d-file are less dangerous: for instance, after} Rd812. Rd1 {, in the event of} Bxa2 {, White regains his pawn with} ({while if} 12... Nge7 {, to be able to recapture on c6 with the knight and keep thequeens on the board, then} 13. a3 {, and if} Qe5 14. f4 Bxc3 15. Qxc3 Qe4 16.Kf2) 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qxd8+ Qxd8 15. Rxd8+ Kxd8 16. Bxa7 {. There are otherpossible lines, but White has no difficulties in any of them.}) 10... O-O-O {QUESTION: And White is just lost now, isn't he? I'm astounded. --- ANSWER:You're not the only one. Euwe labelled it "One of the most famous 'won'positions in the history of chess", and added: "It's rather sad to thinkthat a World Champion, and such a World Champion, should get into such ahopeless position by move 10 with the White pieces". --- EXERCISE: Lasker islost, but we know that this doesn't mean that Black is not going to encounterdifficulties. What did Lasker play now? --- ANSWER:} 11. a3 {Defending againstthe most direct threat, which was 11...Nxd4 12 Bxd4 Qb4.} ({Although thiscomes at the cost of making a move which doesn't help White's development,there was nothing else; if} 11. Qd2 {, hoping to play Rd1 or castle, then} Nxd412. Bxd4 Bc5 {. As Nunn pointed out, "A catastrophic opening is depressingfor any player, and it's worth looking at how Lasker could often turn apotential disaster around by remaining calm and adhering to the sameprinciples that hold for defending any inferior position: try to spin the gameout and give your opponent awkward decisions to make." --- And the firstreward for that attitude wasn't long in coming.}) 11... Nh6 $4 {A move thatlooks extremely strong; the knight is heading for f5, while leaving the wayopen for the f8-bishop, but here considerations don't count for much; tacticswill decide.} ({Janowski misses a great opportunity to gain a decisiveadvantage - the most direct was} 11... Bc5 {, indicated by Tarrasch, and if}12. b4 Bxd4 13. Bxd4 ({instead,} 13. bxa5 {is hardly an improvement, as after}Bxc3+ 14. Bd2 Rxd2 15. Qxd2 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Nxa5 {Black has a winning advantage}) 13... Qg5 $1 14. h4 ({or} 14. Ne2 Nxd4 15. Nxd4 Qe5+) 14... Qg6 15. Bd3 f5 ({better than} 15... Rxd4 {, which also wins}) 16. Be3 Qxg2) ({As indicated byReinfeld and Fine,} 11... Nge7 {also was adequate. White is unable to freehimself from the pins on the d-file and subsequently the e-file, while after}12. b4 Qe5 13. Nce2 ({if} 13. Ncb5 {then} a6 {wins}) 13... Nf5 14. Rc1 Nxe3 15.fxe3 Qxe3 16. Rc3 Qe4 17. b5 {Black is able to bring all his pieces into play,regaining the knight and achieving an overwhelming advantage with} Be7 18. bxc6Bf6 19. cxb7+ Kxb7 {, and there is no defence.}) 12. b4 Qe5 {EXERCISE: Thereis no doubt that the white position is on the verge of collapse; White's taskis to put up the maximum possible resistance. What do you think Lasker playedhere? --- ANSWER:} 13. Ncb5 $1 {Exploiting the difference between 11...Nh6 and11...Nge7.} ({Instead,} 13. Nce2 $4 Nf5 {would transpose to the line with 11...Nge7 12 b4 Qe5 quoted above.}) 13... Nf5 $6 {Logical and this was the ideabehind 11...Nh6, but it gives no advantage. --- EXERCISE: And now how didLasker offer maximum resistance?} ({Here Euwe wrote: "Incidentally healready had an opportunity here to become a victim of a Lasker trap", whichis a slight exaggeration.} 13... a6 $6 {, with the knight on e7, was winningfor Black, but here with} 14. Qc1 $1 {White is able exploit the now clearweakness of the c6-knight; if} axb5 {then} 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qxc6+ Qc7 17. Qa6+{, with adequate compensation for the piece, as Tarrasch indicated. Indeed,after} Qb7 18. Rc1+ Bc4 ({not} 18... Kb8 $4 19. Bf4+ {, winning}) 19. Qa5 Qc620. a4 {Black must seek a draw by repeating moves with} Qc7 21. Qa6+ Qb7 22.Qa5 Qc7 {.}) ({Speeding up development with the spectacular} 13... Bc5 {is not advantageous either; after} 14. bxc5 {The alternative here is} Nxd4 {, when} (14... Rxd4 15. Nxd4 Rd8 16. Nxc6 $1 Rxd1+ 17. Rxd1 bxc6 18. Be2 {White threatens to castle and the two rooks would be stronger than the queen.}(18. Z0)) 15. Nxd4 $2 {, loses to} ({but after} 15. Nd6+ $1 {the game ends ina draw:} Rxd6 16. cxd6 Qa5+ 17. Bd2 Qe5+ 18. Be3 Qa5+) 15... Nf5 {.}) ({Nonetheless, there was a stronger continuation. It's nothing spectacular, butthe simple} 13... Nxd4 $1 {leads to a slightly better endgame for Black. After}14. Nxd4 Be7 ({not} 14... Kb8 $4 15. Nc6+) 15. Qd3 $1 {seeking the exchange ofqueens,} ({and better than} 15. Qc1+ $6 Kb8 16. Nf3 Qe4 17. Be2 Bf6) 15... Ng416. Qb5 Qxb5 17. Bxb5 Nxe3 18. fxe3 {Black has the bishop pair, while Whitehas a backward pawn, although, as Nunn pointed out, the strong knight on d4minimizes the black advantage.}) 14. Rc1 $1 {ANSWER: "White must throweverything into the counterattack. The fact that he loses a pawn in theprocess is of secondary importance." (Euwe) --- It's the only move to resist,but it's sufficient to equalize; with the pin White neutralizes the knight onc6.} Nxe3 ({Nunn considered "The ingenious attacking attempt} 14... Rxd4 {", when, after the virtually forced line} 15. Nxd4 Nxe3 16. fxe3 Qxe3+ 17.Be2 Bxb4+ 18. axb4 Rd8 19. b5 Rxd4 20. Qc2 Bc4 21. bxc6 b5 {, there areseveral moves (Nunn analyzes 22 Qf5+), but in all cases White's extra rookenables him to equalize: for instance,} 22. Rd1 Rf4 23. Rf1 Bxe2 24. Qxe2 Qc3+25. Rd2 Qa1+ {with a draw by perpetual check.}) 15. fxe3 Qxe3+ 16. Be2 {Black has won a pawn and the white king is stuck in the centre, but there isno advantage, because the black king is also weak; the threat of 17 Nxa7+ is astrong one.} Be7 {Black plans 17...Bf6 and perhaps also 17...Bh4+.} ({There isnothing better:} 16... Rxd4 17. Nxd4 Bxb4+ 18. axb4 Rd8 {transposes to theline with 14...Rxd4 quoted above;}) ({while if} 16... Bd6 {White solves hisdifficulties with} 17. Nxa7+ (17. Rc3 {is also sufficient}) 17... Kd7 18. Naxc6bxc6 19. Nxe6 fxe6 20. Rc4 $1 {(seeking to exchange queens)} Rhf8 21. Qd4 {, and White should draw without any great problems.}) ({Tarrasch initiallythought that} 16... Bb3 $2 {was winning. --- EXERCISE: Why does this actuallylose? --- ANSWER: It loses to a beautiful line pointed out by Znosko-Borovsky:}17. Nxa7+ Kc7 18. Ndb5+ Kb6 19. Qxd8+ $1 (19. Rxc6+ $1 {also works}) 19... Nxd820. Nc8+ Ka6 21. Nc7# {.}) 17. Rc3 $1 {Lasker is no longer satisfied with adraw! Here we can see one of Lasker's great strengths, his fighting spirit,which enables him to save bad positions and win equal positions.} ({Laskerrejects the drawish endgame arising after} 17. Nxa7+ Kb8 18. Naxc6+ bxc6 19.Nxc6+ Kb7 20. Qc2 $1 {(threatening 21 Na5+ and mate)} (20. Nxd8+ $2 {loses to}Rxd8 21. Qc2 Rc8) 20... Rc8 ({after} 20... Bh4+ 21. g3 Bxg3+ 22. hxg3 Qxg3+ {there is nothing more than a draw by perpetual check}) 21. Qc3 $1 Qxc3+ 22.Rxc3 Bf6 23. Rc5 (23. Rc1 {also works}) 23... Kb6 24. Bf3 Bd7 25. a4 $1 Bxc626. a5+ Kb7 27. Rxc6 Rxc6 28. b5 Bc3+ {.}) 17... Bh4+ $6 {Janowski also wantsto win, but with this move he compromises his position.} ({There were twoother interesting possibilities, but neither offers Black any tangibleadvantage: One is} 17... Rxd4 {and after. for instance,} 18. Qxd4 Qxd4 19. Nxd4Bf6 20. Rxc6+ bxc6 21. Nxe6 fxe6 22. Bf3 {, followed by Ke2 and Rc1, Black'sextra pawn will be almost impossible to realize.}) ({Instead, the queensacrifice} 17... Qxc3+ 18. Nxc3 Nxd4 {appeared winning to Reinfeld and Fine,but it isn't so clear; after} 19. Bd3 {, followed by 20 0-0, Black hassufficient compensation to equalize, but nothing more.}) 18. g3 Qe4 $2 {Janowski commits a serious error; everything indicates that, unlike Lasker, hefailed to understand that the situation had changed; first, equality wasrestored and now, following his previous move, the position is fraught withdangers for Black.} ({He should have played} 18... Qxc3+ 19. Nxc3 Bf6 {, whenthe correct move is} 20. Ncb5 ({not} 20. Qc1 Bxd4 21. b5 Ne5 {"and Blackshould win", according to Lasker}) 20... Nxd4 $2 (20... Bxd4 21. Nxd4 Nxd422. Kf2 {"and the position is about even though still full of problems" (Lasker).} (22. Z0)) 21. Qc1+ Kb8 ({or} 21... Nc6 22. Nxa7+ Kd7 23. Nxc6 bxc624. O-O {, winning}) 22. Qf4+ {followed by a Philidor smothered mate:} Ka8 23.Nc7+ Kb8 24. Na6+) 19. O-O {Now it's White who has several threats, such astaking the bishop, 20 Rf4, 20 Bf3, etc.} Bf6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker reply?--- ANSWER:} 20. Rxf6 $1 (20. Bf3 $2 {was bad due to} Bxd4+ {, but byeliminating the annoying bishop White preserves the strong d4-knight.}) 20...gxf6 21. Bf3 Qe5 {This isn't the most tenacious, but Black's position isalready lost in the long run.} ({Hardly better was} 21... Rxd4 22. Nxd4 Qe5 23.Qd2 Bd5 24. Rc5 (24. Nxc6 Bxc6 25. Bxc6 bxc6 26. Rxc6+ Kb8 27. Rc5 {is alsowinning}) 24... Rd8 25. Bg4+ $1 ({better than} 25. b5) 25... Kb8 ({or} 25...Kc7 26. b5) 26. Rxc6 $1 {and wins;}) ({but the most tenacious move was} 21...Bg4 {, which leads to a very difficult endgame after} 22. Nxa7+ (22. Bxg4+ {is also good): for example,}) 22... Kc7 23. Ndb5+ Kb6 24. Qxd8+ Rxd8 25. Bxe4Nxa7 26. Nxa7 Kxa7 27. Rc7 Bc8 28. h4 {, and given the passivity of the blackposition, 'the rest is a question of technique'.}) 22. Nxa7+ Kc7 23. Naxc6 bxc624. Rxc6+ Kb8 25. Rb6+ Kc8 (25... Ka7 {allows mate with} 26. Qa4+ {.}) 26. Qc1+Kd7 27. Nxe6 fxe6 28. Rb7+ Ke8 29. Bc6+ ({If} 29. Bc6+ Kf8 {then} 30. Qh6+ {and mate next.}) (29. Z0 {After this new triumph, Lasker became inactive againfor four years.}) 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "4: Selected Games: 1914-1925"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{St. Petersburg 1914: After retaining his title by beating Janowski inDecember 1910, Lasker's return to the board came about on the 21st of April1914, in St. Petersburg. The best Russian chessplayers and some very strongmasters took part. The tournament was played in two stages: the top fiveplayers from the first stage (with 11 masters) would qualify for the final,which would be played as double-round event. --- In theory there were threenames which were 'certainties' to go through to the final: Lasker, Rubinsteinand Capablanca; and the other two places would be fought over presumably byAlekhine, Nimzowitsch, Tarrasch, Marshall and Bernstein. However, thepredictions were wrong.} 1. Z0 {Lasker began well, with a win followed by twodraws, and in the fourth round he defeated Rubinstein, in an intensemanoeuvring struggle. The rook ending is a classic model and very instructive.--- At the end of the fourth round Lasker was sharing first place withAlekhine and Bernstein, with 3/4, Capablanca had 2/3 (he had already had afree day), while Rubinstein, who was beginning to fall behind, had only onepoint out of three following his defeat by Lasker. Let's take a look at thisgame (see the following game).} *[Event "35: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1914.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Rubinstein, A"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C82"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "131"][EventDate "1914.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 {The Open Defence to theRuy Lopez was in its infancy then. In St. Petersburg it was employed byRubinstein, Tarrasch and even Lasker against Capablanca in the final of thetournament.} 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6 9. c3 Bc5 ({Later} 9... Be7 {became more common;}) ({while a third possibility is} 9... Nc5 {, when after}10. Bc2 {the most popular move is} Bg4 {.}) 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxd2 {Submissively exchanging the centralized knight is considered to be a smallconcession.} ({Over the years the Dilworth Attack} 11... Nxf2 {has been muchdebated;}) ({while} 11... f5 {has also been played;}) ({and currently} 11...Bf5 {is the line with the best reputation.}) 12. Qxd2 $1 ({QUESTION: Why hassuch an unnatural move been awarded an exclamation mark? Surely White willhave to waste a tempo later moving the queen again, to develop the bishop? ---ANSWER: It's true that it looks more logical to develop the bishop with} 12.Bxd2 {, which naturally Lasker knew. The reason behind such 'strange-looking'moves is almost always tactical. Lasker's move keeps the d-file open, so thatWhite can, if it suits him, play Qd3 in one move, or travel to the kingsidewith Qf4 (see the 12...Ne7 variation).}) ({After} 12. Qxd2 $1 Z0 {, theimmediate threat is} 13. Ng5 g6 {and now} 14. Nxh7 $1 Kxh7 15. Qh6+ Kg8 16.Bxg6 fxg6 17. Qxg6+ Kh8 18. Qh6+ Kg8 19. Qxe6+ {, and finally Qxc6.}) 12... f6{The best option, according to Keres.} ({Here's an example: V.Smyslov-V.Ragozin, Moscow 1944, continued} 12... Ne7 13. b4 {preventing the bishop fromretreating to e7, before playing Ng5;} ({in S.Tarrasch-M.Chigorin, St.Petersburg 1893, White played} 13. Ng5 {and Black could have replied with} Ng6)13... Bb6 14. Ng5 Bf5 ({with the bishop on b6, from where it can't easilytravel to the kingside,} 14... Ng6 $2 {is bad due to} 15. Bxg6 hxg6 16. Qf4 {, intending Qh4 and Black doesn't have ...Be7 available}) 15. Bxf5 Nxf5 16. Qd3g6 {, when as well as the move in the game,} 17. e6 ({White has} 17. g4 Ne7 18.Qh3 {, with advantage in both cases.})) ({If} 12... Be7 {then White can play}13. Qd3 g6 14. Bh6 Re8 {and now, for instance,} 15. Qe3 {, followed by 16 Rad1,or 16 Qf4.}) 13. exf6 ({It was also possible to continue with the originalidea of} 13. Qd3 {, to force Black to weaken his kingside with} g6 {, so thatafter} 14. exf6 {White might later be able to play Bh6.}) 13... Rxf6 14. Nd4 {This move allows Black to stabilize the position;} ({subsequently more dynamicsolutions were sought, such as} 14. a4) ({and} 14. b4 Bb6 15. a4 {.}) 14...Nxd4 15. cxd4 {In return for closing the d-file Black has to consent to abackward pawn on c7, which is very difficult to exploit. White, in turn, issaddled with an isolated pawn on d4 and it's also hard to say whether this isweak or not.} Bb6 ({Tarrasch recommended} 15... Bd6 {, giving the bishop morescope; on b6 it remains less active, although it does fulfil the function ofputting pressure on White's isolated pawn.}) 16. a4 Rb8 17. axb5 axb5 18. Qc3Qd6 19. Be3 {"The opinions of the theoreticians regarding this position aredivided: some think that, thanks to his pressure on the c-file, White has theadvantage, others that Black has a solid defence", commented Kasparov. Everything suggests that the second view is more accurate. However, White isthe only one who can try to make progress, and in the long run the blackmajority on the queenside remains unused, while White's kingside majority,once the queens are exchanged, proves to be of value.} Bf5 {Black achievesmore freedom of action thanks to this exchange.} ({EXERCISE: Why did Black notget rid of his backward pawn with} 19... b4 20. Qd2 c5 {- ? --- ANSWER: Due to}21. Bxh7+ $1 Kxh7 22. dxc5 {(or in the reverse order)} Bxc5 23. Qc2+ {,winning a pawn.}) 20. Rfc1 Bxc2 21. Rxc2 Re8 22. Rac1 Rfe6 23. h3 Re4 24. Qd2R8e6 {Black's pressure along the e-file is such that White can make noprogress, so Lasker decides to alter the position.} 25. Rc6 Qd7 ({Rubinsteinrejected the transaction} 25... Qxc6 26. Rxc6 Rxc6 {. White can win a pawnafter, for instance,} 27. Qd3 Rce6 28. Qxb5 Bxd4 29. Bxd4 Rxd4 30. Qb8+ Kf7 31.Qxc7+ Re7 32. Qc3 {, when Black is a little worse. Although it is likely thatthis will end in a draw, Rubinstein didn't want to wait passively.}) 26. Rxe6Qxe6 {With the rook exchange White has made some slight progress, as thepressure on the e-file has diminished and he can manoeuvre more easily.Nonetheless, objectively the manoeuvring capability gained is not verypromising. There is no clear way to make progress. As long as the queensremain on the board, the white kingside majority cannot advance, so whatawaits us is a long manoeuvring phase. Black's chances of active play areeven less, since playing ...c5, assuming White allows it, would leave thepawns on d5 and b5 weak.} 27. Qd3 Qe8 28. Qc3 Kf7 29. Qd3 Kg8 {With queens onthe board it is not wise to expose the monarch, and so it returns to a saferplace.} 30. Qc3 {QUESTION: What's going on here? I don't see any progress onWhite's part. --- ANSWER: You're right, but don't forget that we are studyingLasker here. By now this sort of "cat and mouse game", as Fischer calledit, should come as no surprise. Probe a little here, probe a little there, andkeep on trying, until you make some progress, albeit minimal, and try toprovoke the opponent into making a mistake. --- Let's hand over to Nunn:"Here we see another typical psychological ploy which was often used byanother World Champion, Tigran Petrosian. Lasker offers a repetition, perhapsto see if his opponent is playing for a win, or possibly to show who is incharge."} Qe6 31. Ra1 Qe8 32. Kf1 {QUESTION: I understand that Lasker ismanoeuvring, but what's the purpose of this move? --- ANSWER: At some pointLasker wants to play (or threaten to play) f3, followed by Bf2, but for thathe needs to defend the bishop;} ({however,} 32. Re1 $2 {would allow} Bxd4 {, so he defends the e1-square in readiness to play Re1 at some point in thefuture.}) 32... h6 33. Qd3 ({As after} 33. Re1 {and 34 f3 White will be unableto make progress without exchanging the rooks, Lasker postpones his idea. Ifneed be he can also opt for Rd1 and Rd3, in preparation for f3 and Bf2.}) 33...Kf7 34. Rc1 Kg8 35. Qb3 Qf7 ({Black could already play} 35... c6 {here,defending both pawns so that he could then recycle the bishop; the pawn on c6can be easily defended by the two major pieces.}) 36. Rd1 ({White can't play} 36. Qxb5 $2 {because of} Rxe3 {.}) ({Neither is} 36. f3 $2 {possible, due to}Bxd4 {, so he defends the d4-pawn, to be able to play f3.}) 36... c6 37. f3 {White makes another small improvement to his position; it doesn't change theevaluation of the position much, but seeing the opponent continue to makeprogress, even if only slightly, can have an influence on the mind of thedefending side.} Qf6 38. Qd3 Re7 39. Bf2 {Lasker has succeeded in carrying outhis idea to slightly improve his position. The bishop has more mobility fromf2, and the e-file can be occupied at any moment. As we mentioned, White'sprogress isn't very significant, but it's more than Black can claim.} Qd6 40.Qc2 {Once again putting pressure on the weakness at c6, to reduce the mobilityof the black queen.} Kf7 $6 41. Rc1 Re6 42. Qf5+ $1 Rf6 {EXERCISE: What now?} ({Now if} 42... Kg8 {then} 43. Bg3 $1) ({while after} 42... Ke7 {, having theking in the centre following} 43. Bh4+ g5 44. Qh7+ {and Bf2 is unpleasant,although there is nothing immediate and the current (2018) engines evaluatethis as a balanced position.}) 43. Qe5 $1 {ANSWER: White makes furtherprogress, exchanging the queens, since 43...Qd7 allows 44 Bg3, when thepreviously passive e3-bishop de e3 is transformed into a powerful piece on e5.--- With the exchange of queens White's kingside pawn majority increases inimportance, since now it can advance without risk to the white king; it stillisn't a big advantage, but it's another small step forward.} Re6 44. Qxd6 Rxd6{Despite the exchanges that have taken place over the last few moves theposition remains very close to equal and the most probable result is still adraw. Nevertheless this doesn't prevent White from continuing to try to makeprogress, with both long-term and short-term plans.} 45. Ke2 {Heading for d3,to free the bishop from the defence of the d4-pawn.} Ke7 {The black king forits part is going to d7, to free the rook from the defence of the c6-pawn.This one of several plans that should keep the balance.} 46. Kd3 Rg6 47. g3 ({Naturally White wants to keep his kingside pawns flexible, rather than rushingforward with} 47. g4 $6 {, when after} Rf6 {and ...Bc7 there would be anunnecessary weakness on f3.}) 47... Rf6 48. f4 Kd7 49. Re1 Rf8 50. Ra1 h5 {This move, which guarantees the exchange of a pawn if White plays g4, issufficient to hold the position.} ({Nunn suggested something more active:} 50... g5 51. Be3 Bc7 52. fxg5 hxg5 {, "when Black's pieces displayconsiderable activity; for example, after} 53. Ra7 Kc8 54. Ra8+ Bb8 55. Bxg5Kb7 56. Ra3 Bxg3 {White has no advantage at all."}) 51. Be3 g6 {EXERCISE:How did Lasker continue here? --- ANSWER:} 52. Rf1 {Preparing g4 and in thefuture the advance f5.} Kd6 ({Kasparov suggested} 52... Ke6 53. g4 Bc7 $1 {, when "White has made all his useful moves - what is he to do next? Thecomputer 'looks at' the sharp} 54. f5+ $1 gxf5 55. Bh6 $1 {",} {Today'sengines prefer the simpler} Rg8 {; now 56 g5 is bad, since the pawn can'tadvance and the bishop is out of play on h6, but after} ({and here analyzes} 55... Rf7 56. g5 {, with complicated lines in which Black manages to hold.} (56. Z0)) 56. gxf5+ Kf6 57. h4 Rg3+ 58. Kc2 ({or} 58. Ke2 Rb3) 58... Bb6 59.Bg5+ Kf7 60. Re1 Rf3 {, and after ...Bxd4 the rook and bishop neutralize thef-pawn.}) 53. g4 {Another small step forward; White is very close to beingable to create a passed pawn.} hxg4 54. hxg4 c5 $2 {And finally one of thebest endgame players in history commits a decisive error. Tired of playing catand mouse, he does not want to carry on waiting and creates his own passedpawn, but this leads to a win for White.} ({It isn't clear whether preventing55 f5 with} 54... Ke6 {would be losing after} 55. Rh1 {and Rh6;}) ({but thesimplest was to occupy the h-file himself with} 54... Rh8 $1 {, when after} 55.f5 gxf5 56. gxf5 {a waiting move such as} Kd7 {should be sufficient, planning57...Bc7-d6, for example, and White's passed pawn isn't dangerous after, say,}57. f6 Ke6 58. Bg5 Kf7 {.}) 55. dxc5+ Bxc5 56. Bxc5+ Kxc5 57. f5 {Of course."White creates an outside passed pawn, with his rook ideally placed, 'à laTarrasch', as though urging on the passed pawn from behind, whereas the blackrook is passive. The white king is also well placed: it stands in the path ofthe opponent's passed pawn, securely blocking it", as Averbakh commented.}gxf5 58. gxf5 Rf6 {Restraining the pawn; one of the keys to this endgame isthat if Black captures the white f-pawn and loses his d-pawn, White capturesthe b5-pawn and the black king can't get across in time to occupy b7 afterKxb5 in a pawn ending.} ({Here's the line given by Averbakh without exchangingrooks:} 58... d4 59. f6 Kd5 60. f7 Ke5 61. b4 Kd5 62. Rf4 Ke5 63. Re4+ Kf5 64.Re1 $1 Kf6 65. Kxd4 Rd8+ 66. Kc5 Kxf7 67. Kxb5 {and wins.}) 59. Rf4 b4 {There is no longer a defence; Black is in zugzwang. After 59...Kd6 60 Kd4 heloses as in the game.} ({The most tenacious defence is} 59... d4 {, but after}60. Ke4 Rd6 61. Rf3 $1 Kc4 {White wins with} 62. f6 $1 {:} Re6+ {also losesafter} ({for example,} 62... d3 63. f7 d2 ({or} 63... Rd4+ 64. Ke5 d2 65. Rc3+Kb4 66. f8=Q+ {mating}) 64. f8=Q d1=Q 65. Qc8+ {mating}) 63. Kf5 Re3 ({or} 63... Re8 64. f7 Rf8 65. b3+ Kb4 66. Kf6 {, followed by Ke7 or Kg7 and Blackdoesn't create a passed pawn}) 64. Rf4 Re8 65. f7 Rf8 66. Ke6 b4 67. Ke7 Ra868. f8=Q Rxf8 69. Kxf8 {, followed by Kd6-c5 with an easy win.}) 60. b3 Rf7 61.f6 Kd6 62. Kd4 Ke6 63. Rf2 $1 Kd6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker begin the decisivemanoeuvre?} ({As before, after} 63... Rxf6 64. Rxf6+ Kxf6 65. Kxd5 Ke7 66. Kc4Kd6 67. Kxb4 Kc6 68. Ka5 {, the black king is unable to gain the opposition.})64. Ra2 $1 {ANSWER: This manoeuvre became a classic. "All this is rathersimple and at the same time instructive. Black has stopped the pawn's advance,but now he is helpless against the attack by the rook from the flank. White isthreatening to exchange rooks," commented Levenfish and Smyslov.} Rc7 65.Ra6+ Kd7 66. Rb6 $1 ({Even 'falling into the trap' with} 66. Kxd5 Rc3 {winsfor White due to} 67. Ra8 $1 {.}) ({After} 66. Rb6 {Black resigned; a possiblefinish was} Rc3 67. Rxb4 Rf3 68. Ke5 Rd3 ({or} 68... Rf1 69. Rf4) 69. Rb8 Rf370. f7 Ke7 71. f8=Q+ {.}) (66. Z0 {However, after Lasker's excellent startthings went badly; in the next four games he gained only one and a half points.After the ninth round Capablanca was the overwhelming leader, with 6/8,followed by Marshall on 5½ (out of 9), Alekhine, Tarrasch and Bernstein with5/8. Lasker trailed in sixth, outside the qualification places, with 4½/8.Things were going even worse for Rubinstein, who had just 4/8. --- Lasker wona vital game against Janowski in the tenth round to be among the qualifiers.--- With another victory in the eleventh and final preliminary round Laskermanaged to qualify for the final section with 6½/10, together with Tarrasch,but behind Capablanca, who scored 8/10. The other two qualifiers were Alekhineand Marshall with six points, while Rubinstein only scored 50% and so did notqualify for the final. --- As previously mentioned, Capablanca carried forwarda lead of no less than a point and a half into the final, a considerableadvantage considering that there were only eight games left to play. Laskerwould have to play to win in every game, with much depending on the outcome ofhis two encounters with Capablanca.}) 1-0[Event "36: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1914.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Alekhine, A"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D08"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "69"][EventDate "1914.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker defeated Alekhine in the first round in a complex and hard-fought game.Let's take a look at it.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 e5 {Alekhine played the AlbinCountergambit only twice in his career, both of them in the St. Petersburgevent.} 3. dxe5 {Lasker accepts the gambit, which is considered best.} ({In the tenth round of the preliminaries Tarrasch played the more modest} 3. e3{and Alekhine experienced no difficulties.}) 3... d4 4. Nf3 Nc6 5. a3 Bg4 6.Nbd2 Qe7 7. h3 Bxf3 ({QUESTION: Giving up the bishop pair is a concession inthe long run, isn't it? Is this a good idea? --- ANSWER: More usual is} 7...Bh5 {, but as is the case in nearly all gambits, Black prefers not to lose anytime and to speed up his development.}) 8. Nxf3 O-O-O 9. Qd3 ({Lasker is notinterested in consolidating his extra pawn with} 9. Bg5 {, because Black hasadequate compensation after} f6 10. exf6 gxf6 11. Bf4 Bh6 $1 {when Black'spieces are quickly activated, while White is poorly developed.}) ({The queenmove is useful; it prevents a timely ...d3, connects the rooks, etc, but it'snot clear that it's better than} 9. g3 {.}) 9... h6 $6 {QUESTION: Didn't youjust say that Black wanted to speed up his development? How do you explainthis move? --- ANSWER: Black wants to regain his pawn with ...g6 and ...Bg7,without fearing 10 Bg5 which would allow White to retain the extra pawn. But Iagree, this move is almost a 'betrayal' of the gambit spirit.} ({Tarraschpointed out that if} 9... Nxe5 {then} 10. Qf5+ Nd7 11. Nxd4 {preserves theextra pawn, but this is playable for Black, since after} g6 $1 {he has goodcompensation, thanks to White's lag in development: for instance,} 12. Qc2 ({Black can even afford the luxury of allowing the exchange of queens after} 12.Qg5 Bg7 13. Qxe7 Nxe7 {, followed by ...Nc5, ...Rhe8, etc, depending on whatWhite plays, and once again White has development problems}) 12... Nc5 13. Be3Bh6 $1 {, and Black activates quickly his pieces quickly, while the white kingis still in the centre.}) ({Another reasonable idea is to play an immediate} 9... f6 {, sacrificing the pawn for development.}) 10. g3 g6 11. Bg2 Bg7 ({Since there is no Qf5+, it was possible to capture the pawn with} 11... Nxe512. Nxe5 Qxe5 {, but that would allow} 13. Bf4 {, developing with a gain oftime.}) 12. O-O Nxe5 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker now continue? ---ANSWER:} 14. b4 $1 {White wasn't interested in hanging on to his extra pawn.He wanted to reach an opposite-side castling position in which he has theadvantage of the safer king and the more advanced pawns on the attacking wing.In such situations it's essential to open lines and for that it's necessary toadvance the pawns.} f5 {Black prepares a future ...f4.} ({It wasn't possiblefor him to complete his development with} 14... Nf6 $4 {due to} 15. f4 Bd6 16.c5 {, trapping the bishop.}) 15. c5 $1 {Of course. The support of theg2-bishop favours the rapid opening of lines; there is no good defence against16 c6.} Qe6 {Since ...Nf6 remains impossible, the queen vacates e7 for theknight.} 16. c6 Ne7 {"The best defence under the circumstances; if Black'sown pawns don't give adequate defence for their King then the King will takeshelter behind the enemy pawns", commented Euwe.} ({After} 16... bxc6 {White can play in several ways: for instance,} 17. Bd2 ({or} 17. Bb2 {,followed by Rac1 and Rc5, depending on how Black plays, with Qa6+ at the rightmoment. White's attack is almost automatic.})) 17. cxb7+ Kb8 18. Bb2 {White'sadvantage is huge. It's true that the white pawn on b7 shelters the blackmonarch, but this is only temporary. White had several options here; Laskerdecided to develop his bishop on b2 to put pressure on d4, in order torestrict Black's counterplay.} (18. Bd2 {was also reasonable, leaving thebishop in a more active position, with Rac1 to follow, as in the game.}) ({Euwe suggested another possibility attractive: "} 18. b5 {followed by a4-a5,Ba3-c5, and eventually the powerful breakthrough with b6".}) 18... Rd6 19.Rac1 Rhd8 {The evaluation hasn't changed over the last few moves: White isobjectively winning; he has an extra pawn and the black king is weak, butvictory is still a long way ahead. --- For his part, Black doesn't have muchin the way of counterplay. One plan to improve his pieces is to play ...Nd5-c3;another is to try to break with ...f4, but after the reply g4 the white kingwill be safe; his bishop is good defender, even in the event of the opening ofthe h-file with ...h5. Black will be unable to exploit the file except at thecost of many tempi and diverting forces from the queenside.} 20. Rc2 {Laskercan choose among various way to deploy his pieces, but in the next phase hefails to play the most energetic move on several occasions.} ({Lasker himselfin the tournament book pointed out that "} 20. Qc4 {is stronger", sincethe endgame is advantageous to White; without the queens the extra pawn willgain in importance and in the meantime} Nd5 $2 {is prevented due to} 21. Bxd4 {.}) ({Nunn suggested preventing ...Nd5 without exchanging the queens by playing} 20. Qc2 {, when} Nd5 $2 {, fails to} ({while after} 20... R6d7 21. Rfd1 {once again} Nd5 {is prevented because of} 22. Bxd4) 21. Bxd4 Bxd4 22. Bxd5 {due to the mate in c7.}) ({Another good move is} 20. Rc5 {, which allows} Nd5 {, but after} 21. Rfc1 Nc3 22. Bf3 {Black's activity is curtailed and Whiteplans 23 b5, 23 e3, or 23 Rc2 first, etc.}) 20... f4 21. gxf4 ({This isn't abad decision, but isn't clear that it's better than} 21. g4 {. Admittedly thiswould allow} Nd5 {, since} 22. Bxd4 $2 {, is unplayable due to} ({as such,White must allow ...Nc3, but after, for instance,} 22. Rc5 Nc3 {we reach thesame position as after the suggestion 20 Rc5 above, with a tempo less, butWhite still has a big advantage after} 23. Rc1 {, followed by a consolidatingmove such as Bf3 and/or Rc2. He can then make progress on the queenside withb5 and a4, without fearing ...Nxa4, since this would open the a-file;meanwhile Black doesn't seem to have any dangerous plans available}) 22... Bxd423. Qxd4 Ne3 {.}) 21... Bxf4 22. Rd1 {White prevents 22...Nd5? because of 23Bxd4! and then after 23...Nxb4 24 Qc3 the lines have opened to White's benefit.Black therefore looks for another way to activate his knight.} ({Once againthere were other attractive moves, such as} 22. Bc1 {.}) 22... Nf5 23. Bc1 $2 {EXERCISE: It would suit Lasker to exchange the bishops, which would allow himto regain control of important squares such as c1. However, despite his havingavoided making a tactical mistake on the previous move, this move has atactical flaw - what is it?} ({Lasker could now retain a large part of hisadvantage with} 23. Qc4 $1 Qxc4 ({it wouldn't be good for Black to retreat thequeen to defend c7 with} 23... Qe7 {since then White could play} 24. Bc1 $1 {in favourable circumstances}) 24. Rxc4 {.}) ({EXERCISE: Here} 23. Qe4 {wassuggested as winning, since if} Qb3 {then} 24. Bc1 Bxc1 25. Rdxc1 R6d7 26. Qf4Qf7 27. b5 {. Identify the error in this analysis!}) ({ANSWER: As Euwecommented, "Lasker always had his weather eye open for tactical pitfalls. Heknew exactly what he was doing when he rejected} 23. Qe4 Qb3 24. Bc1 d3 $1 {which puts an entirely different complexion on the game, with Black winning atleast the Exchange". It's true that Black has no advantage, though, after}25. Rxd3 $1 Rxd3 26. Bxf4 Qxc2 27. exd3 {, since} Qxd3 $2 {loses to} 28. Bxc7+$1 Kxc7 29. b8=Q+ {.}) 23... Ne3 $1 {ANSWER: With this elegant leap, surelyoverlooked by Lasker, Alekhine complicates the game and takes the initiative;White is no longer better.} 24. Rc5 {"As usual Lasker is at his best when itcomes to a scrimmage" (Euwe). Lasker recovers from the surprise.} ({He avoids} 24. fxe3 $2 dxe3 {, when the only move to avoid defeat is} 25. Rc6 $1 {and Black is slightly better after} Rxd3 26. Rxd3 Qe7 {.}) 24... Qf6 {Thescenario has changed.} ({Now} 24... Nxd1 $2 {isn't to be feared due to} 25.Bxf4 Nc3 26. Bxd6 Rxd6 ({better than} 26... cxd6 27. Qa6 $1) 27. Bf3 {, when}Qxh3 {loses to} 28. Rxc7 $1 {.}) ({In addition to the text move Black hadseveral others which keep the balance, such as} 24... g5) ({or} 24... Bg5 {, threatening to take on d1, followed by 25...Nxg2, and the b7-pawn is doomed.}) 25. Qe4 ({Lasker maintains the tension, rejecting the quiet line} 25. Re1Nxg2 26. Kxg2 Rd5 ({or} 26... Rf8 27. f3 {, when the chances of unbalancingare very few; his move isn't objectively better, but leaves the position morecomplicated.})) 25... Nxd1 $6 {There were three main options to consider hereand this is possibly the worst of the three.} ({It was better to play} 25...Bh2+ $1 26. Kxh2 Nxd1 27. Bf4 Nxf2 28. Bxd6 Qxd6+ {with check, thanks to 25...Bh2+;} ({on the other hand,} 28... Nxe4 $4 {allows mate following} 29. Bxc7+)29. Qe5 {.}) ({The third possibility was to interpolate} 25... Re6 26. Qf3 {, and now once again} Bh2+ $1 {, this time to exchange queens, and after} 27.Kxh2 Qxf3 28. Bxf3 {White gains compensation for the exchange after} Nxd1 29.Bf4 {, when the most likely result is a draw.}) 26. Bxf4 Nc3 $2 {EXERCISE: Nowthis move really is a blunder, so what should Black have played?} ({ANSWER: AsEuwe pointed out, after "} 26... Nxf2 $3 27. Bxd6 Rxd6 {attack and defencemay have remained in equilibrium". Doubtless Lasker would have continuedambitiously with} 28. Qe8+ Rd8 29. Qe5 Qxe5 30. Rxe5 d3 31. exd3 Nxd3 32. Re3Nf4 33. Bc6 {, and although the material is much reduced, White retainspractical chances.}) 27. Bxd6 $1 Qxd6 ({As in the line with 25...Bh2+!analyzed above, now} 27... Nxe4 {allows mate after} 28. Bxc7+ Kxb7 29. Bxe4+ {.}) 28. Qe5 {And White once again has the advantage; now he will keep an extrapawn.} Qb6 $2 {Black doesn't want to exchange queens now, but this move isweak.} 29. Qe7 $6 {EXERCISE: Lasker remains much better after this, but he hadsomething slightly stronger. What was it?} ({ANSWER: After} 29. Rc6 $1 Qxb7 {the long diagonal has been opened and White can win in several ways; thecomputer indicates} 30. Qf6 ({a more human solution perhaps is} 30. b5 {, also followed by Kh2, and White will win material with the discovered attack}) ({but not the hasty} 30. Rxc3 $2 dxc3 31. Bxb7 c2 {, and Black wins}) 30...Rd7 31. Kh2 {, and the knight is lost.}) 29... Qd6 {A sad return, but there isnothing better;} ({if} 29... Rh8 {now then} 30. Rc6 Qxb7 {and this time} 31.Rxc3 {wins.}) 30. Re5 d3 ({Exchanging queens is hopeless since after} 30...Qxe7 31. Rxe7 {the strong bishop and the extra pawn will soon count: forexample,} Nd5 (31... g5 {isn't any better in view of} 32. Re6 {, for instance,followed by Kf1, Bc6, and once again White slowly improves his position andBlack is defenceless}) 32. Re4 Nf6 33. Re6 Rd6 34. Rxd6 cxd6 35. Bc6 {,followed by activating the king.}) 31. exd3 Qxd3 32. Re3 (32. Re6 {followed by33 Rc6 is also decisive.}) 32... Qd1+ 33. Kh2 Nb5 34. Re6 $1 {Heading for thef-file,} ({but not} 34. Rf3 $6 {due to} Qd6+ {and Black can still resist.})34... Nxa3 35. Rf6 {. There is no defence against 36 Rf8.} 1-0[Event "37: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1914.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Tarrasch, S"][Result "1-0"][ECO "D30"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "91"][EventDate "1914.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{In the next round Lasker, playing Black, had to withstand tremendous pressurefrom Capablanca, but held the draw after 100 moves. He had a free day in roundthree. Let's now see Lasker's win against Tarrasch in the fourth round.} 1. d4d5 2. Nf3 c5 3. c4 e6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. g3 Nc6 6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc59. Nbd2 {QUESTION: The knight goes to d2? Isn't it better on c3? --- ANSWER:This was a new idea at the time; instead of develop his knight to c3 Whiteplays 8 dxc5 in order to play Nbd2, followed by Nb3, attacking the bishop, andfinally blockading the Isolated Queen's Pawn with Nbd4. Lasker's idea is nobetter than playing 8 Nc3; it merely opened new paths.} d4 $6 {QUESTION: Howis this dubious? It isn't it good for Black to prevent White's idea? ---ANSWER: Sometime 'the cure is worse than the disease', as in this case. Thecreator of the defence, Tarrasch himself, makes a mistake. --- While thiscertainly prevents White's idea, Black pays a high price, as we'll see. It wasbetter to allow the knight to be installed on d4, when in return Black has e4for his f6-knight and the free piece-play typical of the opening.} 10. Nb3 Bb611. Qd3 $1 {"Lasker refutes the ill-considered pawn push very shrewdly,"commented Tarrasch. The d4-pawn proves to be weak; Black must defend againstthe simple threat of 12 Rd1 winning the pawn.} Be6 {Black decides to give uphis light-squared bishop to save the pawn. Lasker will soon exploit thebishop's absence.} ({Another way to avoid the loss of a pawn was tocounter-attack against the pawn on e2, but after, for instance,} 11... O-O 12.Rd1 Qe7 13. Nbxd4 Nxd4 14. Nxd4 {Black would have to give up his dark-squaredbishop, and after} Bxd4 15. Qxd4 Qxe2 {White gains a big advantage with} 16.Bg5 {.}) 12. Rd1 Bxb3 13. Qxb3 {With the threat of 14 e3.} Qe7 14. Bd2 $1 {Modest, but Lasker has a specific idea to try to benefit from his currentlyinactive g2-bishop, highlighting the drawback of 12...Bxb3.} O-O {EXERCISE:What was Lasker's idea? --- ANSWER:} 15. a4 $1 {"An exceptionally fine move:the P is to be advanced in order to undermine the position of Black's Q sidepieces", commented Tarrasch.} Ne4 ({Black is unable to play} 15... Qxe2 $216. Re1 Qa6 17. Bf1 {, winning.}) ({Tarrasch suggested} 15... Bc5 16. a5 a6 {, admitting that White would still have the better game, but Black could haveput up greater resistance. White could continue with} 17. Bg5 {: for example,}h6 18. Bxf6 Qxf6 19. Rdc1 Qe7 20. Nh4 {; or with 17 Ne1-d3, and the whiteposition is preferable in both cases.}) 16. Be1 {Of course, it's essential toretain this bishop.} Rad8 17. a5 Bc5 {EXERCISE (simple): How did Laskercomplete his manoeuvre? --- ANSWER:} 18. a6 $1 {With the disappearance of theb7-pawn the g2-bishop acquires tremendous power.} bxa6 ({After} 18... b6 {White still maintains the advantage with} 19. Qa4 {, followed by a timely b4,according to Tarrasch. Let's go further:} Rc8 {can be answered with} 20. Nd2 $1{and after} Nxd2 ({or} 20... f5 21. Rac1 {, preparing 22 Nxe4 and 23 b4, alsowinning a pawn}) 21. Bxc6 Ne4 22. b4 {White wins a pawn.}) 19. Rac1 {This isthe culmination of the idea which began with 15 a4!. Let's appreciate whatsome illustrious commentators have to say about this game: "This is thewhole point of the preceding manoeuvres. Notice also that the advance of thea-pawn has made the White light-squared Bishop very active, for the removal ofthe Black b-pawn has weakened the whole of the long white diagonal" (Euwe).--- "Now all of Black's pieces "hang" badly, the chief threat being Nh4winning a piece" (Reinfeld and Fine).} Rc8 {EXERCISE: White's advantage isalmost decisive, as has been remarked. How did Lasker demonstrate this? ---ANSWER:} 20. Nh4 {Of course, this 'human' move is very strong, threatening towin with 21 Bxe4 Qxe4 22 Rxc5 and the leap Nf5 is also in the air.} ({Theengines indicate that first} 20. Qc2 {is even better, but it's easy tooverlook that when the most natural move is so strong.}) 20... Bb6 {This isn'tthe best response;} ({but even after the more tenacious} 20... Nf6 {Whitegains a big advantage with} 21. Nf5 Qe5 22. Qc2 Nb4 ({if} 22... Nd7 {White canwin by combining his control of the d-file with the strength of his f5-knight,in the precise manoeuvre} 23. e3 $1 dxe3 24. Bc3 $1 exf2+ 25. Kh1 $1 {,followed by 26 Bxg7 and a quick attack on the black king, followed by Qd2, forexample, which is decisive}) 23. Bxb4 Bxb4 24. Qxc8 Rxc8 25. Rxc8+ Bf8 26. Nxd4g6 27. e3 {, and White's two rooks are superior to the queen;} ({anotherpossibility is} 27. Nf3 {, threatening Rdd8 winning the bishop, but this wouldallow Black to fish in troubled waters with} Qxb2 28. Rdd8 Ne4 29. Rxf8+ Kg7 {, with ideas of 30...Qxe2 as well as of 30...Qb6 31 e3? Qb2.})) 21. Nf5 Qe5 22.Bxe4 {The most natural; White wins the exchange. It all seems logical andindeed it should win.} ({Actually, there was an intermediate move that waseven stronger:} 22. Qf3 $1 {was crushing; the power of the g2-bishop, combinedwith the other pieces, is harnessed to take advantage of the badly placedblack knights: for instance, after} Nf6 {the key move is} 23. Qf4 $1 {and after} Qxf4 24. gxf4 {Black loses a piece. --- Nevertheless, as we mentioned, 22Bxe4 is also winning, so hardly merits great criticism.}) 22... Qxe4 23. Nd6Qxe2 24. Nxc8 {EXERCISE: The planned response, which is good, but again therewas a superior alternative, although the key move wasn't easy to appreciate.How could White's play be improved?} ({ANSWER: The zwischenzug} 24. Rd2 $1 {is stronger. After} Qe5 25. Nxc8 Rxc8 {the subtle} 26. Qf3 $1 {is decisive,since Black is unable to reorganize his forces. Now, as well as attacking thec6-knight, the queen on f3 enables White to move Re2, evicting the black queenfrom the e-file and defending the e1-bishop, followed by Rec2: for example,}Qe8 ({in view of Black's numerous weaknesses (including a weak back rank),it's no surprise that after the try} 26... d3 {(to enable the counterblow ...Nd4)} 27. Rxd3 Qe8 {White's strongest move is to 'fall into the trap' with} 28.Rdc3 {, since} Nd4 29. Rxc8 Nxf3+ 30. Kh1 Bd8 {loses to} 31. Ba5) 27. Re2 $1Qd7 28. Rec2 Ne7 29. Rxc8+ Nxc8 30. Qa8 {, winning.}) 24... Rxc8 {EXERCISE:White's advantage is still decisive, and just as before there is more than onegood way forwards. Lasker now played the strongest move, but what is it? ---ANSWER:} 25. Qd5 $1 {A powerful centralization which nullifies all Black'scounterplay.} ({There was at least one other very strong move here,} 25. Rd2 {, and even though (unlike 24 Rd2, with the knight still on d6), Black now has24...Qe4 available, White should win after} Qe4 26. Rdc2 d3 27. Rc4 Qf5 {and now, for instance,} 28. Qd1 $1 {.}) 25... Qe6 ({If} 25... Qe8 {the pin onthe c-file leads to further exchanges; White would play} 26. Bd2 {,threatening to win with 27 Re1.}) 26. Qf3 $6 {Now Black is worse, but he canstill fight. This is the first move of Lasker's that clearly deservescriticism; he has overlooked a tactical point.} ({Instead,} 26. Qxe6 fxe6 {was decisive and now the first key move,} 27. f4 $1 {, preventing ...e5. Thediscovered check is of no help to Black and now White is the faster to regroup:for instance,} Rc7 ({in the event of} 27... Kf7 28. Bf2 Ke7 {White can play}29. Bxd4 $1) 28. Bf2 Kf7 29. Kg2 Ke7 {and White is in time to play} 30. Bxd4 $1{, with a winning endgame. --- As we can see, it isn't a question ofevaluation, but of calculation; without the possibility of 30 Bxd4!, winning,the position would be an onerous technical task.}) 26... h6 27. Bd2 Ne5 {The exchange of rooks was forced in view of White's plan of playing 28 Bd2,followed by Re1 and Rc4, doubling rooks on the c-file.} 28. Rxc8+ Qxc8 29. Qe4Nd7 (29... Ng4 {was more tenacious, but inadequate in the long run. This wouldallow a better regrouping after, for instance,} 30. Kg2 Qd7 31. h3 Nf6 {, when Black's pieces are better coordinated than in the game, although hisposition remains very difficult.}) 30. Rc1 Qf8 31. Bxh6 ({It's temptingcapture a pawn 'for nothing' (if 31...gxh6? then 32 Qg4+), but in fact} 31. Qg4$1 {was more effective and if} Nf6 ({or} 31... Ne5 {then White has} 32. Qf5 {, followed by 33 Rc8.}) (31... Nc5 32. Bb4 {is no more tenacious}) ({while} 31... Qd6 {allows the invasion} 32. Rc8+ Nf8 {and now, for example,} 33. Re8 {, threatening Bf4 and Qc8, or 33 Qe4, and Black is paralyzed.})) 31... Nc5 32.Qg4 f5 33. Qg6 Qf7 34. Qxf7+ Kxf7 {Although earlier Lasker gave Tarrasch somechances to prolong the struggle, from now on he plays in the most precise way.}35. Bg5 Nd3 (35... Kg6 {would merely divert the king from centre.}) 36. Rb1 Ke637. b3 {The first step to prevent an invasion by the black king.} Kd5 38. f3 $1{The black king is unable to infiltrate via c4 or e4.} a5 39. h4 $1 ({Laskerhas no need to centralize his king with} 39. Rf1 {; he can utilize hiskingside majority in an original manner.}) 39... Nc5 40. h5 d3 41. Kf1 a4 $2 {Lasker expected this; Black achieves several things: he exchanges his doubledpawn, he gains two passed pawns, he activates his knight, but... there is animportant snag.} (41... Ne6 42. Bd2 Nd4 {was more tenacious, but wouldn't havesaved the game in the long run.}) 42. bxa4 Nxa4 {EXERCISE: How did Laskerseize the initiative? --- ANSWER:} 43. Bf6 $1 {This is the neat complement tothe idea initiated with 39 h4!. White wins a pawn and his h-pawn becomespassed.} Ke6 44. Bxg7 Kf7 45. Be5 Nc5 46. Rd1 {. Tarrasch, who was so criticalof Lasker for many years, acknowledged Lasker's tremendous playing strength (which was not without errors), and commented: "Lasker again produced awonderful game. He played 'not according to the rules', in 'ultra-modern'style, sharply for a win. Lasker took a serious risk! He was in a difficultposition. But that is his style. --- "His opponents play objectivelycorrectly and obtain good positions, but, strangely enough, Lasker never loses.No one has the right to reproach him for his skill in playing in this style.We must merely again and again be surprised by him. For participating in thetournament Lasker received an enormous fee - 4,000 roubles. I don't findthis too high. Who else could play like this! Patrons don't give their moneylightly, and if in future Lasker will play like this, he deserves much greaterfees." --- With this victory Lasker was at last able to catch up by half apoint. After the first cycle of the final, with four games left, Capablancaled with 11/14, followed by Lasker with 10; further behind were Alekhine (8½), Marshall (7) and Tarrasch (6½).} 1-0[Event "38: St. Petersburg"][Site "?"][Date "1914.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Capablanca, JR"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C68"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "83"][EventDate "1914.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{With his win against Alekhine in the next round, and thanks to Capablancahaving a free day, Lasker shared first place temporarily with Capablanca with11 points, but having played one game more than him. In the second round ofthe second cycle of the final, one of the most famous encounters in thehistory of chess occurred: Lasker vs. Capablanca. Let's look at it.} 1. e4 e52. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 {Although it is no surprise to see Lasker playingthe Exchange variation, it is certainly rather surprising for him to do so inthis game of such almost decisive importance which, as we have pointed out,Lasker was virtually obliged to win against Capablanca to have any chances ofvictory in the tournament.} dxc6 5. d4 {QUESTION: What's this? He exchangesqueens right in the opening, when he needs to win?} ({ANSWER: You're right.Perhaps this decision is the really surprising one; Lasker eschews hisfavourite move,} 5. Nc3 {, and prefers to exchange the queens. ---Nevertheless, this is in no way reflects a reduction in the ambition to win.Lasker preferred a long game, without much debate in the opening, keeping upthe tension. This is not a simplified position heading for a draw; there isstill a lot of life in the position and, as we'll see, Lasker 'played withfire', and very soon complicated the endgame. --- This strategy of postponingthe struggle became more common in later years. The most famous case isKasparov vs. Karpov, in the 24th and final game of their Seville 1987 match;Kasparov had to win in order to retain the title, and he succeeded. Lasker'sgame attracts more attention because it is without queens on the board, andagainst Capablanca, who had not lost a single game in the tournament up untilthen; it's very surprising, but... it worked.}) 5... exd4 6. Qxd4 Qxd4 7. Nxd4Bd6 {QUESTION: Tell me what's happening here? --- ANSWER: The first importantdecision for Black is where to place his monarch. Capablanca opted to deployhis king on the kingside; this is how he explained it: "His reason is thatthe King should remain on the weaker side to oppose later the advance ofWhite's pawns. Theoretically there is very much to be said in favour of thisreasoning, but whether in practice that would be the best system would berather difficult to prove."} ({Capablanca's doubts received confirmationwhen subsequently} 7... Bd7 {, with the plan of queenside castling, became themost usual move.}) 8. Nc3 Ne7 9. O-O O-O 10. f4 {Lasker increases the tensionwith this risky move, which can leave the e-pawn exposed, as well as forceWhite to worry about ...Bc5. Capablanca considered it a bad move.} ({Laskerwas naturally aware of its drawbacks, but he considered that the natural} 10.Be3 {wasn't sufficiently ambitious.}) 10... Re8 $1 ({Black doesn't need to play} 10... f6 {yet; it is playable, but Capablanca's move is better, threatening11...Bc5 12 Be3 Nd5. As Capablanca's later comments indicate, it's possiblethat he was already playing for a win, encouraged by Lasker's risky set-up.}) ({Tarrasch suggested} 10... f5 {: for example,} 11. e5 Bc5 12. Be3 Bxd4 ({it's also possible to play} 12... b6 {, before exchanging on d4}) 13. Bxd4 b6 {.}) 11. Nb3 {A retreat;} ({but} 11. Be3 {is inappropriate because of} Nf5 {.})11... f6 {Capablanca makes a good move, which he explained thus:"Preparatory to ...b7-b6, followed by ...c6-c5 and ...Bb7 in conjunctionwith ...Ng6, which would put White in great difficulties to meet the combinedattack against the two centre pawns".} ({His position is so good that therewere even two somewhat better moves than 11...f6, since 12 e5 is not really athreat while the d6-bishop has the b4-square available, and it would justleave d5 and f5 weak. It was slightly more accurate to play} 11... b6 $1 {;}) ({and even more energetic was} 11... a5 $1 {to exploit the retreat 11 Nb3; thenafter} 12. e5 $6 ({while after} 12. a4 b6 13. Bd2 Ng6 {, followed by ...Bb7the black position is excellent}) 12... Bb4 {White is in difficulties.}) 12. f5{This surprising move received much praise. "A surprising and courageousmove," wrote Reinfeld and Fine, and it is easy to agree, but not with theend of the sentence, "which gives White a definite advantage". --- As wehave already seen, it was not uncommon for Lasker to play moves of this kind,which can be defined as a movement which gives up squares, in exchange forobtaining others (see Game 28, against Salwe). --- Naturally, Lasker was awarethat the second part of the comment by Reinfeld and Fine was doubtful, and inthe tournament book he wrote: "Black did not anticipate this advance. It hasthe weakness of leaving the e-pawn backward, at which Black may now direct hisshots with ease. But, in compensation, not only does it shorten the line ofBlack's queen's bishop, but it narrows the scope of his knight, and prolongsthe line of White's bishop". --- Capablanca was critical: "It has beenwrongly claimed that this wins the game, but I would like nothing better thanto have such a position again. It required several mistakes on my part finallyto obtain a lost position". --- QUESTION: Well then, who is right,Capablanca or Lasker? --- ANSWER: It's quite possible that objective truth isonly one of the factors in this struggle. If I must choose between one or theother, I would lean slightly towards Capablanca's view, but that is of noimportance, given the circumstances. The other factors are that the game wasvery important from the competitive point of view and for both of them it washard to remain objective. --- Capablanca was in the lead (he and Lasker wereon equal points, but he still had a game in hand). We assume that before thegame a draw was quite satisfactory for him, but if in this position he thoughthe was better then it is natural that he would want to play for a win, tostrike a decisive blow. Playing for two results is difficult, even for thegiants of the chessboard. --- Another factor which influences White's decisionis that Black has a good position, and even threatens to gain an advantage ifthe game continues quietly, in other words if Black is allowed to play ...b6, ...c5 and ...Bb7, putting pressure on e4, followed by improving his knight.White is therefore obliged to do something radical, even though it means thathis kingside pawn majority loses some of its strength; a passed pawn is moredifficult to create now, but there was no alternative. --- It's notable that12 f5 is the top choice of the currently (2018) strongest engines, althoughthey don't consider the white position to be superior. We shouldn't forgetthat Fischer used the very same strategy, 14 f5!, in a similar positionagainst Unzicker, in Siegen in 1970. --- Let us also remember finally whatKramnik commented in this respect: "Lasker realized that it's possible toweaken the square e5, because it was difficult to be used. But everybody beganto speak about psychological approach! It's not psychology; Lasker discoveredthe profound concept, which now is used automatically: he let the opponenthave the square e5, but he obstructed the bishop at c8. He was the first torealize it so deeply. The whole point is not in psychology, but in deepinsight of the position."} b6 13. Bf4 Bb7 {Lasker wrote: "Capablancadecided upon this move only after prolonged deliberation.} ({The alternativewas} 13... Bxf4 14. Rxf4 c5 {, in this case White will be unable to establisha knight on e6, but would exchange rooks on the Q file and, virtually, be apawn ahead e.g.} 15. Rd1 Bb7 16. Rf2 Rad8 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Rd2 Rxd2 19. Nxd2 {. Many complications might yet arise, but with best play, White can retain aslight advantage". --- As we shall see, Capablanca was far from convinced ofthe accuracy of this variation.}) ({QUESTION: I have two! Firstly, Lasker'sphrase "White will be unable to establish a knight on e6" makes me doubtwhether 12 f5 really concedes squares to gain other squares, and, secondly,how is it that Capablanca didn't play} 13... Bxf4 {- ? --- ANSWER: Of course,12 f5 gained the e6-square only as a result of poor play by Capablanca, butlet's remember that the position promises White nothing good without thisattempt. --- The fact that Capablanca thought for a long time deciding betweentwo continuations that both seemed good, but were very different, was apractical success on Lasker's part. --- With respect to the second question,this is what Capablanca wrote: "Played against my better judgment. The rightmove of course was 13...Bxf4. Dr. Lasker gives the following variation:} 14.Rxf4 c5 15. Rd1 Bb7 16. Rf2 Rad8 ({But, as Nimzowitsch pointed out immediatelyafter the game, 16...Rad8 given in Dr. Lasker's variation, is not the best. If} 16... Rac8 $1 {then White will have great difficulty in drawing the game,since there is no good way to stop Black from playing ...Nc6, followed by ...Ne5, threatening ...Nc4. And should White attempt to meet this manoeuvre bywithdrawing the Knight at b3, then the Black Knight can go to d4, and theWhite pawn at e4 will be the object of the attack}) 17. Rxd8 Rxd8 18. Rd2 Rxd219. Nxd2 {and he claims that White has the best of it. --- "Taking Dr.Lasker's variation, however, whatever advantage there might be disappears atonce if Black plays} Nc6 {threatening 20...Nb4 and also 20...Nd4, neither ofwhich can be stopped. If White answers} 20. Nd5 {then} Nd4 {for Black will atleast draw. In fact, after 19...Nc6 Black threatens so many things that it isdifficult to see how White can prevent the loss of one or more pawns." ---The current engines see equality in this line of Lasker and Capablanca, butthe practical evaluation is different.}) 14. Bxd6 cxd6 15. Nd4 {"It's acurious but true fact that I did not see this move when I played 13...Bb7,otherwise I would have played the right move 13...Bxf4" is the surprisingcomment by Capablanca.} Rad8 $6 {It seems that Capablanca was in a quandary asto whether to defend and fight for a draw or risk playing to win. With thismove he chose the second option. "The game is yet far from lost, as againstthe entry of the Knight, Black can later on play ...c6-c5, followed by ...d6-d5", he commented.} ({As Kasparov pointed out, the best way to achieveequality was} 15... Bc8 $1 16. Rad1 c5 {: for example,} 17. Ne6 ({after both} 17. Nde2) ({and} 17. Nb3 {Black can play} d5 $1 {: for example,} 18. Nxd5 Nxd519. exd5 Re5 {and Black regains the pawn; it would be risky to give the blackbishop more scope with} 20. g4 {, in view of} Bb7 21. d6 Rd8 {, followed by 22...h5 or 22...Re4}) 17... Bxe6 18. fxe6 Rad8 19. Nd5 Nc6 $1 20. Nxb6 Rxe6 21.Rfe1 Rde8 22. Kf2 {, with equality.}) 16. Ne6 Rd7 17. Rad1 Nc8 {QUESTION: Idon't understand this move. What's the point of it? --- ANSWER: This isanother change of plan on the part of Capablanca. We can safely say that thisis one of only very few games in which Capablanca's play was so indecisive.But if he lacked a clear plan in this case, this is something for which Laskercan claim some credit.} ({Capablanca wrote about his last move: "I now wason the point of playing} 17... c5 {to be followed by ...d6-d5, which I thoughtwould give me a draw, but suddenly I became ambitious and thought that I couldplay the text move and later on sacrifice the Exchange for the Knight at e6and win a pawn for it, and leaving White's e-pawn still weaker. I intended tocarry out this plan either before or after playing ...g7-g5 as thecircumstances demanded. Now let us analyze:} {Again} 18. Rf2 ({If} 18. Nd5 Bxd519. exd5 b5 {and a careful analysis will show that Black has nothing to fear.Black's plan in this case would be to work his Knight around to e5 via c8, b6,and c4 or d7." --- In this line it was subsequently considered that 18 Nd5gave White some advantage, specifically after 19...b5 the suggestedimprovement was} 20. g4 Nc8 21. Rf3 Nb6 22. Rg3 Kh8 ({there is no reason toplay 22...Kh8 yet though and Black can play immediately} 22... Nc4 {and 23...Ne5, when White's initiative doesn't seem very dangerous, but nevertheless itis certain that Black can only aspire to a draw}) 23. Kh1 {, followed by h4and g5.}) 18... d5 19. exd5 Bxd5 20. Nxd5 ({best, since if} 20. Rfd2 Bxe6 {gives Black the advantage}) 20... Rxd5 21. Rxd5 Nxd5 {and there is no goodreason why Black should lose.}) 18. Rf2 b5 19. Rfd2 Rde7 {EXERCISE: Of courseit is clear that Black intends to sacrifice the exchange on e6. How do youthink Lasker reacted? --- ANSWER:} 20. b4 $1 {Saying something like 'Sacrificeif you want to, but I'm going to be able to open lines in the future for mytwo rooks with a timely a4'.} Kf7 21. a3 Ba8 ({Capablanca's commentary is veryinformative: "Once more changing my plan and this time without any goodreason. Had I now played} 21... Rxe6 22. fxe6+ Rxe6 {as I intended to do whenI went back with the Knight to c8, I doubt very much if White would have beenable to win the game. At least it would have been extremely difficult." ---This latest change of plan shows how uncomfortable Capablanca is feeling. Hedoesn't want to wait passively to see whether White's material advantage after21...Rxe6 can be realized and so he seeks counterplay. Delaying the exchangesacrifice can be criticized, but the idea behind playing 21...Ba8 is even moredubious; he wants to create counterplay by opening the a-file, but in the gamethis just helps White.}) 22. Kf2 Ra7 {EXERCISE: Black will open the a-file, sohow do think Lasker responded? --- ANSWER:} 23. g4 $1 {Lasker has clear plansand carries them out even if some aspects of them are dubious. In this casethe idea is to prepare g5; it's an excellent idea that is already familiar tous.} h6 24. Rd3 a5 $6 25. h4 axb4 26. axb4 Rae7 ({"This, of course, has noobject now. Black, with a bad game, flounders around for a move. It would havebeen better to play} 26... Ra3 {to keep the open file, and at the same time tothreaten to come out with the Knight at b6 and c4", commented Capablanca.However, this line is unconvincing; a possible continuation is the powerfulmove} 27. g5 $1 {, since after} hxg5 28. hxg5 fxg5 29. Nxg5+ {Black can't play}Kf6 $2 {, due to} ({while if} 29... Kg8 {then} 30. Rh1 {with a decisive attackalong the h-file}) 30. Nd5+ cxd5 31. Rxa3 {, threatening Rxa8.}) 27. Kf3 {With this move White maintains his advantage, but, as on other occasions,Lasker failed to follow his own advice: "When you see a good move, look fora better one."} ({Both} 27. Kg3 $1 {(Capablanca)}) ({and especially} 27. g5$1 {(Nunn) are more incisive, but it seems that Lasker wanted to pass the timecontrol before taking concrete measures. Once again, Lasker takes account ofthe practical aspect.}) 27... Rg8 28. Kf4 g6 ({Capablanca suggested} 28... g5+{, but it is not a great improvement. After the withdrawal of the king to f3or g3, it is a question of time before White masses on the h-file and opens itat the most convenient moment. --- Capablanca commented: "White has it allhis own way, and finishes the game most accurately, and Black becomes morehelpless with each move. The game needs no further comment, excepting that myplay throughout was of an altogether irresolute character. When a plan is made,it must be carried out if at all possible. Regarding the play of White, Iconsider his 10th and 12th moves were very weak; he played well after that upto the 27th move, which was bad, as well as his 28th move. The rest of hisplay was good, probably perfect." We can agree with Capablanca's criticismsof the moves 10 f4 and 12 f5, since they both have drawbacks that could havebeen exploited. But 27 Kf3 and 28 Kf4 don't really deserve censure; these onlydelay the conclusion, without allowing any improvements on the part of theopponent.}) 29. Rg3 {"Preparatory to Rdg1 and g5", commented Lasker.} ({White's advantage is so great that he could already play} 29. g5 {, but thereis no need to rush.}) 29... g5+ ({The exchange sacrifice} 29... Rxe6 30. fxe6+Kxe6 {would give only practical chances; White has many plans available,including} 31. Rgd3 {, followed by Ne2 and h5, seeking invasion squares forthe knight.} ({Nunn analyzes} 31. g5 {deeply and concludes that it's alsowinning.})) 30. Kf3 Nb6 31. hxg5 hxg5 {EXERCISE: What did Lasker play now? ---ANSWER:} 32. Rh3 $1 {"The open h-file is worth more than a pawn",commented Lasker.} ({This is much stronger than} 32. Rxd6 Nc4 {, followed by33...Ne5+.}) 32... Rd7 ({In the event of} 32... Nc4 {one way to make progressis} 33. Kg3 {, intending 34 Ra1, threatening Rh7+, and also preparing a shotthat we should keep in mind, 34 e5!, making way, after 34...Nxe5, for 35 Ne4,with unstoppable threats.}) 33. Kg3 {"This threatens e5" (Lasker). Just asin the note to 32...Nc4, the white king moves out of range of checks in orderto carry out this advance at the most favourable moment.} Ke8 {"Thus thethreat is defended, but only temporarily", commented Lasker, although infact it was still possible to play 34 e5!. However, as throughout the game,once the advantage became a big one, and in the absence of any counterplay,Lasker keeps improving his position before undertaking any more drasticmeasures.} 34. Rdh1 Bb7 {EXERCISE: And now? What did Lasker play? --- ANSWER:}35. e5 $1 {Finally! The invasion by the knight is decisive.} dxe5 36. Ne4 Nd537. N6c5 ({There were several winning moves here, for instance,} 37. Rh8 {before N6c5.}) 37... Bc8 38. Nxd7 Bxd7 39. Rh7 Rf8 40. Ra1 $1 {Bringing theother rook into play quickly terminates the game.} Kd8 41. Ra8+ Bc8 42. Nc5 {. "This fine game uniquely epitomizes Lasker's genius" (Reinfeld and Fine).--- This win by Lasker had an unexpected consequence. He was free the next day,but Capablanca lost unexpectedly to the tail-ender, Tarrasch. As early as thefourteenth move he made a serious tactical error which led to his losing apiece, and although he fought on tenaciously, he had to resign after 82 moves.--- Lasker now had a one-point lead, which was reduced to half a point beforethe final round, meaning that, in order to be sure of winning the tournament,he had to defeat Marshall, and he did so. --- The result was: "1. Lasker -13½ out of 18; Capablanca - 13; 3. Alekhine - 10; 4. Tarrasch - 8½; 5.Marshall - 8. And he showed that, as a couple of decades earlier, he still hadno equals in the world!" (Kasparov),} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "The Years 1914 to 1920"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The outbreak of the First World War naturally also had an impact on the worldof chess. Lasker was not very active during those six years. He gavesimultaneous displays and only contested two events: in 1916 he defeatedTarrasch 5½-½ in Berlin and in 1918, also in Berlin, he won a double-roundquadrangular tournament with 4½/6, followed by Rubinstein (4), Schlechter (2)and Tarrasch (1½).} 1. Z0 {His next commitment, the only truly serious onein seven years, was to be the world title match against José Raúl Capablanca.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Loss of the title"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Loss of the title, 1921 World Championship Match with Capablanca: Laskerdefended his title against Capablanca in Havana, from 15th of March to the20th of April 1921. The duel proved to be a crushing victory for Capablanca.It was scheduled to be 24 games, but after the fourteenth game, with 4 winsfor Capablanca and 10 draws, Lasker abandoned the match.} 1. Z0 {At the startof 1922 Lasker published a short book, in Berlin, in which he talked about thepreparations for the match (where there were moments of tension), and thematch itself, commenting briefly on the games and giving the reasons for hisdefeat. He wrote: "Capablanca's style overwhelms by its logic. It's theoutcome of straightforward interior work; it represents hot-forgedpurposefulness [...] I was unable to put up anything to match Capablanca'slogic, save combinations that were void of accuracy, strength, and scope."Lasker also had difficulty adjusting to the climate of Havana. --- Afterlosing the world title Lasker became competitively inactive once more foranother two years, just giving simultaneous displays and being the guest ofhonour at a number of places.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Mährisch-Ostrau 1923"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker's return to active chess came as something of a surprise. In July of1923 he returned to competition in a tournament in Mährisch-Ostrau (Moravska-Ostrava). For the first time Lasker confronted the new generationwith their so-called "hypermodern" ideas, players such as Richard Rétiand Ernst Grünfeld, as well as more familiar opponents.} 1. Z0 {Afterstarting with a draw against Grünfeld, Lasker faced Tarrasch in the secondround. It was an intense struggle in which Lasker was worse for a large partof the game, but he won. Lasker continued combining wins and draws, and aftereight rounds he was in first place with 6½/8, but he was not alone. Réti wasup there with him, so that their encounter in the ninth round could prove veryimportant.} *[Event "39: Maehrisch Ostrau"][Site "?"][Date "1923.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Reti, R"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "D15"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "86"][EventDate "1923.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. Nf3 d5 2. d4 Nf6 3. c4 c6 {Lasker plays the Slav Defence once again afteran interval of no less than 33 years. In total there were only seven suchoccasions (+3 -2 =2); his two losses were against Horatio Caro, in Berlin in1890, in only 14 moves, and later against Capablanca in New York in 1924.Those defeats did not prevent Lasker from winning both tournaments (he tiedwith his brother Berthold in Berlin).} 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 {The main line;} ({but} 5. a4 {is almost exclusively played these days.}) 5... b5 6. a4 b4 7. Na2 ({This retreat, immediately regaining the pawn, is more popular than} 7. Nb1 {, which allows} Ba6 {, delaying the recovery of the pawn, although this moveis also playable.}) 7... e6 8. Bxc4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 Nbd7 11. b3 {Alekhine was very critical of this idea. Commenting on his game againstTarrasch, from Hastings 1922, he said: "It's surprising that in an identicalposition Réti continued here against Lasker with b3 and Bb2, whichdangerously weakens the square c3. But in this variation the square b3 shouldbe reserved for the queen knight". In that game Tarrasch had played 10...Bb7and the game continued 11 Rd1 Nbd7 12 e4; Alekhine developed his queen'sbishop to g5, followed by playing Nc1-b3.} a5 12. Bb2 c5 13. Rfd1 Qb6 14. Nc1Ba6 {This is the reason why Lasker held back from playing ...Bb7 earlier; withthe exchange of the light-squared bishops, Black solves his mobility problemsand seeks to exploit, in the long run, the weakness of the b3-pawn.} 15. dxc5$6 ({Here} 15. Bxa6 Qxa6 16. Qxa6 Rxa6 17. Nd3 {has been suggested, and"White has the somewhat better endgame", but after} cxd4 18. Nxd4 {Blackcan play} Ne4 {in preparation for ...Ndc5, taking aim at the weakness of b3,no white advantage is visible.}) ({Although with the move played White plansto occupy c4 with a good knight, this exchange also facilitates the attack onb3, so it isn't the most precise. Instead,} 15. Nd2 $1 {seems better, with theidea of 16 Nd3, and after} cxd4 16. Bxd4 Bc5 {White simply retreats with} 17.Bb2 $1 {.}) 15... Nxc5 16. Ne5 {EXERCISE: The position is close to equality,but Black has a slight initiative. What do you think Lasker played now? ---ANSWER:} Bxc4 $1 {This will allow Black to continue to put pressure on theb3-pawn. Although he has to move the queen on the next move, this is nohardship for him.} ({On the other hand, a natural move such as} 16... Rfc8 {would allow} 17. Ncd3 $1 {, and the white pieces start to come to life.}) 17.Nxc4 Qa6 18. Bd4 Rfc8 {A natural move, which includes an inactive piece in thestruggle, but it's not the most incisive move.} (18... Nfe4 $1 {was better; atfirst sight it looks much less logical than Lasker's move, but with thepossibility of...Nc3, among other ideas, it hinders White's regrouping. Let'sinvestigate this a little further:} {Best seems} 19. Ra2 $1 {, when a possiblecontinuation is} ({If} 19. Bxc5 $2 {, Black renews the pressure on b3 with}Nxc5 {, and after} 20. Rb1 Rfd8 21. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {Black takes control of thed-file.} 22. Z0 (22. Z0)) 19... Nc3 20. Bxc3 bxc3 21. Rc2 Bf6 {, with the ideaof ...Rab8; then} 22. e4 {can be answered with} Rfd8 $1 {, and the weakness ofWhite's back rank prevents} 23. e5 $2 {on account of} Bxe5 $1 {, so that Blackhas time to play ...Bd4.}) 19. Bxc5 $1 {Eliminating the pressure on b3 and nowthe white pieces can emerge from their prison.} Bxc5 ({If} 19... Rxc5 {then}20. e4 $1 {, limiting the mobility of the f6-knight.}) 20. Qf3 $1 ({QUESTION:Why not play} 20. e4 {here too? --- ANSWER: With the bishop on c5, 20 e4 isn'tso good; Black can} Qb7 $1 21. Re1 Rd8 {, threatening 22...Nxe4, followed by ...Rd4.}) 20... Be7 ({QUESTION: Isn't it more logical to play} 20... Nd5 {, aiming at the c3-square? --- ANSWER: The move played represents a notabledecision on Lasker's part. He rejected 20...Nd5 possibly in view of theresponse} 21. Ne2 ({or possibly because} 21. e4 Nc3 {(21...Nb6 is also anoption)} 22. Rd7 Rf8 23. Nd3 Qc8 24. Nxc5 Qxc5 25. Qd3 Rac8 {(to have ...Nxa4available if the rook moves from a1) would lead to balanced play. ---Shereshevsky made this comment on the move chosen: "Lasker provokes hisopponent to play a more active manoeuvre with the knight, Ncl-d3-e5, afterwhich White seizes all the central squares. In return the black knight getsthe chance to come to c3. Lasker's enormous experience of defendingstrategically difficult situations probably prompted the idea that thefavourable placement of just one piece may prove to be his sheet anchor, byutilising which he will be able to neutralise the menacing-looking offensiveof the large army of white pieces."})) 21. Nd3 ({The passive} 21. Ne2 {was also possible, of course, but why renounce a more active plan?}) 21... Nd522. Nde5 Bf6 ({Lasker didn't expel the invading knight with} 22... f6 $2 {, because this loses to} 23. Rxd5 $1 {, since if} exd5 {there is a smotheredmate with} 24. Qxd5+ Kh8 25. Nf7+ Kg8 26. Nh6+ {and Qg8+, while other movesjust lose material.}) 23. e4 Nc3 {The strong knight on c3 is a good antidote,neutralizing the activity of the other white pieces, meaning that for now theposition is balanced.} 24. Rd6 $6 ({If} 24. Rd7 {then} Ra7 {, so Réti 'gainsa tempo' by attacking the black queen but, just as with 17 Nxc4, the queenimproves its position, in this case even more so.}) ({It's understandable thatfor Réti it was very difficult psychologically to conclude that despite allhis recent activity, his position is in danger, and the safest plan was tohead for a draw. This could have been achieved with} 24. Nd7 $1 Nxd1 25. Rxd1Rd8 ({if} 25... Rxc4 {then} 26. Nxf6+ {leaves the black king weak, so thisisn't an improvement}) 26. Rd6 Qa7 27. Nxf6+ gxf6 28. Qxf6 Rxd6 29. Nxd6 Qc730. Qg5+ {and it ends in a draw after} Kf8 31. Qh6+ Ke7 32. e5 {.}) 24... Qb725. Re1 {White has defended his pawn and all he needs now, before resuming hisactive play, is to make an escape square for his king.} Bxe5 $1 {Exchangingthis bishop is done only for a specific reason; it's the first step inLasker's grand plan.} 26. Nxe5 {EXERCISE: What was the reason behind Lasker'slast move? --- ANSWER:} Qc7 $1 (26... Rd8 {gives no more than comfortableequality after} 27. Nc4 e5 28. Rxd8+ Rxd8 {and now, for example,} 29. Nxa5 Qc730. Nc4 Nxa4 31. Rd1 {.}) 27. Nc4 {Forced.} ({Lasker sets White problems,exploiting the weakness of White's back rank, which prevents} 27. Qd3 $2 {due to} Nxe4 $1 28. Rxe4 $2 Qxd6 $1 {.}) 27... e5 $2 {This prevents White fromadvancing with e5, which would provide him with an outpost on d6, but isn'tthe most effective move. Lasker fails to play the third key move.} ({It wasnecessary to cold-bloodedly calculate the consequences of} 27... Nxa4 $1 {.} {If, instead,} 28. e5 {, with the idea of 29 Red1 and 30 Rd7 (as well as 30bxa4 Qxc4 31 Qxa8! followed by mate), the knight is unable to move from a4 dueto 29 Nb6, but Black has time to play} ({Then} 28. Red1 {would threaten to winwith Rd7, but Black can defend with} Rf8 29. Rd7 Qc5 {.} (29... Z0)) 28... Ra7$1 {, escaping the influence of the white queen on f3 and also evading thepossible fork on b6. Then after} 29. Red1 {Black can play} Nc3 {, since} 30.Rd7 ({while if} 30. R1d2 {then simply} h6 {, with the idea of ...a4, or even30...a4 right away}) 30... Qxd7 {leads a lost endgame for White. --- QUESTION:OK, you've convinced me, but in that case why didn't Lasker play 27...Nxa4 - ?--- ANSWER: That we don't know. Maybe he was short of time or maybe he made amiscalculation; we've got no firm information.}) 28. Qf5 $1 {Réti repliesforcefully, threatening to win with 29 Rd7, as well as to capture the e5-pawn.Now the white position is preferable.} Ne2+ {QUESTION: Now this is a surprise,isn't it? What is Lasker hoping to achieve? Wasn't it better to defend with 28...Ra7 - ?} ({ANSWER:} 28... Ra7 {would have been answered with} 29. h4 Re8 ({not} 29... Nxa4 $4 {because then White wins with} 30. Red1 {, threatening Rd7,and if} Nc5 31. Qxc8+ $1 {, forcing mate}) 30. h5 {, and Black is underunpleasant pressure. --- Nunn explains Lasker's decision like this: "Atypical Lasker move. Seeing that there is no really satisfactory continuation,Lasker chooses a move which at least creates complications and gives White thechance to go wrong."}) 29. Kf1 $2 {EXERCISE: What does your intuition tellyou? Which way should the white king go? --- This looks obvious; it eliminatesany problems of back-rank mate, it attacks the knight, the king looks safe,etc.} ({Now} 29. Rxe2 $6 {would run into} Qxd6 $1 {, when the only way toavoid loss is} 30. Qxf7+ $1 {, but after} Kh8 {White has no advantage.}) ({ANSWER: Who would even have considered such an absurd-seeming move as} 29. Kh1$2 {. And yet the text move, which intuitively seems the better of the two, isin reality worse, for tactical reasons, naturally. --- In this case, as inother similar ones, where the position is untypical, to quote Nunn: "Oneshould be aware that intuition can lead one badly astray in situations whichdon't fit standard patterns."} {The best defence is} Rd8 ({29 Kh1! is,indeed, better, when} 29... Nd4 {fails to} 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 {, since after} Qc3 32. Qxc3 bxc3 {, Black's passed pawn can be stopped this time byexploiting the weakness of Black's back rank with} 33. Nxc8 $1 Rxc8 34. Red1Nd2 35. f3 c2 36. Rc1 {followed by Kg1-f1, etc.} (36. Z0)) 30. Qxe5 Rxd6 31.Qxd6 Qxd6 32. Nxd6 Nd4 33. Re3 Rd8 34. Nb7 Rd7 35. Rd3 ({not} 35. Nxa5 $2 Nxb3$1) 35... Rxb7 36. Rxd4 {and now, for instance,} g6 {, followed by 37...Rc7-c3,when it's likely to end up as a rook ending with four pawns against three,where there are practical chances of a win, but it's a theoretical draw.})29... Nd4 30. Qxe5 Nxb3 31. Nb6 {EXERCISE: How can Black show that 29 Kf1 wasan error? --- ANSWER:} Nd2+ $1 {This check wouldn't exist after 29 Kh1. Nowthe knight reaches c4 and Black has the advantage.} 32. Kg1 ({Not} 32. Ke2 $4Nxe4 33. Nxc8 Qc2+ 34. Kf3 Qxf2+ {, forcing a winning simplification.}) 32...Nc4 {Following the exchange of knights Black's passed b-pawn gives him a clearadvantage.} 33. Nxc4 Qxc4 34. Qf5 $2 {The imprecise play by both sides in thefinal stage of the game was probably due to time pressure. White's plan is toplay e5-e6, seeking counterplay, but it's inadequate.} ({It was rather moretenacious to give the white king some luft with} 34. h4) ({or} 34. g3) ({or else enter a worse endgame with} 34. Qd5 Qxd5 35. exd5 {.}) 34... Rab8 (34... b3 {was slightly quicker, but this move is also effective.}) 35. e5 ({Here} 35. Qd5 {has been suggested, but it doesn't change much after} Qc3 36.Qd2 {when exchanging queens is good for Black, but it seems even better to play} Qa3 {, followed by 37...Qxa4 or 37...b3.}) 35... b3 36. e6 fxe6 37. Rdxe6 Rf8({There was a quicker win with} 37... b2 38. Re7 b1=Q 39. Rxb1 g6 $1 {, andthe queen is unable to defend the rook on b1.}) 38. Qe5 Qc2 39. f4 b2 {Thepassed pawn is decisive; the black queen can easily rush back to the defenceof its monarch.} 40. Re7 Qg6 41. f5 Qf6 $2 {A strange mistake by Lasker inthis phase of the game; with this move he squanders at least two winningcontinuations and puts the victory at risk.} ({It was much better to drive thewhite king to a worse square with} 41... Qb6+ $1 {and after} 42. Kh1 {, onlynow} ({or} 42. Kf1 {, and the f5-pawn later falls with check}) 42... Qf6 {, and White is unable to regroup in the way that was possible in the game.} 43.Rb1 Qxe5 44. Rxe5 Rfc8 45. Ree1 Rc2 {, followed by ...Rb4, or ...Kf7 first.}) (41... Qh6 $1 {was also winning: for instance,} 42. Rb1 Qc1+ 43. Kf2 ({or} 43.Qe1 Rfc8) 43... Qc2+ 44. Kg3 Rb3+ {.}) 42. Qd5+ $2 {Returning the favour.} ({White could have offered much greater resistance with} 42. Rb1 $1 Qxe5 43. Rxe5Rfc8 44. Kf2 Rc1 45. Re1 Rc4 46. Re2 Rcb4 47. Ke1 {. If Black had interpolatedthe check 41...Qb6+! then after 42 Kh1 Qf6 the white king would have beenunable to arrive in time to defend against Black's invasion.}) 42... Kh8 43.Rb7 Qc3 ({If now} 43... Qc3 44. Rf1 {the quickest and simplest way to exploitthe passed pawn is by playing} Rxb7 ({but there are several other ways, such as} 44... Qe3+ 45. Kh1 Qf4 $1 46. Kg1 Rxb7 47. Qxb7 Rb8) 45. Qxb7 Qe5 46. Rd1 Rb8{followed by 47...h6.}) (43... Z0 {This win put Lasker in the lead, but Rétidid not relax his pace. Before the final day Lasker had only a half point leadover Réti, so that Lasker had to win his last round game to ensure theoverall victory. As on so many other occasions Lasker won the decisive game,against Tartakower this time. --- Thus Lasker made a brilliant comeback. Hewas undefeated, with 10½/13, followed by Réti (9½), and Grünfeld (8½).Further down were the future world champion Euwe, Tartakower, the futurechallenger for the world title, Bogoljubow, Tarrasch, Rubinstein, etc.}) 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "New York 1924"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Following Lasker's defeat by Capablanca in 1921 and Lasker's subsequentinactivity, until the start of 1923, and prior to Mährisch Ostrau, at the ageof 54 Lasker's career seemed almost over. In the 1940s Capablanca would die atthat age, and later Alekhine died aged only 53.} 1. Z0 {After the MährischOstrau tournament things were still not clear. Tartakower wrote in 1924:"Despite his misfortune in Havana, it would be a mistake to think thatLasker's star is on the wane." --- And very soon Lasker would show just howhis star was getting on. The USA organized a super-tournament, twenty yearsafter Cambridge Springs. It was played in New York from the 16th of March tothe 17th of April 1924. It was one of the strongest in history, with thepresence of the world champion Capablanca, his predecessor, Lasker, and thetitle hopefuls Alekhine and Bogoljubow, together with veterans with greatvictories to their names and some new figures: Marshall, Janowski, Tartakower,Réti, Edward Lasker, Maróczy and Yates. --- Lasker was free for the firstround and drew in the second with Capablanca; in the third he came up againstAlekhine, who was then the sole leader with two points. Let's see thatencounter.} *[Event "40: New York"][Site "?"][Date "1924.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Alekhine, A"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "D35"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "72"][EventDate "1924.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Nbd7 5. cxd5 ({In the book which he wroteon this tournament Alekhine was very self-critical regarding his play in thisgame, and he began by censuring this move, stating that} 5. Bg5 {waspreferable, to retain the option of exchanging on d5 at a more favourablemoment. Objectively, though, the move doesn't merit criticism.}) 5... exd5 6.Bf4 ({The main line is} 6. Bg5 {; the text move is also playable, naturally,but it too was censured by Alekhine,}) 6... c6 {Lasker defends the d5-pawnprior to attacking f4-bishop.} 7. e3 Nh5 {This move was a novelty at the time.It's a good idea, since it forces White to decide the fate of the f4-bishop.} ({The most common move here has been} 7... Be7 {, followed by 8...0-0, although8...Nh5 has also been seen and remains playable.}) 8. Bd3 $6 ({"Of threepossibilities undoubtedly the least favourable", commented Alekhine, and inthis case his criticism is definitely justifiable. "Simpler would have been} 8. Bg3 {," he added,}) ({"which, however, might have been modified stillmore by means of} 8. Be5 {It's curious that in a later simultaneous exhibitionAlekhine tried 8 Be5 against R.Krenkamp, in Cleveland 1924. Black didn't play8...f6?! though, but chose} Nxe5 {and the game continued} ({and, if then} 8...f6 {, then} 9. Bg3 {, etc."} (9. Z0)) 9. Nxe5 Nf6 10. Bd3 Bd6 11. f4 Bd7 12.O-O Qc8 13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bf5 16. Qh5 {.} {Instead Blackplayed} Bxe4 $2 {, which was answered by an error on Alekhine's part; he couldhave gained a big advantage with} ({Here Black needed to play} 16... Bxe5 17.fxe5 Be6 {, with a position that looks somewhat dubious, but in fact hasnothing seriously wrong with it.} (17... Z0)) 17. Nxf7 $1 {,} ({but insteadplayed} 17. Qxf7+ $2 Kd8 18. Qxg7 Re8 19. Nf7+ Kc7 20. Nxd6+ Kxd6 {, and waslost after} 21. Rae1 Qd7 {.})) ({8 Bg3 is indeed a good reply, althoughAlekhine also pointed out the continuation that has become the most popularhere,} 8. Bg5 {, and after} Be7 9. Bxe7 Qxe7 {the most usual move is} 10. Qc2 {.}) 8... Nxf4 9. exf4 {The idea for allowing the pawns to be doubled on f4 isseen in various positions arising from the Queen's Gambit. White gains astrong square on e5 for his knight. Nevertheless, in this precise structure itisn't the most promising idea. Let's take a brief look at another example,comparing this structure, with a black pawn on d5, with the classic model gameJ.R.Capablanca-A.Becker, Carlsbad 1929 (see the following game).} Bd6 10. g3 ({QUESTION: This is passive, isn't it? I thought that the idea was to play} 10.Ne5 {. --- ANSWER: Alekhine explained his decision thus: "Here, for example,he ignores his original intention of playing 10 Ne5, on account of the hostilereply of} Qh4 {, which would have forced} ({after 10 Ne5 the reply} 10... Qb6 {would need to be considered too, attacking b2 and d4, although White can thenplay} 11. Qe2 {, followed by 12 0-0-0}) 11. g3 {. Nevertheless, after} Qh3 12.Qc2 {, the strong position of his knight would in any event have given somecompensation for the weakness of his white squares." However, he indicatedthat after} Nb6 {, followed by a timely ...f6, White would have to retreat hisknight anyway.}) 10... O-O 11. O-O Re8 12. Qc2 Nf8 $1 {Normally the bestsquare would be f6, but Black wants to retain the possibility of playing ...f6against a future Ne5 by White, and furthermore the knight can go to e6 in thefuture, attacking the weak d4-pawn.} 13. Nd1 $6 {White wants to attack, andtransfers his knight to e3 to be able occupy f5 with the knight at anopportune moment.} ({That's why he didn't play} 13. f5 {, which would restrictthe development of the c8-bishop, but would also leave White without a clearplan.}) ({"Likewise the move of} 13. Ng5 {, suggested by several, would haveyielded nothing, for instance:} g6 14. Rfe1 f6 15. Nf3 Bg4 16. Rxe8 Qxe8 17.Re1 Qd7 {, etc", commented Alekhine, correctly;}) ({and he suggested thenatural} 13. Rfe1 {, which gives balanced play, but everything indicates thatAlekhine wanted to complicate the game, since if it progresses quietly Blackwill have the better prospects in the long run, thanks to his bishop pair andWhite's isolated d-pawn.}) 13... f6 {Lasker begins to slowly strengthen hisposition, confident in his medium- and long-term prospects, since he can keepimproving his pieces, step by step.} ({He could have played} 13... Bg4 14. Ne5Bh3 15. Re1 Qb6 {, which wins a pawn, but after} 16. Ne3 Qxd4 17. Bf5 Bxf5 18.Nxf5 {, although White's compensation looks insufficient, it would be the typeof position that Alekhine was seeking, with active pieces.}) 14. Ne3 Be6 15.Nh4 $6 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker reply? --- Nunn gives you a hint: "Whitehas no immediate threats, so Black has considerable flexibility in the way hearranges his pieces. However, he should not play planlessly since given timeWhite may be able to develop an initiative on the kingside. A good first stepis generally to see what advantages your position possesses, and what targetsthere are in the enemy position."} ({Once again Alekhine criticized his move:"Loss of time! From now on White loses quickly because at any cost hestrives for an attack in utter disregard of his inferior development. Had hebeen content to remain more passive (for instance:} 15. Rfd1 {and, if} Bf7 {, then} 16. Bf5 {), Black would have found it by no means easy to formulate anattack."}) 15... Bc7 $1 {ANSWER: The clearest target is the weak pawn on d4,which can be attacked by the bishop; the fact that the bishop isn't doinganything useful on d6, nullified by the pawn f4, is all the more reason forrecycling it to b6.} 16. b4 {Alekhine suggested playing 15...a5 prior to ...Bc7 in order to prevent this advance, but Lasker is unconcerned about the gameopening up, since after all he has the bishop pair. Furthermore, unlike in the'minority attack' in normal positions of the Queen's Gambit, here any weaknessthat White can inflict on Black's queenside won't be so dangerous, with thewhite pieces concentrated on the opposite wing.} Bb6 17. Nf3 $6 {This wouldseem to indicate that Alekhine was very dissatisfied with his previous play.} ({Retreating the knight is an admission of failure. It was more natural to play} 17. Rfd1 {(leaving the other rook to play on the queenside, assuming noimportant change in the position), since if} Bxd4 18. Bxh7+ Nxh7 19. Rxd4 {White would have no grounds for complaint about the change of structure; hispieces would be active at last and the chances equal.}) 17... Bf7 $1 {Laskerimproves another piece, again with a clear plan to put pressure on a weakness.His idea is to play ...Bh5 to attack the knight on f3; if he is able to forceWhite to move g4 the white structure will be further weakened and the weaknessof the dark squares can be highlighted.} 18. b5 $6 {Although playing b5 wasthe idea behind 16 b4, right now the white pieces will not be the ones tobenefit from the opening of lines since, as we pointed out earlier, they arepoorly placed to support a queenside attack. --- EXERCISE (simple): How didLasker reply?} ({Alekhine himself criticized this move: "The decisivemistake. Doubtless Black had the better game, but, with} 18. Bf5 {, in orderto be able to parry} Bh5 {with} 19. Bg4 {, the game would still have been held." --- Nevertheless the proposed solution is also inadequate; the exchange ofthe light-squared bishops is favourable to Black, i.e.} Bxg4 20. Nxg4 Re4 {and 21...Ne6.}) 18... Bh5 {ANSWER: Of course. "Black forces an additionalbreach in the king's wing and thereafter wins quite easily" is Alekhine 'sdisappointed comment.} 19. g4 (19. Be2 {is passive and Black can progressunhindered with} Rc8 {, with ideas such as ...Re4 followed by ...Ne6.}) 19...Bf7 20. bxc6 Rc8 (20... bxc6 {was playable, because} 21. Qxc6 $6 Ne6 {favoursBlack, but this move might be necessary later and in some lines recapturing onc6 with the rook might prove preferable.}) 21. Qb2 $6 {Abandoning the b1-h7diagonal gives Black more freedom.} ({Nunn suggested} 21. a4 Rxc6 22. Qb1 {, "which at least threatens 23 a5. Black retains the advantage, but White isfighting."}) 21... bxc6 {Now that White has released the pressure along thediagonal, 22...Ne6 has become a threat.} 22. f5 Qd6 {With the threat of 23...Qf4, demonstrating the main drawback of the f5 advance.} ({There were othergood moves, such as} 22... c5) ({and} 22... h5 {, but Lasker prefers toactivate his queen first, improving a piece, just as he did earlier with 15...Bc7! and 17...Bf7!.}) 23. Ng2 {In few games was Alekhine forced into such apassive position as the one that Lasker has imposed on him. The most strikingaspect is that Lasker has achieved this, not with aggressive or spectacularmoves, but by slight improvements to his pieces.} Bc7 ({Although} 23... c5 {was once again a good alternative, Lasker preferred to focus on White'skingside weaknesses. Yes, h2 is defended for now, but Lasker has plans toincrease the pressure.}) 24. Rfe1 {EXERCISE: What did Lasker have in mind toplay now, back when he opted for 22...Qd6 - ? --- ANSWER:} h5 $1 {The firststep, obliging White a weaken his kingside even more.} 25. h3 ({"Through adouble pawn sacrifice:} 25. g5 fxg5 26. Ne5 Nd7 27. f4 gxf4 28. Nf3 {, theensuing attack with its mating objective could have been staved offtemporarily. That, of course, would have been but a poor consolation" wroteAlekhine.}) 25... Nh7 {Once again the idea was to improve a piece; the knightis activated, with the deadly threat of 26...Ng5.} 26. Rxe8+ Rxe8 27. Re1 {There are several good moves now, but Lasker chose the strongest.} Rb8 {Generally speaking, it suits the attacking side to keep more pieces on theboard. The e1-rook isn't a vital defender, whereas on the other hand, theblack rook can at any moment link up with the attack via the b-file.} 28. Qc1Ng5 {Closing the circle; Black threatens to invade on h2 and White is unableto prevent the loss of material.} 29. Ne5 {'Fishing in troubled waters'.} ({This temporary blocking of the diagonal h2-b8 won't work, but neither would} 29. Nxg5 Qh2+ 30. Kf1 fxg5 {, threatening to win the g2-knight with 31...Qh1+,or play 31...Ba5 followed by 32...Re8.}) 29... fxe5 30. Qxg5 e4 31. f6 {EXERCISE: In a lost position White sets one last trap. He presents hisopponent with several good possibilities and one bad one. Lasker played one ofthe good ones, but what move would you choose here? --- ANSWER:} g6 {This isthe best response, retaining the threats against the white king.} ({AsAlekhine wrote: "Likewise after} 31... Qxf6 {, White would have had to givein very soon.}) ({Only} 31... Qh2+ {could not have been played by Black: forinstance} 32. Kf1 Qh1+ 33. Ke2 exd3+ 34. Kxd3 Qxh3+ 35. Ne3 Kf8 36. Qxg7+ Ke837. Kc2 {."}) 32. f4 (32. Qh6 Qxf6 {is also hopeless for White.}) 32... hxg4{"Dr. Lasker selects the shortest road to victory," wrote Alekhine.} (32...exd3 $2 33. gxh5 {complicates the game unnecessarily;}) ({while after} 32...exf3 $6 33. Re5 {Black would have to find the only move to win, which is} Bb6$1 {.}) 33. Be2 ({After} 33. hxg4 {Black could safely play} exd3 {.}) 33...gxh3 {And the white position suffers further material loss.} 34. Bh5 Rb2 35.Nh4 Qxf4 36. Qxf4 Bxf4 {. "Lasker obtains a winning position against one ofthe world's strongest players by doing little more than improving the positionof first one piece and then another. Games like this are more instructive thana sacrificial brilliancy, because the opportunity for a brilliancy only comesvery rarely, whereas chances to improve piece placing arise in almost everygame" (Nunn).} 0-1[Event "Carlsbad"][Site "?"][Date "1929.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Capablanca, JR"][Black "Becker, A"][Result "1-0"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r1bqkb1r/pppn1ppp/4p3/8/2BP1P2/2N2N2/PP3PPP/R2QK2R b KQkq - 0 8"][PlyCount "20"][EventDate "1929.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Here White's isolated d-pawn is theoretically weaker, since with a black pawnon e6 instead of d5, Black has the half-open d-file, but this is of littleimportance in the middlegame. One difference in White's favour, compared toour game, is that his light-squared bishop is stronger, and also the f4-pawncan be used as a battering ram to open lines with a timely f5. Alekhine hadnone of this available. --- After} 8... Bd6 9. g3 Nf6 10. O-O O-O 11. Qe2 b612. Rfd1 {(it's notable that in the whole game Capablanca never played Ne5)}Bb7 13. Rac1 a6 14. Bd3 Bb4 $2 {the game concluded quickly:} 15. Ne4 $1 Qd5 $216. Nfg5 $1 Ne8 ({Or} 16... Kh8 17. Rxc7 {, as indicated by Becker.}) 17. Nxh7$1 f5 18. Nhg5 $1 1-0[Event "41: New York"][Site "?"][Date "1924.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Reti, R"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "A12"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "90"][EventDate "1924.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker continued collecting wins. After the first cycle he was the leaderwith 7½/10, followed by Alekhine (6½) and Capablanca and Réti (6). Thesituation was similar to the one at St. Petersburg in 1914; the world champion(Capablanca in this case) trailed behind, the leader seemed untouchable andthe tournament seemed almost decided, but there still remained ten games toplay. --- Lasker began the second cycle at the same pace, with two victories,after that, Lasker had 9½/12, followed by Réti (8), Capablanca (7½),Alekhine (7), etc. In the next round Lasker played Black against Capablanca,who needed to beat him as his only chance of fighting for overall victory, andhe did so in a magnificent game. --- The tournament became more exciting,although Lasker still had a clear lead. With seven games left, Lasker was infirst place with 9½/13, followed by Capablanca (8½), Réti (8), Alekhine (7½), etc. --- Lasker had a free day in the fifteenth round, and Capablancawon, so that, very much as in St. Petersburg, Lasker and Capablanca moved intoshared first place, but this time with Capablanca having played one more game.--- In the sixteenth round Lasker confronted one of his pursuers, a player whowas having a magnificent tournament, implementing plenty of new ideas, RichardRéti. Let's look at that game.} 1. Nf3 d5 2. c4 c6 ({In the sixth round ofthe tournament Yates had opted for} 2... e6 {, although the game developed insimilar fashion to this one, since Black subsequently played ...e5 and wasable to develop his bishop outside the pawn chain.}) 3. b3 ({Varying from} 3.d4 Nf6 4. Nc3 dxc4 5. e3 b5 {, as played in R.Réti-Em.Lasker,Mährisch-Ostrau 1923 (Game 39).}) 3... Bf5 {Alekhine commented in thetournament book: "With this move Dr. Lasker as second player applies theLondon system of development, which, with colours transposed, has severaltimes stood the test against the double fianchetto", referring to the LondonSystem, played with White after 1 d4, which has been revived in recent years,having been employed by world champion Magnus Carlsen among others.} ({Theset-up adopted here by Lasker is now known as the New York System, or Lasker'sSystem. Capablanca preferred} 3... Bg4 {against Réti in Moscow 1925; bothpossibilities, developing the bishop outside the pawn chain, either to f5 org4, are still regarded as completely sound.}) 4. g3 Nf6 5. Bg2 Nbd7 6. Bb2 e67. O-O Bd6 (7... Be7 {is also played; on d6 the bishop allows a later ...Qe7,creating the possibility of ...Ba3. Black mustn't forget that the bishop isundefended on d6, so a possible e4 by White, after the moves} 8. d3 {and 9Nbd2, must be taken into account.}) 8. d3 O-O 9. Nbd2 {This line was still inits infancy, so it's understandable that at first the masters failed to graspall the details of the position. Réti repeats the plan that had beensuccessful against Yates, without deviating, even though there were betteroptions. Nunn made a instructive comment: "Réti tended to play this systemwith the idea of delaying any action in the centre for a considerable time,but these days players are aware that central activity by e4 is often aneffective strategy."} e5 $6 ({As Kasparov pointed out, the most logicalcontinuation was the aforementioned} 9... Qe7 $1 10. a3 a5 {, with a standardposition.}) ({QUESTION: But how can a move like 9...e5, occupying the centre,be dubious? --- ANSWER: At first glance this is an excellent move, so much sothat Alekhine praised it, considering it to be a superior version of theaforementioned game against Yates, in which 9...e5 was played in a similarposition, but with the bishop still back on c8. --- The problem with 9...e5 inour game isn't positional, but tactical. The equally natural move} 9... h6 $6 {, to provide a retreat for the f5-bishop, has the same drawback as we'll seein the following note.}) 10. cxd5 cxd5 {EXERCISE: How can it now bedemonstrated that 9...e5 is inaccurate? --- ANSWER:} 11. Rc1 $6 {Réticontinues with the plan that was successful against Yates, to play Rc1-c2followed by Qa1 and Rfc1.} ({White can gain a slight advantage with} 11. e4 $1{, when the fact that the bishop on d6 is loose limits Black's options. It'spossible that Black would then be obliged to surrender the bishop pair to hisopponent: for example,} dxe4 ({if the bishop instead retreats, with} 11... Be6{, for instance, then White plays} 12. exd5 {and Nc4}) 12. Nxe4 {but after} Bc7{White can play} ({and Black has to play} 12... Bxe4 {or else retreat thebishop;} 13. Z0 (13. Z0)) 13. Rc1 {, with slight but unpleasant pressure, whenit would be dubious to accept the pawn with} Nxe4 ({but if} 13... Rc8 {, then}14. Nh4) 14. dxe4 Bxe4 {due to} 15. Ba3 Re8 16. Ng5 $1 {and White's greaterpiece activity amply compensates for the pawn.}) 11... Qe7 12. Rc2 {"Rétifollows out his tried plan of development, but, after a few moves, is forcedto play for a liberating sacrifice which at the best will yield drawingchances. Rather a dubious outcome for the 'opening of the future!'" wasAlekhine's sour comment.} ({Réti later recommended} 12. Re1 {with the plan ofe4;}) ({but instead the now familiar idea of} 12. e4 $1 {is better, gaining along-term advantage after, for instance,} dxe4 13. dxe4 {is better, gaining along-term advantage after, for instance,} Be6 (13... Nxe4 $2 14. Nh4) ({or} 13... Bxe4 $2 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Nh4) ({or} 13... Bg4 14. Nc4 Bc5 15. h3 {Black is forced to concede the bishop pair to prevent the loss of a pawn}) 14.Nc4 Bxc4 15. Rxc4 {.}) 12... a5 13. a4 $2 {EXERCISE: Here Black played a movewhich later became standard in this variation; what was it?} (13. e4 $1 {was still possible, but Réti sticks to the plan that had previously broughthim success. First he needs to prevent ...a4, but the inclusion of the moves12...a5 and 13 a4 clearly favours Black, since the weakness of b5 isunimportant, whereas the weaknesses of the b4-square and the backward b3-pawnwill prove serious.}) 13... h6 $1 {ANSWER: This enables the bishop on f5 toretreat to h7 at an opportune moment, when it's attacked or, in this concretecase, as a preparatory step for the ...e4 break. Going back a little, 12...h6!would have been even more precise than 12...a5.} 14. Qa1 $6 {Here the pressurethat the queen exerts on the long diagonal is harmless and the remoteness ofthe queen from the centre will take its toll.} ({It was better to play} 14. e4Bh7 15. Qe2 {, with equal chances.}) 14... Rfe8 15. Rfc1 {White has completedhis plan, the same one that brought him success against Yates, but he no hasno entry point on the c-file and Black's pieces are much better placed here,as we'll see.} Bh7 {Of course, moving out of range of the f3-knight, with thethreat of 16...e4, followed by ...e3.} 16. Nf1 {The knight retreats, defendingthe e3-square, but this backward step doesn't come cost-free. --- Let'scompare this position with the one in Réti's game against Yates after Black's16th move (see the following game).} Nc5 $1 {Rejecting the win of the exchange.} ({"By means of} 16... e4 17. dxe4 {, then} dxe4 (17... Bxe4 18. Rd2 {gives no more than equality}) 18. Nd4 e3 19. Nxe3 Bxc2 20. Rxc2 {the exchangecould have been won, but thereupon the two united white bishops would haveacquired altogether too much power. Black, therefore, prefers rightly to puton additional pressure" (Alekhine).}) 17. Rxc5 {"With correct positionjudgement White seeks his salvation in this sacrifice by which he can disposeof one of Black's centre pawns.} (17. Qa2 {, for instance, would have beenapparently less profitable on account of} Na6 {", wrote Alekhine;} (17... d4{is also possible, keeping the knight on c5 for the moment, putting pressureon b3, with the idea of ...Nd5-b4.})) 17... Bxc5 18. Nxe5 Rac8 {Although Whitehas a pawn for the exchange and a dominant central knight, the compensation isinsufficient, because only Black can improve his position. Lasker now decidesto occupy the open file.} ({Other ideas included} 18... Rad8 {, overprotectingthe d5-pawn;}) ({or immediately} 18... Qd6 {, with the unpleasant threat of ...Qb6. If White feels obliged to play d4, this would close the diagonal of theb2-bishop and at the same time increase the scope of the h7-bishop.}) 19. Ne3Qe6 ({Black seeks more than the advantage offered by} 19... Bxe3 20. fxe3 {and then, for example,} Bf5 {, with the plan of ...Qe6, exchanging rooks andoccupying the c-file, etc.}) 20. h3 {"White gets no adequate compensationfor the exchange and for the present must be content to wait. The harmlesstext move nevertheless has a distinct object which, strangely enough, isoverlooked by Dr. Lasker" (Alekhine). This move prepares a manoeuvre to'activate' the queen.} Bd6 $2 {"A mistake which might have had unpleasantconsequences", wrote Alekhine. After a single weak move the advantage candisappear and even change sides. --- EXERCISE: There were several promisingcontinuations, so what would you have played?} ({ANSWER: Alekhine suggested} 20... b6 $1 {, securing the position of the bishop, and he added "After} 21.d4 {he would still have had sufficient counterplay by occupying the square e4,and in the event of other moves a plan leading to simplification could havebeen undertaken.}) (20... Bxe3 $1 {was also good: for example,} 21. fxe3 Rxc1+({less clear is} 21... Qb6 22. Bd4 Qxb3 23. Rf1 $1 {, threatening 24 Nxf7 aswell as 24 Rxf6, followed by Nd7 or Ng4}) 22. Qxc1 Rc8 23. Qd1 {, controllingc2, and now, for example,} Nd7 {.}) ({Finally} 20... Qd6 $1 {was also strong,threatening to win with 21...Bxe3 22 Rxc8 (forced) 22...Bf2+ and 23...Rxc8.})21. Rxc8 Rxc8 $2 ({It's notable that both players underestimated White'schances; as we'll see, it was preferable to play} 21... Qxc8 {.}) 22. Nf3 $2 {"White is not aware that Dame Fortune smiles at him" was Alekhine'scomment. Réti continues with his plan, without realizing that there wassomething better.} ({White could have made good use of his move 20 h3 andBlack's inaccuracy 21...Rc8 by playing} 22. N5g4 $1 Nxg4 23. Bxd5 ({or} 23.hxg4 {followed by Bxd5, with gain of time on the queen, ending up with twopawns for the exchange and a slight advantage.})) 22... Be7 ({The currentengines (early 2018) calculate that Black is not losing after} 22... Bxg3 23.Bxf6 gxf6 24. Ng4 {, but no human player would opt for this, and I doubt thatthe engines that will be available in a few years time will have the same'opinion'.}) 23. Nd4 Qd7 {The position is equal once again, but very complex.Black has a slight material advantage, but there is no clear plan for him tomake progress. Meanwhile White has a very solid position. Alekhine nowsuggested 24 Nb5, with plan of Bd4 and Nc3, but Réti had another idea,initiated earlier with 20 h3.} 24. Kh2 $6 {"The beginning of an artificialmanoeuvre, the insufficiency of which is demonstrated by Dr. Lasker withmarvellous clearness and precision," commented Alekhine. --- EXERCISE: Theposition still isn't advantageous for Black, but it's a fighting position,where the priority is to set the opponent problems. What move enabled Laskermake progress in this respect? --- ANSWER:} h5 $1 {With the idea of openinglines against White's king or else provoking the weakening move 25 h4. ---Going back, instead of 24 Kh2?! it was better to play 24 g4!.} 25. Qh1 {Consistent, but harmless.} (25. Nb5 {was preferable, restricting Black'sactivity along the diagonal h2-h8; Black would possibly continue with} Bf5 {.})25... h4 $1 {Lasker sacrifices a pawn to weaken the white king.} ({There wasno risk in playing the passive} 25... Rd8 {, as Alekhine pointed out, but 25...h4 "is much more energetic and to the point", even though White's positionis still not inferior.}) 26. Nxd5 {This move allows White's king position tobe weakened, but now this is inevitable.} ({The unfortunate position of thewhite queen means that} 26. g4 $6 {is now bad due to} Qd6+ {and ...Qb4,} ({or} 26... Bd6+ {and ...Be5. Nevertheless, the move played maintains equality.}))26... hxg3+ 27. fxg3 Nxd5 28. Bxd5 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker now apply morepressure to the white position? --- ANSWER:} Bf6 $1 {The pin is unpleasant;} ({after} 28... Bf6 {, Black's threats include} 29. Z0 Bxd4 ({or} 29... Rc5 30. e4Bxd4 31. Bxd4 Rc2+ {, when the white queen is lost}) 30. Bxd4 Rc2 31. Qf3 Bf5 {, and the rook on the seventh rank is decisive after} 32. g4 Be6 33. Bxe6 Qxe6{.}) 29. Bxb7 $2 ({The only way to resist was by playing} 29. Qf3 $1 {, whenthe queen aids the defence; the engines fail to find anything direct for Blackthen, but he can continue to manoeuvre.}) 29... Rc5 ({As Kasparov pointed out,} 29... Rd8 30. e3 Bxd3 {was also good; better in fact, but the position isvery complicated and inaccuracies or errors are understandable in timepressure.}) 30. Ba6 $2 {Threatening an awkward check on a8 and with the ideaof bringing the bishop to c4, 'plugging' the c-file, guarding the b3-pawn andattacking f7. But... --- EXERCISE: What move of Lasker's now gained him theadvantage?} ({The fatal last move before the time control", commentedKasparov, and he added: "Alekhine attaches an exclamation mark to it, butthe cold-hearted Fritz shows that essential was} 30. Be4 {Besides, Stockfish 9(July 2018) 'agrees' that 30 Be4 is best, but then prefers} Bxe4 (30... Bxd431. Bxh7+ Kxh7 32. Qe4+ f5 {." The Fritz of fifteen years later refined theline given by its 'older brother': instead of} 33. Qxd4 {,} ({it prefers} 33.Qh4+ $1 Kg6 34. Qxd4 Qxd4 35. Bxd4 Rc2 36. Kg2 Rxe2+ 37. Kf3 Re1 38. Bc3 Rb139. Bxa5 Rxb3 40. Ke3 Ra3 41. Bc7 Rxa4 42. d4 {"and the position is poisedbetween a draw and a win for Black" (Nunn).})) 31. Qxe4 Re5 $1 {, with a bigadvantage to Black. Of course, such investigation with strong engines couldcontinue almost ad infinitum.}) 30... Bg6 $1 {ANSWER: This simple moveprovides an escape hole for Black's king and renews the threat to capture ond4.} 31. Qb7 Qd8 {Guarding the back rank, but this is unnecessary now;} ({as Kasparov pointed out,} 31... Qd6 $1 {was stronger; one of the advantages ofthis move, compared to the move played, is that it attacks g3 and in somelines Black can increase the pressure on that square with ...Rg5, ...Be5 or ...Bh4: for instance} 32. Ba3 (32. b4 $2 {loses to} Rg5) 32... Bxd4 33. Bxc5 Bxc534. Bc4 {fails to} Qd4 35. Qg2 Qe3 {, followed by ...Bh5.}) 32. b4 ({Openingup the second rank almost always loses and here} 32. e3 {fails to} Bxd4 33.Bxd4 Rc2+ 34. Kh1 Qd6 {, and the white queen is unable to come to the aid ofthe defence.}) 32... Rc7 (32... axb4 33. Qxb4 Qe7 {was also good, and evenobjectively better, keeping the queens on, since the white pieces are verypoorly coordinated and the white king is a target. Instead, Lasker prefers avery advantageous endgame.}) 33. Qb6 Rd7 34. Qxd8+ Rxd8 35. e3 $6 ({Thesurprising} 35. Nc6 $5 {gives up a piece, but it gives White some practicalchances of a draw after} Rd6 36. Bb5 ({better than} 36. Bxf6 $2 Rxc6) 36...Bxb2 37. bxa5 {, with four pawns for the rook, including a passed pawn, whichmeans that Black will need to play accurately. It's a typical computer idea,although the engines also consider that it should eventually lead to a lostendgame; Black should be able to win by returning a piece at an opportunemoment and then winning with the advantage of the exchange.}) 35... axb4 {Black's passed pawn gives him a winning advantage, although it's going torequire support.} 36. Kg2 ({A trifle better would have been} 36. Bc4 {",according to Alekhine. Then the simplest would be to play} Bxd4 {, followed by...Bf5 and ...Be6; transferring the bishop to e6 will help the b-pawn toadvance and neutralize White's a-pawn. White has no less than three passedpawns, but their advance is less dangerous.}) 36... Bxd4 37. exd4 {EXERCISE (simple): How did Lasker significantly improve his position?} ({A great dealof analytical effort was devoted to the line} 37. Bxd4 Rxd4 $2 ({but there isa simpler way to win, which is the now familiar idea of including the offsidebishop in the struggle with the manoeuvre} 37... Bf5 $1 38. Bc4 Be6) 38. exd4b3 {.}) 37... Bf5 $1 {ANSWER: Of course, with our familiar recipe.} 38. Bb7 Be6{Now this bishop prevents White from making any progress.} 39. Kf3 Bb3 {This wins;} ({as does} 39... Bd5+ $1 40. Bxd5 Rxd5 41. Ke3 {(White needs torush with the king to the queenside and defend the bishop)} Ra5 42. Kd2 Rxa443. Kc2 {, and now the rook can switch to the kingside to capture theunprotected pawns, i.e.} Ra6 44. Kb3 Rg6 45. g4 Rh6 46. Kxb4 Rxh3 {, followedby 47...Rxd3, or 47...Rg3 if White defends the d3-pawn.}) 40. Bc6 ({Now if} 40.a5 {, Black can win even more easily with} Bd5+ {.}) 40... Rd6 ({With} 40...Bd5+ {there would be a transposition to the previous note; the move playedalso wins.}) 41. Bb5 Rf6+ ({Here it was simpler to play} 41... Re6 {, followedby...Bd1+ and ...Re2, not allowing the white king to cross over to defend thequeenside, but Lasker's move also wins.}) 42. Ke3 Re6+ 43. Kf4 {Now the rookpenetrates and the win is very simple.} ({If} 43. Kf3 {instead, then naturallyBlack plays} Bd1+ {and 44...Re2.}) ({"Only a little better was} 43. Kd2 Rg644. g4 ({or "} 44. d5 $1 Bxd5 45. Be5 {, but even here Black should win after} Bc6 46. Bd4 Bxb5 47. axb5 Rxg3 48. h4 Rg4 {" - Nunn}) 44... Rh6 {" (Kasparov).}) 43... Re2 44. Bc1 Rc2 45. Be3 Bd5 {. The b-pawn decidesproceedings. --- With this win the similarities to the St. Petersburgtournament of 1914 came to an end, as Kasparov pointed out: "After thisimportant win Lasker scored a further 5½ out of 6 (!), and Capa was not ableto keep pace with him."} 0-1[Event "New York"][Site "?"][Date "1924.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Reti, R"][Black "Yates, F"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "r3r1k1/pp1q1pp1/2bb1nnp/3pp3/8/1P1PNNP1/PBR1PPBP/Q1R3K1 w - - 0 17"][PlyCount "1"][EventDate "1924.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The differences are greatly in favour of Lasker's set-up; all his pieces arebetter than Yates'. --- In the Yates game Réti played} 17. d4 $1 {andobtained a clear advantage.} *[Event "42: New York"][Site "?"][Date "1924.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Marshall, F"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C68"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "87"][EventDate "1924.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Bxc6 dxc6 5. d4 Bg4 ({Marshall seeks acomplicated game, so he deviates from the main move} 5... exd4 {. "Thispeculiar gambit prepares difficulties for Black for the reason that he islater forced so to play, with more or less success, in order to recover thepawn sacrificed" was Alekhine's critical comment.}) 6. dxe5 Qxd1+ 7. Kxd1O-O-O+ 8. Ke1 ({Marshall already had experience of this line; in N.Whitaker-F.Marshall, Atlantic City 1921, White chose} 8. Ke2 {, and Marshall was fineafter} Re8 9. h3 ({if} 9. Bf4 {then} f6 $1 {is good, regaining the pawn}) 9...Bxf3+ 10. Kxf3 Rxe5 11. Bf4 Rb5 12. b3 {, but here he badly miscalculated with}g5 $2 {, and stood worse after} 13. c4 Rb6 14. Bd2 c5 15. Bc3 f6 16. h4 {.})8... Bc5 (8... Re8 {was good, just as after 8 Ke2, but Marshall decides tovary and play in the gambit spirit, for which he shouldn't be criticized.}) 9.h3 Bh5 10. Bf4 f5 {Marshall continues to play in a manner both ingenious andcorrect. --- EXERCISE: How do you think Lasker responded to this freshsacrifice? --- ANSWER:} 11. Nbd2 {Declining the offer; now White threatens 12exf5 followed by g4.} ({On the other hand, if he'd answered 10...f5 with} 11.exf5 Bxf3 12. gxf3 Rf8 {then Black would regain one pawn and exert unpleasantpressure along the f-file, which would enable him to regain the second pawnwithout any problems.}) 11... Ne7 {Black continues developing his pieces.} ({An alternative was to seek compensation in the bishop pair and the awkwardposition of the white pieces by playing} 11... fxe4 12. Nxe4 Ba7 {,threatening 13...Bg6.}) 12. Bg5 {"Threatening 13 Nb3, as well as 13 exf5,thereby forcing the exchange of Black's troublesome queen 's bishop" (Alekhine).} ({This exchange could also be forced by playing} 12. exf5 {, threatening 13 g4, and after} Bxf3 13. Nxf3 Nxf5 14. Ke2 Rhf8 {(threatening ...Nd4+)} 15. c3 Nd6 $1 {, with the idea of a timely ...Ne4, Black would obtainactive play in a complex struggle. Lasker prefers to clarify the position.})12... Bxf3 13. gxf3 Rhe8 {Black brings his last inactive piece into play andhas compensation for the pawn.} 14. Rd1 ({Not} 14. exf5 $2 {, when with thewhite king in the centre, Black becomes dangerously active, with} Rd5 {, forinstance, as suggested by Alekhine, and White's pawn centre collapses.}) ({QUESTION: The move ...Bd4 is always in the air, so why doesn't Lasker play} 14.Nb3 {to eliminate this possibility? --- ANSWER: Lasker didn't play 14 Nb3 sothat the knight continues to support the centre, and also has the option ofgoing to c4 or f3, depending on how Black plays.}) 14... fxe4 15. fxe4 ({If} 15. Nxe4 {then} Rxd1+ 16. Kxd1 Bd4 {and Black's activity is sufficientcompensation for the pawn.}) 15... h6 16. Bh4 Bd4 17. Nc4 {With his previousmoves, preventing 16...Bd4, "White has evidently prepared the showy move ofNc4", commented Alekhine.} g5 ({In the event of} 17... b5 {Lasker hadprepared the same response,} 18. c3 $1 {. As in many other lines, afterexchanges White emerges with an extra pawn in the centre; in fact, he isvirtually a pawn up in view of Black's damaged queenside structure. Here's asample line:} Bxc3+ 19. bxc3 bxc4 20. Rxd8+ Kxd8 21. Bg3 g5 22. h4 $1 Ng6 23.hxg5 hxg5 24. Ke2 Nxe5 25. Rh7 {and Black even has an extra pawn, but it isuseless and White is better.}) 18. c3 {Alekhine is very pessimistic about theblack position: he wrote that "Herewith the situation is cleared at last,for the exchange which follows strengthens the position for White in thecentre quite decisively, and even the fact that Black, in the progress of thegame, succeeds finally in regaining the gambit pawn cannot any more alter theresult of the game"; the game remains complicated nevertheless.} Ng6 19. cxd4({Better than} 19. Bxg5 Bxc3+ {;}) ({but} 19. Bg3 Nxe5 {and deciding laterwhat sort of endgame to play was certainly a reasonable alternative,considering the improvement for Black at move 20.}) 19... Nxh4 20. Ke2 Rd7 $2 {This move is a definite blunder, allowing White to make an important stepforward. --- QUESTION: But you don't say why it's bad! It threatens to doubleon the d-file, or perhaps the f-file, and it doesn't look bad? --- ANSWER:I'll reply after the following exercise, although I'll tell you now that inthis position, where White has a strong formation and central pawn superiority,making moves on general grounds is not enough. Concrete measures are required,to prevent White from consolidating his central majority and starting toadvance it. --- EXERCISE: What did Lasker play in this position?} ({Black'sbest move was} 20... Rf8 $1 {, threatening ...Rf4, and it's not obvious thenhow White can make progress: for instance,} 21. Rhf1 Rf3 22. Rd3 Rxd3 23. Kxd3Ng2 {, threatening to give perpetual check with 24...Nf4+ and ...Ng2+, due toWhite's need to defend the d4-pawn; if} 24. Rd1 {, then} ({while} 24. Rg1 {allows} Nf4+ 25. Ke3 Rxd4 $1) 24... Rf8 {.}) 21. f3 $1 {ANSWER: PreventingBlack from paralyzing White's game with ...Rf8.} ({Instead of 21 f3!, the'human' move chosen by Lasker, the engines discover that} 21. f4 $1 gxf4 22.Rhg1 {, with the idea of Rg4, is strong.}) 21... Ng6 ({After} 21... Red8 {can play} 22. Rhg1 {, planning Ke3, since} Rxd4 $2 {runs into} 23. Nd6+ {.})22. Ne3 {Threatening to go to g4 or f5. Lasker considered that it wasn'tnecessary to prevent Black's reply.} ({As Alekhine put it, "White could alsoprevent the subsequent clearing of the centre through} 22. b4 {, but this wasnot essential, inasmuch as he remains with a clear advantage".}) 22... c5 23.dxc5 Nf4+ 24. Kf2 Rxd1 25. Rxd1 Rxe5 (25... Nxh3+ 26. Kg3 Nf4 27. Nd5 Ng6 ({while after} 27... Nxd5 28. Rxd5 c6 29. Rd6 Rxe5 {White's active pieces, plusthe central majority, lead to a rook ending which is much better for him after}30. Rxh6 Rxc5 31. Kg4 {, followed by Rg6, gaining two connected passed pawns,which should be decisive}) {, was no better, due to} 28. Rh1 {.}) 26. Nd5 $1 {Expelling the knight, so that White's king can become active.} Nxh3+ ({Now theknight is stuck and White once again obtains two connected passed pawns, buteven after} 26... Ng6 {White can continue to make progress with, for instance,}27. Kg3 {(intending Kg4)} h5 28. b4 {, etc.}) 27. Kg3 g4 {"Black had reliedupon this reply to let him out of his difficulties (28 fxg4 Ng5). Therejoinder, however, destroys all his hopes", wrote Alekhine, although thereis more than one winning move now.} 28. Nf6 $1 {Threatening both 29 Nxg4 and29 f4.} ({Also strong, and even giving Black less choice, was} 28. Re1 $1 {.})28... h5 ({Black could have tried} 28... Rxc5 {, but then White has severalways to win. As well as 28 f4, which can transpose to the game,} 29. Nxg4 {also works: for example,} Ng5 30. Nxh6 ({or} 30. Rh1 {, and White's twoconnected passed pawns supported by all three of his pieces should decideevents, even if Black wins all White's queenside pawns.})) 29. f4 {This wasthe idea;} ({although Alekhine pointed out an even faster line -} 29. fxg4 $1{is stronger: for instance,} Ng5 (29... hxg4 30. Nxg4 {isn't any better}) 30.gxh5 Nxe4+ 31. Nxe4 Rxe4 32. Rh1 {, and the passed pawn decides.}) (29. Re1 $1{is also good, removing the rook from the possible fork given in the next note;after} Rxc5 30. f4 {there is a transposition to the game.}) 29... Rxc5 {EXERCISE: The win is simple again, but there is always a danger of letting theadvantage slip. Lasker played the best move, but what is it?} ({The lastchance to resist was} 29... h4+ $1 30. Kxh4 ({the ending after} 30. Kxg4 Nf2+31. Kxh4 Nxd1 32. fxe5 Nxb2 {is less good}) 30... Nxf4 31. b4 Ne6 32. Kxg4 Rg5+33. Kf3 {, although White emerges a passed pawn up and retains winning chances.}) 30. Re1 $1 {ANSWER!} ({Not} 30. e5 $2 {immediately, because of the nowfamiliar resource} h4+ $1 31. Kxh4 Nxf4 32. e6 Re5 {, and the advantageevaporates.}) ({Another good move, though, was} 30. Rf1 {.}) 30... Rb5 31. e5 {Now the connected passed pawns win easily.} Kd8 32. Nxh5 Ke7 33. f5 Ng5 {Anything else and the eventual advance of the passed pawns would conclude thegame.} 34. Kxg4 Nh7 35. Nf4 Rxb2 36. Nd5+ Kd7 37. e6+ Kd6 38. e7 $1 {Thequickest.} Kxd5 39. Re6 {Of course the pawn can't queen yet because of 39...Nf6+, but now Black feels obliged to sacrifice his rook for the passed pawnsand all resistance is quickly terminated.} Rg2+ 40. Kf4 Rg8 41. e8=Q Rxe8 42.Rxe8 c5 43. Rd8+ Kc6 44. Rh8 {Lasker had achieved one of the great triumphs ofhis career, possibly the greatest. He finished in clear first place with 16/20,followed by Capablanca (14½) and Alekhine (12). It did not go unnoticed thatthe first three places in St. Petersburg 1914 and New York 1924 were exactlythe same.} ({If} 44. Rh8 Nf6 {then} 45. Rh6 {wins.}) 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Moscow 1925"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Another top-level tournament took place in Moscow, from the 10th of Novemberto the 8th of December 1925. --- *Twenty-one players took part, eight of whomhad played in New York 1924. The most significant absentee from thistournament was Alekhine, but to make up for that the strongest Soviet masterswere there, plus Rubinstein, and among others a young Mexican, Carlos Torre.} 1. Z0 {For Lasker, the tournament can be divided into two parts: up to thehalfway point he was in the fight for first place. After eleven rounds theleader surprisingly was Bogoljubow, who played the best tournament of hiscareer. He led with 8½/11, followed by Lasker with 8/10, Torre 7½/10Marshall 7/10, etc.} *[Event "43: Moscow"][Site "?"][Date "1925.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Rubinstein, A"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "D47"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "114"][EventDate "1925.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. Nf3 Nbd7 6. Bd3 dxc4 {Although thismove, with the idea of expanding on the queenside, had been played earlier, itcame to the fore when Akiba Rubinstein himself played it in Carlsbad 1923,against Teichmann, although it came to be called the Meran variation followingthe game E.Grünfeld-A.Rubinstein, Meran 1924. --- Here we are almost at thebirth of the variation, which many decades later was used by world championssuch as Euwe, Botvinnik, Smyslov, Kasparov, Anand and Kramnik, as well as manyof the world's greatest players in their time.} ({Previously} 6... Bd6 {had been the main move here.}) 7. Bxc4 {This was the second and last time thatLasker played the Meran variation. In the first round of the tournament,against Capablanca, he played 7...c5, which transposes to a uncommon line ofthe Queen's Gambit Accepted, with each side playing Bxc4 and ...c5 in twomoves; an endgame was reached which Lasker held without any great difficulties.} b5 8. Be2 (8. Bd3 {later become accepted as the most critical line.}) 8... a69. O-O ({The aforementioned game Teichmann-Rubinstein continued} 9. a4 b4 10.Nb1 c5 11. O-O Bb7 12. Nbd2 Be7 13. Nc4 O-O 14. Nfe5 cxd4 15. exd4 a5 16. Bg5Nd5 {, which gave Black no problems.}) 9... Bb7 10. b3 ({It's understandablethat White didn't play more ambitiously, with} 10. e4 {, for instance, whichsubsequently became the main line. The move played is passive.}) 10... Be7 (10... c5 {is the standard continuation, bringing the b7-bishop to life. Laskerprefers to delay this, which in this position is correct, because White isunable to exploit it due to his rather unambitious set-up.}) 11. Bb2 O-O 12.Ne5 {EXERCISE: Rubinstein varies from the plan of advancing with a4, as playedby Teichmann, which is designed to provoke ...b4 and gain the c4-square at thecost two tempi, but which caused Black no problems in the game. How do youthink Lasker responded? --- ANSWER:} c5 {Now he plays this, the most naturalmove, denying White the opportunity to exert pressure on the backward c-pawnwith his intended move Bf3. Even though this wasn't a serious threat, therewas no reason to allow it.} ({In the event of} 12... Nxe5 13. dxe5 Nd5 {, exchanging on d5 gives equal play, but} 14. Ne4 {, with the idea of Nd6 israther more unpleasant.}) 13. Bf3 Qc7 14. Nxd7 Nxd7 {The position is equal,but both sides are showing some ambition.} ({Lasker loses control of d5 withthis move, but he rejected} 14... Qxd7 {in order to avoid} 15. dxc5 {, with anequal endgame.}) 15. Ne4 ({The attempt to exploit Black's loss of control ofd5 with} 15. d5 $2 {fails to} Ne5 {;}) ({while if} 15. Bxb7 Qxb7 16. d5 {Black can respond in several ways,} {or with the sharper} Ne5 ({such as thequiet} 16... Bf6 17. dxe6 fxe6 18. Qg4 Qc6 {, when the weakness of the e6-pawnis unimportant;} (18... Z0)) 17. dxe6 fxe6 {, when after} 18. Nxb5 Nf3+ (18...Rfd8 19. Qe2 Nd3 {is another possibility}) 19. gxf3 axb5 20. f4 Bf6 21. Bxf6gxf6 22. f3 c4 {the position is more complicated, and there are chances forboth sides.}) 15... Rad8 {Preparing to retreat the queen to b8, with pressurealong the d-file.} 16. Rc1 Qb8 17. Qe2 cxd4 18. exd4 $6 {A strange decisionbecause, as Rubinstein would have known perfectly well, the position is notone that favours the Isolated Queen's Pawn, since Black has good control of d5and the bishop is badly placed on b2.} ({EXERCISE (simple): For some reasonRubinstein rejected} 18. Bxd4 {, which keeps the play balanced. How would youthen answer} e5 {- ?} {but} 19. Bc5 $1 {holds the position, and there is noadvantage to Black either in trying to make the ...f5 idea work: for instance,after} ({ANSWER: Naturally} 19. Bb2 $2 {would lose to} f5 20. Ng3 e4 {;} (20...Z0)) 19... Rfe8 (19... Nxc5 20. Nxc5 {is not a problem}) 20. Bxe7 Rxe7 {, the simplest is} 21. Qc2 {when} f5 $6 {fails to} 22. Nd6 $1 Bxf3 23. Nxf5 {and 24 gxf3.}) 18... Rc8 19. g3 {The white position is slightly uncomfortable,but tenable.} ({One plan to equalize could be to play Nc5 under goodcircumstances, but there is no time for this: for instance,} 19. a3 Qa8 $1 20.b4 $2 Nb6 21. Nc5 {can be answered with} Bxf3 22. Qxf3 Qxf3 23. gxf3 Nc4 {, with advantage to Black.}) 19... Qa8 $1 {Black's advantage is minimal, butit's essential to keep setting the opponent problems, however small, as Laskerunsurprisingly does. Now the pin on the knight at e4 limits White's mobility alittle more.} ({It still isn't the right moment to bring the knight to d5,since it must maintain control of c5: for instance,} 19... Nb6 $6 {could beanswered with} 20. Bg4 $1 {, intending Nc5, and if} ({better than the immediate} 20. Nc5 {, since this way White retains the bishop}) 20... f5 $6 {then still}21. Nc5 {.}) 20. Kg2 Rfd8 21. Rxc8 {White has no clear plan for makingprogress, whereas at the right moment Black can try ...Nf6 or ...Nb6. TheIsolated Queen's Pawn isn't a serious problem while the queens are still onthe board, so Rubinstein decides to exchange all the rooks, when the positionshould still be tenable.} Rxc8 22. Rc1 Rxc1 23. Bxc1 h6 $1 {An escape hole forthe king is always useful and this modest move also helps restrict White'sdark-squared bishop, as well preventing any attempt to exchange the bishopswith 24 Bg5. Indeed, otherwise White could play 24 Bg5, answering 24...Bf8with 25 Bf4, planning Bd6, getting rid of his worst piece. Typically, Lasker'smove also has a tactical point.} 24. Bb2 ({Now} 24. Bf4 $2 {loses materialafter} g5 $1 25. Bd6 g4 $1 26. Bxe7 gxf3+ 27. Kxf3 f5 {.}) 24... Nb6 {Headingfor d5,} ({although} 24... Qc8 {was also worth consideration.}) 25. h3 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker keep up the pressure?} ({In the event of} 25. Nc5 {Black would maintain a slight advantage after} Bxf3+ 26. Qxf3 Nd5 27. a3 a5 {.}) 25... Qc8 $1 {ANSWER: Preventing Nc5. Black's control of the c-file meansthat White must now be on his guard against a possible invasion by the blackqueen. Even though Black's advantage remains minimal, White's defensive taskis rather unpleasant.} 26. Qd3 Nd5 27. a3 {White prevents ...Nb4.} Nb6 $1 {QUESTION: He's only just played ...Nd5 and now for no apparent reason he movesthe knight away. I don't understand. Is this really progress? --- ANSWER:Don't get cross! Of course, Black's not going to win quickly, and the mostprobable outcome, if the slight advantage doesn't increase, is that he won'twin at all. The most than the position allows is to continue creating problemsfor the opponent. --- With 27 a3, the b3-pawn lost its natural support, soLasker now intends to put pressure on it, trying to force it to advance to b4,which would give him the c4-square for his pieces, ideally for the knight;meanwhile, having to defend the b3-pawn limits White's mobility. Another ideais to play ...a5-a4, also with the idea of gaining control of the c4-square.}28. Kh2 {White isn't afraid of Black's plan, and merely waits.} ({With} 28. Qc3{he could force the temporary retreat of the black queen; Black would play} Qa8{, with a slight advantage.}) 28... Bd5 29. Kg2 Qc6 30. Nd2 $6 ({Now} 30. Kh2$6 {would be answered with} a5 $1 {, and White's problems start to mount.}) ({Slightly better was} 30. Nc3 {, controlling d5, although after} Bxf3+ 31. Qxf3Qd7 {Black would continue with 32...a5, planning ...a4, and White would stillhave to defend a slightly worse position.}) 30... a5 {Lasker continues toimprove his position.} ({Here} 30... Bxf3+ {was interesting, when} 31. Qxf3 $2{, loses to} ({so} 31. Nxf3 {would be necessary, to which the reply would be}a5) 31... Nd5 {, followed by 32...Qc2.}) 31. Qc3 $2 {Rubinstein collapses. ---EXERCISE: How did Lasker punish White's blunder?} ({It was necessary tocontinue passive defence with} 31. Bxd5 Nxd5 {It was necessary to continuepassive defence with} 32. Kh2 a4 33. bxa4 bxa4 34. Nc4 Qb5 {Black continues toput pressure on the white position.}) 31... Bxf3+ $1 {ANSWER: Now thisexchange wins the a3-pawn by force, and Black gains a passed pawn which isenough to win.} 32. Nxf3 ({If} 32. Qxf3 $2 {then} Nd5 $1 {, threatening ...Qc2,when} 33. Qe4 {loses to} f5 $1 34. Qf3 Qc2 35. Qe2 Kf7 {, and White isdefenceless, as indicated by Réti and Bogoljubow.}) 32... Qxc3 33. Bxc3 a4 $134. bxa4 {Of course;} ({since if} 34. b4 {then} Nc4 {wins the a3-pawn, whichis also the case after Rubinstein's reply.}) ({The try} 34. Ba5 {loses simplyto} Nd5 ({winning a pawn right away with} 34... axb3 $1 {also works, since} 35.Bxb6 $2 {loses to} Bg5 $1 {and the b-pawn queens}) 35. b4 Bf6 $1 {, tying thewhite knight to the defence of d4, followed by 36...Nc3 and ...Nb1.}) 34...bxa4 35. Kf1 {This loses;} ({as does} 35. Bb4 Bxb4 36. axb4 a3 37. Nd2 {, and now, while the white king heads for queenside, the black king occupiesthe centre and invades the kingside and/or Black wins the b4-pawn and then thed4-pawn. A sample line is} a2 38. Nb3 Kf8 39. Kf3 Ke7 40. Ke4 Nd5 {and theb-pawn falls (Bogoljubow).}) 35... Bxa3 36. Ke2 Kf8 37. Kd3 Nd5 38. Be1 Bd6 39.Kc4 Ke7 40. Ne5 Bxe5 {There are many ways to win, but Lasker chooses thesimplest, simplifying.} 41. dxe5 Kd7 42. Bd2 h5 43. Bc1 Kc6 44. Ba3 Nb6+ 45.Kd4 {If the white king goes to the queenside to capture the a-pawn then, aswe've already mentioned, this leaves the kingside undefended. So White prefersto keep his king in the centre for the time being and later seek counterplayon the kingside, although of course this won't be successful unless there is aserious error on Black's part.} ({After} 45. Kb4 {a sample winning line is} Kd546. Bb2 Ke4 47. Kb5 Nd7 48. Kxa4 g6 {, followed by ...Nxe5.}) 45... Kb5 46. Bf8Nc4 47. Kc3 g6 48. f4 Ne3 49. Kd3 Nd5 50. Ba3 ({After} 50. h4 {the structurewould be a fixed target and Black could win with} Nb6 {, aiming at the g3-pawn:for instance,} 51. Kc2 Nc4 52. Kc3 Ne3 53. Kb2 Nf5) 50... h4 $1 51. gxh4 Nxf4+52. Ke4 {EXERCISE: Many moves win now, but what would you choose? --- ANSWER:}Nh5 {A good decision.} (52... Ng2) ({or} 52... Nd5 {also win;}) ({but not} 52... Nxh3 $2 {which loses half a point after} 53. Kf3 Kc4 (53... g5 $2 {is worse, losing to} 54. h5) 54. Kg3 Ng1 55. Kf2 {, with a draw, as pointedout by Euwe.}) 53. Kf3 Kc4 54. Bb2 Kb3 55. Ba1 a3 56. Kg4 Kc2 57. Kg5 {Withthe idea of capture the f7-pawn, but this is as futile as anything else atthis stage.} Kd3 {. Heading for f5 when White plays Kxf7, after which Blackcan mop up all White's pawns.} (57... Kb1 {was also winning, as shown by} 58.Bd4 Ng3 {, followed by 59...Ne2 and the pawn queens.}) (57... Z0 {In thetwelfth round everything changed for Lasker. He lost a famous game againstTorre; in a superior position he made a serious tactical mistake, somethingvery rare in his career. Apparently he was distracted by a piece of good news:he received a telegram just before making the fateful move, informing him thathis play Vom Menschen die Geschichte had been accepted by a German theatre.--- In any event, his play was affected for the rest of the tournament. In thefinal ten games he managed to only score six points, which was enough for himto finish second with 14/20, behind Bogoljubow (15½), but ahead, once more,of Capablanca, who finished in third place with 13½. --- After his decentperformance in Moscow Lasker once more distanced himself from competitivechess, devoting himself to giving simultaneous displays, as well as to Bridgeand Go. He also completed his masterpiece, Lehrbuch des Schachspiel, which helater translated himself as Lasker's Chess Manual.}) 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "5: Selected Games: 1934-1936"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker didn't play any official games after the 1925 Moscow tournament, andpossibly he thought he would never play chess again.} 1. Z0 {However, in 1933the rise of Nazism forced him to leave Germany with no material possessionsand so he had to emigrate and start to play chess again in order to improvehis economic situation.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Zürich 1934"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{His return to chess was at the Zürich tournament, played between the 14thand the 28th of July 1934. It was a very strong tournament; taking part werethe world champion Alekhine, the twice-challenger for the title Bogoljubow, aswell as Euwe, Flohr, Nimzowitsch, etc.} 1. Z0 {Lasker was now 65 years old,almost twice the age of most of the participants, but his start wasextraordinary. In the first round he faced Max Euwe, who only a year laterwould be proclaimed world champion. Let's look at that game (see the followinggame).} *[Event "44: Zuerich"][Site "?"][Date "1934.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Euwe, M"][Black "Lasker, Em"][Result "0-1"][ECO "D64"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "100"][EventDate "1934.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 Nbd7 5. e3 c6 {This order of moves seemsto be preparing to bring the queen out.} (5... Be7 {is more common,maintaining the possibility of playing ...c5 in one move. Lasker mainly played5...Be7, even in important events such as his match for the world title withCapablanca.}) 6. Nf3 Be7 ({Lasker doesn't exploit the opportunity provided by5...c6 of playing the Cambridge Springs variation with} 6... Qa5 {, which hedid play too in official games, against Edward Lasker in New York 1924 andlater against Vera Menchik in Moscow 1935; Lasker won both these games.}) 7.Qc2 {Euwe 'punishes' Lasker's move order; with the pawn on c7 and alreadycastled, Black's strongest move is considered to be 7...c5!. --- QUESTION: Howcan this apparent inaccuracy on Lasker's part be explained? --- ANSWER: We canonly speculate, but let's do it. It's possible that Lasker didn't fear 7 Qc2,since in the eleventh round of the same tournament, against Johner, Laskerplayed the 'correct' way with ...Be7, without moving the c-pawn, but thenagainst 7 Qc2 he played not 7...c5, but 7...c6, reaching the same position asin our game. --- It's also possible that (especially against his Swissopponent) Lasker thought that playing 7...c5 led to excessive simplificationand offered him fewer winning chances. Ironically though, Johner was the onlyone of the eight masters who finished in the bottom half of the table to gaina draw against Lasker. --- Lasker did play 7...c5 after his retirement,against Marshall in New York 1940, and was fine, although later he made aserious blunder and lost.} O-O {Via various move orders Lasker reached thisposition many times throughout his career.} 8. a3 {This is the start of 'thestruggle for a tempo'. White delays Bd3, waiting until Black plays ...dxc4, sothat he can take on c4 with the bishop in one move, and meanwhile he tries tokeep making useful moves. --- QUESTION: I understand, but moves like a3 or,for example, h3 aren't very useful, are they? --- ANSWER: We'll talk about h3later, but for now let's say that there's no doubt that 8 a3 is useful, sinceit prepares a retreat for the bishop on a2 after playing Bxc4, and furthermorein one particular line, which could have happened in the game, it controls b4,preventing ...Qb4+.} Re8 ({Curiously, in the fifth game of the match in Havana1921, Lasker experimented with} 8... c5 $6 {against Capablanca, a movecriticized by both players; he could well have ended up in trouble but hemanaged to draw. Lasker never repeated that strange choice; in most cases heplayed 8...Re8.}) 9. Rc1 ({The game against Johner continued} 9. Rd1 a6 {, when White transposed to the so-called Carlsbad structure with} 10. cxd5 {, and after} exd5 11. Bd3 Nf8 12. Ne5 Bg4 13. Rc1 Bh5 14. O-O Bg6 {Laskerstood well and outplayed his opponent in a manoeuvring game, even reaching awinning position, but an error on move 41 spoiled the win and the result was adraw.}) 9... dxc4 ({Against Ragozin in Moscow 1935, Lasker played} 9... a6 {. Here he gives up the struggle for tempo and opts to continue with a sequenceknown as 'Capablanca's freeing manoeuvre', with the idea of exchanging piecesand increasing his mobility. Capablanca also played 9...a6 many times. Can youguess what Alekhine usually played against that? Yes,} 10. h3 {.}) 10. Bxc4 Nd511. Bxe7 Qxe7 {We can say that both sides have benefited from the exchange ofbishops; White, because he's exchanged the opponent's better bishop, leavinghim a very passive bishop on c8, and Black, as we mentioned above, hasincreased his mobility.} 12. Ne4 {This is the standard move, which has severalvirtues: it controls c5 and avoids further exchanges;} ({which could happenafter} 12. O-O Nxc3 13. Qxc3 e5 {, with which Black solves the problem of hisc8-bishop, reaching a standard position.}) ({In D.Bronstein-L.Tan, Petropolis1973, White carried out an original manoeuvre, playing} 12. Ne2 {; just aswith Ne4, the knight might be going to g3, but White gains the additionalpossibility of playing e4. Black should now have played 12...N5-b6, followedby ...e5, with a reasonable position, but he played the immediate} e5 $2 {and Bronstein gained the advantage with} 13. Bxd5 $1 cxd5 14. Nc3 {.}) 12...N5f6 13. Ng3 {In general Black must now decide how to activate his bishop,whether with ...e5 or ...c5; but here 13...e5 is a serious error in view of 14Nf5, followed by 15 Ng5, so it's essential to focus on the other possibility.}c5 {In similar positions, with the white pawn on a2, in their 1927 matchCapablanca played ...Qb4+ some eight times against Alekhine.} ({Thealternative was to prepare ...c5 by first playing} 13... b6 {; even thoughthis allows} 14. e4 {, Black appears to hold after} c5 15. e5 Nd5 16. Nf5 exf517. Bxd5 Rb8 18. O-O g6 {, followed by 19...Bb7 or 19...cxd4, depending on howWhite plays.}) 14. O-O cxd4 15. Nxd4 Nb6 16. Ba2 (16. Bb5 Bd7 17. Qc7 {was asuggestion by Alekhine, but it doesn't seem dangerous, since Black is able tosolve his problems with natural moves:} Nbd5 18. Qxb7 Reb8 19. Qa6 Rb6 20. Qa5Bxb5 21. Nxb5 Qb7 {, regaining the pawn with ...Rxb2.}) 16... Rb8 ({In asimilar way to what we've already looked at, it was possible to play} 16... Bd7{, when} 17. Qc7 {gives White nothing after} Nbd5 {.}) 17. e4 {EXERCISE: Blackhas difficulties; he must deal with White's threat of e5, followed by Ne4-d6.What did Lasker play?} (17. Qd2 {intending Qa5 is an interesting idea fromAlekhine, casting some doubt on 16...Rb8; it is slightly reminiscent of 21Qd2!, played in the 34th game of his match with Capablanca in Buenos Aires1927, although there the queen also had ideas on the kingside.}) 17... Rd8 $1 {ANSWER: The start of a notable defensive manoeuvre to restrain White'sinitiative; the idea is to vacate the e8-square before playing ...Bd7.} 18.Rfd1 Bd7 19. e5 Ne8 {This was the idea; d5 is reserved for the other knight.It's true that the knight is passive at the moment, but it controls the d6-and f6-squares, which could be important in the event of Black playing ...g6,for example in response to an attack on h7.} ({After} 19... Nfd5 {instead,White has various moves and plans available. After} 20. Ne4 {, Black can play}({another idea is} 20. Qd2 {, preparing to play 21 Ne4, answering} Ba4 {with}21. Re1) ({finally, since a good defence to} 20. Bb1 {is} Qh4) (20. Qe4 {is interesting, planning 21 Bb1.}) 20... Ba4 21. b3 Bc6 {, and the a3-pawnhangs.}) 20. Bb1 g6 21. Qe4 {EXERCISE: The white queen has been centralized,with ideas such as h4-h5. How did Lasker reply? --- ANSWER:} Ba4 $1 {We'vealready seen something similar. This provocative move seeks to createweaknesses in the white camp, as a basis for counterplay;} ({on the other hand,a routine move like} 21... Nd5 $6 {leads nowhere after} 22. Ba2 {, when itseems best to return to b6.}) 22. b3 {This is debatable; now the a3-pawn isattacked and White will have to keep advancing his queenside pawns. ---QUESTION: But I can't see what's wrong with gaining space on the queenside.Black doesn't seem to be in any state to take advantage of this?} ({It'spossible that} 22. Re1 {was better, to which Black would possibly respond with}Qd7 {, followed by ...Rbc8.}) 22... Bd7 {ANSWER: You're right, it isn'texactly bad, but the advances make some squares available for Black to use,which is something that he really needs right now, so that the struggle won'tbe confined to the kingside, where White has the advantage. --- Lasker prefersto maintain the position.} ({Instead,} 22... Bc6 $1 {was interesting, forcingWhite to decide between sharpening the struggle by sacrificing the a3-pawn,with} 23. Qf4 Qxa3 24. h4 {for instance, or exchanging on c6 with equality.})23. a4 (23. h4 {was also worth consideration here, as Euwe pointed out. After}Qxa3 24. h5 {White gains compensation, but no advantage: Black can continuewith} Rbc8 {and later ...Nd5; the black queen can rush back into defencequickly and the opening of the queenside prevents White from attacking incomfort.}) 23... Nd5 {This centralization has other virtues: it eliminates theattack on b7, enabling Black to play ...Rc8, and eyes b4 as a possibledestination. Meanwhile, thanks to the moves 21...Ba4! and 22 b3, White nolonger has the possibility of the unpleasant Ba2 idea, as mentioned earlier.}24. Bd3 {The bishop seeks a more active square.} Rbc8 25. Bc4 Bc6 {A gooddefence against the positional threat of Bxd5.} ({Of course} 25... Nec7 $2 {, moving away the defender of d6 and f6 and clogging up Black's development,would be bad;}) ({the alternative was} 25... Rc5 {, intending 26...Rdc8, andWhite must take account of ...Nb6 or ...Bxa4, but Lasker prefers to maintainthe tension.}) 26. Nxc6 ({QUESTION: I don't understand; the bishop is goingnowhere, so why hurry to exchange it? The queen could evade the influence ofthe c6-bishop with a useful move such as} 26. Qg4 {, couldn't it? --- ANSWER:Probably your move was a good alternative; clearing e4 for the g3-knight isinteresting. A possible continuation might be} Nb6 {and after} 27. Nxc6 Rxd1+28. Rxd1 bxc6 29. Ne4 {Black can play} Qc7 {and it isn't easy to make progresswithout sacrificing material; after} 30. f4 {it's essential to consider} Nxc431. bxc4 Qa5 {. Euwe instead decided on a plan of concrete plan of attack,keeping the rooks on the board and avoiding any material sacrifice for themoment.}) 26... bxc6 {QUESTION: Why did Lasker give himself two isolatedpawns? Was this forced?} ({ANSWER: No, it wasn't.} 26... Rxc6 {was a goodalternative, but Lasker's move is more ambitious. In the first place thestructural weakness can't be exploited immediately, but only in a as yetdistant endgame. Nevertheless, the principal virtue of capturing on c6 withthe pawn is that it allows Black to play ...c5, controlling d4 and b4 andcreating the possibility of using these squares as outposts.}) 27. Rd3 {This was Euwe's idea. It's ambitious; the rook wants to go to the kingside,without ruling out the ideas of h4-h5 as well as a later Ne4.} ({It was stillworth considering giving priority to the idea of placing the knight on e4, byplaying} 27. Qg4 {, but of course in that case it was better to have played 26Qg4.}) ({Another way, easier for a computer to devise than for a human, was toprepare Ne4 with} 27. Qe2 Qg5 28. Qb2 {.}) 27... Nb4 {Clearing the d-file andpreparing ...c5, with the idea of ...Nc6 and ...Nd4.} 28. Rf3 Rc7 {Laskerdecides to become active on the d-file, to distract White from his attack, soassigns the leading roles to his rooks, postponing any redeployment of theknight on b4, which is active enough for now.} ({Only after seeing that thisnatural plan isn't precise would we give priority to the other idea, which was} 28... c5 {, followed by ...Nc6, to occupy d4.}) 29. h4 {Euwe continues withhis plan, but this was a good opportunity to revert to the idea of placing theknight on e4.} ({Indeed, it was possible to play} 29. Qe3 {, taking advantageof the absence of the knight from d5. --- QUESTION: That would enable 30 Ne4right away, which seems better for White, doesn't it? --- ANSWER: Perhapsobjectively yes, slightly, but it allows Black to infiltrate with} Rcd7 30. Ne4Rd1+ {, and everything depends on the evaluation of this position, i.e.whether the infiltration supplies sufficient counterplay. After, for instance,}31. Bf1 R8d3 32. Rxd1 Rxd1 33. g3 Nd5 34. Qe2 Rd4 {the black position isslightly inferior due to the passivity of the knight on e8, but it isn'tanything serious. --- From the practical point of view it wasn't easy for Euweto change his plan of attack if he couldn't see any clear drawback to the ideahe started with 26 Nxc6.}) 29... Rcd7 30. h5 {EXERCISE: While Black hasoccupied the open file, White's offensive on the kingside has continuedadvancing. What did Lasker play at this point? --- ANSWER:} Qg5 $1 {A strongdefensive move, preventing the threat of 31 Qg4 followed by Ne4. Laskerpostpones any decision about playing ...Rd1+ or ...Rd4 and puts pressure onthe e5-pawn, which limits the mobility of the white pieces.} 31. Re1 Rd4 {Forcing the white queen to retreat.} 32. hxg6 hxg6 ({Of course, not} 32... Rxe4$4 33. gxf7+ Kf8 34. Nxe4 Qg7 35. fxe8=Q+ Kxe8 {, when the strongest move is}36. Nc5 {and the knight invasion on e6 is devastating.}) 33. Qe2 Rd2 34. Qf1 {White sticks to the idea of attack. --- EXERCISE: Euwe has the obvious idea ofplaying 35 Ne4, so how did Lasker deal with this threat?} ({Offering theexchange of queens with} 34. Qe3 {would be an admission of failure, since theendgame isn't advantageous to White. Naturally Euwe was aware that the queennow occupies a passive position, but he considered that this would only betemporary. We'll come back to this position at move 37.}) 34... Nc2 $1 {ANSWER: Lasker not only ignores the threat of 35 Ne4, but even forces White toplay it, since moving the e1-rook loses the e5-pawn and the whole positioncollapses.} 35. Ne4 Qxe5 $1 {This is a procedure that we've seen Lasker employbefore. On this occasion the queen sacrifice is made under advantageousconditions.} 36. Nf6+ Qxf6 37. Rxf6 Nxf6 {Lasker chooses the safest option,which guarantees him a strong initiative without any risk and offers anadvantage without any tactical complications.} ({He could have gained a biggermaterial advantage with} 37... Nxe1 38. Rxg6+ fxg6 39. Bxe6+ Kg7 {, but thiswould allow White some practical chances with} 40. Qa6 {. It's time for us togo back and state clearly that 34 Qf1 deserves a question mark.}) 38. Rc1 {EXERCISE (simple): How did Lasker reply?} (38. Re2 {would lead to anunpleasant endgame a pawn down after} Rd1 39. Rxc2 Rxf1+ {, but Euwe's move isworse.}) 38... Ne4 {ANSWER: Of course, the f2-pawn is the target, and Blackemploys the formerly passive e8-knight, no less. The black position is winning.} 39. Be2 ({This only delays the loss of the f-pawn by one move, but there wasnothing better: for instance,} 39. f3 {loses to} Ne3 {.}) 39... Nd4 40. Bf3Nxf2 {Winning a second pawn without in any way relaxing the initiative. NowBlack threatens to win with 41...Nxf3+ followed by 42...Rd1.} 41. Qc4 Nd3 42.Rf1 Ne5 {Black will now be able to open up the seventh rank, reducing thesecurity of White's king.} 43. Qb4 Nexf3+ 44. gxf3 Ne2+ {Lasker redeploys theknight to a more aggressive position, preparing the final attack.} ({Therewere many ways to win by now; 45 Qxd2 wasn't a threat, due to 45...Nxf3+, sothe preparatory} 44... Rd5 {was another good way to continue.}) 45. Kh2 (45.Kf2 Nf4+ {is no better; then} 46. Ke3 {, allows mate in two starting with} ({after which} 46. Kg3 g5 {wins quickly}) ({while the endgame after} 46. Qxd2Rxd2+ 47. Ke3 Rd3+ 48. Kxf4 Rxb3 {is untenable}) 46... Ng2+) 45... Nf4+ 46. Kh1R2d4 47. Qe7 Kg7 {Threatening 48...Rh8+ 49 Kg1 Rd2. The attack is unstoppable.}48. Qc7 R8d5 49. Re1 Rg5 (49... Rg5 {plans to win with, among other things,}50. Z0 Nd5 51. Qh2 {(against the threat of 51...Rh4+)} Rh5 {.}) 50. Qxc6 Rd8 {After drawing in the second round with Flohr, Lasker scored two wins insuccession, which put him in first place. Next came a defeat to Ståhlberg,but then he won another two games and after seven rounds he had 5½ pointsand led the table jointly with Flohr. --- "However, the tournament's secondhalf would not go so well for him. He won 4 games, but also lost 3, two ofthem with White - against Bogoljubow and Nimzowitsch - and one with Blackto Alekhine. Interestingly, this was the first game each one had ever won fromLasker", according to Vladimir and Isaak Linder in their book about Lasker.--- That work puts forward a possible explanation for the decline in Lasker'splay: "The less fortunate finish of this tournament for Lasker was whollyunderstandable. The tournament followed a very tough schedule: eight hours ofplay a day, with no free days and no adjournment days". --- Lasker finishedfifth, with 10/15, behind Alekhine, Flohr, Euwe and Bogoljubow, but ahead ofBernstein, Nimzowitsch, Ståhlberg, etc. --- Lasker's comeback in Zürich gavehim the chance to get back into practice and to recover a good deal of hisstrength. In his next tournament his performance and his play were astonishing,considering that he was already 66 years old.} 0-1[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Moscow 1935"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker's next engagement was in Moscow, from the 15th of February to the 14thof March 1935. --- The tournament was stronger than the one in Zürich. Thelocal contingent included twelve Soviet masters, led by a young Botvinnik,plus Capablanca, Flohr, Spielmann, Ståhlberg, Lilienthal, Pirc and the femaleworld champion, Vera Menchik. This time the rate of play was less demanding;every four days there was a day reserved for adjourned games and then a freeday.} 1. Z0 {In the first round Lasker won a very complicated game against theSoviet master Kan. The Linder brothers commented: "The ex-World Champion'sfirst victory in this tournament was met by an ovation from the tournamenthall". --- In the next seven rounds Lasker drew six games and defeatedChekhover. Then in the ninth round Lasker, after a gap of ten years, playedagainst Capablanca once more; this time both of them were ex-world champions.}*[Event "45: Moscow"][Site "?"][Date "1935.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Capablanca, JR"][Result "1-0"][ECO "C15"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "127"][EventDate "1935.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. e4 e6 {QUESTION: The French Defence? Capablanca didn't play this often, didhe? Why did he choose the French? --- ANSWER: You're right; the last timeCapablanca had played the French Defence in an official game had been almosttwenty years earlier, when he lost to Chajes in New York 1916. --- It'spossible that he was influenced by Lasker's bad results against this defencein Zürich 1934, where he suffered two defeats against Nimzowitsch andBogoljubow, playing lines considered unpromising. Returning to the choice ofthe French Defence on Capablanca's part, it's possibly the defence with whichhe obtained the worst results; after this defeat he lost two important games,against Alekhine and Keres at AVRO 1938.} 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nge2 {Following this encounter, this became Lasker's favourite move against theWinawer;} ({previously he had played} 4. Bd3) ({and} 4. e5 c5 5. Bd2 {.}) 4...dxe4 5. a3 Be7 ({Another popular line is} 5... Bxc3+ 6. Nxc3 Nc6 {.} ({It'spossible that the revival of 4 Ne2 around that time was partly due toAlekhine's tremendous win against Nimzowitsch in Bled 1931, in only 18 moves,where instead of 6...Nc6 Black played} 6... f5 $6 {, which Alekhine punishedwith} 7. f3 $1 {.})) 6. Nxe4 Nf6 7. N2c3 {The line was still in its infancy,so inaccuracies are understandable. --- The problem with the text move is thatit prevents White's most effective defence of the d4-pawn, with c3, against atimely ...Nc6. Lasker himself played 7 N2g3 against N.Riumin in the thirteenthround, and in the fifteenth round, in the game R.Spielmann-J.R.CapablancaWhite also chose 7 N2g3.} ({Later the accepted moves became} 7. N2g3) ({and} 7.Qd3 {.}) 7... Nbd7 $6 {Capablanca makes no attempt to take advantage of thedrawbacks of 7 N2c3.} ({Here} 7... O-O {, retaining the possibility ofdeveloping the knight on c6, was more ambitious. It's surprisingly difficultthen for White to develop his pieces harmoniously: for instance,} 8. Bd3 $2 {can be met with} Nc6 {.}) ({The immediate} 7... Nc6 {is also preferable to thetext.}) 8. Bf4 ({QUESTION: Why did Lasker not play the obvious} 8. Bd3 {, now that he has no problems with his d-pawn? --- ANSWER: We're in agreementhere; it's a strange decision. It's difficult to understand why Laskerpreferred this move to 8 Bd3. Perhaps the idea was to preserve the possibilityof queenside castling after, let's say,} O-O 9. Qf3 {, but we can't be sure.})8... Nxe4 {Once again Capablanca makes no attempt to exploit White's play.} ({The deployment of the bishop on f4 can be met with} 8... Nd5 {and Black standswell after} 9. Nxd5 ({after retreating with} 9. Bg3 $6 {White must constantlywatch out for a timely ...f5-f4, as Bohatirchuk pointed out}) 9... exd5 10. Nc3c6 {. --- As Nunn pointed out: "Capablanca's strategy is simply to exchangeas many minor pieces as possible, but this leaves White with a small butdefinite advantage based on his slight space advantage and more active bishops."}) 9. Nxe4 Nf6 10. Bd3 O-O $6 {Another natural move, but this has negativeconsequences; the natural course of the struggle leaves the 'French bishop' onc8 very passive. --- EXERCISE: How did Lasker now gain the advantage?} ({The same thing would happen after the suggestion of} 10... Nxe4 $6 11. Bxe4 c512. dxc5 {, when the white bishops are very troublesome.}) ({An idea foraltering the 'normal' course of the game would be} 10... Nd5 11. Bd2 O-O {Lasker could have tried to sharpen the struggle with} 12. Qh5 {. Then} ({when after} 12. O-O) ({or} 12. c4 {the counterblow} f5 $1 {is good, with abetter position for Black than in the game.} (12... Z0)) 12... g6 (12... f5 13.Ng5 h6 14. Nf3 {wouldn't be attractive}) 13. Qh6 Nf6 {would perhaps be best,when the optimistic} 14. Ng5 $2 Qxd4 15. Bc3 {is refuted with} Qxf2+ $1 16.Kxf2 ({or} 16. Kd1 Rd8 $1) 16... Ng4+ {.}) 11. Nxf6+ $1 {ANSWER: Curiously itwas with another exchange of pieces, but this allows him to bolster hisd4-pawn and leaves Black still with the problem of his 'bad bishop'.} Bxf6 12.c3 {And Black is left with the dilemma of how to complete his development, towhich there is no obvious solution.} Qd5 {Capablanca tries to solve hisproblems tactically, but it won't work.} ({The natural} 12... b6 $2 {ispunished with} 13. Qh5 $1 g6 (13... h6 {runs into} 14. Bxh6 $1) 14. Qf3 Bd7 15.Bxc7 {, as indicated by Becker.}) ({Pachman commented that} 12... c5 $2 13.dxc5 Qd5 {is also unsatisfactory due to} 14. Qc2 $1 {, attacking h7 andpreparing Be4; then after} g6 15. Bd6 Qxg2 {White can win the exchange with}16. Be4 ({or to try for more with} 16. O-O-O Re8 17. Be4 {, followed by 18 c6.})) ({Finally, after} 12... Be7 13. O-O {Black is still unable to play} c5 $2 {due to} 14. dxc5 Bxc5 15. Bxh7+ {and 16 Qh5+.}) ({It's possible that} 12... Bd7{would be the most tenacious option, with the idea of ...Bc6. Then if} 13. Be4{the best response would be the 'ugly'} Bc6 {and after} 14. Bxc6 bxc6 {Whiteis better, but isn't easy to take advantage of Black's bad structure; Blackwould continue with ...a5 and ...Rb8, with ...Be7 to try to play ...c5.}) 13.Qe2 {QUESTION: Why is this better than the natural 13 0-0 - ? Black still hasthe problem of his c8-bishop and furthermore c7 is attacked. --- ANSWER:Lasker will have had difficulty deciding which of the several possibilitieswas the strongest. There was a choice between 13 Qc2 and 13 Qe2, both with theidea of Be4, and your suggestion of 13 0-0. Lasker's choice is possibly theweakest objectively, but it can't have been a simple choice.} ({After} 13. Qc2$1 {while the complications arising after} Qxg2 (13... g6 {, Black is obligedto remain passive following} 14. Be4 Qd8 15. O-O {;} (15. Z0)) 14. Bxh7+ Kh815. Be4 Qg4 16. Bxc7 e5 {, which a few years ago were regarded as unclear, nowonly provoke a smile of condescension from 'Stockfish and Co.'; the enginesindicate that White can gain an advantage with both} 17. d5 ({and} 17. h3 {, to displace the black queen and then take on e5. --- Naturally it's adifferent matter confronted with the position for the first time over theboard and having to calculate at move 12, when it might seem that Black haspractical chances.})) ({Your move} 13. O-O $1 {is, indeed, best, but thereason isn't so obvious. At first sight you might think, as several annotatorshave done, that Black could play} c5 14. dxc5 Rd8 ({not} 14... Qxc5 $2 15. Bd6$1) 15. Bd6 b6 {. --- EXERCISE: Demonstrate that this variation isn't good forBlack! What can White play? --- ANSWER: White can make use of the diagonalh1-a8 with a move which isn't obvious when you're calculating after 12...Qd5:in the event of} 16. Re1 ({or} 16. Qc2 {, Black is in time to play ...Bb7,followed by regaining the pawn}) ({but instead White can play} 16. f3 $1 Bb717. Be4 {, with an extra pawn and a clear advantage.})) 13... c6 $6 ({Blackcan't play the desirable} 13... c5 $2 {due to} 14. Be4 {. The move playedleads a passive position of the sort that should be avoided 'like the plague';instead Black should seek lines that offer greater practical chances.}) ({Black could try to 'fish in troubled waters' with} 13... Qxg2 $5 {and after}14. Be4 Qh3 15. Bxc7 {with} Bg5 {Black can prevent White from castling, butthe opening of lines against Black's castled position is more important, notforgetting the precarious position of Black's queen. A possible continuation is} 16. Rg1 Qh6 (16... Qh4 {is an improvement, but the difficulties remain after}17. Bg3 {and 18 h4}) 17. h4 $1 Bxh4 ({or} 17... Bf6 18. Qf3 {, threatening Bf4}) 18. Rh1 {, with the idea of 19 Bg3.}) 14. O-O Re8 {This is another attemptto find active possibilities, but its usefulness is doubtful;} ({it was betterfor Capablanca to resign himself to playing quietly with} 14... b6 {.}) 15.Rad1 {Eliminating any possibility of Black playing 15...e5 (16 dxe5 and Bxh7+would follow), with a move that is indeed useful.} Bd7 $6 {It's notable thatthis developing move is another inaccuracy. --- QUESTION: So, it's better toplay ...Bd7 after bringing the queen back to d8? --- Is that correct?} ({White is better, but his advantage can be restricted slightly by playing} 15...g6 16. Be5 Qd8 {, and only then 17...Bd7.}) 16. Rfe1 {ANSWER: Admittedly itisn't exactly any cause for celebration, but it's the lesser of the evils, fortactical reasons. The move 15...Bd7?! gives White an extra possibility ofexploiting the fact that with the queen on d5 the bishop can turn out to be atactical weakness. We'll see this more clearly later. --- Lasker increases thepressure with natural moves, but Black's inaccuracy is spared an even moresevere punishment.} (16. Be5 $1 {would have been very strong, when thetactical weakness of the d7-bishop is apparent in that Black can't play} Bxe5$2 {, due to} ({while} 16... Be7 17. Be4 Qa5 18. Rd3 $1 {gives White a winningattack with so many pieces aiming at the undefended black monarch}) 17. Bxh7+$1 Kxh7 18. dxe5 {, followed by 19 Rxd7.}) 16... Qa5 17. Qc2 {Trying to forcea weakness in Black's castled position;} ({another idea was} 17. Qf3 {,planning Qh3.}) 17... g6 ({If} 17... h6 {then the typical manoeuvre} 18. Qe2 {, planning Qe4;}) ({while in the event of} 17... Qh5 {, the queen isn't a verygood defender, and is in a delicate position after} 18. Re3 {,} ({or perhapsbetter} 18. Be4 {, followed by Rd3.})) 18. Be5 {Once the dark squares havebeen weakened it is appropriate to exchange the dark-squared bishops, toweaken Black's castled position.} Bg7 $6 {An inaccurate move. --- EXERCISE:How did Lasker highlight the negative side of Black's move?} ({It was betterto play} 18... Qd8) ({or} 18... Bxe5 19. Rxe5 Qd8 {, returning with the queento defend the weakened kingside.}) 19. h4 $1 {ANSWER: This is also a standardmanoeuvre; the pawn advances to weaken Black's castled position. Thispossibility could have been avoided with the improvements mentioned on theprevious move.} Qd8 ({Weakening the kingside further with} 19... h5 {doesn'tinspire confidence. Then it's stronger to play} 20. Bxg6 $1 ({the simple} 20.Re3 {is possible, but Black can stave off immediate defeat with the sad-looking} f5) 20... fxg6 21. Qxg6 Re7 22. Rd3 Rf8 23. Rg3 Rff7 24. Ree3 {, with theidea of Ref3, with a winning attack.}) 20. h5 Qg5 21. Bxg7 {Lasker continuesto play methodically and he keeps his advantage; now he exchanges the bishops,so to be able to play Re5 and then double rooks on the e-file. This is a goodplan, but not the best, for tactical reasons.} ({It was stronger to launch animmediate attack, beginning with} 21. hxg6 hxg6 {, followed by bringing therook into the attack with} 22. Re3 $1 {(the main target is the weakenedg6-pawn; the plan is 23 Rg3 followed by Bxg6)} Bxe5 23. dxe5 $1 {(with 'X-ray'pressure on the d7-bishop)} Rad8 24. Rg3 Qh5 25. Rh3 Qg5 {. EXERCISE: What'sthe strongest move now?} ({if} 25... Qxe5 {then} 26. Bxg6 fxg6 27. Qxg6+ Qg728. Qh5 {, with the idea of Rg3, and if} e5 29. Rxd7 $1 Qxd7 30. Qh8+ Kf7 31.Qh7+ Ke6 32. Qg6+ {with a decisive gain of material}) 26. f4 $1 {ANSWER: Linescan be opened with this move.} Qg4 {is not satisfactory either; the blackqueen is short of squares and one way to win is} (26... Qxf4 27. Bxg6 Re7 ({or} 27... Rf8 28. Rf1 Qxe5 29. Bh7+ Kg7 30. Qd2 f6 31. Qh6+ Kf7 {, and wins}) 28.Rf1 Qxe5 29. Bxf7+ Rxf7 30. Rxf7 Kxf7 31. Rh7+ Kf8 32. Qf2+ Qf5 33. Qh4 {, and wins.}) 27. Rf1 {(planning 28 Rff3, or 28 Qf2 followed by Rh4)} Kg7 28.Qd2 Rh8 29. Be2 (29. Rff3 {also works}) 29... Qf5 30. Rxh8 Rxh8 31. b3 $1 {, planning 32 g4 and 33 Bf3, trapping the queen, with a winning position. ---In many of these lines we can see that the g6-pawn is very vulnerable, butafter the exchange 21 Bxg7 Kxg7, the g6 point is reinforced by the blackmonarch.}) 21... Kxg7 22. Re5 {EXERCISE: Lasker is still better, although heisn't winning if Black defends in the best manner. What should Black play?} Qe7$2 {This allows White to proceed without difficulties.} ({ANSWER: It wasnecessary to play} 22... f5 {, when White doesn't have any crushing plan. Ofcourse White is better, with a chronic black weakness on e6 and weak darksquares, but there is nothing immediate. --- White can continue in variousways; he can retain the queens or go into a better endgame. One possibility is}23. Be2 {(planning Rd3)} gxh5 24. Qd2 {, aiming for an endgame with the blackstructure even weaker; after} h6 25. f4 Qh4 26. Rf1 {(planning Re3-h3)} Kh7 {and, besides} 27. Re3 {,} ({White can play} 27. Qe1 {, the exchange of queensis almost forced and once White has regained the pawn on h5 he will have theadvantage. There are many more possibilities, naturally. We should note thatafter the exchange of bishops and with the queens on the board, Whiteshouldn't be in any hurry to exchange on g6, since the opening of the h-filemight favour Black and not White.})) 23. Rde1 Rg8 {EXERCISE: Black plans, ifpossible, to bring his king to the queenside with 24...Kf8-e8-d8, so how didLasker continue now? --- ANSWER:} 24. Qc1 $1 {White's attack requires thesupport of the queen, whether to go to f4 or to control the h6-square.} (24.Qd2 {was equally strong.}) 24... Rad8 25. R1e3 ({It was also good to play} 25.Qf4 {first.}) 25... Bc8 {Black allows White to continue making progress.} ({It's possible that} 25... f6 {offered more practical chances, although it'sunderstandable that voluntarily weakening the position even more wouldn't bean easy decision.} {or else play} 26. Ra5 {and after} ({White can maintain thepressure with} 26. R5e4 {;} Z0 (26... Z0)) 26... a6 {try to continue theattack; there is many possibilities now: for example,} 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Rg3Be8 ({better than} 28... f5 29. Qf4 {, dominating all the dark squares}) ({or} 28... g5 29. f4) 29. Rh5 $1 Kf8 30. Qe3 {, followed by Rh6, and White has allhis pieces active, whereas Black's are poorly coordinated.}) 26. Rh3 Kf8 ({In the event of} 26... f6 {White can increase the pressure with} 27. Qf4 {, since} fxe5 {loses to} 28. h6+ Kh8 29. Qxe5+ Rg7 30. Bxg6 $1 hxg6 31. hxg7+Kg8 32. Rh8+ Kf7 33. g8=Q+ Rxg8 34. Rh7+ ({or} 34. Qf4+ {.})) ({Playing} 26...f5 {represents a serious positional concession, as we already know, since itweakens the dark squares irreparably and allows White to gain control ofvarious key squares. A possible continuation is} 27. Qe3 {, followed by Bc4,} ({or else} 27. hxg6 hxg6 28. Qf4 {, followed by 29 Bc4 or 29 Ree3.})) 27. Qh6+Rg7 28. hxg6 hxg6 {EXERCISE: White has several advantageous continuations.Lasker chose the most convincing, so what did he play? --- ANSWER:} 29. Bxg6 $1{Demolishing the defence and gaining a decisive material advantage.} Qf6 (29...fxg6 {loses to} 30. Qh8+ Kf7 ({or} 30... Rg8) 31. Rf3+ {.}) 30. Rg5 $1 {It isn't necessary to retreat the bishop after pocketing a pawn. Continuingthe attack is stronger. The move played defends the bishop and plans 31 Rf3,to which there is no adequate defence.} Ke7 ({After} 30... Rd5 {but as Beckerindicated, White wins with} 31. Rxd5 ({the strongest continuation isn't theimmediate} 31. Rf3 $6 {which fails to} Qxf3 $1 32. gxf3 $2 (32. Bh5 {is better}) 32... Rxg5+ {and wins}) 31... cxd5 32. Qh8+ Ke7 33. Qxc8 Qxg6 34. Qc7+ Ke8 ({or} 34... Kf6 35. Rf3+) 35. Rh8+ Rg8 36. Rxg8+ Qxg8 37. Qc8+ {.}) 31. Rf3 Qxf3{Black wins rook and bishop for the queen, but he's unable to resist in thelong run, because he can't construct a fortress, due to, among other things,the weakness of the dark squares and the passive bishop, which were the twomain factors in this game.} 32. gxf3 Rdg8 33. Kf1 ({Euwe pointed out aslightly better option,} 33. Qh4 {: for instance,} Kd7 34. Qf4 fxg6 35. c4 {, but Lasker's move is also effective.}) 33... Rxg6 34. Rxg6 Rxg6 35. Qh2 {EXERCISE: White can play just as he pleases; in the long run the victory willnot escape him. Nevertheless, there was a quicker way, as Euwe pointed out.How could Lasker have continued?} ({ANSWER: With} 35. Qf4 $1 {the queenattacks f7 and therefore prevents ...Kd7. This wins more easily, since after}Rg8 {the queen can infiltrate with} 36. Qc7+ Kf6 {which White could alsoprepare with} 37. Qe5+ {, as after} ({when White can continue with} 37. f4) ({or} 37. Ke2 {first, starting an invasion with the king;} Z0 (37... Z0)) 37...Ke7 {, he can pick off the a7-pawn with} ({while the black position is leftparalyzed after} 37... Kg6 38. Qg3+ Kh7 39. Qh4+ Kg6 40. Qg4+ Kh7 41. Qh5+ Kg742. Qg5+ Kh7 43. Qf6 Rf8 {, and now the white king begins its invasion with}44. Ke2) 38. Qc5+) 35... Kd7 36. Qf4 f6 37. c4 a6 38. Qh4 Rg5 39. Qh7+ Kd8 40.Qh8+ Kc7 41. Qxf6 {Here the position was adjourned for an hour and a half.Albert Becker commented in the 'Wiener Schach-Zeitung' of April 1935 thatLasker's quiet play after the resumption can be explained by his desire toavoid any errors due to fatigue; he wanted to be able to adjourn the game fora second time, which would give him the opportunity to rest before the furtherresumption.} Rf5 42. Qg7+ Bd7 43. Ke2 Kc8 44. Qh8+ Kc7 45. Qh2+ Kc8 46. Qd6 Rh547. Ke3 Rf5 48. Ke4 Rh5 49. Qf8+ Kc7 50. Qf4+ Kc8 51. Qd6 Rf5 52. Ke3 Rh5 53.Kd3 Rf5 54. Ke2 Rh5 55. Kd2 Rf5 56. Ke3 Rh5 57. Qf8+ Kc7 58. Qf4+ Kc8 59. Qd6Rf5 60. Qg3 Rh5 61. Qg4 Rf5 62. Qg8+ Kc7 63. Qg3+ Kc8 64. Qg6 ({Here theposition was adjourned for the second time and Capablanca resigned withoutresuming. Becker indicated one way to win after} 64. Qg6 Kc7 {:} 65. Qg3+ Kc8 {and now White brings the king to the queenside,} 66. Kd3 Rh5 67. Kc3 Rf5 ({if} 67... b6 {White gains the same result with} 68. Qd6 Rf5 69. f4 Rh5 70. Qb4 Kc771. c5 $1 {, followed by invading with the monarch via a5-b6, as Nunn noted})68. c5 $1 Rd5 69. Kb4 Rxd4+ 70. Ka5 {, followed by 71 Kb6.}) 1-0[Event "Training match, Moscow"][Site "?"][Date "1947.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Botvinnik, M"][Black "Ragozin, V"][Result "1-0"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][SetUp "1"][FEN "2rr1k2/pb2npq1/1p2p1p1/1R4Q1/3P2N1/2PBR3/P4PP1/6K1 w - - 0 28"][PlyCount "23"][EventDate "1947.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Kotov commented: "The weakness of the Black squares on the kingside isimmediately apparent. Black's possession of the d- and c-files is nocompensation in view of the fact that White's active pieces don't let him usethese files. White's plan is simple. He will increase the pressure on theweakened black squares, aiming for a bishop sacrifice on g6 so that his queenand rooks can get a mating attack. There are also knights on the board, butthey will soon be exchanged since White's knight will be too strongly postedat f6."} 28. Nf6 {With the idea of continuing with 29 Rh3-h7.} Ng8 29. Nxg8Kxg8 30. Qe7 Bc6 $2 31. Rbe5 Rd7 32. Qh4 Qh8 33. Qf4 Qg7 34. Rg3 (34. Bxg6 $1 {was already playable: for example,} fxg6 (34... Qxg6 35. Rg5) 35. Rxe6 {with a decisive attack; the move played is also very strong.}) 34... Bd5 35.Reg5 Rxc3 36. Bxg6 Rxg3 37. Bxf7+ Kf8 38. Rxg7 Rxg7 39. Bxe6+ {. Kotov alsocommented: "When you follow how precisely Botvinnik carries out the plan ofexploiting the black squares, you are full of praise, but... To be fair wemust note that it was not so hard for white to find the right plan here; allhe had to do was to copy the play of Lasker against Capablanca at Moscow1935", according to Botvinnik himself. --- Let's go back to Moscow 1935.After the win against Capablanca, in the following ten rounds Lasker won threemore games, and drew seven. The final result was joint first Botvinnik andFlohr with 13/19, in third Lasker 12½ (undefeated), fourth, Capablanca 12,etc. --- Master Subarev wrote: "67-year-old Lasker is the moral winner ofthe Moscow tournament. His play was just as deep and rich as in the best yearsof his phenomenal chess talent." --- After the Moscow tournament, Laskerreceived the offer to become a member of the Academy of Sciences of the USSRand to work in an institute of mathematics. Shortly after, the Laskers movedto Moscow. Later Lasker received Soviet citizenship.} 1-0[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Moscow 1936"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{The final year of official competition was not so good for Lasker. His nexttournament was also in Moscow, from the 14th of May to the 8th of June 1936.--- Ten players took part in a double-round event. In the first part Laskerfinished with 5/9, sharing second to fourth place with Botvinnik and Ragozin,although a long way behind Capablanca (6½), but in the second half he scoredonly three points, suffering four defeats and only one win. For the first andonly time in his career Lasker scored less than 50%.} 1. Z0 {Capablanca wasthe winner, with 13/18, followed by Botvinnik with 12, Flohr 9½, etc. Laskerfinished sixth with 8 points.} *[Event "?"][Site "?"][Date "????.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Nottingham 1936"][Black "?"][Result "*"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "1"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]{Lasker last tournament was in Nottingham, played from the 10th to the 28th ofAugust 1936. It was one of the strongest in history, with three ex-worldchampions competing, Lasker, Capablanca and Alekhine, as well as the thencurrent world champion, Euwe. Also present were the new stars Botvinnik, Flohr,Fine and Reshevsky, as well as strong grandmasters such as Bogoljubow,Tartakower and Vidmar and four British masters. --- Lasker was by now 67 yearsold, and he had just put up a weak performance in Moscow, so that hisprospects were not the most hopeful. Lasker himself had commented that he wasgoing to his "final failure" in Nottingham.} 1. Z0 {It was his lasttournament, but it was not a failure. He finished with 8½/14, sharing seventhplace with Flohr, but not far behind the leaders. Capablanca and Botvinnik wonwith 10 points, followed by Fine, Reshevsky and Euwe (9½), and Alekhine with9. --- Alexander Alekhine wrote in the Manchester Guardian: "I consider thatit is almost impossible to criticise Lasker, so great is my admiration for himas a person, an artist and a chess writer. At his 67 years, thanks to hisyouthful energy, will-to-win and incredibly deep treatment of the chessstruggle, he remains the same Lasker, if not as a practical player, then as achess thinker." --- In the tournament book Alekhine described Lasker'sperformance like this: "The chess players of the present and all latergenerations should take Lasker as an example."} *[Event "46: Nottingham"][Site "?"][Date "1936.??.??"][Round "?"][White "Lasker, Em"][Black "Alexander, CH"][Result "1-0"][ECO "A26"][Annotator "Zenón Franco"][PlyCount "67"][EventDate "1936.??.??"][SourceTitle "MBM: Lasker"][Source "Everyman Chess"][SourceDate "2018.11.14"][SourceVersion "1"]1. c4 {This was the fourth time Lasker opened with the English in an officialgame.} e5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 ({The only time that Lasker had this positionbefore was against Lisitsin in Moscow 1935; there he opted for} 3. Nf3 Nf6 {and here he relinquished the possibility of fianchettoing the bishop by playing} 4. d4 {.}) 3... g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 ({The main alternatives are} 5. Rb1) ({and} 5. e3 {, which had the approval of Alekhine, who pointed out that thiswas Botvinnik's choice against Alexander in the first round, with reversedcolours.}) 5... Nge7 6. Bd2 {Lasker wants to move away from the more naturalpaths and to keep his options open. Naturally he is not aspiring to gain anopening advantage, but is merely trying to reach a fighting position.} ({The most usual moves are} 6. Nf3 {, transposing to lines in which Nf3 isplayed earlier;}) ({and} 6. Rb1 {, while it's notable that in the three gamesin which Capablanca played similar positions, he considered that when Blackdevelops the knight on e7 the most appropriate response for White is to playh4 at some moment.}) ({Capablanca played the immediate} 6. h4 {a few monthsbefore in Margate against Milner-Barry and after} h6 7. Bd2 d6 {the game tooka direction that is familiar to us from more modern games: Capablancacontinued with} 8. Rb1 O-O 9. b4 {, but he gained no advantage.}) ({InNottingham, against Alexander in the thirteenth round, he implemented the sameidea, but first played} 6. Nd5 {and after} O-O 7. h4 Nd4 8. Bg5 f6 9. Bd2 c610. Nxe7+ Qxe7 11. e3 Ne6 12. Ne2 f5 {Black was fine, but neverthelessCapablanca won both games.}) 6... O-O ({In J.Capablanca-R.Grau, Buenos AiresOlympiad 1939, Black played} 6... d6 {and after} 7. Rb1 O-O {White came backto the idea of playing} 8. h4 {. Following} h5 9. b4 {the position becameunclear, with the knights taking centre stage in the following moves, but after} Nf5 10. b5 Ncd4 11. Nh3 Ne6 12. Ng5 Nc5 13. Nge4 Nd4 14. Nxc5 {White hadgained the advantage.}) 7. Nf3 Nd4 {"The idea of protecting the d5-squarewith a pawn is in harmony with the character of the position", commentedAlekhine; Black is preparing ...c6, postponing the decision about what to dowith the d7-pawn.} 8. O-O c6 9. Rc1 {"White is not in a hurry, and obviouslyprepares for a long positional battle", wrote Alekhine. It's notable thatthis is one of the top options of the current engines, although none of themsee any advantage on White's part.} d6 {Black also keeps his options open.} ({He could have gained good play by first exchanging with} 9... Nxf3+ {,preventing White from capturing on d4, and only after} 10. Bxf3 {playing} d6 {, followed by 11...Be6 (or 11...Bh3) and 12...Qd7, but what he played isn'tinferior.}) 10. b4 ({Lasker continues to refrain from exchanging on d4, giventhat} 10. Nxd4 {doesn't give White much after} exd4 11. Ne4 f5 12. Ng5 h6 13.Nf3 g5 {, with the idea of ...Ng6 and a future ...f4.}) 10... Nxf3+ {This isthe simplest way to complete development.} ({Another idea, more aggressive butalso more committal, was} 10... Ne6 {, planning ...h6 and ...f5, on the basisthat the closed position allows Black to play with his development incomplete.}) 11. Bxf3 Bh3 12. Re1 Qd7 {EXERCISE: How did Lasker now continue? --- ANSWER:}13. b5 $1 {All the preparations are complete and it's time for the plannedbreak.} c5 {This is a concession; Black prevents the opening of the b-file andthe creation of a weakness on c6, but the black pawn structure loses mobilityand now he must rely entirely on gaining counterplay with a timely ...f5advance. It's not all negative though; White's queenside initiative has beennullified and the loss of control of d5 isn't an immediate worry, since afterNd5 Black simply exchanges the knights.} 14. Ne4 {"An original move,preventing for the moment 14...h6, because of 15 Bxh6, etc. Black's next twomoves are not actually weak, but show lack of a general plan," wroteAlekhine.} ({Lasker's move sharpens the struggle much more than the alternative} 14. a4 {, with the plan of a5-a6. Since Black is unable to play} h6 {he mustconstantly consider how strong Ng5 is against whatever plan he chooses.}) 14...Qc7 $6 {Lasker's decision is fully justified after this timid (or optimistic?)response, which prepares to bring the bishop back from h3 before playing ...f5.} ({Alekhine considered that "Black should answer it by} 14... Kh8 {and if}15. Rb1 {, then} h6 16. Qc1 f5 17. Nc3 Kh7 {with a perfectly satisfactoryposition".}) ({It's not clear that} 14... f5 15. Ng5 Bg4 {would be bad,reaching an untypical position, but everything indicates that this was not atall to the taste of Alexander, who preferred positions that were clearer.}) 15.Rb1 Bd7 ({As Euwe suggested, Black could still try to play actively, bykeeping his bishop on h3 and playing} 15... h6 {, preparing ...f5.}) 16. Qc1 {Lasker wants to discourage the advance ...f5, since after Bh6 the exchange ofbishops would leave Black's king weaker than White's. One of Black's tasks wasto evaluate this position: is Bh6 really to be feared?} b6 $2 {Alexander seemsto respond to that question with a 'yes', but tactically this isn't correct."One might call this tempting Providence in the most definite way. ---EXERCISE: How did Lasker demonstrate that 16...b6 is an error?} ({Why leavethe queen's rook on the diagonal of the hostile king's bishop? The natural} 16... f5 17. Nc3 Rae8 {followed, if necessary by ...b6, would leave White withonly an insignificant advantage" (Alekhine).}) 17. Bg5 $1 {ANSWER: Thisattack on the knight, combined with the inevitable Nf6+, leaves Black in atricky situation.} Nf5 {"A desperate attempt to save the Exchange" (Alekhine).} ({"The refutation of Black's last move, as he cannot now play} 17... f6 $2 18. Bxf6 ({the order} 18. Nxf6+ $1 Bxf6 19. Bxa8 {is slightly moreprecise}) 18... Bxf6 (18... Nf5 {is more tenacious}) 19. Nxf6+ {followed by 20Bxa8" (Alekhine).}) 18. Nf6+ Bxf6 19. Bxf6 Rab8 $6 {Black fails to offerresistance.} (19... Rae8 {was better, when the virtue of playing the rook toe8 is that it prepares the counterblow 20...Re6, which is effective in theevent of the knight on f5 being attacked. However, Lasker would have played}20. Bd5 $1 {, and after} Ng7 21. Qg5 {(threatening 22 Be7)} Be6 22. g4 {White has a big advantage and Black has no counterplay, although still thereis nothing immediate.}) 20. Bg4 $1 {Now there is no counterblow with 20...Re6,so that the threat of Bxf5 followed by Qh6 will win the exchange.} (20. g4 {was of similar strength.}) 20... Ng7 21. Qh6 Ne8 22. Be7 Ng7 23. Bf6 Ne8 24.Be7 Ng7 25. Bxf8 Rxf8 26. Bf3 {"After the loss of the Exchange, Black has nomore fighting chances, as Dr. Lasker promptly demonstrates", wrote Alekhine.The rest is very simple.} Nf5 27. Qd2 Nd4 28. Bg2 Bc8 29. e3 Ne6 30. f4 Bb7 31.a4 f5 32. Bxb7 Qxb7 33. Qg2 Qe7 34. Qd5 {. This was the last tournament gameplayed by Emanuel Lasker. --- At the end of October 1937 Lasker and his wifeMartha travelled to the USA, to see their family. Martha fell ill, and thenthe Second World War broke out, so they never returned to Europe. EmanuelLasker died in New York on the 11th of January, 1941.} 1-0